 'Normal'=>'Instantly Fix or replace a Prop (Physical Descendant).',
 'Crossed'=>'Target drops a random Prop (Physical Descendant).'),
array('WyrdTarot'=>'Chi',
 'Normal'=>'Target pulls another card and gains Chi equal to 7 + the Pips.',
 'Crossed'=>'Target loses 15 Chi.'),
array('WyrdTarot'=>'Safe Passage',
 'Normal'=>'Target may leave the Location or Stage (without passing Diff). Cut to destination (where applicable).',
 'Crossed'=>'The Target is Intercepted or Ambushed (usually by the Player).'),
array('WyrdTarot'=>'Miracle',
 'Normal'=>'Automatic Success +4 Additional Success Levels/ Draw Maximum Roll +4 Ordeal Cards',
 'Crossed'=>'Target fails with a Disaster (Score of -1 and +4 Failure Levels)/ -5 Ordeal Cards.'),
array('WyrdTarot'=>'Double Bluff',
 'Normal'=>'Grants Target an additional pile where cards may be played upon them.',
 'Crossed'=>'Closes Pile. All cards beneath the Double Bluff are discarded,
 no card may be played on the Double Bluff until a Crisis removes it.'),
array('WyrdTarot'=>'Double Score',
 'Normal'=>'Add a rolled Score to the Score the Target generates again (x2/x3) this may allow more cards to be Drawn, etc. while atop the pile.',
 'Crossed'=>'Halves all Scores the Target generates whilst atop their pile.'),
array('WyrdTarot'=>'Heal Wounds',
 'Normal'=>'+2 Success Levels to all attempts to treat Wounds on or by the Target while atop the pile.',
'Crossed'=>'+2 Failure Levels to all attempts to treat Heal Wounds on or by the Target while atop the pile.'),
array('WyrdTarot'=>'Trap',
 'Normal'=>'+2 Success Levels to all Actions to do with setting, designing and causing damage from traps (Snare Attacks).',
 'Crossed'=>'+2 Failure levels to all Actions to do with disarming, avoiding, and soaking damage from traps.'),
array('WyrdTarot'=>'Crisis',
 'Normal'=>'Automatic Proficiency Crisis. Add a Proficiency to an Annex (or merge two Proficiencies into a Skill).',
 'Crossed'=>'Re-roll a Proficiency Crisis.'),
array('WyrdTarot'=>'Aegis',
 'Normal'=>'Discards all cards of an incoming attack.',
 'Crossed'=>'Adds +10 Penetration Pips to an Attack card in play.'),
array('WyrdTarot'=>'Fast Talk',
 'Normal'=>'+1 Success Level on any social action (they believe the lie) or Psych Attack.',
 'Crossed'=>'+1 Failure Level of any social action (they won\'t believe the truth) or Psych Attack.'),
array('WyrdTarot'=>'Surprised',
 'Crossed'=>'Target may disregard current RT, GRT, Pool Size and take a Full-Action.',
 'Normal'=>'Target is immediately affected by GRT of 2'),
array('WyrdTarot'=>'Stalemate',
 'Normal'=>'Target may automatically Stalemate any Test (Scoring exactly the Difficulty). Automatically pay a Stage / Obstacle cost in an Ordeal.',
 'Crossed'=>'Adds +1 Success Level, +1 Failure Level and +1 Unsoakable Distract to the target.'),
array('WyrdTarot'=>'Failure',
 'Normal'=>'Target rolls a Complete Failure or +2 Failure Levels.',
 'Crossed'=>'+2 Success Levels to one Roll or Ordeal Card.'),
array('WyrdTarot'=>'Psst',
 'Normal'=>'Add a card from your Hand to the Target&#39;s Hand and Draw 2 cards.',
 'Crossed'=>'Take a random card from the Target&#39;s Hand and add it to your own. They may draw a replacement.'),
array('WyrdTarot'=>'Shake Off',
 'Crossed'=>'Target takes 1d4 Unsoakable Distract Wounds.',
 'Normal'=>'Target discards <strong>all</strong> Distract Wounds'),
array('WyrdTarot'=>'Relieve Wound',
 'Crossed'=>'Draw and Apply one Unsoakable Wound to the Target.',
 'Normal'=>'Remove the Target\'s largest Wound.'),
array('WyrdTarot'=>'Charm',
 'Normal'=>'Target gains +2  Success Levels on any Social actions while atop the pile. Additionally adds a "Charm" Reserve for Target that they may "Prepare" Ordeal cards to for any social action.',
 'Crossed'=>'Target takes +2 Failure Levels on any Social actions while atop the pile. Additionally automatically closes and discards any "Charm" Reserve.'),
array('WyrdTarot'=>'Plan',
 'Normal'=>'+1 Success Level to everyone following the Plan while atop pile. Additionally creates a "Plan" Reserve for the team, that they may each Prepare one card from their Hand to, as an Ordeal Card. The Plan Reserve may be used for any Planned action. The Reserve is Discarded when the Plan is covered or Discarded.',
 'Crossed'=>'+2 Success Levels when working alone while atop pile. When played on a Target their Hand is Prepared as Ordeal Cards into a "Plan" Reserve, and they redraw they Wyrd Tarot Hand. The Reserve is Discarded when the Plan is covered or Discarded.'),
array('WyrdTarot'=>'Mage',
 'Normal'=>'Magic On. Target has +2 Success Levels to all Magical Attacks, Defences, etc. while atop Pile. Additionally creates a "Magic" Reserve for the Target.',
 'Crossed'=>'Magic Off. Target has +2 Failure Levels to all Magical Attacks, Defences, etc. while atop Pile. Additionally discards all "Magic" Reserves.'),
array('WyrdTarot'=>'Death',
 'Normal'=>'Automatically adds +21 Pips to any Attack made by the Target. Stakes are Extreme while atop Pile. All Hitches created by or on the Target are "Dying", "Dead" or "Destroyed" ',
 'Crossed'=>'Automatically adds +21 Pips to any Defence. Stakes are Low while atop Pile. All Hitches created by or on the Target cannot be "Dying", "Dead" or "Destroyed".'),
array('WyrdTarot'=>'Reroll',
 'Crossed'=>'Automatic Proficiency Crisis. You can add a Proficiency to, or create, an Annex (if you have a slot free).',
 'Normal'=>'Reroll any dice including a Proficiency Crisis.'),
array('WyrdTarot'=>'Breach',
 'Crossed'=>'Discards the highest card of an incoming attack',
 'Normal'=>'Adds +12 Penetration Pips to an Attack card in play.'),
array('WyrdTarot'=>'Enrage',
 'Crossed'=>'+1 Success Level on any social action or Psych attack.',
 'Normal'=>'+1 Failure Level of any social action or Psych attack.'),
array('WyrdTarot'=>'Surprise',
 'Normal'=>'Target may disregard current RT, GRT, Pool Size and take a Full-Action, right now.',
 'Crossed'=>'Target is immediately affected by GRT of 2'),
array('WyrdTarot'=>'Unbalance',
 'Crossed'=>'Target may automatically Stalemate any Test (Scoring exactly the Difficulty). Automatically pay a Stage / Obstacle cost in an Ordeal',
 'Normal'=>'Automatically gives target 1 Unsoakable Distract Wound and adds +1 Success Level and +1 Failure Level to their next action.'),
array('WyrdTarot'=>'Rise',
 'Crossed'=>'Target rolls a Complete Failure or Draws minimum.',
 'Normal'=>'+2 Success Levels to one roll, or Ordeal Card.'),
array('WyrdTarot'=>'Doom-theft',
 'Crossed'=>'Add a card from your Hand to the Target&#39;s Hand and Draw 2 cards.',
 'Normal'=>'Take a random card from the Target&#39;s Hand and add it to your own. They may draw a replacement.'),
array('WyrdTarot'=>'Distractions',
 'Normal'=>'Target takes 1d4 Unsoakable Distract Wounds.',
 'Crossed'=>'Target removes <strong>all</strong> Distract Wounds'),
array('WyrdTarot'=>'Wound',
 'Normal'=>'Draw and Apply one Unsoakable Wound to the Target.',
 'Crossed'=>'Remove the largest Wound from the Target.'),
array('WyrdTarot'=>'Gun',
 'Normal'=>'Target may ignore Range Difficulties and add +1 Success Levels when acting at Range, all Ranged Attacks increase in Stake 1 Level (to Extreme) while atop pile.',
 'Crossed'=>'Target takes -2 Success Levels and Range costs +18 Pips (+36 Score) to all actions, all Ranged Attacks decrease in STake 1 Level (to Low) while atop pile.'),
array('WyrdTarot'=>'Spot Hidden',
 'Normal'=>'+2 Success Levels (+38 Score) to all Target\'s tests to do with perception and senses while atop pile.',
 'Crossed'=>'+2 Success Levels (+38 Score) to all Target\'s tests to do with hiding, sneaking, etc. while atop pile.'),
array('WyrdTarot'=>'Fear',
 'Normal'=>'Cause Fear. +2 cards to Psych Attacks and +1 card to Psychology Tests the Target causes while atop the pile.',
'Crossed'=>'Self-Control. -1 Card from Psychology test (Immunity to Fear) and -2 from Psych Attacks on the Target while atop the pile.'),
array('WyrdTarot'=>'Wildcard',
 'Normal'=>'May be played as any Non-Court card (or as an Ordeal Card Joker with +22 Pips of Liberty Penetration)',
 'Crossed'=>'May be played as any Non-Court card Crossed'),
array('WyrdTarot'=>'Wildcard',
 'Normal'=>'May be played as any Non-Court card Crossed (or as an Ordeal Card Joker with +22 Pips of Wyrd Penetration)',
 'Crossed'=>'May be played as any Non-Court card'));
	public static $deck;
	private static $noDecks;

	private static $yarn =  array(
					//diams
		array('Yarn_Name'=>'The Ambition','Yarn_Description'=>'The Card of new Ambitions, sudden monetary gains, new business opportunities, new treasures or rumours of treasures and money being made. There may be conflict and collisions, new obstacles in the way or a Rival\'s ambitions may block progress.','Significator'=>['Plot'=>'This Plot is known as the "Rags-To-Riches" Plot. It seeks Characters of poor circumstance (the more Hitches the better) often from the Below side, and raises them up, granting them power and success. Such Characters often move from the Below side to the Pressed Side, and even reach the Dominant side occasionally (during a Revolution for example). However, once they are raised in riches and power, the Plot will pick a new Pauper to Hook from the Below.','Side'=>'A side marked by The Ambition will have a strong desire to improve their situation during the Plot, this may cause them to act carelessly, but ruthlessly to achieve their ambition.','Character'=>'The Ambition significator will make a Character who is defined by their Ambitions. The Character should set an Ambition. This should be a difficult to achieve ambition, such as "Become the Greatest Living Swordsman". <p>This gives the Character a <strong>Gain (Yin) Sway</strong> when they speak about this ambition or their current goals (which are usually a step toward their ultimate goal).</p><p>Gain (Yang) Sway when they choose an option or take an action that hastens this ambition.</p><p>They will also <strong>Gain Chi</strong> if their ambition is thwarted by another\'s actions.</p><p>Additionally, when directly working towards their Ambition (such as training or challenging other swordsmen) they may add +1 Success Level.<p>','Scene'=>'The Ambition Scenes are the scenes where we see a glimpse of what Characters want. Yarn-Tellers can play The Ambition to bring their own Ambitions closer, or reveal what another\'s goals are.'],'Beat_Type'=>'1', 'Conflict_Embodiment'=>'3', 'Facet_Embodiment'=>'4', 'Hook_Aspect'=>'Geometry: Goal', 'Aspect_Description'=>'The Hook targets the Character\'s Geometry by appealing to the Geometry Goal. This is often tied to a Character’ personal ambitions.','Hook'=>'Opportunity', 'Hook_Description'=>'The Story hooks Characters by offering them an opportunity to Gain something they want or need to fulfil an ambition.', 'Gain'=>'Ultimate Power (A Super-Skill Descendant / An Artefact)', 'Fray'=>'Quest', 'Fray_Description'=>'The Fray is a Quest, usually based on the Facets of the Conflict, for something the PC requires or desires.', 'Snag'=>'Falling Behind', 'Snag_Description'=>'The Character\'s Rival or Opposition makes a Gain (or just advances to the next Stage of a larger Plot\'s Ordeal). You may Play another Card as a Gain, or use this card\'s <em>Ultimate Power</em>.','NPC'=>array('Archetype'=>'Enchanter','Persona'=>0,'Core'=>11,'Hitch'=>21,'Description'=>'Enchanters or Enchantresses are magic users that use Charms and Enchantments to get what they want. If magic is off then they will use hypnotic or psychological tricks to charm, manipulate and seduce.'),'Sweeping'=>'Win','Sweeping_Text'=>'The Pressed side has a Win, this may be a battle against a weak or weakened foe, or they might catch a lucky break, or lottery win. The Win doesn\'t have to be big, just enough to keep hope alive, but a Gain is in order. Perhaps even the Resolution of a Hitch.','History'=>'Glory','History_Description'=>'The past is coloured by previous successes. This is not usually just nostalgia, but some past glory that has been lost or ignored.', 'Situation'=>'Rivalry', 'Situation_Description'=>'The situation of Ambition is that your ambitions are rivalled by the ambitions of others. Either someone wants the opposite of what you want, or they want the exact same goal, but if they have it you will not (such as wanting the same land, descendant or treasure).' ,'Solution'=>'Objectives','Solution_Description'=>'The way out of this situation involves setting small, accomplishable objectives. By breaking big tasks and broad ambitions into smaller steps and practicable goals.'), //ace
		array('Yarn_Name'=>'The Wraith','Yarn_Description'=>'Whether an expression of the supernatural or simply the psychological forces at play. The card is about People\'s Emotions and especially Fears. These can be as simple as a fear of missing out, or falling behind others, or expressions of deeper phobias. It is a card of small gains and intense, but limited resistance.','Significator'=>['Plot'=>'This Plot is known as a "Ghost Story" it may be Horror Genre, or may be a Morality Tale. It will involve either the Supernatural (in the form of a Ghost or Haunting from the Dominant, Shadows or External sides) or some sort of Psychological Terror (the Scare - usually a Dominant Side feature). Wraith Plots will always try to pile on the emotional damage, adding +1 Success Level to any Negative Psyche Attack.','Side'=>'A side of a conflict marked by the Wraith will be considered history by the rest of the conflict, forgotten or assumed dead, occasionally they are dead, but still their name acts as an Embodiment, influencing other Characters to revive the side.','Character'=>'The Wraith Significator indicates a Character that is haunted by their past. They may see actual ghosts or spirits, but more normally they are plagued by thoughts, feelings, dreams and memories that they would like to forget.<p>They <strong>Gain Yin</strong> when they mope, brood or act depressed.<p><p><strong>Gain Yang</strong> when they engage with situations or people that remind them of their past.</p><p><strong>Gain Chi</strong> when they tell others their story.</p><p>Additionally they gain +1 Success Level with any situation that relates to their past.</p>','Scene'=>'A Wraith Scene is a a spooky or kooky scene that is meant to be memorable by how much it disturbs or freaks out the Characters. It can be as complex as demonic invasions or as simple as saying that you realise the little girl you were talking with, never blinked once. Yarn-Tellers may use the Wraith to disturb, unnerve and disquiet even psychologically powerful Characters.'],'Beat_Type'=>'2', 'Conflict_Embodiment'=>'3', 'Facet_Embodiment'=>'7', 'Hook_Aspect'=>'Persona: Shadow', 'Aspect_Description'=>'The Hook targets the Character\'s Persona, specifically by appealing to the Shadow of their Persona.','Hook'=>'Banshee\'s Wail', 'Hook_Description'=>'The Story opens with a warning, usually the warning is a Plot Revelation, but it may traditionally be a warning of a death in the family. The point is to make the PC\'s a little more afraid.', 'Gain'=>'A single coin, suitable for paying a ferryman (Yin/Yang Gain).', 'Fray'=>'Insubstantial', 'Fray_Description'=>'The Fray is an insubstantial, or trifling matter, but failure may have profound consequences later. An example may be a single question asked by a co-worker, it seems unimportant at the time, but is actually part of an human resources investigation. Usually a Test on a single Facet (A,C,O,Q,V,Z) (although an appropriate Annex might help). The difficulty is usually quite low (between 1-15). Facet Tests are meant to be quick, easy checks, a simple roll. Failures may involve negative Psyche effects.', 'Snag'=>'Haunting', 'Snag_Description'=>'The Character may see an actual ghost, or may be reminded of a previous situation, drawing comparisons with the current Fray. The Haunting Snag usually has a magical or psychological effect that may often create new Hitches.','NPC'=>array('Archetype'=>'Necromancer','Persona'=>18,'Core'=>15,'Hitch'=>14,'Description'=>'Necromancers are a spiritual or mage type who deal exclusively with the dead and Undead.'),'Sweeping'=>'Boo!','Sweeping_Text'=>'A jump scare that isn\'t harmful to the Characters, like having someone tap on a the window / knock on the door during a tense moment, or having a dog suddenly bark out of sight. Can act to ease Tension, or ratchet up suspense. A Boo! can also be enough to Resolve a Fear Hitch, under the right circumstances.', 'History'=>'Haunted','History_Description'=>'Sometimes the past will not let us go. Some moments stay with us forever, haunting our dreams, asking what if we had done something differently. This past event is always present somehow, whether dredged up by others, present in laments and fears that stay with us, or just fondly remembered, for some important reason.', 'Situation'=>'Past', 'Situation_Description'=>'The current situation is actually a problem with the past, some old problem that was not properly dealt with has once again raised its head, or some event years ago has now caused this situation. ','Solution'=>'Courage','Solution_Description'=>'The situation will only be dealt with by a demonstration of courage, this may mean facing an old fear, or simply resisting this situation come what may.'), //2
		array('Yarn_Name'=>'The Grindstone','Yarn_Description'=>'The Grindstone is the card of hard work, wearing down opposition, or training yourself to a finely sharpened point. It is a card of determined hard-won success for little reward or bitter, grinding defeat.','Significator'=>['Plot'=>'The Grindstone Plot is one that seeks to grind down the Characters that it Hooks, it tries to exhaust and wear them down, not so that they may be destroyed, but be improved, sharpened and refined. It knocks a Character down so that they may build themselves up again. All Tests and Ordeals the Plot creates will have twice the Difficulty, or increased Stakes.','Side'=>'A side marked by the Grindstone can expect to be tested and worn down, either to exhaustion or even near death, however if they are allowed to recuperate, they become stronger than before.','Character'=>'The Grindstone Significator indicates a  Character who works hard for what they have.<p>They <strong>Gain Yin</strong> by doing any routine task, such as washing, cleaning, maintenance, etc. </p><p>They <strong>Gain Yang</strong> by working up a sweat, doing hard work or exercise. </p><p>They <strong>Gain Chi</strong> whenever they receive any payment for their work, goods or services. </p><p>Grindstone Characters additionally gain a +1 Success Level whenever they are faced with gruelling working conditions or circumstances.</p>','Scene'=>'A Grindstone Scene wears at the Characters it affects It may force them to expend Yarn, Chi or Sway on their actions during the Scene. This is usually the result of a strong Warp (Ordeal, Test, Quest), or a terrible Weft (that includes Tests, Ordeals and no Gains). Yarn-Tellers should be aware that the Grindstone should not kill, but may Cripple, or Fatigue.'],'Beat_Type'=>'3', 'Conflict_Embodiment'=>'3', 'Facet_Embodiment'=>'8', 'Hook_Aspect'=>'Power Root', 'Aspect_Description'=>'The Hook targets the Character\'s Power, specifically the Root Facet of that power, this may be a chance to increase a Facet Boon, or a promise of a large amount of Facet Sway.','Hook'=>'Working Start', 'Hook_Description'=>'The Conflict engages with a Character\'s current task. This is best expressed in TV by the cold start or In Media Res, that involves the Character\'s day-to-day job.', 'Gain'=>'Wage (Normal Chi Gain or payment, may be daily, weekly, monthly or yearly)', 'Fray'=>'Working', 'Fray_Description'=>'The Test is like a Facet Test (A,C,O,Q,V,Z), but the Difficulty is a little higher (Diff 16+). These Tests are simple, and intended to just check some aspect of the Character, they represent a normal day at work, usually.', 'Snag'=>'Drudgery', 'Snag_Description'=>'Boredom is the enemy in this Snag. Whatever the Fray, the Snag is either the Fray or the aftermath is tedious. The Snag will inevitably have a negative Psychological effect, which can leave people despondent, dismayed and even suicidal.','NPC'=>array('Archetype'=>'Tradesman','Persona'=>2,'Core'=>8,'Hitch'=>17,'Description'=>'The Tradesman, be they Carpenter, Plumber, Builder, Electrician, or jobbing Programmer.'),'Sweeping'=>'Wages','Sweeping_Text'=>'A Wage (or bonus) is a single Cash (Chi) Gain, Wages are a Skill Treasure Descendant', 'History'=>'Toil','History_Description'=>'The Grindstone indicates a history of hard work, or exploitation, that has lead to this current situation. Either someone has worked long and hard to bring this about, usually alone, but sometimes with others, or someone has got rich off the back of other people\'s work.', 'Situation'=>'Grind', 'Situation_Description'=>'The Grindstone indicates the current situation is wearing you down. This may be the daily grind getting you down, or it may indicate that you are working too hard.','Solution'=>'Effort','Solution_Description'=>'The Grindstone shows the way out of your current predicament involves a lot of hard work, there is a long slog ahead of you before you will make any real progress at all.'), //3
		array('Yarn_Name'=>'The Book','Yarn_Description'=>'The Book is the card of knowledge, authority and responsibility. Books are information in permanent form, frozen thoughts, and as such are technology, language and magic. Books are granted authority, and define monotheistic religions, for example, but they may sometimes contain mistakes (in translation, spelling, or printing), or the author\'s opinions presented as facts, that can lead one astray. By the Book Characters act with this same occasionally flawed authority.','Significator'=>['Plot'=>'The Book Plot indicates a Plot that is reworking some other work (rather like The Myth). It may be a retelling of an older story, or a retelling of history, re-imagined in a new place or time. The new Plot will always have differences to the original (often completely inverting the Conflict or Final Resolution), but is fundamentally the same thing. Book Plots often rely heavily on Revelations and characterisations  in their Conflict.','Side'=>'A side of a conflict that is marked by the Book is granted authority, but that authority is flawed in some way. Perhaps they misinterpret the law, or a religious document, or place the wrong emphasis in between the two...','Character'=>'The Book Significator indicates a Character who does things by the Book. <p>They <strong>Gain Yin</strong> when they remind others of the rules, and point out rule-breaking.</p><p><strong>Gain Yang</strong> when they follow or enforce proper procedures and rules.</p><p><strong>Gain Chi</strong> when they are respectful of others and polite.</p><p>The Book also grants them a +1 Success Level if they break a rule.</p>','Scene'=>'The Book Scenes tend to be scripted. They might be a section of descriptive prose, narration or scripted dialogue, perhaps a Character will tell their back-story, motives or simply mislead. Words are important to this scene, which is more likely to be an argument than a fight, and more often a conversation or revelation. Yarn-Tellers should use this card carefully, as they will be required to narrate the details, or play out the conversations.'],'Beat_Type'=>'4', 'Conflict_Embodiment'=>'3', 'Facet_Embodiment'=>'10', 'Hook_Aspect'=>'I-Ching: Second Hexagram', 'Aspect_Description'=>'The Hook targets the Character\'s I-Ching, specifically the 2nd Hexagram. Usually this 2nd Hexagram defines only a way of gaining Chi, Yin or Yang for the Character, so the Hook will provide whatever circumstances that Gain requires.','Hook'=>'Tone, Theme or Thesis', 'Hook_Description'=>'The Conflict hooks the Characters by a powerful scene that sets the Tone for the Story, that may also specify the Theme or Thesis of the Conflict with an immediate Revelation.', 'Gain'=>'Knowledge (Lore or Learning Descendant of Skill or Talent Level)', 'Fray'=>'Research', 'Fray_Description'=>'Usually a Low Stakes Ordeal that involves a Character finding out some information, it may involve reading (web-pages, books, articles, papers), visiting a Location (usually a Library, Archive, or a website), asking people questions, in interviews or by polling, or (more rarely) conducting experiments.', 'Snag'=>'Missing Page', 'Snag_Description'=>'The Book Snag is a missing page or piece of the puzzle. They may have done the research, or reached their goal, only to discover they don\'t have the final item they require. They may be able to find another copy, or someone who has read that page though, so all is not lost.','NPC'=>array('Archetype'=>'Teacher','Persona'=>14,'Core'=>14, 'Hitch'=>2,'Description'=>'Teachers are those who Teach. They may be religious people or school teachers, or they can even be Professors (although not Archetype Professors). Teachers usually have at least a Talent in what they Teach, but not always, their true Power lies in Teaching things they don\'t even know themselves.'),'Sweeping'=>'RTFM','Sweeping_Text'=>'You find or are directed to a book, tome or manual that can give you a Gain of a Teaching in a Skill, etc. Example, after asking why a green light started flashing on their flight suits they were handed the Operators Manual by the Technician in the bay. They will still need to find time to read the manual...', 'History'=>'Ancient','History_Description'=>'The Book card indicates that the past in this case is some ancient, half-forgotten knowledge that must be researched to be properly understood. This can indicate a forgotten piece of a character\'s history, or some actual historical situation affects this moment.', 'Situation'=>'Authority', 'Situation_Description'=>'The Book indicates the current situation is something to do with authority, often the law or some rule, this may not necessarily be criminal law, property, corporate, civil, commercial, international, family, employment, administrative, religious, physical and temporal laws can apply. This authority may be the direct source of the situation or simply complicate it.','Solution'=>'Research','Solution_Description'=>'The Book indicates that the future, and a route out of this current situation, is certain, all ready decided and written down somewhere, only research and copious amounts of study and reading are required to find out exactly where and what that is.'), //4
		array('Yarn_Name'=>'The Forest','Yarn_Description'=>'Far from the City, beyond the farms lie the deep, dark woods, the ancient forests of the world. This is the card of quiet woodlands and quiet yearnings, the Forests are places of plenty, but they are also places of darkness. Animals that know no fear of man haunt these places. It is a card of loneliness, abandonment, and very real needs — such as comfort, warmth and security.','Significator'=>['Plot'=>'The Forest Plot is about making the Hooked Characters learn their place in the greater world. Often, they learn their place is not where they thought it was (and it certainly isn\'t the Forest itself). In the deep, dark forest all Stakes are Higher than you might expect, especially for the side that has this Significator.','Side'=>'A side marked by the Forest will be isolated from the other sides, occasionally physically removed entirely and sometimes suffer only External Embodiments from the other sides, all these interactions increase in Stake by at least one step.','Character'=>'The Forest Significator indicates a Character who is uncomfortable in normal society.<p>They <strong>Gain Yin</strong> when they are silent or alone. </p><p><strong>Gain Yang</strong> when they walk away, leave the path, or sniff the air. </p><p>They <strong>Gain Chi</strong> when they enjoy the elements directly upon their body, wind in their hair, sun on their face. </p><p>They also gain a +1 Success Level when in the shadows of trees.</p>','Scene'=>'The Forest Scenes are set deep in the wilds of the world, far from normal civilisations. These are the settings for Ordeals, Tests and Quests or quiet, but deeply personal Revelations. Yarn-Tellers may use The Forest in an urban environment to signify urban jungle, with its own predators and prey.'],'Beat_Type'=>'5', 'Conflict_Embodiment'=>'3', 'Facet_Embodiment'=>'15', 'Hook_Aspect'=>'Core', 'Aspect_Description'=>'The Hook targets the Character\'s Core, the Facet(s) that Characters think of as the essence of themselves. ','Hook'=>'Witch\'s Cottage', 'Hook_Description'=>'Traditionally the Witch\'s Cottage is a run down shack hidden in the woods. It is thought that no one lives there any more, at least until the first child went missing. The Conflict begins with a missing child, or a strange ruin found of the beaten path.', 'Gain'=>'Serenity, the Character finds a small Location where they can relax and meditate. This Location can help them to rest and recover more quickly from stress and negative effects.', 'Fray'=>'Forced March', 'Fray_Description'=>'Usually a Medium Stakes Solitary Motional Ordeal, like hurrying to catch the bus, racing to the airport, getting the shopping done before the dinner party, or getting an army through the Forest before nightfall. A Forced March Ordeal usually involves an Obstacle or two.', 'Snag'=>'Dangerous Shadows', 'Snag_Description'=>'It is dark in the forest and difficult to see what is going on. Dangers lurk in the Shadows as well, from thorns and brambles that catch and scratch to the Big Bad Wolf. Even lighting fires for light will quickly increase the danger as a forest fire blazes around you. The Snag can either add additional Obstacles, darkness, dangerous conditions and/or enemies, to the Fray, and raise the Stakes; or it creates a second short Higher Stakes Ordeal immediately after it.','NPC'=>array('Archetype'=>'Woodsman','Persona'=>16,'Core'=>18,'Hitch'=>15,'Description'=>'The Woodsman is a forest worker or hunter, commonly found with an axe and a bow, or in modern times a chainsaw and perhaps a shotgun or rifle. The Woodsman usually has a family to support and is eager to return to them with food or having earned money working in the woods. They always have wilderness survival skills and often a high Craft.'),'Sweeping'=>'The Enchanted Forest','Sweeping_Text'=>'The Enchanted Forest is a place of transformation. The Character that enters the Enchanted Forest has no pressing need to act, they may eat, drink, heal, rest and relax. Magic lies in the Enchanted Forest and the Character may return having had a Revelation, or having made a Gain, as well as having healed.', 'History'=>'Backwoods','History_Description'=>'The Forest indicates the past of this situation was a place far from civilisation, it may be a literal backwoods location that is important, but more likely this indicates that the situation derives from a past natural event or disaster, such as an autumnal landslide that causes the river to divert or dam up in the spring, causing a terrible harvest in the countryside and creating a flour buying panic in the city come winter.', 'Situation'=>'Darkness', 'Situation_Description'=>'The Forest is dark and full of unknown terrors, so too is the current situation. It is difficult to see in the forest and hard to make out both predators and prey, even when they are almost on top of you. Information is sparse and will remain so for some time.','Solution'=>'Wandering','Solution_Description'=>'The Forest indicates that the solution to the current situation requires wandering, usually in the form of walking, hiking, marching or trekking, often through a wilderness of some sort. This is usually a purely physical trek, but occasionally it may have a spirit-quest or pilgrimage element to the journey.'), //5
		array('Yarn_Name'=>'The Sun','Yarn_Description'=>'The Card of light, warmth and hope. But one should also be aware that light can blind, warmth can burn and hope can be false. While everything about this card is direct and to the point, just as the sun appears to move straight across the sky, this is not the actual truth and things appear to change, as we see them in different lights.','Significator'=>['Plot'=>'The Sun Plot is about Hope. It offers hope to the hopeless, a new hope to the downtrodden, and reversals of fortunes. Of course, the truth is that for every hope that the Sun grants, another must be dashed. For every plant that grows in the light, another is scorched and dies of dehydration, because it would have preferred the shade. ','Side'=>'The Side that has the Sun on their side has been marked as being powerful and important. They are on the rise, growing in power, and are not tested as strongly by the Plot as other sides. However, if they do fail, failure will be especially harsh to them, and may see Deaths and Destruction.','Character'=>'The Sun Significator indicates a Character who <strong>Gains Yin</strong> when they are warm and pleasant.<p><strong>Gains Yang</strong> when they are blunt or harsh.</p>They <strong>Gain Chi</strong> when they give people hope or inspire them.</p><p>They also gain +1 Success Level when they are stood in sunshine.</p>','Scene'=>'The Sun Scenes are generally outdoors, often fun involving sun, sea and sand at the beach, but occasionally tortuous, sun, sand and no water to see, desert scenes. The sand is completely optional. Sun Scenes are usually Ordeals, but may be Tests with a Gain or Revelations, and are often just rests (or Wefts). Yarn-Tellers can decide if the Sun is harmful (sun burn, sun stroke and heat exhaustion) or helpful (restful, fun, pleasant weather) during play.'],'Beat_Type'=>'6', 'Conflict_Embodiment'=>'1', 'Facet_Embodiment'=>'1', 'Hook_Aspect'=>'Geometry (Yin)', 'Aspect_Description'=>'The Hook targets the Character\'s Geometry Yin Gain, whatever is required to gain Yin will be offered by the Hook.','Hook'=>'Dawn Chorus', 'Hook_Description'=>'The story hooks the character with a morning messenger (or other media such as the morning newspaper or update) bearing important news. It may be news that a friend is ill, or that the enemy is closing in, or that you have won a lottery. Regardless, this begins the Conflict with a Gain or Revelation.', 'Gain'=>'Gold and Gems (Yarn Gain)', 'Fray'=>'Burning Sun', 'Fray_Description'=>'A High Stakes Solitary Motional Ordeal, where you must survive a dangerous situation, travel and often accomplish other tasks along the way, it might be as simple as making it back to the oasis after your camel was bitten by a snake, or it could be dashing through rush hour traffic to deliver pizzas when a shoot-out takes place. There are usually Obstacles involved and occasionally Traps.', 'Snag'=>'Changing Light', 'Snag_Description'=>'Although the Characters may have achieved whatever was required, it is no longer enough, or they misunderstood what they were looking at. Changes to orders, Rule changes, Late entries, Disqualifications, Reinforcements, or even moving the goalposts on the Pressed side can all be caused by Changing Light. Often the changing light is the fault of the Dominant Embodiment, other times it just happens. The Snag may act as a Revelation, but what <em>exactly</em> was revealed by the Changing Light?','NPC'=>array('Archetype'=>'Nerd','Persona'=>23,'Core'=>18,'Hitch'=>17, 'Description'=>'The Nerd has some subject, genre, or technology that obsesses them. There\'s nothing they love more than to talk about or consume their "books / shows". '),'Sweeping'=>'Basking','Sweeping_Text'=>'The Pressed side experiences the warmth and glory of the Sun, and gets to bask in it. The Basking Character usually makes a Gain as they are rewarded, and appreciated for what happened in the Fray.', 'History'=>'Good-times','History_Description'=>'The Sun indicates here that in the past there was a time and place of great joy and hope.', 'Situation'=>'Hope', 'Situation_Description'=>'The Sun here indicates a good situation, this is usually not a situation that you want to change, you want to enjoy it. Of course, such a pleasant situation will never last.','Solution'=>'Hope','Solution_Description'=>'The Sun tells us that no matter how dark things seem right now (and they do seem bad) this will pass. The light will always return, the sun will always rise again.'), //6
		array('Yarn_Name'=>'The Drive','Yarn_Description'=>'The card of vehicles, engines and powerful motivations. The Drive is about speed, motion and pressing forwards, regardless of dangers or costs. Sometimes these motivations to move are internal to a Character, and they may be driven by Faith or Doubts, other times they are external, being driven on by some force beyond their control.','Significator'=>['Plot'=>'The Drive Plot is usually a journey or odyssey. Sometimes the Vehicle is important, becoming a Character (often a Rival), other times it is barely mentioned. The Journey though is always more important than the destination. ','Side'=>'Drive Plots can affect individual sides of a Conflict, forcing them to move to find what they seek, or indicate that they have drive and will get closer to what they are working towards.','Character'=>'The Drive Significator indicates a Character who loves to drive (or pilot).<p>They <strong>Gain Yin</strong> when they talk about vehicles, motors, engines, riding animals. </p><p><strong>Gain Yang</strong> when they look after, or maintain a vehicle or riding animal. </p><p><strong>Gain Chi</strong> when they drive or ride a vehicle or riding animal. </p><p>They also gain a +1 Success Level when they are driving a vehicle or riding a riding animal.</p>','Scene'=>'The Drive Scene is usually a car chase or race Ordeal, but it could be a quiet drive in the countryside, or a quick flit on a plane somewhere. Travel by vehicle is suggested and usually with a soupçon of action and danger.'],'Beat_Type'=>'7', 'Conflict_Embodiment'=>'3', 'Facet_Embodiment'=>'10', 'Hook_Aspect'=>'Geometry (Yang)', 'Aspect_Description'=>'The Hook targets the Character\'s Geometry Yang Gain, whatever is required to make a Yang Gain is offered by the Hook.','Hook'=>'Action', 'Hook_Description'=>'The Conflict opens with Action, usually a Motional Ordeal like a Car Chase, or Race.', 'Gain'=>'A Vehicle (A Vehicle Descendant) whether it is a run-down pick-up truck, a luxury yacht, or a Void-runner Space-liner.', 'Fray'=>'Furiously Fast', 'Fray_Description'=>'An Opposed Motional Ordeal, usually of High or Extreme Stakes. This is usually a car chase or race (although it may be a Flee! situation). There are ample opportunities for Stunts and Obstacles during this Ordeal and all drivers are expected to complete them.', 'Snag'=>'Collision', 'Snag_Description'=>'There is a traffic accident, or crash. Maybe someone runs into the PCs or they barrel into someone else. Either way Draw 5 Ordeal Cards and apply one each to each Driver, their Vehicles, and one for any bystanders/passengers (that usually Splashes). These Wounds may be soaked by safety systems and the Characters armour/Incarna as appropriate. If no vehicles are involved then you may Draw 3 and play one card on each \'Driver\' who in this case is just running.','NPC'=>array('Archetype'=>'Jockey','Persona'=>23,'Core'=>14,'Hitch'=>20,'Description'=>'The Jockey is a professional vehicle or riding animal fan. They love the things they drive and ride, spending hours cleaning, grooming, tweaking, and modifying their rides. They drive (or ride) the vehicles (or animals) they love for a living, whether trucks, jet-fighters or thoroughbred horses.'),'Sweeping'=>'Get a Ride','Sweeping_Text'=>'When a Character needs to travel a long way, they can get a ride, and arrive fresh and rested in a new location. Getting a Ride will sometimes result in a Gain or Revelation, but is mostly about travel and rest.', 'History'=>'Driven','History_Description'=>'The Drive indicates that either vehicular travel or some powerful motivations lie in the past of the situation. Did someone travel from far away in the past? Or has someone been driven to create this situation?', 'Situation'=>'Careen', 'Situation_Description'=>'The Drive indicates a situation that is careening out of control, it may be right on the verge of disaster. Often this is a case of the characters not paying proper attention to the situation.','Solution'=>'Steer','Solution_Description'=>'The Drive indicates that the way out of the current situation is to take control of the situation and guide it towards a different destination than it may have been headed, or at least to ease on the brakes so everything doesn\'t fly off the rails.'), //7
		array('Yarn_Name'=>'The Cultist','Yarn_Description'=>'The Cultist is the card of the dark sides of belief and belonging. Everyone holds at least one belief that another would find dark, extremist, or just plain weird. Sometimes it is a religious belief, sometimes its just your weird head-cannon to tie the classic series to the reboot directly. This is the card that shows us those parts of a character. It asks questions of them, such as: What do they really believe? Do they identify more with a Villain or Hero? What is their inner darkness? How far will they go? What lines will they never cross? and exactly how bad was that last instalment/season?','Significator'=>['Plot'=>'The Cultist Plot is about conspiracies and Characters who are not what they first seem. There may be a secret cult, or a hidden group that is manipulating the situation. The Cultist Plot will often rely on occult details or supernatural effects in some genres, in others it may be a conspiracy of silence that is to blame.','Side'=>'The Side marked by the Cultist are tight-knit, and secretive, they try their best to hide their connections and actions from everyone else in the Plot, and are often discovered only by Revelations.','Character'=>'The Cultist Significator indicates a Character who has odd, often dark, beliefs.<p>They <strong>Gain Yin</strong> when they keep secrets, or make indirect references to their beliefs. </p><p><strong>Gain Yang</strong> when they lie about their actions, or reveal some aspect of their belief (swear by a weird god or saint). </p><p>They <strong>Gain Chi</strong> when they practice their religion, or belief alone, or share it with others. </p><p>They gain a +1 Success Level to all actions to do with the beliefs and lore of their Cult.</p>','Scene'=>'The Cultist Scene typically is a religious or psychological based Warp or Weft. Yarn-Tellers can use the Cultist to imply hidden forces, occult influences or just a strange person.'],'Beat_Type'=>'6', 'Conflict_Embodiment'=>'0', 'Facet_Embodiment'=>'1', 'Hook_Aspect'=>'Geometry (Nemesis)', 'Aspect_Description'=>'The Hook targets the Character\'s Geometry through the Harmonic Nemesis, creating another Character who this Character will naturally hate.','Hook'=>'Craze', 'Hook_Description'=>'The Conflict hooks Characters with a new craze, fad or fashion that is related to the Conflict. Kids and young adults are often the early adopters of the new craze, but the fad may be more cultish. in extreme examples the Dominant Embodiment will have this fad cult based around themselves.', 'Gain'=>'Fan Club (a group of Chorus Allies who are "fans" of the Character', 'Fray'=>'Persuasion', 'Fray_Description'=>'The Fray consists of trying to persuade someone (a group of potential allies, a mentor or guardian, an Opposed Embodiment, or any Rival) to your point of view. Persuasion is either a Sub-Ordeal conversation, a Zeal vs Personality Test, or a Low / Soul Stakes Ordeal, depending how the Yarn-Teller wants to run it. Of course matters may be complicated if you are trying to convince a braying mob of your innocence, and the ultimate goal of the Cultist is always to try and persuade another to join the same cult.', 'Snag'=>'Kidnapped', 'Snag_Description'=>'One of the Embodiment\'s allies, friends or family, goes missing and needs saving. Usually they have been kidnapped by Mooks(Vex/Chorus/Cast Extras) working for the Opposed Embodiment.','NPC'=>array('Archetype'=>'Fan','Persona'=>23,'Core'=>18,'Hitch'=>15, 'Description'=>'The Fan has some subject, genre, or technology that obsesses them. There\'s nothing they love more than to talk about or consume their "books / shows". Sometimes divided into cultists, fanboys, and fangirls, these people are naturally drawn to groups of similar minded people.'),'Sweeping'=>'Worshipped','Sweeping_Text'=>'The Pressed Embodiment Gains a following, usually represented as a Group Descendant, the following is normally Chorus and Cast Extras.', 'History'=>'Beliefs','History_Description'=>'The Cultist indicates that the history of this situation is to do with dark or dangerous beliefs, it may be some old pagan beliefs or some crazy modern conspiracy theory.', 'Situation'=>'Conspiracy', 'Situation_Description'=>'The Cultist indicates that the current situation involves a conspiracy, they may operate in secret, perhaps use magic or forbidden technology and may even pretend that they are all one individual.','Solution'=>'Occult','Solution_Description'=>'The Cultist indicates that the situation is best relieved by judicious use of occult knowledge, this might be knowledge of a forgotten religion, understanding of tarot, astrology, herbalism, alchemy, hermeticism, or just magic.'), //8
		array('Yarn_Name'=>'The Priest','Yarn_Description'=>'The Priest is the card of the mortal and divine interacting. This can be literally a Priest (or other religious figure), or it can be some interaction that seems charged by divinity, ethics or morality, one of those times when the universe seems to be teaching us a lesson. These lessons are usually some allegory for an aspect of a religion, or a universal deity of some sort, but can be humanistic lessons such as "Don\'t be a Dick.". These Lessons often involve loss, anguish and difficult ethical and moral choices — one could easily interpret the card as the death of a loved one, for example.','Significator'=>['Plot'=>'The Priest Plot is a Plot where the sacred and profane are both important. The worlds of mortal and divine mix and interfere. Often the Plot will centre around a hallowed character (such as a Priest, Monk, Nun, Priestess, etc). ','Side'=>'If a side of a larger Conflict is marked by the Priest then that side will generally act as a go between or messenger between two of the other sides.','Character'=>'The Priest Significator indicates a Character who has a strong, personal connection to the divine. <p>They <strong>Gain Yin</strong> by prayer or meditation.</p><p><strong>Gain Yang</strong> by sharing stories or parables from their religion, and drawing comparisons between their current situation and those from their religious texts. </p><p>They <strong>Gain Chi</strong> when they perform religious rituals or demonstrate divine or spiritual powers or prowess. </p><p>They also gain +1 Success Level to do with all aspects of their religion or spirituality</p>','Scene'=>'The Priest Scene is a scene with religious or divine importance. A Yarn-Teller may use it to allow divine intervention, a resurrection or miracle of a higher order, or the Scene may concentrate on the profane, mundane activities that many of the Priesthood (or more usually Monks) must do, such as cleaning, working, meditation, gardening, farming beneath the guise of religious duty or faith.'],'Beat_Type'=>'7', 'Conflict_Embodiment'=>'1', 'Facet_Embodiment'=>'3', 'Hook_Aspect'=>'Geometry (Gift)', 'Aspect_Description'=>'The Hook targets the Character\'s Geometry via its gift. This is often a chance to create a situation where the gift will be useful.','Hook'=>'A Prayer', 'Hook_Description'=>'The Hook of this Story is nothing more than a cry for help, an overheard prayer, confession or scream calls the PC to action. To Hook some Characters it is necessary to allow the Prayer to intrigue, or tempt the Character into action rather than directly ask them for help.', 'Gain'=>'Parish, the Parish is an area or territory that a priest is made responsible for. An actual Parish is a Real Estate or Province held by the Church and wardened by a Priest. (Gain Large Location)', 'Fray'=>'Shepherd', 'Fray_Description'=>'A usually Medium-Soul Stakes Ordeal that involves guiding, teaching and protecting a "<em>flock</em>" of animals or people. This can be as simple as leading goats to pasture, sitting with a dying person, or as complex as herding cats, or calming and consoling parents after a sectarian attack on a primary school.','Snag'=>'Humanitarian Crisis', 'Snag_Description'=>'Often this Snag is about the aftermath of the Fray, but sometimes it is part of the Fray. It involves a threat to the well-being of entire communities. Plagues, famines, droughts and wars are common causes of a crisis, as are other natural disasters.','NPC'=>array('Archetype'=>'Martyr','Persona'=>23,'Core'=>12,'Hitch'=>3,'Description'=>'A Martyr is a fanatic dedicated to their cause who is willing to die (or at least get badly injured) for their beliefs.'),'Sweeping'=>'Sacred Treasure','Sweeping_Text'=>'The Pressed Embodiment gains a Sacred Treasure of some sort. It should be noted that Sacredness is recognised differently by different people, for some sports or film memorabilia can be sacred, for others only divine artefacts are truly sacred.', 'History'=>'Mystic','History_Description'=>'The Priest indicates that the history of this situation is one where the sacred, divine or spirit world has become involved with the profane normal world. This may have been a ritual, ceremony, the past situation may involve some hallowed ground, spiritual relic, prophecy or scripture.', 'Situation'=>'Sanctified', 'Situation_Description'=>'The Priest indicates a situation where divine or spiritual power is expressed. This may be a case of an actual miracle, or simply a case of blessings being bestowed or even withheld.','Solution'=>'Intervention','Solution_Description'=>'The Priest indicates that the way out of this situation is going to require intervention from the spiritual or religious world. This can be a quiet word from a member of the clergy or a divine miracle.'), //9
		array('Yarn_Name'=>'The Loner','Yarn_Description'=>'The Loner is the card of someone who while they may appear to succeed in some aspects of life, they are often failing in others. They may be rich, but lonely, or have many friends, but no true love. They may not feel they lack anything, and are content, but still are pitied by others. Then again the loner may seek solitude, moving far from home (to a new location), or driving others away for their own safety, as they know that what they undertake is not safe for others to assist. It is a card of collateral damage, Pyrrhic victories and great costs, but also huge rewards, if potential dangers are limited by careful planning.','Significator'=>['Plot'=>'The Loner Plot is unique and unconnected to other Plots and events. It is a one off, freak Plot, that may centre around an unusual individual (less often a small group).  The Character is usually socially awkward or even socio — or psychopathic in nature. Loner plots are light on Revelations, and almost always leave open questions behind them (such as what was that about? Who was that guy?). ','Side'=>'Sides of a plot marked by the Loner are not actually a side so much as a collection of individuals, they share no common goals, and may even be separate Sides effectively.','Character'=>'The Loner Significator indicates a Character who does not really enjoy the company of others.<p><strong>Gain Yin</strong> when you are alone. </p><p><strong>Gain Yang</strong> when you ignore others, or try to drive others away. </p><p><strong>Gain Chi</strong> when you move away from others, or they move away from you. </p><p>They also gain +1 Success Level when acting on their own, or without backup.</p>','Scene'=>'The Loner Scene is about isolation. A Yarn-Teller may play it to isolate Characters from each other, to drive wedges between them, or to simply separate them for a time.'],'Beat_Type'=>'8', 'Conflict_Embodiment'=>'2', 'Facet_Embodiment'=>'2', 'Hook_Aspect'=>'Geometry (Chi)', 'Aspect_Description'=>'The Hook targets the Character\'s Geometry particularly their Chi Gain offering them an easy source of Geometry Chi.','Hook'=>'Help!', 'Hook_Description'=>'The Hook is a direct call to help from someone (usually at least a Cast Extra) known to the Character often an Ally or Friend. The person calling for help usually believes (typically with good reason) that only the Character will help.', 'Gain'=>'Riches (Talent Treasure Descendant)', 'Fray'=>'Lone Wolf', 'Fray_Description'=>'A Complex Ordeal for a single Character (or small group), where as well as trying to get through enemy territory (and accomplish some goal beyond survival), the Character will also be fighting a spread out, but vastly numerically superior force. Individual enemies may be weaker or similar in power level to Lone Wolf Character. The fight may be limited to Medium Stakes in some cases (such as during training exercises, or in cultures where firearms and blades are unfashionable), but is usually High, or Extreme Stakes.', 'Snag'=>'Pyrrhic Victory', 'Snag_Description'=>'After the Fray, the Embodiment should realise the cost of the battle was too high. Maybe there are too many dead on their side, too many dead on the other — maybe seeing a Cast/Chorus Extra from an earlier scene, now lying dead. There is always collateral damage, so even if everyone is alive, their ancestral home is collapsing in flames behind them.','NPC'=>array('Archetype'=>'Miser','Persona'=>16,'Core'=>2,'Hitch'=>10,'Description'=>'The Miser is a lonely figure that loves their money more than any person in their life. They are usually quite rich, but do not like spending their money (which is often why they have so much).'),'Sweeping'=>'Independence','Sweeping_Text'=>'The Pressed Embodiment achieves some amount of independence in comparison to before. This may mean they move out of a guardian\'s home (gain Location), get a new job (gain Wages Treasure Descendant), it may also represent the Resolution of a Dependence Hitch.', 'History'=>'Isolation','History_Description'=>'The Loner indicates that the current situation is rooted in past problems of isolation, but this isolation has now come to an end. A character who was isolated, imprisoned, or exiled by a corrupt lord now seeks revenge, or a location or knowledge that was isolated, and unknown, is discovered and made public, bringing this new problem.', 'Situation'=>'Abandoned', 'Situation_Description'=>'The Loner indicates that the current situation has been caused by a character, location, vehicle or object being abandoned, deserted or discarded. Where previously they had companionship they are now alone, where they had life only ghosts remain, or where once they were treasured, now they are forgotten and in disrepair.','Solution'=>'Alone','Solution_Description'=>'The Loner indicates that there is a route out of the current situation, but it is a path that can only be walked by a single person. Sometimes this means abandoning your companions to succeed, other times it means scattering so as to not draw attention together.'), //10
		array('Yarn_Name'=>'The Teacher','Yarn_Description'=>'The Teacher card represents not just teachers, but schools in general, and the Teachings that the Teacher gives. The Teacher represents patience and courtesy, but is also a taskmaster, that demands you demonstrate what you have learnt.','Significator'=>['Plot'=>'The Teacher Plot seeks to educate and elucidate, sometimes teaching only one side, other times teaching all sides. The lesson may be through the use of metaphor or allegory, more often it is a little more direct. These Plots are based around facts and truisms, often of a religious or moral nature, occasionally of a scientific or spiritual one. The Teacher Plot is also about testing if the student is ready, and rites of passage in general will feature strongly in these tales. ','Side'=>'When one side is marked by the Teacher they are usually tasked with teaching a lesson to another side, often this may be a lesson about humility, but almost any lesson will do.','Character'=>'The Teacher Significator indicates a Character who is a teacher.<p>They <strong>Gain Yin</strong> when they ask a question or confirm an answer. </p><p><strong>Gain Yang</strong> when they explain, or answer a question. </p><p>They <strong>Gain Chi</strong> when they set tasks, or someone else asks a question.</p><p>They also gain +1 Success Level on any action to do with what they teach.</p>','Scene'=>'The Teacher Scene is nothing but a learning moment. A Yarn-Teller can use the card to teach another, or to learn themselves, information will be shared and retained.'],'Beat_Type'=>'4', 'Conflict_Embodiment'=>'1', 'Facet_Embodiment'=>'2', 'Hook_Aspect'=>'Geometry (Perfect)', 'Aspect_Description'=>'The Hook targets the Character\'s Geometry through the Perfect Harmonic. This is a "Perfect" Character for this one, perhaps a lover, friend, mentor or guide, offered up by the plot as part of the Hook.','Hook'=>'Exposition', 'Hook_Description'=>'The Story opens with exposition, this may be "incluing" where hints about the world are scattered about the text, or more normally with this card, direct narration that describes the setting. This is usually exposition done by a figure of authority, such as a teacher or politician, reciting the information for the PCs and audience.', 'Gain'=>'Mentor Ally, Learning Descendant, Annex Training or Proficiencies','Fray'=>'Study', 'Fray_Description'=>'The Study Ordeal consists of studying, researching, experimentation, and perhaps learning. It might be a Teaching Moment in a classroom, a meticulously planned and executed heist, a science experiment or sitting the bar exam. It may even lead to a scientific discovery, or similar paradigm changing moment.','Snag'=>'Disruptive', 'Snag_Description'=>'The Embodiment\'s plans, Descendants, or allies are damaged, or interrupted by disruptive forces. Like the child that behaves inappropriately the moment the teacher\'s back is turned, there is a disruptive force present that complicates all of the PCs plans, not necessarily out of opposition, but as often boredom, or ignorance.','NPC'=>array('Archetype'=>'Professor','Persona'=>14,'Core'=>14,'Hitch'=>12,'Description'=>'The Professor is an educator, always teaching and explaining. Of course, they don\'t always agree with the latest theories, but anything thirty years old or more is usually accepted.'),'Sweeping'=>'Mentor Ally','Sweeping_Text'=>'The Pressed side Gains an Ally who will act as a Trainer, Coach, or Mentor. This leads to additional Trained and Learning Descendants', 'History'=>'School-Days','History_Description'=>'The Teacher indicates that the past of this situation goes all the way back to when the characters were being educated. This can mean a call back to something learnt in school, or that this situation has roots in the characters school-days.', 'Situation'=>'Examination', 'Situation_Description'=>'The Teacher indicates the current situation is similar to a formal examination, this doesn\'t necessarily mean a written exam, but the character is being tested somehow. Such tests can be about trust, honourableness, worthiness, character or ability as well as academic knowledge.','Solution'=>'Teaching','Solution_Description'=>'The Teacher indicates that the solution to this problem is not learning some new skill or knowledge, but sharing the knowledge and skills you have with others, this will enable them to learn to feed, defend and improve themselves in the future.'), //J
		array('Yarn_Name'=>'The Forge','Yarn_Description'=>'The Forge is the card of the workshop, or factory. It is a magical place, a womb of creation, where earth, air, water and fire are combined to create new objects like swords. The Forge is a place of sweat and hard work, but offers great rewards for this work.','Significator'=>['Plot'=>'The Forge Plot is a construction or creation plot. It is normal for such plots to be solely about the creation of a new technology or prototype, although there are always politics, market forces and other factors that revolves around a creation plot like this. ','Side'=>'The Forge is often useful as a Side Significator indicating that the side marked is trying to create something (or has created something).','Character'=>'The Forge Significator indicates a Character who is most likely a Smith or Artist. The card makes them even more so... <p>They <strong>Gain Yin</strong> by gathering resources, ores, fuel, and materials. </p><p>They <strong>Gain Yang</strong> by planning, drawing, and designing, writing notes on papers, preparing resources, etc. </p><p>They <strong>Gain Chi</strong> by creating Descendants (helping to pay off some of the costs of the Creation). </p><p>They also gain a +1 Success Level when they are creating.</p>','Scene'=>'The Forge Scene is often used for Descendant Creation (or shopping). A Yarn-Teller can play the Forge to allow themselves an Item Creation or Shopping Ordeal/Test or a Descendant Gain, they can also be used for personal Revelations by artist and craftsman Characters, as they work in their workshop.'],'Beat_Type'=>'5', 'Conflict_Embodiment'=>'3', 'Facet_Embodiment'=>'13', 'Hook_Aspect'=>'Geometry (Yang)', 'Aspect_Description'=>'The Hook targets the Character\'s Geometry specifically how they generate Yang and creates a situation that allows them to generate Yang this way.','Hook'=>'Loss', 'Hook_Description'=>'The Hook for the Character is a loss of something that can be replaced. Perhaps they have broken their sword, or their base is burnt down. The Conflict may drive them to replace this loss, or it may be part of a Villain\'s plan.', 'Gain'=>'Temporal, Material and Economic Power (Power Descendant)', 'Fray'=>'Creativity', 'Fray_Description'=>'The Ordeal is about the Character acquiring a Descendant. Maybe they go shopping and hunt around for a deal, but usually they make one themselves (or summon one magically, perhaps). The point is that they have to beat a Summoning / Creation difficulty somehow.',  'Snag'=>'Requirements', 'Snag_Description'=>'Either during the Fray or after it, the PCs will discover that they require something that they do not have. It might be an ingredient, or component, a specific person or piece of information. The point is, they cannot succeed without this thing.','NPC'=>array('Archetype'=>'Alchemist','Persona'=>2,'Core'=>11,'Hitch'=>3,'Description'=>'The Alchemist, also known as the Mad Scientist or Inventor likes to Craft new things, but they are not always as useful as the Alchemist thinks they will be.'),'Sweeping'=>'Upgrade','Sweeping_Text'=>'The PC improves or replaces a Descendant with an improved version, additional Nimbeds or Umbrals may be added to make the Descendant more powerful.', 'History'=>'Creation','History_Description'=>'The Forge indicates that the current situation has its roots in a past of creation. Often some object or treasure was created in the past, a sword of kings forged and placed within a stone, or a ring of power, for example, but sometimes it is about the creation of a location or pact.', 'Situation'=>'Working', 'Situation_Description'=>'The Forge indicates that currently the character is working steadily towards their goals. The work is usually hard, complex, and slow-going but they still feel productive.','Solution'=>'Innovation','Solution_Description'=>'The Forge indicates that the solution to the current situation is some innovation, perhaps a new strategy, tactic, contraption, device, weapon, spell, technology, gambit, or gimmick that can be used to save the day. Often this is a new application of an old idea, such as using trebuchets which were designed to lob stones and break walls down, to launch dead animals into a city over the walls, or barrels of flaming pitch instead.'), //Q
		array('Yarn_Name'=>'The Star','Yarn_Description'=>'The Star represents the pinnacle of success, the height of fame. It is the card of glory, excesses and undreamt of achievements, but it is also the card of jealousy, betrayals and rock and roll suicides. The Star may burn bright, but ultimately the night is dark.','Significator'=>['Plot'=>'The Star Plot is mostly about darkness, it may be the darkness in people, or the darkness of space, the cave or night. Darkness is danger, which surrounds the Star, or the Characters in this Plot. The Plot may tempt all Hooked Characters with Glory, Success and/or Fame, making them important heroes (or villains) that will shine brightly in the dangerous darkness. ','Side'=>'The Side marked with the Star believes they are ascendant, but they are surrounded by darkness. The Star marked side will gain fame, and success, but the cost is that all other sides become at least loosely allied with the Shadows (or External in the case of a Shadow Side with a Star) Side','Character'=>'The Star Significator indicates a Character who believes themselves to a Star. </p><p>They <strong>Gain Yin</strong> when they are praised or others do things for them. </p><p>They <strong>Gain Yang</strong> when they perform or practise. </p><p>They <strong>Gain Chi</strong> when they affect another with a Psyche Attack (positive or negative).</p>','Scene'=>'The Star Scene is one that focuses on a single Character for all of the Scene. The Character may have to face opponents, Ordeals or Tests alone, without their usual allies and friends. Yarn-Tellers can play this card to get themselves some one on one Referee time, or to focus that attention elsewhere...'],'Beat_Type'=>'9', 'Conflict_Embodiment'=>'1', 'Facet_Embodiment'=>'3', 'Hook_Aspect'=>'Geometry (Goal)', 'Aspect_Description'=>'The Hook targets the Character\'s Geometry via their Goal, offering them what they want.','Hook'=>'Danger', 'Hook_Description'=>'The Hook just consists of some enormous danger, it may be looming, it may be coming, or it is right here, right now. The Hook may include a Revelation and/or a High-Stakes Ordeal.', 'Gain'=>'Stardom brings great wealth and recognition. Mansions, cars, space-yachts, all are available, with only one or two Hitches (usually Exposed and Dependence Hitches).', 'Fray'=>'Wish', 'Fray_Description'=>'The Fray consists of a Quest, usually to accomplish something personally important to the Character.', 'Snag'=>'A New Star Rises', 'Snag_Description'=>'An new Facet Embodiment appears, which destabilises the situation against the PCs, often making them work with Rivals or even former enemies. This could be a separate Facet joining the Conflict (or popping in from another usually larger Plot) or just another, stronger Embodiment of the Dominant side of this Conflict, such as when Guard and a Gladiator who have clashed on the battlefield before, join forces to fight a Dragon that threatens both armies.','NPC'=>array('Archetype'=>'Star','Persona'=>0,'Core'=>0,'Hitch'=>9,'Description'=>'The Star is not just famous, they are at the pinnacle of their profession. They may not be as talented as some others in their field, but are famous outside of it.'),'Sweeping'=>'Darkness','Sweeping_Text'=>'The PC makes a powerful gain, but of a dark and terrible nature, such as a Dark Matter Descendant, Dark Territory, Demonic Pact, or a Monster Ally.', 'History'=>'Glory','History_Description'=>'The Star indicates that this situation is based on past glories. These may be the glories of a character, or part of a national history, but the point is that pinnacle for the character or society has long passed.', 'Situation'=>'Betrayal', 'Situation_Description'=>'The Star indicates that situation is a betrayal of some kind. This betrayal may be a case of an unfaithful lover, reprehensible retailers, snitching subordinates, treasonous underlings, tattling ex-lovers, or treachery, but is often caused by jealousy of the character\'s perceived success, wealth, fame, rank or position.','Solution'=>'Lodestar','Solution_Description'=>'The Star indicates that a guide will appear that will lead the characters out of this situation. This guide can take the form of a leader, often from among the characters, or some external sign or portent that will lead the way. The difficulty for those in this situation is knowing which sign, guide or portent is the true lodestar and which are not.'), //K
		//hearts
		array('Yarn_Name'=>'The Lovers','Yarn_Description'=>'The Lovers card represents the forces of romance and love, and the tough choices that they bring. As a force, Love is usually seen as positive, building and holding together families even through the most trying times, but love can also be destructive. The torrid affairs of untamed hearts ruin families\' lives and destroy homes everyday. These are powerful forces, Soul Stakes that play with people\' hearts. They are not for the faint of heart, but then what romantic is truly a coward?','Significator'=>['Plot'=>'The Lovers Plot is a Romance. These come in a number of types, but usually involve a hero, or heroine, at least one Love Interest, and a number of Love Rivals. Stories may be complicated by multiple Love Interests, or both sides having Love Rivals, or by additional Rivalries beyond love. Romances generally end with marriage, or death, occasionally both. ','Side'=>'The side of a Conflict marked by The Lovers will face a choice (usually between Love Interests, but it may be who to make a friendship or alliance with or whom to attack).','Character'=>'The Lovers Significator indicates a Character who is a Lothario or temptress. <p>They <strong>Gain Yin</strong> by being touched by another Character. </p><p>They <strong>Gain Yang</strong> by flirting, or seducing another Character. </p><p>They <strong>Gain Chi</strong> when they are intimate with others.</p><p>They gain +1 Success Levels with all attempts at flirting, charm, kissing or similar socio-sexual acts.</p>','Scene'=>'The Lovers Scene can represent a romantic (or just sexual) interlude. Yarn-Tellers can play the card and fade to black, if they wish... Alternatively, the Yarn-Teller can use the card to effect profound changes in how they are perceived by those around them. Hate being transformed into Love, or vice versa.'],'Beat_Type'=>'1', 'Conflict_Embodiment'=>'1', 'Facet_Embodiment'=>'15',  'Hook_Aspect'=>'Geometry (Perfect)', 'Aspect_Description'=>'The Hook targets the Character\'s Geometry via their Perfect Harmonic, this may be a soul mate, best friend, lover or just a Perfect business partner.','Hook'=>'Who is That?', 'Hook_Description'=>'The Story opens with a new Character appearing who is of interest to the PC (usually as a friend or potential new love interest).', 'Gain'=>'Monster Lover - A Powerful Ally that even has some Monster Facets.', 'Fray'=>'Test of Love', 'Fray_Description'=>'The Fray is a Test, Ordeal or Quest, usually set by the PC\'s Romantic Interest as a Test of their Love. Such tests can include humiliating yourself, surviving battle, or going against your normal nature, to prove that your have grown as an individual. Tests of Love can also include Quests where the Quest giver is a friend or member of the family.', 'Snag'=>'Love Triangle/Jealousy', 'Snag_Description'=>'The Embodiment\'s love interest (who may be the Opposed Embodiment / a Rival / another PC, etc) and the Embodiment\'s relationship is complicated by a third-party. This may be a Love Rival of the Embodiment, who will try to win the love interest\'s heart, or it may be an alternative love interest, or any variation (the adulterous husband/wife). This Snag can act as a Hook for a Story in its own right to explore the Tension inherent in the Love Triangle. Or perhaps The Character\'s Rival or the Opposition Gains a Romantic Interest. Ideally this should be someone the Character is already interested in, but will otherwise just be someone wonderful. If there is no Romantic sub-plot currently in play, then the Opposition makes an important alliance / treaty that will cause the PCs to become jealous.','NPC'=>array('Archetype'=>'Lover','Persona'=>11,'Core'=>15,'Hitch'=>9,'Description'=>'The Lover, is a hedonist, who is a master of making themselves and others feel good. Lovers are usually beautiful, or at least distinctive looking (or raunchily dressed).'),'Sweeping'=>'Love','Sweeping_Text'=>'The Pressed Embodiment finds love, or a reasonable facsimile there of. This might involve a Gain of an Ally, Romantic Interest, or even a pet. Or it could just be a de-stressing evening in a night club that turned into breakfast.', 'History'=>'Affair','History_Description'=>'The Lovers indicates that this current situation owes something to a often passionate and sometimes illicit affair between at least two of the characters involved in the situation. This often implies past love triangles, flirtatious behaviour, intrigues and attachments which will complicate the current problem.', 'Situation'=>'Choice', 'Situation_Description'=>'The Lovers indicates a serious choice that must be made by the character, often between two potential lovers, or even lives. Often there is little to decide the issue between these choices, they are rarely so clear cut as one is good and one is bad, but rather each has a balance of pros and cons. This choice is intended to be difficult and often permanent.','Solution'=>'Alliance','Solution_Description'=>'The Lovers indicates that the true way out of the current situation is through an alliance (historically secured with a marriage), sometimes between conflicting sides, but more often with a neutral, but powerful third-party.'), //ace
		array('Yarn_Name'=>'The Burn-Out','Yarn_Description'=>'The Burn-Out is the card that represents the lingering embers of the once great. Where once a mighty, powerful fire roared, now there is just smoke and warm ashes. It can represent collapse after a great effort, or a futility in beginning.','Significator'=>['Plot'=>'The Burn-Out Plot is about things from the past, that were once great, but have now fallen apart. It may be a plot about an ancient ruin, or an old civilisation, something about this place, or people, has become relevant again. It is history trying to repeat itself, but trying again in an old palette, not quite updating the story as it might. Perhaps a village is found in the Italian Alps where Latin is still spoken, aliens appear over Stonehenge, or an old tired king, longs to relive his glory years. ','Side'=>'A side marked by the Burn-Out is a side that has seen better times, they may be old, or infirm from illness, or in the case of obstacles, descendants and so on just a little worn out. Of course, an elderly master, while not at the height of his powers, is no less formidable.','Character'=>'The Burn-Out Significator indicates a Character who was great, powerful or a genius, but is now less.<p>They <strong>Gain Yin</strong> when they mope, don\'t bother getting properly dressed or prepared, or ignore a question. </p><p>They <strong>Gain Yang</strong> when they volunteer information or solutions, help others, or offer food. </p><p>They <strong>Gain Chi</strong> when they freak out about something (usually a Triggered Hitch). </p><p>They also gain a +1 Success Level to any activity that can be done while wearing slippers and either eating cereal or watching video.</p>','Scene'=>'The Burn-Out Scene is usually used for a calm following a disaster. Yarn-Tellers can use it to get a break when they need one, or can use it to ramp up the temperature an pressure on someone, creating a fiery Ordeal or Accident that must be dealt with.'],'Beat_Type'=>'2', 'Conflict_Embodiment'=>'0', 'Facet_Embodiment'=>'5',  'Hook_Aspect'=>'Persona (Shadow)', 'Aspect_Description'=>'The Hook targets the Character\'s Persona specifically via the Shadow of the Persona, which means appealing to the darker nature of the Persona.','Hook'=>'Smoke Signals', 'Hook_Description'=>'There\'s no smoke without fire, people say. So when this Conflict starts rumours and gossip, leaving smoking guns and other clues that point to something being up, you can be sure the PCs will jump to all the wrong conclusions, or if they don\'t someone else will interpret the same signals as the PCs guilt.', 'Gain'=>'Someone\'s (potential Rival, Ally or Opposed Embodiment) contact details', 'Fray'=>'Burn-out', 'Fray_Description'=>'This Fray is an intense Ordeal designed to exhaust the PC to the point of collapse. This may involve staying active for far too long (working night and day for a week), or expending all of your fuel or ammo during the Ordeal. Exactly how the Fray exhausts the Character\' resources will depend on the Character and Situation. Generally speaking the Stakes of the Ordeal are usually Medium or High. It is usual during a Burn-Out for the Plot to use Carnage Wounds (and Carnage+) as defence cards, not attack. Ideally the Ordeal will end with a Fatigue Hitch being triggered.', 'Snag'=>'Futile Pursuit', 'Snag_Description'=>'Regardless of the Fray result, the Snag makes clear that the Fray was a wasted effort. Even though you succeeded, it is a useless success, perhaps you plan the perfect Heist only to discover they emptied the Vault hours before, or you fight your way to the Vampire\'s castle, only to watch it vanish as you reach the walls.','NPC'=>array('Archetype'=>'Burn-out','Persona'=>9,'Core'=>7,'Hitch'=>23,'Description'=>'Burn-Outs are sarcastic and usually pretend to be Sloths, rather than Adventurers say. They would much rather not get involved , if they can help it.'),'Sweeping'=>'Ashes','Sweeping_Text'=>'The Pressed Side has an Test or minor Ordeal that they must deal with. Such as clearing the ash from the Forge after making a sword.' , 'History'=>'Collapse','History_Description'=>'The Burn-Out indicates that the current situation is rooted in a collapse in the past. This might be a mental, emotional, political, social, economic, or structural collapse, but this current situation is fall out from this event.', 'Situation'=>'History', 'Situation_Description'=>'The Burn-Out indicates the current situation is an echo or repeat of some previous event. This may be a case of history literally repeating itself, or it may be a more figurative, with things generally following cycles of growth and collapse.','Solution'=>'Exhaustion','Solution_Description'=>'The Burn-Out indicates that sometimes there is no easy solution to a problem, and that the best we can hope for is the enemy to exhaust themselves somehow, perhaps even getting bored and going home. This situation has no solution, unless you can work out how to wear down the opposition forces, making them expend resources and troops.'), //2
		array('Yarn_Name'=>'The Question','Yarn_Description'=>'The Question card stands for nothing more, or less, than a question. It could be an unspoken question, or a question that is asked over and over again. Sometimes the question will be the same, other times it will be unique. Sometimes the question has an answer, other times it is rhetorical, and just occasionally the answer itself is the question.','Significator'=>['Plot'=>'The Question Plot is at its simplest a Mystery Story, which of course asks an often simple question. Usually the Question is "Whodunnit?", but even then there are hidden questions of "how" and "why" that may have equally satisfying answers. Any Mystery will fit within the Question, from "How do we lift the curse?" through "Where are we" to "how can we make money from it?"','Side'=>'When a side is marked by the Question they will often ask an important question (who is the chosen one? What is the Matrix? Where is the Ark? What will we do? How will we survive? etc) and will also usually be expected to answer questions (often including the one they asked), perhaps as a Revelation or Ordeal.','Character'=>'The Question Significator indicates a Character that asks questions.<p><strong>Gain Yin</strong> when they listen to others speak. </p><p><strong>Gain Yang</strong> when they elicit information from someone without asking a direct question. </p><p>They <strong>Gain Chi</strong> when they ask a question.</p><p>They gain +1 Success Levels whenever they are interrogating or questioning someone.</p>','Scene'=>'The Question Scene is a Scene that has a lot of questions. It might be a pub-quiz or more likely a suspect interrogation. Yarn-Tellers should play this card when they want to make Revelations, or gain information.'],'Beat_Type'=>'3', 'Conflict_Embodiment'=>'0', 'Facet_Embodiment'=>'3',  'Hook_Aspect'=>'Persona (Question)', 'Aspect_Description'=>'The Hook targets the Character\'s Persona, but via a Question based upon this Facet. For example an Idol will be Questioned about their Feelings.','Hook'=>'Question', 'Hook_Description'=>'The Conflict Hooks the Character a question. This Question may be one they ask themselves, "What was that noise?", "Who is at the door?", or it might be a question that they overhear, "How many men have you got for the job?". The Hook may even be a mystery in its own right.', 'Gain'=>'An truthful, honest answer (sometimes the best Gain of all).', 'Fray'=>'Questioning', 'Fray_Description'=>'Questioning can be a terrible Fray. Inquisitions, interrogations, inquiries, examinations. Questioning can be a Low to Soul Stakes Ordeal, or even a simple Facet Test. Usually the PCs are the one\'s questioned, as the Challenge is normally greater that way.', 'Snag'=>'Puzzle', 'Snag_Description'=>'The Snag is a Puzzle, some additional complication. Maybe the Fray is set in a Maze, or having completed the Fray the PCs are now faced with a riddle that must be solved to continue. Perhaps Clues must be deciphered, or the PCs have to unlock a combination lock to open a door, or maybe the door itself is hidden, and the Puzzle is a secret room.','NPC'=>array('Archetype'=>'Inquisitor','Persona'=>4,'Core'=>13,'Hitch'=>7,'Description'=>'The Inquisitor asks questions, and rely on methods of persuasion (such as how their interrogation room / torture chamber is set up), to pressure people into answering.'),'Sweeping'=>'Deeper Questions','Sweeping_Text'=>'The PCs make a Revelation, that reveals more complications and deeper questions for the future.', 'History'=>'Shrouded','History_Description'=>'The Question indicates that the history of this situation is shrouded by the mists of time, there will be mysteries, questions and enigmas that hide the truth.', 'Situation'=>'Query', 'Situation_Description'=>'The Question indicates the current situation involves trying to find an answer to a question, this question may be simple or a complex cross-examination.','Solution'=>'Doubt','Solution_Description'=>'The Question indicates that the solution to this situation must rely on not taking any fact for granted, trust no one, and question everything that you think you know.'), //3
		array('Yarn_Name'=>'The Myth','Yarn_Description'=>'The Myth represents those untruths that can gather a truth of their own. It maybe a simple lie that was believed, a complex misunderstanding, or story told as an allegory or warning, such as the stories of Ginny Greenteeth teach children to avoid water, and the myth of the the Big Bad Wolf teach them to avoid the dark woods.','Significator'=>['Plot'=>'The Myth Plot is a plot that concerns enormous lies and/or ancient legends. The Plot usually utilises ancient stories and myths, but recast within the terms of the current Conflict. This might create a modern version of Arthurian Legend, or Robin Hood, or it might highlight the similarities between the perils of AI and Golems. There is often some aspect of the updated retelling that makes a lie of the original Myth, while retaining some Truth from it (AI is compared to Golems, Pygmalion, Brazen Heads, Talos, Homunculi and Frankenstein\'s Monster, but isn\'t really the same as any of them). ','Side'=>'A side marked with the Myth will either have some huge lie that they have to maintain, or will be a reference to some group from a myth or legend. They may not be Achilles, but they are strong with a hidden weakness, or they may not be Odysseus, but they do have to go on a long trek, and everyone thinks they are dead when they get back.','Character'=>'The Myth Significator indicates a Character who lies easily and fluently.<p>They <strong>Gain Yin</strong> when they bend the truth, or present it in a way that makes it unbelievable. </p><p>They <strong>Gain Yang</strong> when they lie, or "embellish" a story. </p><p>They <strong>Gain Chi</strong> when their (mostly) true stories are disbelieved, or their lies and embellishments are repeated as fact. </p><p>They also gain +1 Success Levels to all actions to do with belief, lies and myths.</p>','Scene'=>'The Myth Scene concerns itself with Misconceptions, Fables and Legends. It may be a Scene where ancient lies are revealed, perhaps a fresh web of lies are woven, or there may be some connection or echo of some heroic tale. Yarn-Tellers may play the card to weave lies, create propaganda, illusions, or fake news to support their position, evoke Mythic themes, or examine deep themes of the Epic\'s or Cycle\'s Conflict.'],'Beat_Type'=>'4', 'Conflict_Embodiment'=>'0', 'Facet_Embodiment'=>'6',  'Hook_Aspect'=>'Persona (Avoid)', 'Aspect_Description'=>'The Hook targets the Character\'s Persona specifically by using what they like to Avoid as a stick, and perhaps offering a Persona Gain as a carrot if that fails.','Hook'=>'Mistake', 'Hook_Description'=>'The story hooks the character with an apparent mistake. A misdelivered parcel, or message, or some other confusion. Often opens a comedy.', 'Gain'=>'A Lore Descendant (as part of a Revelation about themselves)', 'Fray'=>'Legend', 'Fray_Description'=>'The Fray concerns a Legend. Maybe the PCs need to solve an ancient mystery to find a legendary treasure, defeat a legendary Monster, find a legendary place, or otherwise achieve the apparently impossible.', 'Snag'=>'Fable', 'Snag_Description'=>'Either the Fray involves the PCs having to lie for all they\'re worth, or they make a false Revelation. The False Revelation may retcon the last Revelation (making everything learned false) or it can make the next Revelation false, as the Yarn-Teller prefers.','NPC'=>array('Archetype'=>'Fabulist','Persona'=>7,'Core'=>7,'Hitch'=>18,'Description'=>'Fabulists like making things up, sometimes they don\'t even know that they are imagining these things, they might just be hallucinations that bear a passing resemblance to reality. Then again some people are pathological liars, they just can\'t help adjusting the narrative of their life.'),'Sweeping'=>'Myth Revealed','Sweeping_Text'=>'A Lie from earlier is revealed (such as information from an earlier Revelation, or some assumption the PCs made).', 'History'=>'Mythic','History_Description'=>'The Myth indicates that the past situation is based on a legend, folklore, or myth. This may be a huge myth such as Arthurian legends or local folklore.', 'Situation'=>'Untruths', 'Situation_Description'=>'The Myth indicates that the current situation has been caused by misinformation, deceit, conspiracy theories, fake news or just lies.','Solution'=>'Lie','Solution_Description'=>'The Myth indicates that the way out of the current situation is to lie for all you are worth, bluff, misdirect, lie, fake, feign, falsify and forge it until you make it.'), //4
		array('Yarn_Name'=>'The Joke','Yarn_Description'=>'The Joke card represents a funny situation. It may be as simple as a pun, or as complicated as a wildly complex sequence of rational, normal seeming events that leads to an ultimately absurd situation.','Significator'=>['Plot'=>'The Joke Plot is traditionally known as a Comedy. Comedies are usually built around a central misunderstanding, or confusion that creates the comedic situation. Classically these are cases of mistaken identity, suspected infidelity, misunderstandings, gossip and rumour. In more modern comedies, these components may be present along with satire, parody, witty banter, comedic insults, social awkwardness, and slapstick to create funny, farcical, or just cringe-worthy situations. ','Side'=>'A Side with The Joke Significator is usually comedic relief, and is often considered a joke by the other sides. In some genres, and under some Yarn-Tellers the Joke Side can always invoke the "Rule of Funny" to get by, survive or even succeed, depending upon how funny the Joke is...','Character'=>'The Joke Significator indicates a Character who is a comedian. <p>They <strong>Gain Yin</strong> when they act stupid or uncomprehending. </p><p>They <strong>Gain Yang</strong> when they tell jokes, or attempt humour. </p><p>They <strong>Gain Chi</strong> when anyone laughs. </p><p>They also gain +1 Success Levels on any Positive Psyche Attacks that they may attempt.</p>','Scene'=>'The Joke Scene is intended for a moment of comic relief, a reduction of tension with a silly situation. Although occasionally a Prank can heighten tensions rather than relieve them. Yarn-Tellers can play the card to create Pranks and Jokes, that will not impact the main Plot, if they wish, or they can impact the Plot <em>with</em> humour. Satirical lampooning of the Dominant force can act to reduce their control, etc.'],'Beat_Type'=>'5', 'Conflict_Embodiment'=>'0', 'Facet_Embodiment'=>'3',  'Hook_Aspect'=>'Persona (Motivation)', 'Aspect_Description'=>'The Hook targets the Character\'s Persona specifically via their Motivation. An Idol may be tempted by Social Interactions and a crowd of cheering grateful masses.','Hook'=>'Set up', 'Hook_Description'=>'The set up is the beginning of the joke, in a comedy this is usually a misunderstanding, in a shorter joke this is a question, somewhere in between it is a sentence or two that creates a narrative framework that misleads the audience. At its very simplest it is a cliché, such as a bunch of adventurers walk into a bar. Occasionally, it is a physical set up to a prank or stunt that will be important later. And every now and then it is a literal set up, with a situation created to put the PCs in the Narrative.', 'Gain'=>'Friends (a Group of 2-12 Vexes, or 2-6 Chorus Extras)', 'Fray'=>'Caper', 'Fray_Description'=>'Capers are usually Low to Medium Stakes (although Higher Stakes Capers are possible) where multiple deceptions, confusions and complex physical activities occur that are all connected to trying to achieve some goal, often a heist or con-game. Humour is usually part of a Caper, such as swapping priceless jewels for plastic kids jewellery, or million-dollar bonds for monopoly money. In a real criminal enterprise such frivolities would create additional leads for the police, during a Caper though they will just confound, bemuse and amuse.','Snag'=>'Shenanigans', 'Snag_Description'=>'Someone, or occasionally something, is out to cause mischief. The Fray may be complicated by additional pranks, deceptions, antics and high-jinx. Then again, perhaps following the Fray there is some additional escapades of tom-foolery that the PCs must suffer through. This Snag can often be a sign that a capricious foe or Rival is involved in the Plot, such as those who carry F&aelig;ry-blood.','NPC'=>array('Archetype'=>'Clown','Persona'=>7,'Core'=>9,'Hitch'=>9,'Description'=>'Clowns are a type of entertainer that act as though they are separate to society and its norms. The Clown\'s performance while comedic is based on the idea that the absurd is normal for the Character, whereas the normal is extraordinary. Not to be confused with the Fool.'),'Sweeping'=>'Comic Relief','Sweeping_Text'=>'Comedy is an easy way to release Tension. A joke during a Tense moment can ruin a Thriller though, so use carefully. Comedy Relief can help Characters come to terms with recent events though. Often a Character may be comic relief, a Comic relief Character receives ', 'History'=>'Funny','History_Description'=>'The Joke indicates that the history of the current situation is funny somehow, there may be a joke, or just some humorous twists and situations.', 'Situation'=>'Jape', 'Situation_Description'=>'The Joke indicates the current situation is not a serious one, it may be a joke, a prank or simply a funny story. This is not usually a dangerous situation, although sometimes it might appear so at first. Sometimes the humour may begin to run amok and a Jape can become a farce, where anything that can go wrong will, at least humorously.','Solution'=>'Humiliation','Solution_Description'=>'The Joke indicates that the way out of the current situation is through humiliation, this may mean humiliating some one else (often a bully) or humiliating yourself.'), //5
		array('Yarn_Name'=>'The Unicorn','Yarn_Description'=>'The Unicorn card represents either a powerful, magical engine of transformation and freedom, that is difficult to find, obtain or master, or it is something entirely imaginary. It is a dream that is chased, sometimes the dream is achieved, often it is not, but may have led you to a better or worse place than you started. Occasionally the Unicorn is nothing but a Nightmare.','Significator'=>['Plot'=>'The Unicorn Plot is usually described as a "Snark hunt", which is a hunt for something that may not exist (Unicorn and Boojum Hunt are also used). This might be a wild goose chase, or an investigation into a conspiracy, that might not exist. Occasionally a Unicorn plot will actually involve a powerful magical creature (although rarely in a fantasy context) or artefact. Unicorn Plots often involve a Monster, although this is sometimes a human Monster who hunts the Unicorn. ','Side'=>'When only one side is marked by the Unicorn it usually means that that side will undergo a powerful transformation, or change. Just occasionally it means that the side will be rendered powerless or paralysed by a Virtue Embodiment from another side.','Character'=>'The Unicorn Significator indicates a Character given to flights of fantasy (who may also be a powerful supernatural creature in their own right).<p>They <strong>Gain Yin</strong> when they daydream, talk to themselves, or pretend to be things they do not appear to be. </p><p>They <strong>Gain Yang</strong> when they are speak with authority or demonstrate knowledge or wisdom. </p><p>They <strong>Gain Chi</strong> when they use magic, or misdirection and deception to get what they want.','Scene'=>'The Unicorn Scene reveals the "Otherworld" of the story, this might be the world of Fey, a world beyond a magickal portal, or some criminal underworld, or world of the Super-Rich that is divorced from normal reality. Yarn-Tellers can play the Unicorn to reveal or portal between these worlds, or to create powerful magical Monsters and events.'],'Beat_Type'=>'6', 'Conflict_Embodiment'=>'0', 'Facet_Embodiment'=>'13',  'Hook_Aspect'=>'Persona (Gain)', 'Aspect_Description'=>'The Hook targets the Character\'s Persona specifically via their Gain, this Hook should offer a chance for them to make this Gain several times ideally.','Hook'=>'Unicorn\'s Promise', 'Hook_Description'=>'The Unicorn\'s Promise is a complex Hook, that can express in many ways. It might be a dream revelation, or a situation that seems dire until someone suggests what sounds like a simple solution, but is actually a more difficult, or dangerous situation than the original, it can be a situation that seems impossible, but that there is some magical solution that is perhaps achievable.', 'Gain'=>'Dream (sometimes a new dream or goal is the best Gain, other times getting what you dreamed of is better).', 'Fray'=>'Tame the Untameable', 'Fray_Description'=>'This is a Fray that seems impossible. In fact the impossible task is possible, but you have to look at the problem in a whole new way. Just as the fierce Unicorn is entirely untameable, and a vicious killer, and yet if a virgin sits nearby and waits, the Unicorn will approach her, and fall asleep on her lap, allowing itself to be tamed.', 'Snag'=>'Played', 'Snag_Description'=>'The Fray, whatever it was, was just a distraction while the Opposed Embodiment acted to achieve their Ends. Or the PCs discover that they have been misled and have worked towards the Opposed Embodiment\'s goal, which makes the Fray a ploy used by the Opposed Embodiment. It is usual at this point for the Opposed Embodiment to reveal that they were actually the feeble old man all along, or whoever.','NPC'=>array('Archetype'=>'Artiste','Persona'=>11,'Core'=>2,'Hitch'=>2,'Description'=>'The starving artist is an ancient archetype, this isn\'t <strong><em>strictly</em></strong> that archetype. These may be starving, and they may even create art, but they get much more pleasure from the trappings of the art world than actually doing anything as uncouth as selling art. For them to be known as an artist is enough.'),'Sweeping'=>'Dream / Nightmare','Sweeping_Text'=>'The PCs manage to sleep, but have strong powerful dreams. ', 'History'=>'Alternate','History_Description'=>'The Unicorn card reveals an alternate history, that may differ dramatically to the accepted past, this maybe because the alternate includes magic, f&aelig;ry creatures, ancient astronauts, conspiracy theories, references alternate timelines, or occurs due to reality coalescence or Yarn-Teller side-stepping.', 'Situation'=>'Boojum', 'Situation_Description'=>'The Unicorn indicates a situation has arisen that might be blamed upon a fantastic creature, but that there is a chance that the creature itself does not exist. This may be a wild goose chase or Snark Hunt, but there is always something behind the accounts or corpses, even if it is a person, pet or wild animal. Almost always a Boojum will never be clearly identified, and the situation may end with no one really sure what exactly they drove off, away, or killed.','Solution'=>'Magic','Solution_Description'=>'The Unicorn card indicates that the way out of this situation is through magic, it may be a particular magic artefact or spell is required, but often almost any magic will do. In genres normally without true magic, then prestidigitation, illusion and deception will have to be used instead.'), //6
		array('Yarn_Name'=>'The Stag','Yarn_Description'=>'The Stag card represents nature in the form of  visceral, animal life. Animals are driven by base desires, the simplest principles, and so the card shows us this, indicating that the events are concerned with an individual\'s strength and survival, and perhaps more importantly the long term survival of the species. The Stag is usually timid and will avoid threats, but may be quick to fight during the rutting season, and vicious with those antlers. It is this rutting behaviour that sets the Stag apart.','Significator'=>['Plot'=>'The Stag Plot is a natural story, concerned with the normal conflicts of nature, the difficulties of survival, hunting, mating and child-rearing. These can be stories of nature, or children raised by wolves, bears and lions, or they can be coming of age tales, that mark important and natural events in any life. ','Side'=>'When one side is marked with The Stag they are often elevated by the season or story (as the Stag bellows and threatens during the rut). The Stag side may become Monster Facet Embodiments for the duration of the Story usually during the Zenith. ','Character'=>'The Stag Significator indicates a Character who is physical, athletic and sexual. <p>They <strong>Gain Yin</strong> when they practice, train, or exercise. </p><p>They <strong>Gain Yang</strong> when they compete with another, or show off. </p><p>They <strong>Gain Chi</strong> when their accomplishments are recognised. </p><p>They gain +1 Success Level on any purely physically athletic action (such as rutting, running, jumping, swimming, punching, kicking, head-butting).</p>','Scene'=>'The Stag Scene is physical and sometimes hedonistic, there is often a sense of importance or occasion to these Scenes though. They can be important watershed moments for the Characters. Yarn-Tellers can play a Stag card to create a Physical Ordeal (such as a race or chase), or a scene of debauchery (such as a night in a brothel or strip club). They can also use them to mark such events as weddings and coming of age (manhood/womanhood) events.'],'Beat_Type'=>'7', 'Conflict_Embodiment'=>'1', 'Facet_Embodiment'=>'0',  'Hook_Aspect'=>'Persona', 'Aspect_Description'=>'The Hook targets the Character\'s Persona. For example: In order to Hook a Reaper you need to offer them something to collect or gain.','Hook'=>'Taste of Desire', 'Hook_Description'=>'The Story hooks the character by offering what they currently desire (although not perhaps what they really need). This temptation usually includes a taste of what is to come, a kiss from a potential lover, a hit of their addiction to sooth the tremors, a morsel of food for the starving man, but it is not enough to satiate them, yet.', 'Gain'=>'Herd (3-60) Cast Extra Allies', 'Fray'=>'Hunt', 'Fray_Description'=>'A Hunt is a High Stakes Complex Motional Chase Ordeal. The PCs may be trying to find food, or they may be the hunted, trying to escape, then again not all hunts are for food, the search for a mate or a place to live can also be hunts. Hunts can involve Snares, Traps and Obstacles, as well as deadly predators and dangerous prey animals.', 'Snag'=>'Seductions', 'Snag_Description'=>'After the Fray the PCs or their allies are offered temptations. These may be tempting offers to change sides, or actual seductions, by a love interest (or a love interests Rivals) in some cases. When a PC is seduced it is usual that the some thing reveals later that they have slept with the enemy, and may be betrayed ','NPC'=>array('Archetype'=>'Flirt','Persona'=>11,'Core'=>15,'Hitch'=>9,'Description'=>'Flirts, are incredibly common in liberated societies, they may be common in more conservative times and places, but must do their best to keep secret their nature. Which is hard, as being flirty exposes them (they wouldn\'t want a persecuted Hitch too!).'),'Sweeping'=>'Stag Challenge','Sweeping_Text'=>'The PCs get to rest, meanwhile their opponents (often the Dominant Embodiments) are challenged by one of their Rivals.', 'History'=>'Bloody','History_Description'=>'The Stag indicates that the history of the current situation is rooted in bloody soil, this may be some old battle, a long gone hunt, or some other slaughter.', 'Situation'=>'Survival', 'Situation_Description'=>'The Stag indicates that the current situation is literally one of survival, the stakes are high right now, and failure could easily mean death. There is a often a wilderness or urban jungle element to this situation, and very often a pursuit, chase, hunt or other Motional Ordeal.','Solution'=>'Hyperarousal','Solution_Description'=>'The Stag indicates that the route out of this current situation is via the "Acute Stress Response", or the "Fight-or-Flight Response", the heightened hormones, and physical responses the body makes when hyperaroused are the key to winning the fight (often by intimidation and raw aggression), fleeing successfully, or the other one.'), //7
		array('Yarn_Name'=>'The Wizard','Yarn_Description'=>'The Wizard card represents a person with complete mastery of their surroundings and in complete control of themselves. A talented, skilful, and powerful person who has the ability to create and achieve almost any goal they set themselves.','Significator'=>['Plot'=>'The Wizard plot is sometimes a world changing plot. Nothing that follows a Wizard Plot will ever be the same again. They are often huge events that change the nature of reality, or the fabric of society are the order of the day. But they can also be small moments of magic, especially when they fall as a Side Significator.','Side'=>'When a side is marked by the Wizard they have an expert or specialist at something, they might be an elite hacker, or an expert sword-smith, or an actual spell-throwing, wand-carrying wizard. Usually they have one, sometimes the whole side may be Wizards, often of different types of specialists.','Character'=>'The Wizard Significator indicates a Character who is an ace in their field. They are a wizard at what they do. <p>They <strong>Gain Yin</strong> when they share wisdom, or tips with another. They gain from learning as well as teaching tips. </p><p>They <strong>Gain Yang</strong> when they work at what they are good at (research, or practical). </p><p>They <strong>Gain Chi</strong> when they don\'t do exactly what they are asked for, complicate matters, or achieve something unique or important.</p><p>They also gain a +1 Success Level on any Test, Ordeal or Action that they are a "Wizard" at.</p>','Scene'=>'The Wizard Scene is a tiny piece of magic in a heartless universe. Yarn-Tellers can play the card to perform immense magics, or so that they can meet any suitable expert, potentially as an Ally (although often not).'],'Beat_Type'=>'6', 'Conflict_Embodiment'=>'0', 'Facet_Embodiment'=>'2',  'Hook_Aspect'=>'Power', 'Aspect_Description'=>'The Hook targets the Character\'s Power or Super-Annex, offering some upgrade, edge or perhaps just a change of Tangle or Umbral.','Hook'=>'Summoning', 'Hook_Description'=>'The story opens a summoning, this may mean a message, an invitation, police at the door, or magical circles across dimensions. Sometimes the PCs are the summoners, but usually they are the Summoned. Someone powerful wants to see them, or has something to give them, or take from them.', 'Gain'=>'Magic Spell / Tool / Treasure (Skill Descendant / Talent / Power Descendant)', 'Fray'=>'Wizard Duel', 'Fray_Description'=>'A Wizard Duel should be a unique experience. Every Wizard is a master of themselves and their environment, so when two Duel it will reflect their individualities blended together. The Duel will be an appropriate Stake for both Wizards, from Low to Extreme, Soul, or Paradoxical. Unlike most Ordeals during Proficiencies each Wizard must agree the Proficiencies of the other. During this "negotiation" the rules will usually be stated, with a later intent to bend or break them for an advantage.',  'Snag'=>'Strange Ways', 'Snag_Description'=>'Wizards naturally complicate everything. They over think situations and plans, or use incredible obscure or clever ideas. They build secret ways, like escape routes, or magically create extra ways to complicate things. The Snag complicates the Fray in unique, complex ways, at the very least adding secret passages for people to vanish into or arrive out of.','NPC'=>array('Archetype'=>'Expert','Persona'=>11,'Core'=>11,'Hitch'=>15,'Description'=>'The Expert is a master of their subject environment, and as such stand with one foot in the normal world and another in their field. They can be Witch-Doctors literally carrying profound messages between the spirit world and the physical world, or they can be IT specialists, interfacing electronic fora and digital FAQs to the recurring malware vector in marketing via direct meat-space social linguistics.'),'Sweeping'=>'Magical Gain','Sweeping_Text'=>'This can be an actual Gain, such as a magickal spell, tomb or sword, or more likely it is a magically gained Revelation, such as a portent or vision.', 'History'=>'Fortune-teller','History_Description'=>'The Wizard indicates that the past is somehow tangled with the future directly, this is usually in the form of some sort of prophecy, or fortune-telling, but it may be a result of predestination paradoxes because of time travel. Either way the past and future are some how connected in this situation.', 'Situation'=>'Wizardry', 'Situation_Description'=>'The Wizard indicates The current situation is caused by wizardry of some sort. Where possible magic has caused the situation, cursing someone, or creating a portal are typical examples, otherwise the threat can be scientific, technological, or computational wizardry instead.','Solution'=>'Mastery','Solution_Description'=>'The Wizard indicates that the way out of this current situation is through mastery, this may be mastery of a particular skill or proficiencies such as swordsmanship, it could be mastery over your surroundings, or some subject matter, but it always includes self-mastery. This is often a test of self-knowledge, self-restraint and self-control, as well as the mastery of annex, descendant or location.'), //8
		array('Yarn_Name'=>'The Lady','Yarn_Description'=>'The Lady card represents luck, freedom and liberty. Symbolic of gambling and games of chance, the lady can seem carefree and easy, but she can turn on you in an instant, especially if you disrespect her. The Lady is the card of random factors, bizarre coincidences, and insightful synchronicities, never dismiss her as dumb luck.','Significator'=>['Plot'=>'The Lady Plot is one of luck. Good luck, bad luck, coincidence and random events. These plots tend to favour certain types of Characters, naive fools, beginners, risk-takers, gamblers and their ilk. What is true though is the Lady often loses interest in her Hooked Characters, and being fickle may decide to start all over again. The Lady can smile or frown upon a side, causing lucky gains or unlucky losses. ','Side'=>'A side marked by the Lady will feel they are lucky, and take more risks. Perhaps they believe now is the time to act, or that they are poised to score the highest in the exams, who knows they might be right. What is true is that the side marked by the Lady will interact with all the other Embodiments during the Plot. They may not be all at once, and might not involve rational conflict, but they will interact directly with Embodiments of all the other sides.','Character'=>'The Lady Significator indicates a Character who is a risk-taker, a gambler or gamer. <p>They <strong>Gain Yin</strong> when they play a game, or keep a score. </p><p><strong>Gain Yang</strong> when they make, or take, a bet. </p><p><strong>Gain Chi</strong> when they win a bet. </p><p>They also gain a +1 Success Level on any game of Skill or Chance.</p>','Scene'=>'The Lady Scene is a scene of extreme luck, coincidence and special circumstances. Yarn-Tellers may play the card to win a game of chance, or bet, arrange some helpful or terrible coincidence, or unleash chaos, as required.'],'Beat_Type'=>'7', 'Conflict_Embodiment'=>'3', 'Facet_Embodiment'=>'20',  'Hook_Aspect'=>'Core', 'Aspect_Description'=>'The Hook targets the Character\'s Core. For example: In order to Hook an Enhancer Core, create a situation that only someone with access to that Nimbed could solve.','Hook'=>'Coincidences', 'Hook_Description'=>'The Hook of this Plot is about lucky breaks, coincidental leads, chance encounters or random factors aligning. The PCs are usually involved in some other business (like a high Stakes Motional Ordeal) when suddenly they run into the next Bad Guy\'s minions or more coincidentally the return of an old one.', 'Gain'=>'Cash, Car, Companionship (<strong>Gain Chi</strong>, A Descendant and at least a Cast Extra Ally)', 'Fray'=>'Games', 'Fray_Description'=>'The Fray is a game, it could be a game of chance, skill or athleticism. Games are obviously usually Low Stakes, but higher Stakes games exist. Playing Chess with Death would count as Soul Stakes (at least), a game of Russian Roulette is Extreme Stakes, and so on. Games can be teaching moments, with Mentors teaching tactics in Chess or ethics, morals or any amount of knowledge being passed via the game. Games can be Ordeals or Tests, or can be played out for real if desired.', 'Snag'=>'Accident', 'Snag_Description'=>'A freak chain of events, or lack of attention, causes a Character to hurt themselves. Maybe they pull a muscle training, drop a knife on their foot, or step on an upturned nail. Draw 3 cards and apply the most appropriate Card or Trick as an attack on the Hooked Character/Party.','NPC'=>array('Archetype'=>'Lady','Persona'=>11,'Core'=>7,'Hitch'=>15,'Description'=>'A Lady is a deceptive manipulating Rake who relies as much on pretending to be something they are not as being a Rake. They often Pretend to be Leaders, Healers or Fanatics.'),'Sweeping'=>'Lucky Break','Sweeping_Text'=>'Lucky Breaks can be big Gains, Revelations or just a rest depending on how badly Pressed the Characters are. Lucky Breaks can grant all three, but there will be some chance or random factor (often a Liberty or Key Test) to make Gains or Revelations', 'History'=>'Luck','History_Description'=>'The Lady indicates that the history of the current situation is one of coincidence or blind luck. Sometimes this might mean a simple coincidence such as a character presently sharing a name with another character, other times the coincidences are extreme, where they also coincidently lived in the same apartment some time before, and even look similar, then again a situation can often be created by someone winning a lottery, or more likely an illegal poker tournament.', 'Situation'=>'Fluke', 'Situation_Description'=>'The Lady indicates that the current situation is a fluke occurrence, this can be a chance, but relatively common happening, such as bumping into an ex while shopping, to an incredibly lucky stroke of fortune, such as winning the lottery, or surviving a terrible accident.','Solution'=>'Gamble','Solution_Description'=>'The Lady indicates the solution to the current situation is for the character to take a risk, this may be a wager, gambling game, or a leap of faith.'), //9
		array('Yarn_Name'=>'The Jester','Yarn_Description'=>'The Jester card represents satire, comedy, and the absurd. It might be a witty exchange of insults, a bit of rec-room banter, a carefully arranged practical joke, or simply a sense of disjunction in a world turned upside-down. There might be mimicry, disguises, acting, buffoonery, or the delicate terror of a vacant stare.','Significator'=>['Plot'=>'The Jester Plot is also a comedy, although unlike the Joke, the Jester is more parody and satire of something else than a comedy in its own right. A Jester has things to say, about politics, about society, about the audience, where as the Joke just wants to make you laugh the Jester wants to make you laugh and think. The Jester doesn\'t just make a Pun at random, the Pun will fully reflect the situation at hand.','Side'=>' When a side is affected by a Jester they are marked out politically, perhaps they have the ear of the press, or the people directly, or perhaps they are an advisor to the crown, then again they may just be comedic relief.','Character'=>'The Jester Significator indicates a Character who pokes fun at their betters. <p>They <strong>Gain Yin</strong> when they mock or make jokes about their superiors, leaders or friends. </p><p>They <strong>Gain Yang</strong> when they defend someone, or distract an attacker with humour. </p><p>They <strong>Gain Chi</strong> when they mock or poke fun at some one of higher status than themselves.</p>','Scene'=>'The Jester Scene is intended for comic relief, rather like the Joke card. However, the Jester indicates the Scene will contain a Character who is Comic Relief rather than the Scene being comic. Yarn-Tellers can play the card to create a Comic-Relief Character (usually an Ally or Rival), who will help them, or hinder their enemies somehow.'],'Beat_Type'=>'8', 'Conflict_Embodiment'=>'2', 'Facet_Embodiment'=>'5',  'Hook_Aspect'=>'Hitch', 'Aspect_Description'=>'The Hook targets the Character\'s largest Hitch, either threatening to trigger the Hitch or actually triggering it, depending upon which will motivate the Character more.','Hook'=>'Entrance', 'Hook_Description'=>'The Hook is literally an entrance. This usually refers to the sudden, dramatic appearance of a new or returning Embodiment, but it can also be an opening, door or any threshold, or cliff-edge moment. In Old Comedies the players would sing as they paraded in, setting up the story with the first song, in old serials they would show how the Cliff-Hanger ending of the last Chapter was resolved (often with a retcon).', 'Gain'=>'An unlikely, but powerful Ally (A Eusaivean with a Bulmäs best friend, a Knight with a Dragon steed, a cyborg with a pet Rust monster)', 'Fray'=>'Insult Tennis', 'Fray_Description'=>'Insult tennis is a Low-Medium Stakes Opposed Ordeal, the PCs and their foes or Rivals exchange insults, and cutting remarks. In effect the Tennis is a battle or duel fought to the first blood (although in this case first emotional outburst) with Psych attacks.', 'Snag'=>'Upside-Down', 'Snag_Description'=>'Nothing makes sense, the good becomes bad, the powerful become weak, and the weak become powerful. Even though they may have won the Fray, everything is turned on its head. Perhaps it turns out that they were deceived all along, and were working for the bad guys, or maybe they never really grasped what was going on and picked the wrong side.','NPC'=>array('Archetype'=>'Comedian','Persona'=>4,'Core'=>9,'Hitch'=>7,'Description'=>'The Comedian asks questions and expects only laughs as answers. They use humour to deflect and manipulate people, and can usually create powerful Psych attacks with a "Jokes" Power.'),'Sweeping'=>'Wandering Fool','Sweeping_Text'=>'The PC moves (usually via a Motional Ordeal) to a new Location. For the PCs this journey may be aimless wandering, but in fact it is a hunt for something they need. Often the Fool will encounter a lesson in the new location, or maybe just rest, heal up a bit, and maybe get a bite to eat or a little spending cash on the way.', 'History'=>'Absurd','History_Description'=>'The Jester indicates that the past history that lead to the current situation is absurd in some way, this may mean that the recorded history is nonsense, written by lunatics and the severely misinformed, or that the time-line itself may be twisted, looped or adjusted to create an absurd situation.', 'Situation'=>'Misunderstanding', 'Situation_Description'=>'The Jester indicates that this situation is a misunderstanding of some sort, perhaps a knight has got the wrong idea about what his lord wants, or more often a case of mistaken identity, these misunderstandings are often comedic in nature, but do not have to be.','Solution'=>'Laughter','Solution_Description'=>'The Jester indicates that the way out of the current situation is to make someone laugh, often this is in a sense of tension breaking comic relief, but humour is always subjective.'), //10
		array('Yarn_Name'=>'The Mask','Yarn_Description'=>'The Mask card represents the false fronts that we play. There are few people who are completely open and honest with everyone in their life, most of us choose to hide aspects of ourselves from view and don a mask. For some, undercover agents and those running for their lives, the mask becomes their only existence.','Significator'=>['Plot'=>'The Mask Plot is a a plot about secret identities and double-lives. The Plot might be about Superheroes, dealing with a real life and a costumed identity, or an undercover cop in a crime syndicate, or a cyber-ninja infiltrating an opposed mega-Zaibatsu. Mask Plots can become farcical, unless there is real Tension that they will be discovered, and that it will have profound consequences. It is sometimes a necessary part of the Mask plot to have the hero discover exactly how bad it can get, with loved ones threatened or killed by the Plot. ','Side'=>'When a side is marked by the Mask the side may pretend to be something they are not, such as the Above pretending to be the Shadows or vice-versa.','Character'=>'The Mask Significator indicates a Character who can pretend to be things they are not. <p>They <strong>Gain Yin</strong> when they wear a mask, disguise or shape-shift. </p><p>They <strong>Gain Yang</strong> when they deceive another or pretend to be something they are not. </p><p>They <strong>Gain Chi</strong> when they are not recognised for who, or what, they are. </p><p>They also gain +1 Success Level with all disguise, masks and make-up actions.</p>','Scene'=>'A Mask scene is a scene where things are not as they first appear. Perhaps the location is a Facade, such as movie set, or that what was intended to be paying in some cash to the bank, gets subverted when masked robbers walk in and unload a shotgun into the ceiling.'],'Beat_Type'=>'4', 'Conflict_Embodiment'=>'0', 'Facet_Embodiment'=>'15',  'Hook_Aspect'=>'Core', 'Aspect_Description'=>'The Hook targets the Character\'s Core. For example: In order to Hook a Traveller, create a barrier that stops them from travelling, or something that draws in Travellers like a roadside attraction of sorts.','Hook'=>'False Face', 'Hook_Description'=>'The Story opens with the Plot presenting a false face, it may be a pretext for something else, or a pretence of some sort, but the plot does not represent itself truthfully. It may hide its Conflict Embodiments (perhaps making the Player Characters not the Pressed Characters), make false Revelations, or false promises in general.', 'Gain'=>'Secret Identity (this can just be a disguise Descendant, or a whole lifestyle including Locations, or even a whole new Alternate)', 'Fray'=>'Masquerade', 'Fray_Description'=>'Masquerades can be simple fancy dress parties, or they can be complex political or covert Ordeals full of under-the-table deals, or thinking bigger they can be their own Stories with sub-rosa themes, Quests to deceive, mislead and be underhanded with others, or even a Witness Protection Program or Deep Cover / Sleeper Agent situations that last decades.', 'Snag'=>'Red Herring', 'Snag_Description'=>'There is some false information around, it may have already have misled the PCs, but worse yet the next Revelation they make will be deliberate misinformation by the Yarn-Teller or Plot. Perhaps they will be told the truth in the end, or might even spot the lie eventually, but this isn\'t a simple lie, it will be close to the truth and they will find supporting evidence.','NPC'=>array('Archetype'=>'Spy','Persona'=>7,'Core'=>7,'Hitch'=>13,'Description'=>'The Spy lives quietly, hiding amongst their enemies, they are a Pretender who will become whatever they need to be to avoid suspicion, while constantly working on their devious, deviant, plans. During active missions Spies will often become Leaders, or Scouts to maximise the gains they make.'),'Sweeping'=>'Lost-in-the-crowd','Sweeping_Text'=>'No matter the Fray the PCs get to vanish in the wind after it. They change or adopt disguises, head to a safe-house, or vanish into the night. They can rest, recover, shop, create or train for the next Fray.', 'History'=>'Facade','History_Description'=>'The Mask indicates that the past of this situation has been changed by time and rumour, or altered deliberately, aspects of the true history have been rewritten, with cover stories being created. This may have been to protect some identities (or alliances), preserve some societal myth, or simply be by the mists of time.', 'Situation'=>'Disguised', 'Situation_Description'=>'The Mask indicates that the current situation is based around disguises, masks and perceptions. Perhaps an enemy is disguised among you, a spy or a mole in your organisation, or more often you must don a disguise in order pass undiscovered through enemy territory or spy upon them. Disguises can involve playing a role, pretending to be something you are not, or just not being recognised for who you really are.','Solution'=>'Bluff','Solution_Description'=>'The Mask indicates that the solution to your current situation is to bluff it out, this may be a simple lie, or a complex deception, reliant on many players, trickery and shenanigans.'), //J
		array('Yarn_Name'=>'The Cloak','Yarn_Description'=>'The Cloak card is symbolic of the warmth and protection of a good coat, privileges of rank, and the hidden aspects of life. This can be those parts that are private, or actual secrets, perhaps even hidden passages, or secret tunnels. It is the card of secrets, thieves and cowards, as well as nobility, cunning, and superheroes.','Significator'=>['Plot'=>'The Cloak Plot is usually a Spy or Superhero Story, like the Mask. Unlike the Mask, The Cloak is about secrets, and privileges, not dual identities, so while the Characters\' secrets may be threatened, they do not have to live as another Side or person. Cloak Plots will usually kill Embodiments on all sides, but often new Embodiments will be recruited during the Plot','Side'=>'A Cloaked side may be better protected or privileged than normal, or they may be secretive, hidden from view, indeed they can be so cloaked their Embodiments may not obviously appear, like the DeeperShadows Side. When the Cloak marks the DeeperShadows the DeeperShadows may actually Embody and act, although they will suicide rather than reveal anything about themselves if captured (which would be very unlikely anyway).','Character'=>'The Cloak Significator indicates a Character who keeps their real self hidden. <p>They <strong>Gain Yin</strong> when they hide or avoid conversation. </p><p>They <strong>Gain Yang</strong> when they lie or tell a story. </p><p>They <strong>Gain Chi</strong> when they ignore their Persona. </p><p>They also gain +1 Success Level to any hide actions, or remaining hidden.</p>','Scene'=>'The Cloak Scene is any Scene where what actually happens is in some way hidden, or misleading. A Yarn-Teller may play the Cloak to hide themselves or others, granting them an ambush, escape or a rest, as required. The Cloak allows them to make secret actions with little chance of detection.'],'Beat_Type'=>'5', 'Conflict_Embodiment'=>'0', 'Facet_Embodiment'=>'4',  'Hook_Aspect'=>'Hitch', 'Aspect_Description'=>'The Hook targets one of the Character\'s Hitches, usually a Flaw. For example: In order to Hook a Duty (Honour-bound) Hitch simply threaten the Character\'s honour, or have them swear to do something.','Hook'=>'Cloaked Threat', 'Hook_Description'=>'The Hook tells the Character directly of some looming, but secretive danger, rumours of a new mob boss, prototype fighter with incredible stats, or any mysterious stranger or player.', 'Gain'=>'Secret Alliance (the creation of a secretive Pact Descendant)', 'Fray'=>'Hide!', 'Fray_Description'=>'These Ordeals may involve hiding, or concealing something. The PCs may have to hide themselves from detection, or they may have to conceal something else, perhaps not letting the guards take the kid who just burst into the room and hid under the sofa. As such Hiding can be as much about bluffing as it is physical concealment, but is an Opposed Ordeal of almost any Stakes.', 'Snag'=>'No Witnesses', 'Snag_Description'=>'Whatever happened during the Fray, there is no one to bear witness to the result. This means the truth of what happened will be clouded by speculation and suspicions, mostly directed at the PCs. Alternatively, the Fray is complicated by the PCs having to insure they are not spotted, and that their involvement remains secret.','NPC'=>array('Archetype'=>'Rogue','Persona'=>7,'Core'=>13,'Hitch'=>7,'Description'=>'Rogues are scoundrels, who rarely attack in a fair fight. Ambushes and sniping tactics are more their Style, perhaps with a little smuggling, pickpocketing or burglary along the way.'),'Sweeping'=>'Magic Cloak','Sweeping_Text'=>'The PCs may gain an actual cloak of invisibility, or more likely they gain a Revelation that they could not have got any other way, perhaps overhearing or intercepting a communication from the Opposed Embodiment.', 'History'=>'Shrouded','History_Description'=>'The Cloak indicates that the history of this situation is shrouded, this may mean that the truth cannot be known, or that the truth is known, but not widely shared. Unlike the Mask there is no cover story or fiction, just lingering mysteries and hidden facts.', 'Situation'=>'Hidden', 'Situation_Description'=>'The Cloak indicates that the current situation involves hiding or being hidden. This may involve an enemy force hidden with-in the lord\'s territory, or having to hide yourselves or some contraband. Occasionally the Cloak will indicate a hidden force, advantage, or strength that is being overlooked.','Solution'=>'Skulk','Solution_Description'=>'The Cloak indicates that the solution to the current situation is most often to hide, and remain unseen, while observing yourself. This may reveal information that will be useful, allow you to ambush your enemies, or simply flee the area undetected.'), //Q
		array('Yarn_Name'=>'The Physician','Yarn_Description'=>'The Physician card is representative of medicine, healing and bad news. If a character is injured, or sick they can seek relief and respite through the Physician. If they aren\'t then the bad news could be simply that the Apple-a-day isn\'t actually medical insurance, but more likely there is a new Hitch on some character\'s horizons.','Significator'=>['Plot'=>'The Physician Plot is all about a medical situation, common to all medical dramas. It may be that the Plot centres on a disease, or plague that must be contained, and treated. Or the Plot may be about a specific Physician, perhaps new to a practice, or who has decidedly unorthodox practices. ','Side'=>'When a side is marked by The Physician they are marked as having a Skill, Talent, or Power that is essential to the well-being of one the other sides (usually the Dominant Side, sometimes the Above, Pressed or Below). Often the Physician will have to be persuaded, or paid, to use this ability, sometimes they will behave as an ally to anyone needs their help.','Character'=>'The Physician Significator indicates a Character who cares deeply about the well-being of others. <p>They <strong>Gain Yin</strong> when they rest, read or examine something or someone. </p><p>They <strong>Gain Yang</strong> when they ask questions, make observations, or write notes. </p><p>The <strong>Gain Chi</strong> when they solve a problem, heal a Wound, or reduce a Hitch. </p><p>They gain +1 Success Levels to all attempts to Heal Wounds or reduce Hitches.</p>','Scene'=>'The Physician Scene is when the Characters get better from any wounds they may have taken. This may consist of a Surgical Ordeal, or just a montage of push-ups. Yarn-Tellers can play this card to remove and Heal Wounds, and even some Hitches (such as a "Dying" Hitch - usually converting it to a Scars Hitch). It can even raise the dead, under the right circumstances. The Referee can (and should) limit the effectiveness of the card, requiring downtime, or new Hitches.'],'Beat_Type'=>'9', 'Conflict_Embodiment'=>'1', 'Facet_Embodiment'=>'5',  'Hook_Aspect'=>'Hitch', 'Aspect_Description'=>'The Hook targets one of the Character\'s Hitches. For example: In order to Hook a Arachnophobe Character, one should simply have to threaten them with a spider, or better yet, make the bad guy into a spider and have word of them reach the PC.','Hook'=>'Bad News', 'Hook_Description'=>'The Hook just consists of terrible bad news, often medical in nature, such as an incurable (or at least perilous) disease diagnosis.', 'Gain'=>'Savant — Powerful Ally (Demon/Solo/Fae/Grand-Mercari)', 'Fray'=>'Medical Situation', 'Fray_Description'=>'This is a medical situation, maybe the PCs need Surgery (or to conduct it), perhaps they need to deal with a large scale accident, disaster, or plague.', 'Snag'=>'Medical Ethics', 'Snag_Description'=>'The Fray is complicated by a question of medical ethics, there are four main forms, Autonomy (the right to refuse treatment), Beneficence (acting in the best interest of the patient), Non-maleficence (Do no harm), and Justice (insuring the most worthy get the necessary help). This may be as simple as rich client verses poor client or as complex as the cure being as bad as the disease.','NPC'=>array('Archetype'=>'Medic','Persona'=>15,'Core'=>12,'Hitch'=>5,'Description'=>'The Medic is a healer, a surgeon, or a doctor. They seek to treat and heal injuries and disease wherever they find it.'),'Sweeping'=>'Medical Attention','Sweeping_Text'=>'The PCs get all the healing they can take, often plus some recovery time. This sort of intense medical attention can usually reduce, remove or resolve Quirk and even Flaw Hitches, it might reduce a Woe, but can rarely remove it.', 'History'=>'Disease','History_Description'=>'The Physician indicates that the current situation has been caused by a disease, illness, plague or similar medical situation in the past. Perhaps the king has had a stroke, and is now bed-ridden, or the kingdom may have been decimated by a plague that has altered the balance of economic power in the country.', 'Situation'=>'Aid', 'Situation_Description'=>'The Physician indicates a situation where another requires aid, or intelligent assistance. This may be healing, diagnosis, treatment, care, nursing, mothering, or even tactical military support, but without this aid there will be probably be injury and death.','Solution'=>'Prescription','Solution_Description'=>'The Physician indicates that the solution to this problem is fulfil a prescription, this might be by purchasing a medicine that a doctor has decided would be right for you, or by following a complex written plan or prophecy that was written before the situation arose, that describes the way out of the situation.'), //K
		//clubs
		array('Yarn_Name'=>'The Court','Yarn_Description'=>'The Court card represents both the Courts of Law and the Legal System, and Royal Courts and Parliaments. It can represent legal and political situations, but also social judgements too.','Significator'=>['Plot'=>'The Court Plot is usually a Legal affair, often a Court case, although it can be political intrigues or social in nature, depending upon the genre and Era. The Plot usually results in one Hooked Character accusing another of something (a crime, an affair, an insult). They must then struggle to either prove their innocence, defy the Court, or accept and often change some aspect of themselves. ','Side'=>'When one side is affected by the Court, they are intended to act as a Judge, or Court (often of public or media opinion), upon the rest of the Plot, which can powerfully influence the resolution of this Plot, even overturning the expected result. When the Dominant Side is marked by the Court then the Pressed side can expect jumped up charges, manufactured evidence, planted evidence, and perhaps even a kangaroo court. The Dominant side is "beyond the law" for some reason (perhaps the Above are corrupt?). If the Pressed side is marked with the Court then you are in lawless wild west territory.','Character'=>'The Court Significator indicates a Character who has some authority. <p>They <strong>Gain Yin</strong> when they work for the good of society. </p><p><strong>Gain Yang</strong> when they support someone else with authority. </p><p>They <strong>Gain Chi</strong> when they direct others behaviour, either by speech, writing, or example. </p><p>They gain +1 Success Level when at least three people acknowledge their authority.</p>','Scene'=>'The Court Scene is usually a judgement of some sort. Most often it is a social judgement, the new partner presented to the friends or family, although it may involve a lawyer too. Yarn-Tellers can play this card when they wish to call down a judgement on a Character. It is especially easy if they have actually broken laws, otherwise this will result in some social or political judgement of the Character it has been played upon. Judgement is not always bad, and if you have been hard done by another, this might let you make a Gain.'],'Beat_Type'=>'1', 'Conflict_Embodiment'=>'1', 'Facet_Embodiment'=>'3', 'Hook_Aspect'=>'I-Ching (First Hexagram)', 'Aspect_Description'=>'The Hook targets the Character\'s I-Ching specifically the Gain of their First Hexagram. For example: If a Character has the Cauldron (50) I-Ching, then the Hook needs to have someone hungry turn up asking for help.','Hook'=>'Arrested', 'Hook_Description'=>'The Story opens with the PCs captured, arrested or detained. It may be a case of mistaken identity, or they could be suspects, or maybe they did break a law or two on the way. This is perhaps justice weighing in on their past misdeeds. Sometimes there may be a bit of a Chase or Escape attempt before they are arrested, in fact a whole Epic can arise from being outlaws.', 'Gain'=>'Accolade (A knighthood, title, medal or treasure, A Super-Skill Artefact Descendant/Province)', 'Fray'=>'Court Appearance', 'Fray_Description'=>'The Fray is a Court Appearance, this may mean that the PCs will be the defendants in a Court Case, or that they will be judged socially when they appear in the "Royal Court" of the friends of a powerful person. Either way is an Opposed Ordeal (or Test) that has variable Stakes from Low to Paradoxical.', 'Snag'=>'Dispute', 'Snag_Description'=>'The Snag is an additional dispute either during the Fray or arising from the Fray. Often this Dispute results from the Fray as a form of Blame-Storming, as everyone discusses where they went wrong and whose fault it was.','NPC'=>array('Archetype'=>'Arbiter','Persona'=>21,'Core'=>3,'Hitch'=>1,'Description'=>'The Arbiter is a judge, referee, lawyer, magistrate or noble, they specialise in listening to arguments and making decisions based on what they\'ve heard. Arbiters interpret emotions, intuitions, law, logic, science, precedent and rhetoric as required by the rules they arbitrate, to decide who wins an argument they sit in judgement of.'),'Sweeping'=>'Sweet Justice','Sweeping_Text'=>'The PCs get some justice, assuming how they behaved this could mean they are awarded damages, accolades, destinies, cause for celebration, get the love interest, or perhaps just laments. This at least grants the PCs a rest, and usually a Gain.', 'History'=>'Casebook','History_Description'=>'The Court indicates that the past of this situation revolves around a previous case, this may be a returning litigant, antagonist or criminal, or an old cold case rears its head.', 'Situation'=>'Litigation', 'Situation_Description'=>'The Court indicates that the current situation is a litigation, this may be an ongoing court case, a civil, criminal, religious, military, or even political trial, sometimes it may be writing a new law, or even trial by combat.','Solution'=>'Arbitration','Solution_Description'=>'The Court indicates that the solution to the current situation is arbitration, this may mean finding a suitable referee, judge, authority or noble who can hear the case, ideally impartially, as well as actually undergoing the arbitration, which may be a negotiation or be adversarial.'), //ace
		array('Yarn_Name'=>'The Eelafin','Yarn_Description'=>'The Eelafin card is representative of the hybrid-faeries, who are characterised as having strong, graceful bodies, with just a hint of madness or wanderlust. Normal humans fear the Eelafin Doom-Weaving, that they usually imagine as curses. The Fae consider themselves half-doom and half-dream, the Eelafin they usually call Changeling, and consider them part-doom, part-doomed, part-dream, part-dreamer, and fear their Liberty and envy their mortality.','Significator'=>['Plot'=>'The Eelafin Plot is a hybrid itself, combining other types of Plots together to create something unique. You can draw for the hybrids, or simply choose. You might make a Romance-Detective Plot, where the "Who-dunnit" is as important than the "Will-They-Won\'t-They". Or maybe throw in a Masked Vigilante, who is also a serial killer... ','Side'=>'When sides of a Conflict are influenced by the Eelafin, they are marked out as being a hybrid, in that they are a half-elf, or cyborg, or something similar, or a changeling, meaning that sometime during the Loom (or during the Zenith) they may change, and reveal, that they were not what was assumed, as a Below Embodiment might reveal they are actually a Prince from the Above side in hiding. Sometimes the changeling will be revealed as being a single Embodiment within a side, to the rest of that side, during the Frame. They are then trying to keep this information secret from the other sides for the rest of the Plot (until the Zenith Final Revelation ideally).','Character'=>'The Eelafin Significator indicates a Character who seems at odds with themselves. <p>They <strong>Gain Yin</strong> when they act fatalistic, pessimistic, or depressed. </p><p>They <strong>Gain Yang</strong> when they act optimistic, positive, or excited. </p><p>They <strong>Gain Chi</strong> when they day-dream, or deal with, or talk about, a situation as it really is. </p><p>They gain +1 Success Level to the separate actions when they perform two or more at a time (shoot two or three targets, shoot while somersaulting, etc).</p>','Scene'=>'The Eelafin Scene is a Scene that straddles two worlds at the same time. This is not the same as a portal or threshold that joins two places with a liminal space. Here the Scene blends the two worlds together, like the recreation of your bedroom deep within the dream. Yarn-Tellers may play the card to create a Scene that blends the real world with another world (often a Quantum Alternate), perhaps in the form of a model, book, or piece of art or technology from that world.'],'Beat_Type'=>'2', 'Conflict_Embodiment'=>'2', 'Facet_Embodiment'=>'1', 'Hook_Aspect'=>'I-Ching (Changing Lines)', 'Aspect_Description'=>'The Hook targets the Character\'s I-Ching specifically the lines that change state between their First and Second Hexagram. The 3rd changing Line of The Creative for example rewards caution and responsibility, allowing the Hook to offer a situation where these may be demonstrated.','Hook'=>'Sensed', 'Hook_Description'=>'The Eelafin are know not just for their Doom-sense, but for their heightened senses in general. Perhaps a cry for help is heard, or a crime is witnessed by the Character to Hook them.', 'Gain'=>'Bloodline/Doom Descendant (some bloodlines and destinies grant extra Skills, Talents or even Powers, the Character discovers one of theirs)', 'Fray'=>'Doom', 'Fray_Description'=>'A Doom is a profound, Chronolithed event, a predestination paradox, or an event that is part of history and should not be changed, they are always Paradoxical Stakes Ordeals. Dooms are sensed approaching by every Mercari, Eelafin, or Yarn-Teller present. While a Doom is influenced and affected by the cards played, it is only the Ordeal cards that define the final success of the Doom, be careful, you may find yourself on the wrong side of history.', 'Snag'=>'Hitches', 'Snag_Description'=>'The Fray is complicated by a situation that involved many of the PCs Hitches. If a Character has a Woe that hasn\'t been triggered recently, now is the time. If they have a a few quirks, find a scenario that triggers them all, sequentially or together. For fairness, every Character involved in the Fray should have at least one of their Hitches triggered regardless of side.','NPC'=>array('Archetype'=>'Fae-Touched','Persona'=>18,'Core'=>21,'Hitch'=>3,'Description'=>'Those who spend too much time around the Fae become different, usually indifferent to mortal rules and morals, their incredible experiences often leave them mad, but gifted with some ability most mortals require years of dedicated practice to learn.'),'Sweeping'=>'Destiny','Sweeping_Text'=>'Destiny sounds like a simple thing, but what it often means is years of study, months of rigorous training, and at least one Crisis. This is one of those events, Gain, as appropriate<ul><li key="mean-1-random">New Proficiencies and a new Skill Annex</li><li key="mean-2-ksflew">Increase an Annex one Tier, gaining Proficiencies as required.</li><li key="mean-3-kskioe">A new Skill/Talent/Power Learning, Training, or Lore Descendant</li><li key="mean-4-wskjee">A new Monolith Descendant</li></ul>', 'History'=>'Betwixt','History_Description'=>'The Eelafin indicates that the current situation has been caused by interaction between two very disparate forces. One side is usually mundane, often ordinary people and the other is usually other-worldly, or super-, preter- or just un-natural such as F&aelig;ries, Increated, Eusaiveans or Toons.', 'Situation'=>'Changeling', 'Situation_Description'=>'The Eelafin indicates that the current situation has somebody who has been replaced, this may be with an actor, a mole, a clone, alien puppet-master, a magical realism replacement such as a shape-shifter, face-dancer, doppelganger, or an actual changeling, or a more supernatural explanation, such as a spirit, angelic or demonic possession or something more weird like a Eusaivean deep cover agent. The replacement may act as completely differently, or more interestingly they may behave almost perfectly the same as the original.','Solution'=>'Combine','Solution_Description'=>'The Eelafin indicates that the solution to the current situation is to combine at least two potential, but often unlikely, solutions together to synthesise a new solution that will probably work.'), //2
		array('Yarn_Name'=>'The Serpent','Yarn_Description'=>'The Serpent card represents words spoken with forked tongues, duplicity, shedding one\'s skin, rebirth, or abandoning the past. It is the card of liars, sinners and the untrustworthy. However, as duplicitous and sinful as the Serpent may be, it is also a card of cool, creative, rational thought and reasoning.','Significator'=>['Plot'=>'The Serpent Plot is all about deceit, lies, and sins. It may be a tale of crime, lust, or passion, or it could be a counter-intelligence operation undertaken for Monarch and country. ','Side'=>'If a side is marked with The Serpent then they are clearly not to be trusted, they may not be actually evil (although often are), but something about circumstance or their nature means they will lie every scene about something, and betray, double-cross, or triple-cross someone before the end of the Story.','Character'=>'The Serpent Significator indicates a lying snake of a Character. <p>They <strong>Gain Yin</strong> when they stay calm, are rational, or reasonable.</p><p>They <strong>Gain Yang</strong> when they are duplicitous, misleading or creative. </p><p>They <strong>Gain Chi</strong> when they lie or sin.</p><p>They gain +1 Success Level to all Psyche defences.</p>','Scene'=>'The Serpent Scene is a Scene of deception, lies or occasionally, a big snake. Yarn-Tellers can play the card to succeed in any kind of lying or deception, they can also play it to create a Monster or to stay cool when under psychological pressure.'],'Beat_Type'=>'3', 'Conflict_Embodiment'=>'2', 'Facet_Embodiment'=>'15', 'Hook_Aspect'=>'I-Ching (Gains)', 'Aspect_Description'=>'The Hook targets the Character\'s I-Ching offering a situation that maximises the potential Gains of the all their I-Ching HHexagrams and Changing Lines.','Hook'=>'Temptation', 'Hook_Description'=>'Offer a Gain to the Character, as their eventual reward.', 'Gain'=>'Fruit of the Tree of Knowledge (A Lore / Learning Descendant)', 'Fray'=>'Persuasion', 'Fray_Description'=>'Persuasion is a Low to Soul Stakes Ordeal where a PC tries to change another\'s mind (often another Side\'s Embodiment) or has someone try to change their minds.', 'Snag'=>'Skin-Shedding' , 'Snag_Description'=>'Snakes rejuvenate by shedding their skins. And the Snag here has an embodiment doing the same. Perhaps the enemy was defeated, the PCs watched him fall, but here he is again, fresh and ready for them, or maybe half-way through the Fray one of the PCs (or more likely an Ally) reveals they were working for the enemy all along, or having won the Fray the PCs now realise that they have fought for the wrong side.','NPC'=>array('Archetype'=>'Snake','Persona'=>18,'Core'=>5,'Hitch'=>1,'Description'=>'Snakes are aggressive fiends, who use others for their own purposes, actually abuse is probably a better term. Snakes lie, and cheat not for gain or revenge, but because it is simply their nature. They have few redeeming features, but do have a Vulnerability, often an allergy or weakness.'),'Sweeping'=>'Rebirth','Sweeping_Text'=>'The PCs are rejuvenated, refreshed, improved, reborn, or upgraded. Some circumstance will heal the worst of their Wounds, resolve a Hitch, or add an Alternate to a Character. The Alternate is usually uniquely suited for exactly the situation the Character finds themselves in.', 'History'=>'Fresh','History_Description'=>'The Serpent indicates that the past is unimportant to this current situation, that isn\'t to say there isn\'t some back-story, simply that it does not strictly inform or set-up the current situation directly.', 'Situation'=>'Scoundrel', 'Situation_Description'=>'The Serpent indicates that the current situation is created by a scoundrel, often an evil, mendacious trickster. The scoundrel may be a dangerous love interest, a swindler and confidence-trickster, a scruffy looking smuggler, a charming illusionist, a predatory psychic medium or whatever.','Solution'=>'Reason','Solution_Description'=>'The Serpent indicates that the solution to the current situation can be reasoned out logically, rationally, or sometimes intuitively, but still dispassionately, once all impossibilities have been discarded.'), //3
		array('Yarn_Name'=>'The Waters','Yarn_Description'=>'The Waters is a card that can literally mean waters, in the form of a river, a lake or an ocean that is important as a location, motif, or symbol, but it can also be symbolic, standing for the darker, violent emotions, that suddenly explode from out of someone. It can be hidden, deep motifs and meanings too. In these waters unconscious acts stir unpredictable actions.','Significator'=>['Plot'=>'The Waters Plot is deep. It may be that there are a lot of sides, or that the Conflict involves deeper themes than normal. Perhaps it is philosophical, an essay on the existential angst that haunts modern life, or how predestination paradoxes and prophesy counter the concept of free-will. Then again, maybe the Story revolves literally around waters, waves, water-craft, and sailors. ','Side'=>'A side of a Conflict marked by the Deep, will often be deeply affected philosophically or emotionally by the events occurring in the main Conflict. This often leads that side to behave outside what is expected, due to the depth of their feelings.','Character'=>'The Waters Significator indicates a deep, philosophical, emotional Character. <p>They <strong>Gain Yin</strong> when they act calm, thoughtful, or philosophical. </p><p>They <strong>Gain Yang</strong> when they act agitated, emotional or angry. </p><p>They <strong>Gain Chi</strong> when they empathise or reflect another\'s emotions. </p><p>They gain +1 Success Level to all Psyche Attacks.</p>','Scene'=>'The Waters Scene is one that features Water. The Waters often represent a moment of death and rebirth, which is a profound Ordeal or Weft. They don\'t all have to be so deep, sometimes it just means it rains. Yarn-Tellers may play the card to gain deep insights, travel by water, or create Ordeals (including rebirth), as required.'],'Beat_Type'=>'4', 'Conflict_Embodiment'=>'3', 'Facet_Embodiment'=>'16', 'Hook_Aspect'=>'Hitch', 'Aspect_Description'=>'The Hook targets the Character\'s Hitches, specifically this one will target a Quirk. Triggering the Hitch as part of the Hook usually, but offering to resolve this Quirk often too. For example, a Character may be wanted by the law, well this Hook can threaten them with jail or offer them a pardon.','Hook'=>'Rising Waters', 'Hook_Description'=>'The story hooks the character with a slowly rising danger. This can be a literal rising water level, or a sign of worse things to come, such as being teased, before it turns to abuse and bullying. The danger is present now, but may not be taken seriously enough yet.', 'Gain'=>'Water Location (such as a pond, pool, lake, river, shore, beach or a suitable water  vehicle)', 'Fray'=>'Drowning', 'Fray_Description'=>'Drowning is any Ordeal where the Stakes rise rapidly during the Ordeal. Drowning might start as Low Stakes (a pleasant swim or putting a meal on credit card), but it soon escalates until the Stakes are Medium (a current starts to drag them out to sea or they have to take a pay day loan after the car breaks down, until suddenly the stakes are High or even higher (far from shore the sharks start circling or finally they made a deal with the devil to pay off the debt).','Snag'=>'Leaks', 'Snag_Description'=>'After the Fray it appears that there is a leak. This could be a case of getting home to find the Embodiment\'s apartment flooded, or it may mean there is a mole in their organization. Either way some things are damaged or lost, or some information makes its way to the Opposed Embodiment.','NPC'=>array('Archetype'=>'Bully','Persona'=>5,'Core'=>3,'Hitch'=>0,'Description'=>'The Bully likes to get their own way, throwing orders and punches as easily and as often as each other, all bullies though are afraid of something and are driven by fury and fear.'),'Sweeping'=>'Salvage','Sweeping_Text'=>'You rescue someone, or something from destruction. This often is a gain of a treasure descendant, vehicle, location or powerful ally.', 'History'=>'Abyssal','History_Description'=>'The Waters indicates that the history that leads to the current situation is either very deep, stretching back to ancient even prehistoric times, and / or very dark, whether emotional, deadly, grim, wicked, sinister, shadowed or obscured.', 'Situation'=>'Uncontrolled', 'Situation_Description'=>'The Waters indicates that the current situation is not a result of any controlled plan or conspiracy, but has occurred as a random chance, or some unconscious instinct or reaction.','Solution'=>'Outburst','Solution_Description'=>'The Waters indicates that the way out of the current situation will involve a building of pressure, often physically, emotionally, psychologically or even psychically, until there is an outburst of some kind. The only real question is who, or what, the required outburst is meant to burst from.'), //4
		array('Yarn_Name'=>'The Shield','Yarn_Description'=>'The Shield card stands for those that defend us, and those who in turn defend them. The Shield is defence, armour, the thin blue line and a standing army. It can mean that something needs defending, that an attack is coming, and serves as a warning.','Significator'=>['Plot'=>'The Shield Plot seeks to defend a position. The Plot may favour a particular Plot Resolution, and will seek to actively defend that position against the Characters. Such Plots can be frustrating, or exciting, depending upon the situation, and the Players actions and resolve. The Shield Plot usually protects the status-quo of the world, always seeking to return the normal balance to the local universe, but it can be overcome and great change brought about through that paradigm shift. ','Side'=>'When a side is marked by the Shield, they will act as the Guardians of the status-quo during the Plot. Trying to stop the Completion from occurring at all if possible, prolonging the Loom as long as they can, or favouring Rejection, Revelation, Reversion, and Revocation endings in that order.','Character'=>'The Shield Significator indicates a Character who acts to protect society, as well as individuals.<p>They <strong>Gain Yin</strong> when they defend the status-quo, or a weaker Character. </p><p><strong>Gain Yang</strong> when they attack an enemy of the state, criminal or traitor to their society. </p><p>They <strong>Gain Chi</strong> when they protect any group or pact which they are part of. </p><p>They gain +1 Success Levels to all active defences.</p>','Scene'=>'The Shield Scene is usually used as a Weft, to protect or shield the Character from harm. It can be used as a Defence Ordeal, forcing the Character to defend themselves against some attack or accident. Yarn-Tellers usually play this card as an Aegis defence, protecting the target from all damage for the duration of the Scene, although they can try the target\'s defences too.'],'Beat_Type'=>'5', 'Conflict_Embodiment'=>'2', 'Facet_Embodiment'=>'3', 'Hook_Aspect'=>'Incarna', 'Aspect_Description'=>'The Hook targets the Character\'s Incarna, this is often a threat to life and limb, or an offer for healing a significant Wound, training or improvement of the Incarna Facet.','Hook'=>'Tone-Setter', 'Hook_Description'=>'The Conflict Hooks the Character with a powerful, Tone setting Scene. The Tone should reflect the Dominant side of the Conflict, usually an under represented Facet on that side of the Conflict. This tone setting serves as a warning of what to expect later.', 'Gain'=>'A Defence Descendant (armour, gauntlets, shield, anti-virus software, insurance, etc)', 'Fray'=>'Raise Shields', 'Fray_Description'=>'This is total war, and during total war you do not go into battle without putting on armour, strapping on a shield, and raising your deflector fields. This is an Extreme Stakes Opposed Ordeal, where the PCs usually defend a position, vehicle or person that\'s under attack.', 'Snag'=>'Redoubt', 'Snag_Description'=>'The Fray is set at least partially in a fortress, police station, dungeon, maximum security prison, airbase, or similarly well-defended place. During the Redoubt Snag every Stage has at least one Obstacle and double the number normally expected in this sort of Ordeal. Stakes will be raised one higher (and Black Twos Wild), and add in as many Vex and Chorus Extras as you think the PCs can possibly handle, and then a handful of Cast Extras on top, that will be scattered throughout the Redoubt.','NPC'=>array('Archetype'=>'Parent','Persona'=>17,'Core'=>5,'Hitch'=>11,'Description'=>'The Parent is an archetype as common as the Mother, or the Father, they are seen as protectors, but family situations often cause arguments.'),'Sweeping'=>'Protected','Sweeping_Text'=>'The PCs will be protected, usually by an Ally and/or Location from a Warp (The Ends, The Fray & The Snag) that <strong><em>does</em></strong> affect the other side(s) of the Conflict.', 'History'=>'Defence','History_Description'=>'The Shield indicates that before the current situation there was a suitable defensive force that defended everyone from this precise problem, what happened to it is probably the source of the current situation.', 'Situation'=>'Defend', 'Situation_Description'=>'The Shield indicates that the current situation will require you to defend yourself, often from a more powerful opponent, although you usually have an advantage in defences.','Solution'=>'Guard','Solution_Description'=>'The Shield indicates that the solution to the current situation is to guard and keep watch, the enemy will reveal themselves eventually, and you must be ready.'), //5
		array('Yarn_Name'=>'The Horde','Yarn_Description'=>'The Horde card signifies a huge crowd and the madness of crowds. Hordes are not calmly queuing citizens. Hordes ravage, pillage and loot, they are rioting, revolutionary, reactionary things. They may be formed from a stampede, panic amongst an orderly crowd can quickly create an unthinking horde.','Significator'=>['Plot'=>'The Horde Plot is about numbers, usually big numbers, occasionally there may be literal mathematics involved, but more normally this is a tale with scores of Characters and plenty of sides. These are Epic plots usually that reflect society from top to bottom, and may span multiple kingdoms or worlds. The main weapon of the Horde Plot is the Sub-Plot, and you can expect additional Arcs and Stories galore, which each Character having at least an Arc of their own, that will interact at least once with one other Character\'s Story. ','Side'=>'When a side is marked by the Horde, they are legion, they can take Pact-Descendant Embodiments, even if they have none, but most of these Embodiments will be a suitable Archetype Character that meets as many of  the Embodiment criteria as possible.','Character'=>'The Horde Significator indicates a Character who is legion. They might be a hive mind, or a linear reincarnation with multi-life recall. <p>They <strong>Gain Yin</strong> when they focus on the bigger picture, ignore details, or act without thinking. </p><p>They <strong>Gain Yang</strong> when they react strongly to something they\'ve seen or heard, or share information with others.</p><p>They <strong>Gain Chi</strong> when they work or attack with others. </p><p>They gain +1 Success Levels to all actions where they can use their Horde lives together (multiple bodies or information from past lives, etc).</p>','Scene'=>'The Horde Scene is a crowd scene. Crowd scenes are commonly used to invoke a sense of scale, huge crowds have a realism to them all of their own. Yarn-Tellers may play the card to create a large force, usually of allies, to arrive. This often results in an Ordeal, but the Horde can ride in like the Cavalry and lift a bad situation too.'],'Beat_Type'=>'6', 'Conflict_Embodiment'=>'2', 'Facet_Embodiment'=>'12', 'Hook_Aspect'=>'I-Ching (2nd Hexagram)', 'Aspect_Description'=>'The Hook targets the Character\'s I-Ching specifically the Gain of their second Hexagram. For example: If a Character has the Cauldron (50) I-Ching as their 2nd Hexagram, then the Hook needs to have someone hungry turn up asking for help.','Hook'=>'Crowd Scene', 'Hook_Description'=>'The story opens with a crowd scene, perhaps a sporting event, concert, theatre performance or just a busy shopping district. This scene can be Tone setting, with musical leading the way, or brutal sports, or it could be just the setting for a sudden burst of action from a Fray.', 'Gain'=>'Membership (new Pack Descendant or Level of same)', 'Fray'=>'Stampede', 'Fray_Description'=>'This Ordeal is usually a high Stakes every one for themselves Motional Ordeal. Stampedes are often caused by another disaster, such as earthquakes, tsunamis, mudslides, floods, fires, and terrorists. The point is huge crowds become very dangerous when everyone starts running in the same direction. Architects design buildings to minimise these risks, but people get both inventive and stupid when the pressure is on.', 'Snag'=>'Numbers', 'Snag_Description'=>'The Numbers Snag can add Numbers to the enemy, multiplying the number of Extras by at least two. This can mean additional forces during the Fray, or it can mean reinforcements afterwards. In some Frays additional Numbers wouldn\'t hurt, so follow those with a Low to High Stakes Opposed Ordeal against a number of Chorus or Vex Extras.','NPC'=>array('Archetype'=>'Zombie','Persona'=>18,'Core'=>18,'Hitch'=>21,'Description'=>'The Zombie can be an example of the walking dead, stumbling or running to consume the next thing. Sometimes they are even undead, mostly they are just sleepwalking through life, staring at a phone screen.'),'Sweeping'=>'Party','Sweeping_Text'=>'The PCs and the pressed side get to party and congregate, letting their hair down together, this can be a bonding moment, or the Opposed Side Embodiment may suffer a Snag while the party is happening. ', 'History'=>'Chaos','History_Description'=>'The Horde indicates that the current situation was created by a chaotic event, such as a huge riot, enormous melee, peasants revolt, or anarchic revolution.', 'Situation'=>'Revolution', 'Situation_Description'=>'The Horde indicates that there are massed forces around you that are working against authority and probably indirectly you. Revolution is fermenting in the streets and houses, usually this is a revolt of the peasants and middle class against the nobility, slaves against slave-owners, or robot-uprisings against their squishy, juicy masters, but other revolutions are possible.','Solution'=>'Overwhelm','Solution_Description'=>'The Horde indicates that the current situation can be resolved most easily by overwhelming it with massive numbers, this might be numbers of people, watts of power, volts of electricity, joules of energy, or even number of tasks, the point is everyone and everything has limits, and can be overwhelmed.'), //6
		array('Yarn_Name'=>'The Crystal','Yarn_Description'=>'The Crystal represents both riches and the fragility of finery. Riches are easily bestowed by the card, but easily taken away again too. The Crystal can represent a change of circumstances, clarity of purpose, or signify a flaw or weakness that is hidden, but very important.','Significator'=>['Plot'=>'The Crystal Plot is about changing circumstances and fortunes. It may appear like a Rags-To-Riches story, but there is more emphasis on realising that money is essentially worthless, and that human connections are more important than money. ','Side'=>'A side marked with the Crystal is getting richer off the events of the Plot, somehow they are making bank off the Conflict, this might be through taxes, sales, services provided or because off a Robin Hood style vigilante, depending upon the genre and era.','Character'=>'The Crystal Significator indicates a Character who so rich that money has no meaning to them. <p>They <strong>Gain Yin</strong> when they listen to another talk. </p><p>They <strong>Gain Yang</strong> when they give advice, aid or time to another. </p><p>They <strong>Gain Chi</strong> when they give Chi or Descendants to other Characters. </p><p>They gain +1 Success Level on all Purchase or summoning Tests and Ordeal actions.</p>','Scene'=>'The Crystal Scene is a point where a great gain is made by the Characters. This may be the final reward, or it may be the McGuffin or some other important Plot Device, it can even be a Revelation of exactly what the Characters need to do to win. Yarn-Tellers may play this card for either a specific Gain (such as "The Grail is mine!"), or a Specific Revelation (such as "I need to know, how do I kill <em>this</em> immortal?".'],'Beat_Type'=>'7', 'Conflict_Embodiment'=>'0', 'Facet_Embodiment'=>'3', 'Hook_Aspect'=>'Hitch', 'Aspect_Description'=>'The Hook targets the Character\'s worst Hitch (usually a Flaw or a Woe) and may trigger it or offer to resolve it as required to Hook the Character.','Hook'=>'Payment', 'Hook_Description'=>'The Story hooks the by offering to pay them. It could be that this plot is part of their normal job, the next case, or delivery, or it might be that they are specifically offered money to look into (or perhaps turn a blind eye to) something.', 'Gain'=>'Treasure Descendant', 'Fray'=>'Crystal Ball', 'Fray_Description'=>'The Fray is an attempt to spy upon the enemy, or predict the future somehow, this may involve a trip to a fortune-teller, or running simulations, or use of Wyrd or Yarn abilities. Regardless of method, the fray consists of trying to create a Chronolith of a suitable size to fix a point in the future, or observe the past, or the enemy\'s current position. This is normally done with a Solitary or Opposed Ordeal of Paradoxical Stakes.', 'Snag'=>'Flawed', 'Snag_Description'=>'The Flawed Snag can express a few different ways depending upon narrative requirements. The Snag can trigger the PCs Flaws during the Fray (or following), or it can attempt to create a new Flaw. Alternatively, the Snag can indicate that the PC\'s plan is flawed, and that the result of the Fray will not be what they expected, or wanted.','NPC'=>array('Archetype'=>'Thief','Persona'=>1,'Core'=>13,'Hitch'=>18,'Description'=>'Thieves see nothing wrong with taking something shiny of someone else. They usually have an environment that they prefer to operate in or on (highways, crowds, banks, homes, museums, etc), and all those wanted posters would make anyone feel persecuted.'),'Sweeping'=>'Crystal Clear','Sweeping_Text'=>'This Sweeping grants the PCs a moment of clarity. The Referee or Yarn-Teller should use direct exposition to explain the situation properly to the PC. This can be handled as the PC making this realisation themselves, and a good Yarn-Teller can sometimes arrange this, but if the attempt fails the Yarn-Teller or Ref should be prepared to explain what\'s really going on. Sometimes this sort of exposition can be handled via Villain monologues, or confessions, but they are not compatible with every genre.', 'History'=>'Risen','History_Description'=>'The Crystal indicates that the history that led to the current situation was a rise of some sort, this may be a rise in wealth, rank, social standing, or something boring like power. Entire empires can rise on the basis of a Crystal History, but more commonly smaller pacts or individuals are usually effected.', 'Situation'=>'Fragile', 'Situation_Description'=>'The Crystal indicates that the current situation is fragile, delicate or easily broken. This is a situation that is about to change, usually for the worse.','Solution'=>'Exploit','Solution_Description'=>'The Crystal indicates that the solution to the current problem is to exploit some flaw in the opposition. This may mean actually directly targeting a Hitch, but more often indicates there is a flaw in their plan, operation, or base that can be exploited somehow.'), //7
		array('Yarn_Name'=>'The Scythe','Yarn_Description'=>'The Scythe card represents an honest day\'s work, usually manual labour, often field or yard work (throughout human history) in a hot harvest sun, but it can represent any work with tools, labour, gathering or harvest activities. The Scythe can also represent danger at work, and of course has a long association with both Death and Time.','Significator'=>['Plot'=>'The Scythe Plot is about everyday life and death. Death is a hum-drum event, it is constantly occurring all around us, this Plot shows us that, but often not through violence or pestilence. The Scythe is a Plot of small, everyday dramas, soap opera, ordinary lives stuff, but death is always a part of that Tapestry. Old people, the ill, the careless, the unlucky, the Scythe may take a swing at them all, and keeps swinging until someone dies. ','Side'=>'When a side is marked with the Scythe then one of the Embodiments is slated to die. It may be the event that kicks off the Conflict as an inciting event, or it may occur in the Zenith, but at least one Embodiment on that side must die.','Character'=>'The Scythe Significator indicates a Character that works hard and expects rewards.<p>They <strong>Gain Yin</strong> when they complain, grumble, or moan. </p><p>They <strong>Gain Yang</strong> when they do work. </p><p>They <strong>Gain Chi</strong> when they rest, or are paid after work. </p><p>They gain +1 Success Levels to any task when they complain about it.</p>','Scene'=>'The Scythe Scene is an Ordeal or Test usually, that features hard work, or work-related injuries, although it can be a Gain in terms of a payment or reward that has been earned. Yarn-Tellers can play the card to injure or just make things harder for a target, or to perform an arduous task automatically such as gathering food, or as a payment such as a salary.'],'Beat_Type'=>'6', 'Conflict_Embodiment'=>'2', 'Facet_Embodiment'=>'6', 'Hook_Aspect'=>'Skills', 'Aspect_Description'=>'The Hook targets the Character\'s Skills indicating that only someone with those precise skills can truly solve this problem. The opposition may even be targeting people known to possess certain Skills.','Hook'=>'Reap What Was Sowed', 'Hook_Description'=>'The Story opens with a call back to something that happened in a previous Story. This story could be a spin-off from the original, or this could just be a reuse of a location, descendant or character.', 'Gain'=>'Personalised Tool (Trophy/Monolith)', 'Fray'=>'Labour', 'Fray_Description'=>'Hard Work and Labour is usually an Extended Ordeal, there is not often opposition, but there may be a requirement for multiple people to work together, or at a pace. The Stakes are usually Low or Medium, but higher Stakes Labour exist (miners, lumberjacks and crab fisherman spring to mind as high or extreme Stakes labour). The point is this work is hard, sweaty, exhausting and will push the PCs to exhaustion.', 'Snag'=>'Scythes, Pitchforks and Torches', 'Snag_Description'=>'When Peasants revolt they have a tendency to grab anything that they can use as a weapon, considering their day to day life involves mowing grass with scythes, lifting the mowed grass with pitchforks and so on they get quite well trained with these tools. This Snag means that whomever is involved in the Fray they are more heavily armed (and better equipped and trained) than you might have imagined. ','NPC'=>array('Archetype'=>'Farmhand','Persona'=>5,'Core'=>1,'Hitch'=>13,'Description'=>'The Farmhand is a simple labourer who happens to be an expert with their preferred tool, whether it be a scythe, a rope, a tractor, or moisture-vaporator'),'Sweeping'=>'Reaping','Sweeping_Text'=>'The PCs will make a major Gain (such as a harvest) if they succeed in a Test or Ordeal (such as Harvesting).', 'History'=>'Worked','History_Description'=>'The Scythe indicates that history leading to this current situation has been worked for by someone. This may mean it was someone\'s full-time job, or just that lots of people helped some mastermind.', 'Situation'=>'Danger', 'Situation_Description'=>'The Scythe indicates that the current situation is dangerous, often this is an occupational hazard, some sort of danger at work, which may be accidental or deliberate. Often this danger will be great enough to raise the Stakes to High or more.','Solution'=>'Tool','Solution_Description'=>'The Scythe indicates that the solution to the current situation is a specialised tool that must be acquired, created, invented, purchased, stolen, summoned or found somehow.'), //8
		array('Yarn_Name'=>'The Crown','Yarn_Description'=>'The Crown is the card of Leadership. It stands for Leaders, Commanders, Monarchy and Politicians. Uneasy lies the head that wears the Crown though, and those in power have additional worries, responsibilities and other troublesome Hitches. The Crown can serve as a warning for Leaders to look within, to act for those they lead, not themselves or ruin may follow. But it can also warn followers to watch those they choose to follow.','Significator'=>['Plot'=>'The Crown Plot is usually a Political Thriller, these are stories of alliances, enmities, betrayals and treaties. There\'s a lot going on and usually a lot at stake. The fates of countries and worlds are decided by Crown Plots, but so too are the fates of businesses and families. ','Side'=>'A side marked by the Crown will face tough leadership decisions, this may be because of the Internal side, which may be placed entirely within the Crown marked Side, or it may be because of another side of the Conflict, as the Yarn-Teller sees fit.','Character'=>'The Crown Significator indicates an absolute monarch, at least within their territory. <p>They <strong>Gain Yin</strong> when they speak to their followers, act emotional, or listen to others. </p><p>They <strong>Gain Yang</strong> when they behave aloof, or polite, use logic, or amuse themselves. </p><p>They <strong>Gain Chi</strong> when they act for the benefit of their followers, country or people. </p><p>They gain +1 Success Levels to all Psyche Defences.</p>','Scene'=>'The Crown Scene is usually a demonstration of power. This may be an Ordeal or more usually it will be an immense Gain (often of a powerful Lore Artefact) with an appropriate Revelation. Yarn-Tellers can play a Crown to have people follow them, gain treasures, or demonstrate their power (usually with an extreme use of their Power or Super-Annex).'],'Beat_Type'=>'7', 'Conflict_Embodiment'=>'1', 'Facet_Embodiment'=>'12', 'Hook_Aspect'=>'Gains', 'Aspect_Description'=>'The Hook targets all ways the Character can Gain Chi, Yin or Yang, combining as many ways to trigger as many as possible into the situation.','Hook'=>'Commanded', 'Hook_Description'=>'The Hook of this Story is simply that the PC is ordered to follow the Plot (investigate the mystery, secure the asset, overthrow the government, etc) by their boss, monarch, superior officer or spouse.', 'Gain'=>'Trophy / Monolith Treasure Descendant', 'Fray'=>'Society', 'Fray_Description'=>'Sometimes we all need a leg up, and friends are the people to do that. Making and keeping friends can be Ordeals in their own right, especially when one is talking about joining clubs, guilds and fraternity houses. Fortunately, they are usually low Stakes, but Opposed by large numbers of people at the same time.', 'Snag'=>'Responsibilities', 'Snag_Description'=>'The Crown demands responsibility from the PCs. Something about the Fray is the PCs personal responsibility. Perhaps they caused some collateral damage and hence are directly responsible for fixing the damage, or is it a case of some old decision they made has just come back to bite them.','NPC'=>array('Archetype'=>'Diplomat','Persona'=>21,'Core'=>16,'Hitch'=>15,'Description'=>'The Diplomat is a mediator, they\'re job is working out treaties and problems.'),'Sweeping'=>'Taxes','Sweeping_Text'=>'The Taxes of the Crown might indicate the PCs collecting taxes from their subjects, or they might be getting a rebate from taxes they have already paid. Either way, they\'ll gain Chi, or a Treasure Descendant.', 'History'=>'Politicized','History_Description'=>'The Crown indicates that the current situation has a history of political intrigues, conflicts and agendas that have led to it becoming something of a political football.', 'Situation'=>'Responsibility', 'Situation_Description'=>'The Crown indicates that the current situation is one where someone is shirking a responsibility, usually of a leadership nature. It could be a king who ignores the pleas of his western barons for aid, a dock-master who is turning a blind eye to a smuggler, or a businessman who isn\'t paying his staff minimum wage.','Solution'=>'Leadership','Solution_Description'=>'The Crown indicates that the solution to the current situation is good leadership, which can sometimes mean the current leader must act, but also sometimes means new leadership must be found.'), //9
		array('Yarn_Name'=>'The Guardian','Yarn_Description'=>'The Guardian card represents the people who protect us. From Parents and Teachers to friends and even social systems such as City Watch or Police. The Guardian will always look out for us, helping us to avoid the worst situations and injuries, as long as we heed their warnings, and they are trustworthy.','Significator'=>['Plot'=>'The Guardian Plot is often a plot about families. These may be coming of age tales (and often are), but a Guardian and Ward relationship will be important to this Plot. Guardian Plots can also fall into Police procedural lines, and Superhero adventures, where protecting others is an important plot point.','Side'=>'A side of the conflict marked by the Guardian will ally themselves with another side of the Conflict, often the Pressed or Below sides, protecting them and acting against their Rivals or enemies.','Character'=>'The Guardian Significator indicates a protector, who guides as well as guards. <p>They <strong>Gain Yin</strong> when they watch or listen to those they would protect, or comfort those who are injured. </p><p>They <strong>Gain Yang</strong> when they offer advice or guide others. They <strong>Gain Chi</strong> when they act to protect or shield another. </p><p>They gain +1 Success Level when they act to assist one of their wards.</p>','Scene'=>'The Guardian Scene is one of the major Ordeals of the Story. Guardians patrol the thresholds of adventure, and must be bested somehow. This may be a coming of age test, or a Guardian Monster Ordeal. Yarn-Tellers can use this card to unleash a Guardian Monster, perhaps as an Ally, perhaps not, they can also be used as a defence, or as a Mentor ally Gain.'],'Beat_Type'=>'8', 'Conflict_Embodiment'=>'2', 'Facet_Embodiment'=>'14', 'Hook_Aspect'=>'Hitch', 'Aspect_Description'=>'The Hook targets the Character\'s Hitches, triggering and threatening to trigger as many as possible at once.','Hook'=>'Help!', 'Hook_Description'=>'The Hook is a direct call to help from someone (usually at least a Cast Extra) such as an Ally or Friend.', 'Gain'=>'A Cast Extra Ally with Power Descendant Armour', 'Fray'=>'Protect and Serve', 'Fray_Description'=>'The Fray is trying to keep people safe in a dangerous situation. Maybe the PCs are cops during a riot, or perhaps there is a natural disaster and very one has to pitch in, then again maybe someone the PCs have a Duty or Devotion to is at risk.', 'Snag'=>'Untrustworthy Guardian', 'Snag_Description'=>'Whether its a bad cop or a demonic schoolteacher, an untrustworthy guardian is a complication that can make things bad for everyone involved.','NPC'=>array('Archetype'=>'Guard','Persona'=>17,'Core'=>1,'Hitch'=>5,'Description'=>'Guards, whether body, security, military, prison, royal or city guards are all essentially the same.'),'Sweeping'=>'Safe House','Sweeping_Text'=>'The Pressed Embodiment finds a safe house. A Location where they can regroup and heal, that is unknown to, or otherwise protected from, the other sides.', 'History'=>'Guarded','History_Description'=>'The Guardian indicates that in the past someone or something was guarded or protected.', 'Situation'=>'Patrol', 'Situation_Description'=>'The Guardian indicates the current situation concerns a patrol, this may be a trek through your own territory, neutral territory or a border with enemy territory, or the enemy patrolling the same.','Solution'=>'Watch','Solution_Description'=>'The Guardian indicates that the solution to the current situation is to remain on guard, watching out for the enemy or their allies. Watch for the enemy and they will reveal themselves, watch the enemy when they appear and they will reveal their weaknesses.'), //10
		array('Yarn_Name'=>'The Tempest','Yarn_Description'=>'The Tempest is the card of violent disturbance. People are scared, afraid, and otherwise perturbed by the violence of this situation, be it of the weather or a Character. Tempests can be tumultuous events of almost any sort, storms, wars, shipwrecks, political upheavals, coups, etc. It is a period of destruction, where the old is torn down, not necessarily to make way for the new.','Significator'=>['Plot'=>'The Tempest Plot is about destruction and tearing down the old world. Huge changes and shifts in social norms are indicated by the Tempest. It is the Plot of disaster movies, apocalypses and wars. ','Side'=>'When a side is marked by the Tempest things will not go well for it. The side may be destroyed, torn apart from within, but sometimes a new replacement Embodiment will appear within the chaos and lead what remains of this side as a stronger, changed version of the side.','Character'=>'The Tempest Significator indicates a Character who is violent and unpredictable.<p>They <strong>Gain Yin</strong> when they are attacked. </p><p>They <strong>Gain Yang</strong> when they attack. </p><p>They <strong>Gain Chi</strong> when they act randomly or react violently. </p><p>They also gain +1 Success Level on every attack.</p>','Scene'=>'The Tempest Scene is usually a survival Ordeal, caused by foul weather, it often throws unlikely people together as they try to survive the turmoil. Yarn-Tellers can play the card to evoke an enormous disaster that will usually befall their enemies, although they do occasionally get out of hand.'],'Beat_Type'=>'4', 'Conflict_Embodiment'=>'3', 'Facet_Embodiment'=>'9', 'Hook_Aspect'=>'I-Ching', 'Aspect_Description'=>'The Hook targets the Character\'s I-Ching. For example: If a Character has the Cauldron (50) I-Ching, then the Hook needs to have someone hungry turn up asking for help.','Hook'=>'It Was A Dark And Stormy Night...', 'Hook_Description'=>'The Story opens with inclement weather, this may reflect the Conflict in some strange way, or simply be a bad night to be out. Into this night is injected a scene of violence, perhaps a murder or assault. It might be the PCs who are attacked, or more likely the dying stranger at their door.', 'Gain'=>'Monolith / Chronolith or Artefact', 'Fray'=>'Tempest', 'Fray_Description'=>'A Tempest is a storm or similar huge event (Terrorist attack, aerial bombardment, war front, tsunami, volcano, etc) that uses 1-12 Force-Of-Nature Extras, or go for a Kaiju in extreme circumstances, to create an Extreme Stakes Motional Ordeal. These events are destructive to Locations / Stages which can result in paths being closed or creating new obstacles. Ideally, the PCs should have their own goals, entirely separate to the Tempest that they are trying to complete against this backdrop of destruction.', 'Snag'=>'Alarming', 'Snag_Description'=>'Ideally, one of the Embodiment\'s Allies, or a random passer-by, is disturbed by the actions, or sight of, of the PCs. This is especially common in bestial or ghostly Characters who didn\'t mean to scare the little girl... Alternatively, the Fray will be complicated by an alarm being triggered, usually by the PCs actions, this can include, Police Alarms, Fire Alarms, Security Alerts, Lock downs, or screams.','NPC'=>array('Archetype'=>'Prince','Persona'=>3,'Core'=>5,'Hitch'=>23,'Description'=>'A Prince is a noble ruler of an area, often brutal and inexperienced, they are usually defined by their doubts and how they deal with them.'),'Sweeping'=>'False Completion','Sweeping_Text'=>'This Sweeping causes the PCs to think that their struggle is over, that they have won early. But this is just the Eye of the Storm, the storm will return. This is occasionally some attempt by the other sides to trick or flush out the PCs, but this should be used rarely and with care, more normally it is a chance to recover and rest, and perhaps a little preparation before the storm returns.', 'History'=>'Destroyed','History_Description'=>'The Tempest indicates that the past leading to the current situation was destructive, attacks, fires and natural disasters like storms can wreck ships, destroy homes and relationships.', 'Situation'=>'Storm', 'Situation_Description'=>'The Tempest indicates that the current situation is a storm of some kind, often this is a natural event, as in a lightning or snow storm, but sometimes this may be a blitzkrieg, bombing campaign or invasion. The Tempest always indicates great danger and at least high stakes are in play.','Solution'=>'Violence','Solution_Description'=>'The Tempest indicates that the solution to the current situation is an act of violence. Of course, there is an ethical debate here, but in this situation violence will succeed.' ), //J
		array('Yarn_Name'=>'The Inn','Yarn_Description'=>'The Inn card represents the den of iniquity, impropriety, sins and vices that every society has. The Inn may simply be the place that exotic outsiders stay in town, but more often it is the place of shady deals, criminal and immoral activities and recreational intoxicants. It offers satisfaction, comfort, protection, anonymity, and a certain lack of consequences to those who visit, with hints of adventure, rebelliousness, risk, and even danger for those that seek it.','Significator'=>['Plot'=>'The Inn Plot is about sins, dirty secrets and adult situations. There is always an air of adventure to the Inn, a temptation that can be a part of coming of age plots, and such like, but is more normally a part of a deeper awakening.','Side'=>'The side of a conflict marked by the Inn will have a good time during the plot, they may party, dance, love, drink, eat and generally be merry, sure there may be drama, fights, even a duel or two, but they will survive and enjoy themselves anyway, usually.','Character'=>'The Inn Significator indicates a Character who revels in the joys of life.<p>They <strong>Gain Yin</strong> when they take pleasure in something. </p><p>They <strong>Gain Yang</strong> when they tempt others. </p><p>They <strong>Gain Chi</strong> when they enjoy something socially. </p><p>They also gain +1 Success Level on all passive defences.</p>','Scene'=>'The Inn Scene is usually a Character\'s first taste of a wider world. There are strange folk in the Inn, some look weird, some speak weird, some just are weird and a few want weird things. A Yarn-Teller can play the Inn Scene to secure themselves a place to stay, or play, or a chance to meet new people.'],'Beat_Type'=>'5', 'Conflict_Embodiment'=>'3', 'Facet_Embodiment'=>'11', 'Hook_Aspect'=>'I-Ching', 'Aspect_Description'=>'The Hook targets the Character\'s I-Ching. For example: If a Character has the Cauldron (50) I-Ching, then the Hook needs to have someone hungry turn up asking for help.','Hook'=>'The Stranger Arrives', 'Hook_Description'=>'The Story opens with a stranger arriving in town. This person may be a Rival or an Embodiment, but more normally is some unknown Ally who brings the PCs some warning or message about a threat beyond the town.', 'Gain'=>'Dark Territory (a Twist riddled Location)', 'Fray'=>'Social Drinking', 'Fray_Description'=>'The Fray involves a complex social Ordeal, usually of Medium Stakes, although higher and lower Stakes versions are possible. There will be drinks, usually alcoholic, which may be replaced or augmented by other recreational drugs. This Fray is social and allows Characters to alter their social status with other Characters, earning respect, friendship or enmity as appropriate.', 'Snag'=>'Illegal or Immoral', 'Snag_Description'=>'Something about the situation is either Illegal or Immoral, ideally it should be a choice between immoral or illegal (such as keeping slaves being immoral, but freeing slaves being illegal).', 'NPC'=>array('Archetype'=>'Bar-tender','Persona'=>12,'Core'=>16,'Hitch'=>10,'Description'=>'The Bar-tender is a common archetype, you\'ll find one behind most bars. They enjoy meeting people and don\'t mind hearing another\'s problems and offering them beverages. May sometimes cross over with Priests and Cleric types, who also practice listening to problems and offering beverages.'),'Sweeping'=>'Party!','Sweeping_Text'=>'The PCs may have cause to celebrate from recent events, more likely they want to distract themselves from recent events with a celebration. There will be drinks, there will be music or games, and there is usually food (often cake). It may be a Character\'s birthday, or a similar anniversary, or a feast or festival.', 'History'=>'Visited','History_Description'=>'The Inn indicates that in the history of the current situation there was a visitation, someone came, or went and visited somewhere. This visit may have been a vacation, a business trip, research, some family emergency, or may even have supernatural or alien connotations.', 'Situation'=>'Hospitality', 'Situation_Description'=>'The Inn indicates that the current situation is one where either you find yourself receiving guests, or you are a guest. This situation can be pleasant or stressful as you may be unfamiliar with each other, when there may be culture shocks on both sides, or you may be too familiar with each other, which can create its own stresses. Hospitality always has its limits, although different lines will be drawn in different cultures.','Solution'=>'Immorality','Solution_Description'=>'The Inn indicates that the solution to the current situation lies in the immoral. Sometimes this may mean contacting the "criminal underworld" to make illegal purchases, other times it means not making it home that night.'), //Q
		array('Yarn_Name'=>'The Færy Noble','Yarn_Description'=>'The F&aelig;ry Noble card stands for the Lords of the Fae. It represents power, of an unearthly, paradoxical, fateful, magical, cruel or capricious nature. It can be a sign of erratic, irrational, or even insane seeming behaviour, but says there\'s a reason beneath. The F&aelig;ry Noble can be involved in important historical events, but you are just as likely to find one engaged in something mundane (at least from their point of view) such as painting the dawn red to warn shepherds of rain. Then again sometimes the card represents a Leader or Mentor who is "(Fairy-)Touched(-in-the-head)". Here again, the irrationality may be signs of genius, prophecy, or insanity, or a mixture.','Significator'=>['Plot'=>'The F&aelig;ry Noble Plot is a tale of imagination and fantasy. Any fantasy so fantastic that it may be a dream, is suitable for the F&aelig;ry Noble. Madness and magic are common themes and you can expect reality warping Yarn-Telling as a common thread. Often these Fantasy events are tied to some idea of prophecy, karma or destiny. ','Side'=>'A side of a conflict marked by the F&aelig;ry Noble are sometimes actually Fae, or time-travellers, trying to keep destiny or history on track.','Character'=>'The F&aelig;ry Noble Significator indicates a powerful, capricious Character. <p>They <strong>Gain Yin</strong> by changing their mind. </p><p>They <strong>Gain Yang</strong> by using their Annexes. </p><p>They <strong>Gain Chi</strong> by utilizing deeper structures than logic, or linear time, which can appear as acting crazy to normal people.</p><p>They gain +1 Success Levels when Stakes are Paradoxical.</p>','Scene'=>'The F&aelig;ry Noble Scene is one where the world is inverted, tipped upside down, or otherwise reordered. Trivial Events are magnified in importance and important events rendered pointless. F&aelig;ry Nobles always seem to appear near great events (although are oddly focused on something else entirely). Yarn-Tellers may play the card to evoke magical, reality altering powers, travel to inner realms, dreams, or other worlds, or use it to summon time-travelling hyper-dimensional beings without human weaknesses like feelings or conscience (if you want).'],'Beat_Type'=>'9', 'Conflict_Embodiment'=>'1', 'Facet_Embodiment'=>'6', 'Hook_Aspect'=>'I-Ching', 'Aspect_Description'=>'The Hook targets the Character\'s I-Ching. For example: If a Character has the Cauldron (50) I-Ching, then the Hook needs to have someone hungry turn up asking for help.','Hook'=>'Danger', 'Hook_Description'=>'The Hook just consists of some enormous danger, it isn\'t looming, it isn\'t coming, it is right here, right now.', 'Gain'=>'Extremely Powerful Yarn-Teller Ally / Artefact Power Descendant', 'Fray'=>'Magic', 'Fray_Description'=>'Maybe there\'s a Ward, a Runic barrier, an Alchemical Seal, or some dark and sinister Psibertek involved, but magic is in the Fray, and the PCs better have a mage on their side. Magic can come in a lot of different flavours, spells and cantrips, glamours and illusions, necromancy, scrying, summoning, invocations and evocations. This is usually a Low to Paradoxical Opposed, Co-operative or occasionally Solitary Ordeal.', 'Snag'=>'Changeable', 'Snag_Description'=>'The Fray is complicated by a changing or changeable situation. Perhaps a race is occurring in a tidal area, or perhaps the Villain is capricious and changes their plan during the middle of the Fray. Maybe the PCs goals should change mid-way through the Fray, as having promised to win, they are made to promise to lose or vice versa.','NPC'=>array('Archetype'=>'King','Persona'=>3,'Core'=>13,'Hitch'=>8,'Description'=>'Kings are Leaders who feel a Duty to protect their subjects not just lead them.'),'Sweeping'=>'Heirophant','Sweeping_Text'=>'The PCs meet a Heirophant or Prophetess Mentor Character who can explain everything, and usually has some special ability the Character\'s will require. This is a combined Gain Ally/Training/Lore Descendant and Revelation. Think Obi-Wan or the Oracle.', 'History'=>'Destined','History_Description'=>'The F&aelig;ry Noble indicates that the history that leads to the current situation is somehow destined or pre-ordained somehow. It may simply be that the historical record includes portents, signs, omens or fore-shadowing of the current situation.', 'Situation'=>'Madness', 'Situation_Description'=>'The F&aelig;ry Noble indicates that the current situation is one that would sound mad if you tried to explain it to someone not involved, this may be due to magic, temporal paradoxes, weird alternate dimensions, supernatural happenings or actual mental illness as required.','Solution'=>'Instability','Solution_Description'=>'The F&aelig;ry Noble indicates that the solution to the current problem is to destabilise it somehow, this may be best achieved through illogical, erratic, capriciousness, impulsive, whimsical, or quirky behaviour, such as you might find among geniuses and lunatics.'), //K
		//spades
		array('Yarn_Name'=>'The Threshold','Yarn_Description'=>'The Threshold Card represents doorways, portals and liminal spaces. It is the edge of something else, a place where one goes from one place to another, often with different rules. It is a card of paradigm shifts, of new places. Great changes, events and dangers may lie ahead, and it is not too late to turn back, but then fresh understandings will not be gained, and no new discoveries will be made.','Significator'=>['Plot'=>'The Threshold Plot is often one of invasion. Of course, who the invaders are, and how they invade varies from Plot to Plot. Threshold Plots can be about stepping into another world (Portal Fantasies), exploring strange new lands, uninvited guests, F&aelig;ry visitors, hauntings, or space invaders. ','Side'=>'A side marked by the Threshold is marked as liminal somehow, they may be on the cusp of a decision perhaps whether to ally with one or the other of the other sides, or they may have contacts beyond this Story, or even world, then again they may be a group of Heroes or Yarn-Tellers that have Alternates in another Era or universe.','Character'=>'The Threshold Significator indicates a Character who is between two worlds, perhaps on the cusp between one thing and another. <p>They <strong>Gain Yin</strong> when they act confused, tired, or shy. </p><p>They <strong>Gain Yang</strong> when they act like a know-it-all, or act arrogant or confident. </p><p>They <strong>Gain Chi</strong> when they cross a Threshold, enter a new space, or notice the time (usually by dusk or dawn). </p><p>They gain +1 Success Levels to all actions in liminal spaces and times (at dusk, midnight, new years, doorways, crossroads etc)</p>','Scene'=>'The Threshold Scene usually represents some portal or barrier that must be overcome or penetrated. A Yarn-Teller may play the card to create a portal or other connection between Locations, which may be permanent or temporary as required, or may play the card to create a Threshold that acts as a barrier that must be overcome with a Test, Ordeal or Quest. A truly crafty Yarn-Teller could even send someone to another lifetime as a distraction.'],'Beat_Type'=>'1', 'Conflict_Embodiment'=>'3', 'Facet_Embodiment'=>'9',  'Hook_Aspect'=>'Hitches', 'Aspect_Description'=>'The Hook targets the Character\'s Hitches, the bigger the better.','Hook'=>'Kick in the door', 'Hook_Description'=>'The Story opens with action, often a Fight, it could be the PCs who kick in a door, or an enemy may burst in.', 'Gain'=>'Ref Special: e.g. (Immortality)', 'Fray'=>'The Edge of the World', 'Fray_Description'=>'This is as bad as a Threshold can get, it is the liminal space between the known and the unknown. It might be the edge of a map, the ocean over the horizon, the edge of space, or the mouth of a cave. Usually such portals and thresholds will have some sort of guardian that must be defeated, sneaked or riddled past with an Ordeal.', 'Snag'=>'The End of the Day', 'Snag_Description'=>'Sometimes the Snag is due to the time which adds some extra complications to the situation. Perhaps the faltering dusk light makes it harder to be spotted, or the first light of dawn may be what shows your silhouettes to the enemy. Then again the night of first frosts, first snows, or the first day of the thaw are all good complications too).','NPC'=>array('Archetype'=>'Hero','Persona'=>6,'Core'=>6,'Hitch'=>8,'Description'=>'The Hero is always the first to volunteer, and the last to quit, they are the star of many an 80\'s action movie.'),'Sweeping'=>'On the Threshold','Sweeping_Text'=>'A quiet moment, almost an aside from the plot, that allows the PCs a breather before they push on. It usually occurs before some major event, while opening a door, or entering or exiting a space, and is often marked by one of the Plot\'s Motifs. They may have fallen in a dark hole, but upon climbing out, the PCs see a butterfly.', 'History'=>'Beginning','History_Description'=>'The Threshold indicates that the history of the current situation is a literal beginning, this may mean that the current situation is just begun (it has no true past), or that it can be traced back to a single instant that coincides with the the beginning of something else, such as the birth of a child, dawning of new age, or crowning of a monarch, etc.', 'Situation'=>'Brink', 'Situation_Description'=>'The Threshold indicates that the current situation is balanced upon the brink of something new, that is only partially known (such as you may know when you are on the brink of a war, but not what the actual war would become). This is a delicate time, where the slightest push may send the situation spiralling out of control.','Solution'=>'Crossing','Solution_Description'=>'The Threshold indicates that the solution to the current situation involves a crossing, this may mean that you must cross to the other side, and join the opposition, or one of them must cross to you, or that you must leave this place behind to solve the issue.'), //ace
		array('Yarn_Name'=>'The Swamp','Yarn_Description'=>'The Swamp is a card the represents a dichotomy. The Swamp is to be feared, it is a place of corruption, decay, stagnation, and many believe it magical, for those who enter it unprepared will die, but for those that know its secret ways, recognise its dangers, then medicinal plants, herbs, and other medicines and magics are revealed. The Swamp can represent potions and medicines that are as foul-tasting as swamp-water, and yet somehow help.','Significator'=>['Plot'=>'The Swamp Plot is about corruption and usually that means business and politics. It may be about crime, dirt, and sin in general, but usually this is a story of greed and power. Occasionally, a Swamp plot will actually be set in a real swamp, but more often it is just a Location, but is treated more like a Character, often fulfilling a Character Role such as love interest or rival. ','Side'=>'A side marked by The Swamp is marked as corrupted and degenerate some how. Sometimes they are in-bred cannibals, other times they are dirty cops, occasionally they can be redeemed.','Character'=>'The Swamp Significator indicates a Character who is corrupt, but powerful. <p>They <strong>Gain Yin</strong> when try to corrupt or tempt another. </p><p>They <strong>Gain Yang</strong> when they act selfishly or for themselves. </p><p>They <strong>Gain Chi</strong> when they demonstrate their power (use their Power or Super-Annex). </p><p>They also gain +1 Success Levels when they are performing immoral or illegal actions.</p>','Scene'=>'The Swamp Scene is usually one of despair or malaise. Swamps when they literally appear are a struggle, at the best of times. Swamps can be beautiful places, but the light has to be just right... Yarn-Tellers may play the card to engage in a little light corruption, make a Gain, or slap an Ordeal replete with Festering Wounds on a Character.'],'Beat_Type'=>'2', 'Conflict_Embodiment'=>'3', 'Facet_Embodiment'=>'11', 'Hook_Aspect'=>'Hitches', 'Aspect_Description'=>'The Hook targets the Character\'s Hitches, the bigger the better.','Hook'=>'What\'s That Smell?', 'Hook_Description'=>'The Story Hooks the Characters with a direct warning and a question, this is usually what\'s that smell? But it can be What\'s that noise, taste or weird light, just as easily. In any case the answer is usually a corpse, occasionally a Monster, and just occasionally a broken sewer.', 'Gain'=>'Dark Territory or Dark Matter Descendant', 'Fray'=>'Quagmire', 'Fray_Description'=>'A Quagmire is a sticky morass or corruption which the PCs find themselves engulfed by. Quagmires can be literal swamps, so called Quicksand, and so on, or more likely they can be sticky situations, economic quagmires are rising debts, negative equity and falling wages, political quagmires are usually the opposite, with money from all sorts of dubious sources flooding in, who only want small concessions and favours. Either way, the PCs will need to extricate themselves somehow.', 'Snag'=>'Unique Situation', 'Snag_Description'=>'The Snag adds the complication to the Fray that the situation or Location is truly unique. It might be that the ingredients for the ritual required grow only in one place, that must be visited, or that the nightclub has the only indoor grass dance floor in the city. It is usual for the unique situation to either threaten the PCs or be threatened by the Opposed Embodiments.','NPC'=>array('Archetype'=>'Witch(-Doctor)','Persona'=>12,'Core'=>22,'Hitch'=>19,'Description'=>'The Witch (or less commonly Witch-Doctor) is a often a bitter outcast from society, who has learned the ways of the swamp, and the medicines found there. Sometimes they may be persuaded, paid or manipulated into helping others with their knowledge, often though they use their gifts to selfish ends. The Witch(-Doctor) is often accused of being able to fly or astral project themselves, and certainly can use herbs and plants to undergo psychotropic journeys. Some will have a Shaman Persona instead and be better socially adjusted.'),'Sweeping'=>'Shower Scene','Sweeping_Text'=>'The Shower Scene may not take place in a Shower or Bath, but represents the PCs trying to scrub free whatever they feel still clings to them. This may be some mud, or it could be an emotional taint. The Sweeping Scene allows the Character to treat their own wounds (especially Psych Wounds) with some ease (Halved Difficulty usually).', 'History'=>'Corrupted','History_Description'=>'The Swamp indicates that the current situation is a corruption of what was before, there will be some similarities left, but this situation is a dark reflection in muddy waters of what came before.', 'Situation'=>'Mired', 'Situation_Description'=>'The Swamp indicates a situation where you are caught somehow, often in a dangerous place. Characters can be mired by debt, by fear, by threats or actual violence, most often there is abuse and corruption around these circumstances.','Solution'=>'Potion','Solution_Description'=>'The Swamp indicates that the solution to the current situation is a potion, which may be magical, medicinal, alcoholic, herbal, curative, miraculous or occasionally poisonous. Sometimes this potion may actually be a pill, herb or antidote, and just occasionally it is just a beverage.'), //2
		array('Yarn_Name'=>'The Key','Yarn_Description'=>'The Key card is representative of a key itself, but also what a key can do, opening, unlocking, or revealing something that was locked away. The Key is not normally associated with the act of locking away again, except when the phrase "throw away the key" is used. It most often represents liberation, escape, or discovery.','Significator'=>['Plot'=>'The Key Plot is a plot to find something essential (the key to the Plot). Usually Key Plots are more often puzzle treasure hunts than combat filled infiltrations, but both are possible.','Side'=>'A side that is marked with the Key is somehow the key to the Conflict. They may have some power or ability that can solve the main issues, perhaps they are some lynch-pin of the Dominant or Pressed side\'s plans, or maybe they are just the problem.','Character'=>'The Key Significator indicates a Character who has a keen mind and nimble fingers. <p><strong>Gain Yin</strong> when they try to work on a puzzle or lock. </p><p>They <strong>Gain Yang</strong> when they use tools or gadgets. </p><p>They <strong>Gain Chi</strong> when they open a door, read an encoded message, or complete a puzzle. </p><p>They gain +1 Success Levels to all actions that require dexterity or curiosity.</p>','Scene'=>'The Key Scene is the most important part of a Story. It may be the "Inciting Event" of the Frame, the "Dark Night Of the Soul" of the Loom, or the Finale of the Zenith. The Key can be any type of Scene (including a Hook), but defines what is important to to the Story within its single Scene. Yarn-Tellers may play the Key card to create any sort of Scene, however the Scene must be Key to targets involvement in the Plot. If the Yarn-Teller fails to invent a suitable Key Scene then the Target decides the nature of the Key.'],'Beat_Type'=>'3', 'Conflict_Embodiment'=>'3', 'Facet_Embodiment'=>'18',  'Hook_Aspect'=>'Hitches', 'Aspect_Description'=>'The Hook targets the Character\'s Hitches, the bigger the better.','Hook'=>'The Key To The Kingdom', 'Hook_Description'=>'The Conflict Hooks the Character with a promise of an incredible treasure or power. Alternatively the Hook may be a literal key, perhaps to a Location that has come into the PCs possession.', 'Gain'=>'A Clue or Key to an Obstacle or Location', 'Fray'=>'The Lock', 'Fray_Description'=>'The Fray is about either opening or closing a lock. It may be a door, vault, safe, computer, chest or something more experimental that needs locking or unlocking. Usually you will require the correct key, password or codebook, or you will have to pick or solve the lock as a Puzzle. The Lock is usually a Solitary Low-Medium Stakes Ordeal, with at least one Obstacle, however storming a keep to drop the drawbridge and raise the portcullis would be a high or extreme Stakes Opposed Motional Ordeal.', 'Snag'=>'Crux', 'Snag_Description'=>'The Fray is made more complicated by being the key to the whole Story. This is the crux of the problem, and as such should have higher Stakes (with black twos wild), and an appearance of the Villain or their forces. If this crucial Fray is lost it must be returned to somehow later.','NPC'=>array('Archetype'=>'Inquisitor','Persona'=>10,'Core'=>12,'Hitch'=>6,'Description'=>'Inquisitors are masters of asking questions and keeping the interrogated threatened and living. Some favour torture, usually with a strong psychological component, others rely on making friends with their subject, master Inquisitors use even more advanced techniques.'),'Sweeping'=>'Lock-In','Sweeping_Text'=>'The PCs find somewhere safe and then secure the doors, by locking, bolting or barricading themselves in. They may rest easy inside for a while, especially if its after-hours in a country pub, not so much if its a supply cupboard during a terrorist incident.', 'History'=>'Discovered','History_Description'=>'The Key indicates that the past that led to the current situation involves some act of discovery, usually something important was discovered years ago at led to the the current situation, but sometimes the situation was created by an attempt at discovering something else (successfully or not).', 'Situation'=>'Locked', 'Situation_Description'=>'The Key indicates that the current situation is locked, it cannot be moved on from until something external to the situation usually unlocks it. It could be two forces are pitted against each other in an eternal stalemate, locked in battle, or it could be that you or an ally are locked in a dungeon or jail.','Solution'=>'Revealing','Solution_Description'=>'The Key indicates that the solution to the current situation is to reveal some secret. Revealing this secret may cause political upset, destabilise an opponent, or turn allies upon each other depending upon the secret revealed.'), //3
		array('Yarn_Name'=>'The Tower','Yarn_Description'=>'The Tower card can represent physical buildings, places, and stability. Less commonly, in the form a Wizard\'s or Watchtower it may represent research, viewing, observation or looking-out. The Tower is a stable landmark, not prone to collapse, except when struck by lightning, which happens often before the lightning conductor, or earthquake, which is considered an act of the gods before the modern day also. The card has a hint of divine retribution about this meaning, which is why it may be called the Tower Struck By Lightning in negative positions.','Significator'=>['Plot'=>'The Tower Plot is one that builds up piece by piece. Such a Plot doesn\'t begin as a Cycle or Epic, it starts small, with a Single Story. The Plot will return, each time promoted, over and over until it dominates the whole Story. Such Plots reflect the emergence of new cultures, new technologies and new societies, it is also useful in world-building as each Story builds upon the last occurrence until the new world is defined. ','Side'=>'When a side is marked with the Tower then they are in a period of construction, getting more powerful and preparing for something beyond this immediate conflict, perhaps a later or larger Plot that needs foreshadowing. Their Embodiments are usually less engaged in the Plot (unless Dominant) than normal because of this work.','Character'=>'The Tower Significator indicates a Character who is a prominent figure of their society. <p>They <strong>Gain Yin</strong> when they speak calmly, suggest an alternative option, or prioritize problems. </p><p>They <strong>Gain Yang</strong> when they keep silent, agree with another or organize assistance.</p><p><strong>Gain Chi</strong> when they demonstrate physical prowess. </p><p>They gain +1 Success Levels when they perform physical actions (firing a gun doesn\'t count).</p>','Scene'=>'The Tower Scene usually represents a Construction or Research Ordeal, often about or to "purchase" a Location. It can also create a Force-of-Nature Extra, as an Earthquake or Storm to attack a building. Yarn-Tellers can play the Tower to Gain (or build) a Location, research a topic, or observe a Location, or perhaps unleash a Storm or Earthquake.'],'Beat_Type'=>'4', 'Conflict_Embodiment'=>'3', 'Facet_Embodiment'=>'16', 'Hook_Aspect'=>'Hitches', 'Aspect_Description'=>'The Hook targets the Character\'s Hitches, the bigger the better.','Hook'=>'Lookout', 'Hook_Description'=>'The Story opens with a Lookout or Scout bringing news, of an impending threat, this might be "Land Ho!", or "Smoke!" or "Three Thousand Orcs and Ogres are marching South along the King\'s road. They will be here in two days, maybe less." or the PCs themselves may be the one\'s to see the threat, and have to raise the alarm.', 'Gain'=>'Location (often Real Estate or a Province where appropriate)', 'Fray'=>'Tower Struck By Lightning', 'Fray_Description'=>'A terrible, traumatic, life changing, paradigm shifting event. Usually a disaster of this magnitude is a Force of Nature Extra (at least), in an Ordeal that has High-Paradoxical Stakes. It is common for new Hitches to result from this Fray, ideally that will deepen the hooks of the Conflict in the PCs, perhaps even causing them to internalise the actual Conflict within themselves.', 'Snag'=>'Hold!', 'Snag_Description'=>'The Fray ends / leads to a situation where the Embodiment must hold position against a force of lesser opponents (usually Vex and Chorus Extras) that outnumber the Embodiment and Allies. Usually this Snag Ordeal will have a limited duration, with either reinforcements arriving, or some extraction team en-route, or perhaps the enemies will stop with dawn\'s light, or at nightfall. Otherwise, the Vexes will come in waves, with rest periods in between.','NPC'=>array('Archetype'=>'Privileged','Persona'=>8,'Core'=>6,'Hitch'=>12,'Description'=>'The Privileged are the high-born, indolent class, who live in fine towers. They live lives of boredom and often corruption, although some may find other hobbies and activities.'),'Sweeping'=>'Stability','Sweeping_Text'=>'The PCs have a stable situation for a while (this may be weeks or months)', 'History'=>'Built','History_Description'=>'The Tower indicates that the current situation has been built, brick by brick, as one might construct a tower. This situation was deliberately engineered by someone for a specific purpose.', 'Situation'=>'Stable', 'Situation_Description'=>'The Tower indicates that the current situation is essentially stable, sometimes this means if you try to change it, something will happen to stabilise it once again, other times it just means that it would be very difficult to change anything.','Solution'=>'Vigil','Solution_Description'=>'The Tower indicates that the solution to the current situation is to watch or look over the situation carefully. This could be a stakeout, observation, or research about the situation, that is itself the solution, rather than revealing a solution.'), //4
		array('Yarn_Name'=>'The Sail','Yarn_Description'=>'The Sail card represents the act of harnessing an external, or higher, power to your needs. Just as a ship\'s sail, or windmill\'s turbine harnesses the elemental wind to drive the ship or mill, so the card can imply that you will make headway, perhaps travel.','Significator'=>['Plot'=>'The Sail Plot is about being at the mercy of greater powers, and learning to survive these immense happenings. The Sail relies on powerful forces from the Cycle or an Epic that drives the forces of the Plot. The Hooked Characters must exist alongside these powerful forces without being directly threatened, usually. The Sail represents harnessing these forces and in this way, you can create Dragon Riders, Demon-hunters, Elemental Bending Styles, or whatever, depending upon what the forces are. ','Side'=>'A side marked by the Sail should make headway during the events of the plot. The Conflict may drive them across a map to a destination, or through an Ordeal to a Creation. It may even indicate they are also the Embodiment of a larger Plot, and will have a Scene from that Plot, or that this whole Plot is an Act or Tract of a larger Plot.','Character'=>'The Sail Significator indicates a Character who has learned to harness some external power for their own ends. <p>They <strong>Gain Yin</strong> when they have time to think, rest, or create. </p><p>They <strong>Gain Yang</strong> when they are busy, working or have been given a task. </p><p>They <strong>Gain Chi</strong> when they use external power to accomplish their goal (engines, sails, horses, whatever really), rather than their own personal power. </p><p>They also gain +1 Success Levels to attempts to harness external power, and the results.</p>','Scene'=>'The Sail Scene is usually a leisurely part of the Story. The Characters can usually rest and recover while they travel, although events can turn, external power is not always consistent or constant. Winds can storm as well as becalm. Yarn-Tellers usually play a Sail card to harness some external power to their ends. They might also use it to gain a vehicle or other Descendant, or to power the same. The Sail can also be used to rest and recover somewhat (with a tendency toward Malformed: Amputated Body-part Hitches replacing "Dying").'],'Beat_Type'=>'5', 'Conflict_Embodiment'=>'3', 'Facet_Embodiment'=>'8', 'Hook_Aspect'=>'Hitches', 'Aspect_Description'=>'The Hook targets the Character\'s Hitches, the bigger the better.','Hook'=>'Embarkation', 'Hook_Description'=>'The Story Hooks the PCs by getting them all aboard the same vehicle. Often a boat (although trains and even cars will work). Often the other side will also have Embodiments on board the same craft, or that will be encountered at the planned stops or eventual destination.', 'Gain'=>'Increase a Facet Boon', 'Fray'=>'Travel', 'Fray_Description'=>'Travelling can be a Motional Ordeal in its own sense, navigating, surviving, but there is more to this than the journey or the destination. Travel truly can broaden the mind, and learning can be part of the Ordeal, raising the Stakes to Soul or Paradoxical levels.', 'Snag'=>'Against the Wind', 'Snag_Description'=>'The Fray is complicated by the situation, sometimes the weather is against you, the wind is blowing you into greater danger, a situation that requires a change of tack. It may be a case of changing the PCs short term goals so they can still accomplish their long term goals.','NPC'=>array('Archetype'=>'Sailor','Persona'=>22,'Core'=>8,'Hitch'=>6,'Description'=>'The Sailor is always full of stories of far away places they watched glide by their ship. They are steady workers who have the occasional tendency to lose body parts, eyes, or gain Scars, and Exposed Tattoos'),'Sweeping'=>'On The Beam','Sweeping_Text'=>'The PCs are headed in the right direction. There\'s a good wind, and a good chance things are going their way, they might even make a Revelation or make a Gain on the way.', 'History'=>'Travelled','History_Description'=>'The Sail indicates that the history that led to the current situation either involved travel, either someone travelled to arrive and created this situation, someone left which created this situation, or someone travelled and brought it back with them.', 'Situation'=>'Becalmed', 'Situation_Description'=>'The Sail indicates that the current situation is that of a sail without wind. This can appear as a lack of motile force, lack of fuel, or lack of power.','Solution'=>'Travel','Solution_Description'=>'The Sail indicates the solution to the current situation can be solved by travelling, this travel may be to retrieve a specific object from a specific location, but more often the away is more important.'), //5
		array('Yarn_Name'=>'The Clock','Yarn_Description'=>'The Clock card represents Time and timings, obviously, but a clock is a complex and difficult to construct mechanism, and so the card also represents long, complex tasks and procedures. The appearance of the card may indicate that a deadline is in place, that action must take place within a certain time, or that patience and waiting are the only way forwards.','Significator'=>['Plot'=>'The Clock Plot is generally a plot with a time limit. Deadlines, time-limits, ticking bombing countdowns are common enough examples. Of course, a time limit alone isn\'t the only thing about a Clock Plot. Clock plots also have lots of moving parts, complex set pieces and multiple sides with many Characters. ','Side'=>'A side marked with the Clock has limited time to achieve their goals, or at least they feel the constraints of time during this Plot. It may indicate that the side is aged and need to recruit new Embodiments, that they are becoming desperate and forced to act during the Plot, or that the time of prophecy has come to pass, and they will now follow their plan to victory.','Character'=>'The Clock Significator indicates a Character who is regulated and unforgiving. <p>They <strong>Gain Yin</strong> when they hold a grudge, recall an event, or talk about the past. </p><p>They <strong>Gain Yang</strong> when they plan ahead, talk about the future, or make a schedule. </p><p>They <strong>Gain Chi</strong> when they are on time, living in the moment, or check the time. </p><p>They also gain +1 Success Level on any action to do with timing, punctuality or precision.</p>','Scene'=>'The Clock Scene is any Scene that time is important in. It may be a specific temporal event (such as the start of a world war, or a presidential assassination) or just a timed event (such as a race or sport), it can also be used to imply extra time (perhaps outside of normal time like Nevertime). A Yarn-Teller can play a Clock card to impose a time-limit or negate it. They might use it to create some free time to recover, or limit how long a target may be able to access their Lores or Descendants.'],'Beat_Type'=>'6', 'Conflict_Embodiment'=>'3', 'Facet_Embodiment'=>'13','Hook_Aspect'=>'Hitches', 'Aspect_Description'=>'The Hook targets the Character\'s Hitches, the bigger the better.','Hook'=>'Countdown', 'Hook_Description'=>'The story hooks the character with a countdown situation. There is limited time until something major happens. How major will vary on the Stakes, with low stakes being responding to a school reunion RSVP, and High Stakes being ambulances racing through traffic to get to a accident scene.', 'Gain'=>'Time (some sense of an extension in a deadline or additional life to live)', 'Fray'=>'Clockwork', 'Fray_Description'=>'Precise, meticulous planning, preparation and timing is required for execution of clockwork, whether its building a clock, or robbing a bank, clockwork is a Complex Procedural and Motional Ordeal that can be of any Stakes. Timing is a natural part of the Clockwork Fray and you can model that with limited Phases per Stage.' , 'Snag'=>'Time', 'Snag_Description'=>'The Fray may be affected by a Time Limit, this is usually applied as a Limit on the total number of Phases that the Ordeal must be completed in (or at least that a certain Stage must be completed by), note that this is in addition to any Phases per Stage Limit that may already be in place because of the Stakes). If a Time Limit is inappropriate for some reason, then the situation must be complicated by History, with past choices limiting future choices.','NPC'=>array('Archetype'=>'Historian','Persona'=>10,'Core'=>2,'Hitch'=>19,'Description'=>'The Historian or Chronicler investigates some events, and then turns those investigations into stories that they write and sell.'),'Sweeping'=>'Recuperation Time','Sweeping_Text'=>'The PCs are not doing well, they need to rest badly, in fact they may be ill from festering wounds, the way everything keeps spinning... They come around in hospital, or at least a bed somewhere, being nursed back to health, they may still be injured, but their wounds have been cleaned and bandaged, and perhaps some antibiotic poultices have been applied, if you are lucky.', 'History'=>'Complicated','History_Description'=>'The Clock indicates that the past of the current situation is a complex, complicated thing, often with many moving parts.', 'Situation'=>'Ticking', 'Situation_Description'=>'The Clock indicates that the current situation is a limited time deal, there is a ticking time bomb or a time limit of some sort on the current situation before it changes, usually to something worse.','Solution'=>'Time','Solution_Description'=>'The Clock indicates that the current situation will be best solved by time. This can sometimes mean that waiting patiently, or hiding in a hole is the way to solve the problem, and just occasionally time travel is the best solution.'), //6
		array('Yarn_Name'=>'The Sword','Yarn_Description'=>'The Sword Card represents danger, combat and peril. The Sword is a weapon, and so it represents warfare, weaponry and attacking forces. Sometimes arguments escalate, the Sword shows us the precise moment that things escalate to High Stakes.','Significator'=>['Plot'=>'The Sword Plot is a War Story. It is a tale of attackers and assaults, tactics and defences.','Side'=>'The side marked by the Sword are aggressive, angry, often dangerous (interactions with them are all one Stake Higher than normal), and when possible on the war path. They will respond to conversation with threats, and to threats with violence, physical challenges will invoke weapons and armed combat.','Character'=>'The Sword Significator indicates a Character who is quick to attack and deadly with it. <p>They <strong>Gain Yin</strong> when they are in peril. </p><p>They <strong>Gain Yang</strong> when they prepare for action. </p><p>They <strong>Gain Chi</strong> when they attack another. </p><p>They also gain +1 Success Levels to all attacks they make.</p>','Scene'=>'The Sword Scene is usually a fight or battle. An Opposed Ordeal at High or Extreme Stakes where lives are on the line. Although it can be used to Gain a Weapon Descendant, Military equipment of some sort, or an effective fighter Ally. Yarn-Tellers may play the Sword to inflict a military defeat, or injury on a target, or they may gain military equipment or allies.'],'Beat_Type'=>'7', 'Conflict_Embodiment'=>'3', 'Facet_Embodiment'=>'19',  'Hook_Aspect'=>'Hitches', 'Aspect_Description'=>'The Hook targets the Character\'s Hitches, the bigger the better.','Hook'=>'Attack!', 'Hook_Description'=>'The Story hooks the character with a sudden attack. This attack should be connected (even if only peripherally) to the main Villain, so a trail of revenge would lead the PCs back. Of course, the attack on the PCs may not have been deliberate, but just be a domino chain of events.', 'Gain'=>'Lower a Hitch Boon by one or several Boons.', 'Fray'=>'Battle', 'Fray_Description'=>'Battle is a massive, Extreme stakes Opposed Ordeal, where at least two armed forces exchange wounds. There will be deaths on both sides usually, or worse, enemies may come in waves, a steady stream, or may be separated by Stages.', 'Snag'=>'A Sword Raised', 'Snag_Description'=>'A Powerful Character (often a Monster with at least TWO Monster Facets and more normally around 5) such as a Cyborg Commando, Griffin and rider, Dragon, Vampire Assassin, Chimera or Demon, who opposes the PCs. This opposition may be temporary, and the Character may turn out to be a potential Ally, but first there will be a fight. This is usually the result of a misunderstanding, that will not be resolved until after they have engaged in battle.','NPC'=>array('Archetype'=>'Warrior','Persona'=>6,'Core'=>19,'Hitch'=>19,'Description'=>'Warriors are military men, usually heroes (although Scouts, Vandals and Gladiators are also possible). All Warriors have a "Special Move" that is drilled into them, usually a standard for that nation\'s military training, or their combat role.'),'Sweeping'=>'The Sweeping Sword','Sweeping_Text'=>'The PCs get to take it easy, as another side (or new Embodiment) suddenly engages the (old) Opposed Embodiment in a direct conflict (usually of raised Stakes, often of High or Extreme). The PCs old enemy may easily defeat this accidental ally, or may fall to this new threat, in which case, expect a Revelation.', 'History'=>'War','History_Description'=>'The Sword indicates that war lies behind the current situation. Sometimes this will be the last great war, other times it will be an older conflict rearing its head again.', 'Situation'=>'Battle', 'Situation_Description'=>'The Sword indicates the current situation is a battle. This might be a minor skirmish, or an enormous world spanning conflict, sometimes you will be on one side, and sometimes you are trapped in between two massive armies.','Solution'=>'Tactics','Solution_Description'=>'The Sword indicates that the current situation can be resolved with superior tactics, there may be some violence involved, and there will always be danger and threats.'), //7
		array('Yarn_Name'=>'The Rival','Yarn_Description'=>'The Rival card represents another Character that rivals or opposes a Player or Non-Player Character in some way. The Rival may be an opponent, a competitor, an enemy, or just interested in the same love interest. Rivals can be strangers or friends, and the card can indicate a rivalry that is growing within a group, or indicate an external threat. In many ways the Rival card be tied to the Friend or Foe Wyrd Tarot cards, as Rivals can become friends, as well as friends become Rivals.','Significator'=>['Plot'=>'The Rival Plot is a plot that focuses upon a Character and their Rival, in the case of a Party of Adventurers, or Team, the Rival plot will consist of a Rival team (usually made of the various types of Rival with a Rival for each Character). The Rivals will have similar, or opposed, goals to the Party, which will naturally bring them into conflict, such as wanting to win the same league, or control the kingdom themselves. ','Side'=>'A side marked with the Rival will act as (and often be composed of) Rivals to at least one Character Embodiment from at least one other side, and sometimes multiple sides and multiple Embodiments.','Character'=>'The Rival Significator indicates a Character who feels compelled to compete against others. <p>They <strong>Gain Yin</strong> when they enter a competition, disagree, or oppose another. </p><p>They <strong>Gain Yang</strong> when they acknowledge or greet someone they acknowledge as a rival. </p><p>They <strong>Gain Chi</strong> when they act in competition against an acknowledged rival. </p><p>They also gain +1 Success Levels when they compete against an acknowledged rival.</p>','Scene'=>'The Rival Scene is usually an appearance of a Character\'s Rival. Rivals can be the same side of a Conflict as the Characters, or another side. Yarn-Tellers can play the card on a target to Reveal or Summon one of the target\'s Rivals. This is often useful for the plot development, and can provide them with new allies (or enemies if things go badly).'],'Beat_Type'=>'6', 'Conflict_Embodiment'=>'2', 'Facet_Embodiment'=>'1',  'Hook_Aspect'=>'Hitches', 'Aspect_Description'=>'The Hook targets the Character\'s Hitches, the bigger the better.','Hook'=>'Rival Arrives', 'Hook_Description'=>'The Story opens with a Rival arriving, or being revealed. This often signifies some sort of competition is occurring (even if neither side is aware of it).', 'Gain'=>'Gain an Ally of a former Rival, or Resolve a Hitch', 'Fray'=>'Competition', 'Fray_Description'=>'Competitions are usually Opposed Ordeals (Stakes vary based on the Competition. Competitions can be friendly rivalries between comrades, or they can be the reason for bitter Rivalries that destroy lives. Almost any event can become a Competition if Characters are willing. Drinking, Sports, Quizzes, Driving, Racing, and so on. Tournaments are a special type of Competition that includes multiple Rounds of Ordeals with each Round representing a single competition / game / match. Tournaments are usually a Story in their own right rather than just a single Fray, but bigger Conflicts may have to use Tournaments for any Competition.', 'Snag'=>'Rivalry', 'Snag_Description'=>'The Fray is complicated by at least one of the PCs Rivals being involved somehow. They may just be present, but immediately start acting to mislead, distract or engage the PC depending upon the nature of the Rivalry. If no Rival is available then an Ally will complicate the Fray by being involved with the Opposed Side somehow.','NPC'=>array('Archetype'=>'Competitor','Persona'=>19,'Core'=>6,'Hitch'=>7,'Description'=>'Competitors are those people who dedicate themselves to a particular sport, game or activity, trying to be the best at some competition. Unspecified Rivals are often Competitors, and sometimes a Competitor may raise to full Rival status.'),'Sweeping'=>'The Enemy of my Enemy','Sweeping_Text'=>'The PCs may make contact with one or more of the Opposed Embodiments Rivals, or a Rival may be entangled in the Plot. Perhaps offering the PCs a place to stay, or some assistance, simply to get back at their Rival. This Rival may even subject the Opposed Embodiment to a Rivalry Snag during their next or current Fray.', 'History'=>'Competition','History_Description'=>'The Rival indicates that the current situation has its roots in an old competition, perhaps a lover\'s ex-lover is back in town, or then again perhaps this is an ancient rivalry between nations, tribes, clans or cities, then again a more recent sporting rivalry, or similar competition can also spawn rivalries.', 'Situation'=>'Rivalry', 'Situation_Description'=>'The Rival indicates that current situation involves a rivalry, usually a Rival character will be involved in the current situation, often competing against the character.','Solution'=>'Feuding','Solution_Description'=>'The Rival indicates that the solution to the current situation is based on feuding, this may mean that you should use your own rivals against your enemies, or more often recruit your enemy\'s rivals to your side.'), //8
		array('Yarn_Name'=>'The Robot','Yarn_Description'=>'The Robot card represents the automatons, and workers, be they real robots, or people who live rigid, regimented lives, like the Eusaiveans. The Robot can represent the unconscious mind, which operates the body for the consciousness, or the mechanistic body itself. It can also represent those who are unawakened (or ain\'t woke) to what is really happening. They might be muggles, grunts, slaves, serfs, or actual robots.','Significator'=>['Plot'=>'The Robot Plot is a special sort of plot that is built with conditional events and essentially is preprogrammed. This sort of Plot can be great for pre-planned Scenarios, but represent a lot of work for the author. At it\'s simplest a Robot plot can be built around a single "rail-road" time-line that all the sides are trying to either maintain, subvert, or break. ','Side'=>'A side marked by the Robot may be composed of actual robots (rarely), or may have a rigid routine that they maintain, usually following all of their society\'s laws and regulations, or may be sleepwalkers somehow, unable to see what is going on around them. Sometimes the Robot side can be awakened, causing strikes, civil disruption, panics, and even revolutions depending upon the plot, setting and genre.','Character'=>'The Robot Significator indicates a Character who follows orders and rules.<p>They <strong>Gain Yin</strong> when they follow rules that they are subject to. </p><p>They <strong>Gain Yang</strong> when they follow legal orders that they have been given. </p><p>They <strong>Gain Chi</strong> when they perform actions automatically (they have practised an action enough that it no longer requires conscious thought).</p><p>They also gain +1 Success Levels to any task they perform automatically.</p>','Scene'=>'The Robot Scene can be used in a number of ways. It can represent a Character going about their automatic scheduled humdrum day, any machine that performs a task, any repetitive task (of the sort that machinery could do), or it can represent an actual robot. Yarn-Tellers can play the Robot on a Target to make them behave like a robot (going about their normal schedule and behaviour, ignoring the Yarn-Teller\'s presence), or can set them a Robot task that they must complete.'],'Beat_Type'=>'7', 'Conflict_Embodiment'=>'0', 'Facet_Embodiment'=>'0', 'Hook_Aspect'=>'Hitches', 'Aspect_Description'=>'The Hook targets the Character\'s Hitches, the bigger the better.','Hook'=>'Previously...', 'Hook_Description'=>'This Story is a continuation, sequel and possibly a resolution to a previous Story. It can help to have a little recap, where was that Story left, what did they PCs know, how much do the Players remember? This Hook is that chance to recap.', 'Gain'=>'Powerful, but subservient Cast or Force of Nature Ally (Supernatural Servant / Golem / Robot / AI / Toon)', 'Fray'=>'An Ordinary Day', 'Fray_Description'=>'An Ordinary Day, just going about doing what you normally do. So much of the day is normally performed by the body and mind on autopilot, imagine if it wasn\'t, imagine trying to do everything in a normal day consciously, as though for the first time. Usually this sort of Fray is part of early world-building to establish the Character, later this Ordinary Day is subverted as the Character has changed and developed, their old Ordinary Day is no longer normal and they may expect Demons or Wizards to burst into the office at any moment, and have to focus on the HR Memo that\'s doing the rounds.', 'Snag'=>'Automatic', 'Snag_Description'=>'The Automatic Snag indicates that the problem that complicates the Fray is an automatic process, this could be indicative of a machine or process that is our of control, or be a failure of a mechanism or computer system that the PCs were relying on (Damage to a crucial Descendant can qualify), or it could be the result of the PCs own unconscious processes rebelling against their conscious decisions.','NPC'=>array('Archetype'=>'Robot','Persona'=>4,'Core'=>8,'Hitch'=>8,'Description'=>'The Robot is usually an android servant or digital assistant. It has some AI and may even be sentient in Science-Fiction. In some genres Robot Archetypes may also be used for slaves, zombies and hypnotized or enchanted servants.'),'Sweeping'=>'Systems','Sweeping_Text'=>'The PCs are helped by systems they or someone else has put in place, maybe the Police turn up and help, maybe the guy on Tech Support really knows his stuff and fixed the issues, or maybe the insurance pays out, covering that nasty damages or hospital bill.', 'History'=>'Controlled','History_Description'=>'The Robot indicates the history of the current situation was controlled, usually this means someone was controlling the situation and created it, sometimes it means they have recently lost control leading to the current situation. Most importantly, who or what, exactly was under control?', 'Situation'=>'Autonomous', 'Situation_Description'=>'The Robot indicates that the current situation is autonomous, it is under its own control, playing out on automatic. This may have been set up by someone, but they are no longer directly involved.','Solution'=>'Automation','Solution_Description'=>'The Robot indicates that the solution to the current situation can be automated, this may mean an industrial process, some sort of magical automation (such as a golem), or an actual robot occasionally.'), //9
		array('Yarn_Name'=>'The Lion','Yarn_Description'=>'The Lion card represents strength, not just individually (which it does) but also strength in numbers. The Lion may indicate also heroic deeds and actions or proud behaviour. The Lion can be seen as a symbol of success and power, but more often it represents a test of that strength, and shows that pride comes before a fall.','Significator'=>['Plot'=>'The Lion plot is a plot about strength (personal or numeric), heroics (hunting or battle prowess are likely) and often pride (usually as part of a dramatic fall). ','Side'=>'A side marked by the Lion sees themselves as strong, and powerful, although others may see them as overly-proud or heroic depending upon their alliances. The side is often challenged by another as a demonstration of strength, which may have profound impacts on the plot as whole.','Character'=>'The Lion Significator indicates a Character who is proud and regal. <p>They <strong>Gain Yin</strong> when they act proud or mention their accomplishments. </p><p>They <strong>Gain Yang</strong> when they demonstrate their strength or physical ability.</p><p>They also gain +1 Success Levels to any action that demonstrates physical prowess and strength.</p>','Scene'=>'The Lion Scene is any scene that tests the strength (or pride) of the Characters. This may be a simple Gossamer Test or a more complex Ordeal. The Lion can also represent an animal (often a pet) or a Guardian Monster. Yarn-Tellers may play the card to summon a Lion (or similar strong animal) to attack their enemies, or they can pass a strength test, or any hunting Ordeals.'],'Beat_Type'=>'8', 'Conflict_Embodiment'=>'3', 'Facet_Embodiment'=>'8', 'Hook_Aspect'=>'Hitches', 'Aspect_Description'=>'The Hook targets the Character\'s Hitches, the bigger the better.','Hook'=>'Pride Comes Before A Fall', 'Hook_Description'=>'The Story Hooks the Character with giving them recognition for some earlier story, this Story is often a Sequel to the earlier episode. Usually makes a Gain (often a Prize, Medal or Award) as acknowledgement of the previous actions of the PC.', 'Gain'=>'Powerful Monster Ally, Super (or Power) Annex or Super-Skill Descendant', 'Fray'=>'Encounter', 'Fray_Description'=>'An Encounter is a Fight against a smaller number of similar powered foes, or a larger group of weaker foes. The Encounter is intended to insert a bit of action, and drama without risking the PCs too much. An Encounter should wear at the party, maybe Crippling or Maiming a few Characters and perhaps giving one Character a new Hitch (Mortal+), Extras (of any size) may die, including Cast Extras. You may want to kill a PC during this Fray if the Stakes are already elevated.', 'Snag'=>'Test of Strength', 'Snag_Description'=>'The Lion Snag is a test of strength, this might be a literal strength test, where the PC must break in a door, or lift a gate, or it may be a more subtle complication where the PCs specific abilities are tested by a Rival, Ally, Mentor, or Opposed Embodiment. This complication can involve asking questions like "How many troops can the PC defeat at once?" and testing that theory. Note that the Test is usually not intended to destroy, and you can capture the party with a "Captured" Confined Hitch rather than a "Dead" Scars Hitch.','NPC'=>array('Archetype'=>'Soldier','Persona'=>19,'Core'=>1,'Hitch'=>8,'Description'=>'The Soldier is a more refined Warrior, usually with better weapons and armour, more Duties and less Scars. Soldiers usually specialise according to the weapons they carry, and may be called Archer, Rifleman, Sniper, Paladin, Knight, etc'),'Sweeping'=>'The Lion Sleeps','Sweeping_Text'=>'The PCs get to rest and recover, but so does the Opposed Embodiment. In fact the Opposed Embodiment and PCs may both make a Gain or Revelation during this Sweeping.', 'History'=>'Proud','History_Description'=>'The Lion indicates that the history of the current situation is a source of pride for some people, this may be such that you should have heard of it already.', 'Situation'=>'Heroic', 'Situation_Description'=>'The Lion indicates that the current situation is in need of a hero, the sort of optimistic, adventurous, possibly psychopathic sort.','Solution'=>'Strength','Solution_Description'=>'The Lion indicates that the solution to the current situation is a show of strength. This may be a display of power, a literal show of strength, or revealing that your forces vastly outnumber theirs.'), //10
		array('Yarn_Name'=>'The Explorer','Yarn_Description'=>'The Explorer card represents the urge to wander, to seek out new places, and make new discoveries. Exploration, investigation and travel are all indicated by the card, but there is another side to the Explorer, sometimes they come as an invader, or a crusader. If you are the Explorer it warns you that you may not be seen as just a tourist by the natives.','Significator'=>['Plot'=>'The Explorer Plot is another good world-builder (although the Yarn-Teller does have to a little more work. The Explorer plot is about exploring a blank map. The map may be of a new land or new world, but the Characters are Hooked to explore and investigate the map, of course each area they go may consider them invaders. ','Side'=>'A side marked by the Explorer behaves as though they are an explorer in a strange land. This may be because they are, or they may be experiencing life beyond their class for the first time, the naive country bumpkin who wishes to be a king\'s guard does not understand things in the city, the princess on the run does not understand why anyone does anything they do, and why none of them do what she tells them. Such Characters are rarely out of trouble for long...','Character'=>'The Explorer Significator indicates a Character that lives to explore and investigate. <p>They <strong>Gain Yin</strong> when they are travel more than 1 kilometre. </p><p>They <strong>Gain Yang</strong> when they explore or investigate a place or person. </p><p>They <strong>Gain Chi</strong> when they make notes, drawings or maps of a location, person or thing. </p><p>They also gain +1 Success Levels when they are in unfamiliar territory.</p>','Scene'=>'The Explorer Scene indicates a Scene where the Character has to explore a Location, or meets an explorer or invader. Such Scenes are often Ordeals although a few may be Wefts. Yarn-Tellers may play the card to "create" a new Location to be explored, or make a Location seem unfamiliar (possibly by side-stepping) or summon an explorer ally or invading enemy for the target.'],'Beat_Type'=>'4', 'Conflict_Embodiment'=>'3', 'Facet_Embodiment'=>'13', 'Hook_Aspect'=>'Hitches', 'Aspect_Description'=>'The Hook targets the Character\'s Hitches, the bigger the better.','Hook'=>'Visitor', 'Hook_Description'=>'The Story opens with an unexpected visitor that may  bring the PCs a Revelation and a Gain. This Visitor is usually a friend or Ally, rather than a Rival or enemy, but occasionally it will be a stranger, who claims a connection that will later be validated or proved a lie.', 'Gain'=>'Discover a new or lost Location / Real Estate / Province / Dark Territory', 'Fray'=>'Explore', 'Fray_Description'=>'The Explore Fray is an exploration of the Conflict, it is time to explore some aspect of the interactions of the Facets in the Conflict. This may be done by actually exploring a Locations that Embodies the Conflict directly, or investigating a Descendant that has an Annex like the Conflict\'s.', 'Snag'=>'Lost', 'Snag_Description'=>'The PCs actions are complicated by there being no map, no GPS or the streets just seem different. The PCs or those they seek are lost, this can be due to High Strangeness like a Yarn-Teller or Time-Traveller side-stepping or ret-conning the area and making the map change.','NPC'=>array('Archetype'=>'Captain','Persona'=>22,'Core'=>3,'Hitch'=>8,'Description'=>'Captains are commanding officers who follow others orders and act as eyes and ears abroad. They are investigators, scouts and spies as much as they are explorers or leaders.'),'Sweeping'=>'Map','Sweeping_Text'=>'The PCs discover, explore, or gain access to a map or directions, that includes a secret passage, short cut or hidden way. This will allow them to appear or escape via this short cut and avoid any police, guards or enemy forces. It may allow them to skip Stages of the next Fray Ordeal or similar.', 'History'=>'Explored','History_Description'=>'The Explorer indicates that the current situation has roots in an old exploration. The area explored or the explorer may be more important to the current situation.', 'Situation'=>'Lost', 'Situation_Description'=>'The Explorer indicates that the current situation involves being lost, usually by having a clear idea where you want to be, but no idea which direction that may lie in.','Solution'=>'Navigate','Solution_Description'=>'The Explorer indicates that there is a solution to the current situation, but it will involve some navigation. Sometimes navigation will have a map, or a compass, other times you\'ll have to draw the map'), //J
		array('Yarn_Name'=>'The Scope','Yarn_Description'=>'The Scope card represents vision, examination, and focus. A scope can be used for assisted vision, it might be a telescope, a microscope, a periscope, reading glasses or a magnifying lens. It is a card that teaches us to focus on details, and to closely examine the facts or the scene.','Significator'=>['Plot'=>'The Scope Plot is a plot about investigation. Investigations can vary in type from genre and era, scouting parties, religious inquisitions, criminal investigations, scientific discoveries and expeditions are all with in the scope of The Scope. ','Side'=>'A side marked by The Scope are watching, observing, often making notes. They may be the media, a journalist, or herald, or an academic, a Chronicler, or historian, or they could be authorities, undercover police, agents and spies, or even aliens or Nephilim. The real question is are they watching everyone the same, or do they have a focus to their investigation?','Character'=>'The Scope Significator indicates a Character that revels in watching and investigating. <p>They <strong>Gain Yin</strong> when they make themselves comfortable, settle down, or adjust their position. </p><p>They <strong>Gain Yang</strong> when they discuss events they have witnessed, take notes, or record information. </p><p>They <strong>Gain Chi</strong> when they watch or observe an event, show, or process from beginning to end, focus on details or draw conclusions. </p><p>They gain +1 Success Levels to all actions to do with sensing, recording, or understanding information.</p>','Scene'=>'The Scope Scene is usually a Revelation, often where something is observed and revealed to the Characters (in extreme cases the villain will be monologue the Plot during a Scope Scene). Sometimes the Scope can be a Test of Senses or an Observation Ordeal (like a Stake-Out). Yarn-Tellers can play the card to pass any sensory Ordeal, or to gain a Revelation. They can also create Observation Ordeals for the target if they wish.'],'Beat_Type'=>'5', 'Conflict_Embodiment'=>'1', 'Facet_Embodiment'=>'1',   'Hook_Aspect'=>'Hitches', 'Aspect_Description'=>'The Hook targets the Character\'s Hitches, the bigger the better.','Hook'=>'Hints', 'Hook_Description'=>'The Hook hints at the Story with clues, background details, and no direct exposition of any sort. The Hook may even modify the Revelations of the Frame to make them into more specific details and less broad exposition. These Hooks may require setting multiple times during other stories before they finally catch the PC.', 'Gain'=>'Improve Alternate Integration', 'Fray'=>'Watch', 'Fray_Description'=>'Watch Frays are Ordeals where PCs have to watch, observe and perceive something. It could be that they are watching their favourite TV show, or a film, the Ordeal will be the Psychological effects of the movie and the story, or perhaps the PCs are on a stake out, watching the enemy base, then again military watches are something else again. Who knows what might attack the party during the night.', 'Snag'=>'Scrutiny', 'Snag_Description'=>'The PCs are being watched, observed by someone, and it could complicate the Fray, for example speak-easy\'s always had lookouts who would warn of the Police approaching. Perhaps the scrutiny follows the Fray, with cameras, lights and microphones being thrust in their face moments after the Fray, as they are asked how they let the bad guys get away, or how you justify so many dead and injured...','NPC'=>array('Archetype'=>'Spy','Persona'=>22,'Core'=>7,'Hitch'=>16,'Description'=>'The Spy may be a foreign agent, or could just be the curtain-twitcher down the street.'),'Sweeping'=>'Vision','Sweeping_Text'=>'The PCs finds, sees, or experiences some Revelation, and gives them a clue (usually a Key Test to spot) to a pair of Gains.', 'History'=>'Detailed','History_Description'=>'The Scope indicates that the history of the current situation is detailed, which usually means complicated machinations and random chance have both conspired to make this happen.', 'Situation'=>'Scrutiny', 'Situation_Description'=>'The Scope indicates that the current situation is one of scrutiny, this may mean you are forced to scrutinise, examining details, researching and looking into something, or be under some one else\'s scrutiny.','Solution'=>'Analysis','Solution_Description'=>'The Scope indicates that the solution to the current situation will be revealed by analysis, sometimes even the act of analysis itself will actually be the solution.'), //Q
		array('Yarn_Name'=>'The Butcher','Yarn_Description'=>'The Butcher card represents blood, death and carrion, but it also represents sustenance, food and support within a community. The hard part of reading the card is knowing when the card is a sign of disaster and when it means a mighty feast, or more importantly who that feast is for.','Significator'=>['Plot'=>'The Butcher Plot is usually set within a small community, and tends to be about survival, this may be survival against a harsh environment, like a drought or harsh winter, or more normally a killer is loose in the community. This killer is usually a serial killer and a member of the community, but it may be a Monster from outside the community in the horror genre. ','Side'=>'The side marked by the Butcher will have to kill by the end the Conflict. This killing may be symbolic, or literal, and can be an animal, or even an insect if need be, although usually the animal will be eaten (unless vermin) or otherwise consumed. In many cases the Butcher also indicates the side may provide a feast to those who are hungry, or that their services and allegiances are for sale.','Character'=>'The Butcher Significator indicates a Character who is a killer, but often for the good of the community. <p>They <strong>Gain Yin</strong> when they provide for the hungry, poor, or in need. </p><p>They <strong>Gain Yang</strong> when they care about how clean their hands are (wash, wipe, wear gloves). </p><p>They <strong>Gain Chi</strong> when they execute, or prepare an attack or piece of meat. </p><p>They also gain +1 Success Levels to all physical attacks.</p>','Scene'=>'The Butcher Scene is usually a High Stakes Ordeal where a killer is involved in most genres, but it can be used to represent a party or feast. Butchers can also represent Allies from within a community. Yarn-Tellers can play a Butcher card to kill (or at least summon a powerful killer to attack the target), or to provide food for a whole community, or host a spectacular feast.'],'Beat_Type'=>'9', 'Conflict_Embodiment'=>'2', 'Facet_Embodiment'=>'4',  'Hook_Aspect'=>'Hitches', 'Aspect_Description'=>'The Hook targets the Character\'s Hitches, the bigger the better.','Hook'=>'Danger', 'Hook_Description'=>'The Hook just consists of some enormous danger, it isn\'t looming, it isn\'t coming, it is right here, right now.', 'Gain'=>'Increase Scale', 'Fray'=>'Hunted', 'Fray_Description'=>'Being Hunted (or hunting) is a High Stakes Ordeal, that may begin with a Stalk or Chase, that explodes into a Fight. A Hunt is usually a team sport, with the Hunter being superior in power level to the Prey.', 'Snag'=>'Big Bad', 'Snag_Description'=>'The Opposed Embodiment or at least one Force of Nature Monster (with at least 2 Monster Facets - usually either the Dominant Facet and it\'s Anti-Facet or the Pressed Facet) Extra engages the party during the Fray. At any time except their Story\'s Zenith Act, the Big Bad is protected by actual \'Plot Armour\' meaning that the Plot Demon will Soak Wounds, etc. for them. Powerful Character\'s can still defeat them (and the Plot by extension) during the early Acts, so Ref\'s should handle with care, and usually use a FON Extra instead. ','NPC'=>array('Archetype'=>'Butcher','Persona'=>12,'Core'=>12,'Hitch'=>4,'Description'=>'The Butcher may engage in slaughtering animals, dressing their meat, or selling the cuts. Butchers can also be killers and careless surgeons.'),'Sweeping'=>'Feast','Sweeping_Text'=>'The Sweeping grants the PCs a huge feast or festival, there may be gains, in the form of gifts as well as food, drink, music and dancing, and there will be meat.', 'History'=>'Slain','History_Description'=>'The Butcher indicates that before the current situation someone or something was killed. This may be an animal, but more often (especially in crime rich genres) is a character, the killing is often deliberate, but can be accidental.', 'Situation'=>'Killer', 'Situation_Description'=>'The Butcher indicates that the current situation involves a killer, this may be a lone psychopath, a predatory animal, or occasionally a monster.','Solution'=>'Feast','Solution_Description'=>'The Butcher indicates that the solution to the current situation involves a feast, usually this means a large celebration where people can eat together and the shared experience will allow them to find common ground, sometimes it may imply that the solution is to over-feed the monster or whatever so it falls asleep and can be killed, even less commonly the only solution will be to eat the cause.'), //K
		array('Yarn_Name'=>'The World','Yarn_Description'=>'The World card represents the whole world, not just the Earth, or any particular planet, or dimension but the Omniverse as a whole. In fact, any wholeness, or completion is indicated by the card, as well as the wilderness and wild places in particular (due to the wild-card nature of the Joker). The World is generally seen as a positive card, but it can be negative in the sense of endings mean farewells, good byes and moving on from one phase to another.<p>The World contains everything and everyone, and so can represent any Facet or all Facets at once. This interpretation of "Everything" can be useful when considering Questions as The World asks us to Question everything, accept nothing at face value and always be on guard, against potentially anything.</p>','Significator'=>['Plot'=>'The World Plot is always a tale that spans multiple Locations, often actually across multiple worlds and time periods. The World Plot is generally at least a Volume, an Epic or Cycle, and can be useful for world-building, if you have no better ideas. World Plots consist of lots of apparently unconnected sub-Plots that examine often random Conflicts (that are still aspects of the World\'s Conflict). ','Side'=>'The side marked by the World in another Plot has more knowledge and experience than may be expected, they have travelled far, and seen things no one else around here has. They may be able to bring this experience of the world into play in odd ways. Most often the Character will have at least one Alternate that is actually an Embodiment for the Shadows or External Side as well.','Character'=>'The World Significator indicates a Character who are very experienced and confident. <p>They <strong>Gain Yin</strong> when they act confident, arrogant, or nonchalant. </p><p>They <strong>Gain Yang</strong> when they can share their knowledge of a situation or thing. They <strong>Gain Chi</strong> when they say farewell, good bye, or wish someone well. </p><p>They also gain +1 Success Level to all actions that they claim they have tried before.</p>','Scene'=>'The World Scene is often the central theme of the Story written large, or can represent the whole Story squeezed within itself, perhaps as a play with a play, or just incredible trials or rewards. World Scenes can be Framing Revelations (revealing the world as it is), represent incredible gains (you can literally Gain a whole world), or an unbelievable Ordeal (such as racing around the world). Yarn-Tellers can play the card for virtually any effect, opening portals, changing paradigms, making huge gains or losses as required.'],'Beat_Type'=>'7', 'Conflict_Embodiment'=>'1', 'Facet_Embodiment'=>'14', 'Hook_Aspect'=>'Hitches', 'Aspect_Description'=>'The Hook targets the Character\'s Hitches, the bigger the better.','Hook'=>'Wildcard', 'Hook_Description'=>'The Hook is just one of those out there crazy starts to a story. Perhaps they come around on a beach near a crashed plane, or wrecked boat, with no memories of where they were going or why. Or maybe they explode from the ground, unsure how or why they were there.', 'Gain'=>'Add Alternate', 'Fray'=>'Wilderness Encounter', 'Fray_Description'=>'A holdover from Old School Gaming. The encounter is a where the PCs meet a larger group of inferior foes (for example 2d20 Vexes, or 2d6 Cast Extras) in the Wild. Encounters are not always balanced, and the PCs may have Flee turning the High Stakes Ordeal into a Chase. Encounters are usually followed by a Gain.', 'Snag'=>'Double Trouble', 'Snag_Description'=>'Add an additional Fray that must be accomplished alongside the first.','NPC'=>array('Archetype'=>'Dragon','Persona'=>1,'Core'=>22,'Hitch'=>0,'Description'=>'Dragons are huge, treasure hoarding monsters... Wait, you know what a Dragon is. In T13, dragons are associated with Vermis Bulmäs in most universes, fantasy universes will have native Dragons who may have been created by Vermis on those worlds long ago. Dragons are thematic beings, physical, but spiritual and magical as well, often representing a powerful combination of unrivalled virtues such as fortitude, strength, willpower, wisdom, or intelligence, as well as sins such as tyranny, greed, avarice, pride, cowardice, and gluttony.'),'Sweeping'=>'Exologue','Sweeping_Text'=>'The Sweeping is an Exologue, where the Character spends a Short Act of a few Scenes in the world of one of their Alternates. This can be used to allow the Pressed Embodiment recovery time in a different time-line (another universe, a past life, etc).', 'History'=>'World','History_Description'=>'The World indicates that the current situation has been caused by major events in world history, such as world-wars, imperial collapses, technological innovations, and natural disasters such as climate change and global pandemics, these can even include events from a cosmic scale, such as planetary collisions, gamma-ray bursts and solar-flares.', 'Situation'=>'Completion', 'Situation_Description'=>'The World indicates that the current situation is one of completion, whatever the situation, it is already too late to stop it. A change is coming and it is this change and how it is weathered that is the real situation here that may be "solved".','Solution'=>'Finish','Solution_Description'=>'The World indicates that the solution to the current situation lies in finishing some task or quest that is already under way. Examples include having to finish your prototype, completing you journey, or finding all the remaining magic crystals.'), //*
		array('Yarn_Name'=>'The Beyond','Yarn_Description'=>'The Beyond card represents that which is outside. In many ways it is the opposite of the World, as that card implies a wholeness and completeness, the Beyond tells us that even the Omniverse has its impossibilities. The Beyond can directly represent unknown factors, or the factors from beyond creation that are called the Increated. The Beyond can also represent the Supernatural, as anything beyond nature is within the bounds of the Beyond.','Significator'=>['Plot'=>'The Beyond Plot is often a tale of horror (usually cosmic), as some force beyond normal is unleashed upon the world. Demons, Undead and other tools of the Increated are common to Beyond Plots. Technically, any unknown can be a part of the Beyond, extraterrestrials, ghosts, spirits, a stranger from out of town, they can all be part of a Beyond tale. The only important factor is that it is Beyond normal in some way. ','Side'=>'A Side marked by the Beyond is usually touched by some other world. This can range from their Embodiments just being considered a bit weird to actually being possessed by the Increated. When the External side or Shadows side is marked by The Beyond then the Embodiments can actually be Aliens, Fantastic races or Increated, Goblins, Demons or Demon-Lords as required.','Character'=>'The Beyond Significator indicates a Character who is an outsider, alien or weirdo. <p>They <strong>Gain Yin</strong> when they speak or act strangely, or ask odd questions. </p><p>They <strong>Gain Yang</strong> when they answer a question, especially if it wasn\'t directed at them, or the answer is weird. </p><p>They <strong>Gain Chi</strong> when they act as if something common or normal is unusual or funny, or they act as though they have forgotten (or never knew the meaning of) a common word. </p><p>They also gain +1 Success Level to any strange, weird or "impossible" action.</p>','Scene'=>'The Beyond Scene is usually used to represent any scene that goes beyond the normal risks or limits of the Plot. This Scene may be at much Higher Stakes than any other, or it may involve forces that have not appeared in this story, and actually represents the Frame of a second, larger Story impinging on the first. Yarn-Tellers that play a Beyond card can narrate almost anything following it. The Referee and other Yarn-Tellers should try to roll with this Narration as much as possible. Narration during a Beyond may not directly contradict any previous Narration, or it runs the risk of becoming Unreliable Narration, which in turn can be ignored by later Yarn-Tellers.'],'Beat_Type'=>'6', 'Conflict_Embodiment'=>'3', 'Facet_Embodiment'=>'17', 'Hook_Aspect'=>'Hitches', 'Aspect_Description'=>'The Hook targets the Character\'s Hitches, the bigger the better.','Hook'=>'Wildcard', 'Hook_Description'=>'The Hook is just one of those out there crazy starts to a story. Perhaps they come around on a beach near a crashed plane, or wrecked boat, with no memories of where they were going or why.', 'Gain'=>'Add Alternate', 'Fray'=>'Wandering Monster', 'Fray_Description'=>'A holdover from Old School Gaming. The encounter is against a random Monster (Force of Nature Extra or similar powerful individual) or a group of similar powered Characters (Cast Extras) or a large group (2 to 1 outnumbering) Chorus (Extras) or a tide of Vex Extras.', 'Snag'=>'Triple Threat', 'Snag_Description'=>'A Triple Threat Draws and Plays an additional 2 Cards one as a Second Fray Ordeal and one as a Snag ','NPC'=>array('Archetype'=>'Undead','Persona'=>16,'Core'=>17,'Hitch'=>5,'Description'=>'Undead come in lots of different types, but you\'d be surprised how many can be modelled with this Archetype.'),'Sweeping'=>'Interlogue','Sweeping_Text'=>'The Sweeping is an Interlogue, where we cut away from the Pressed Embodiment to find out what is happening to some other Characters usually in a different Plot, but it can be a Scene or Two for the Dominant Embodiment.', 'History'=>'Supernatural','History_Description'=>'The Beyond indicates that the events that have led to the current situation were not natural in nature, some supernatural, preternatural, spiritual, divine, mystical, spectral, magical, occult or other-worldly force (often the Increated or F&aelig;) are involved.', 'Situation'=>'Unlimited', 'Situation_Description'=>'The Beyond indicates that the current situation is unlimited, it could destroy the universe, unmake anything, or change everything. It is an ultimate threat and often appears unstoppable, although usually there is a solution.','Solution'=>'Outside','Solution_Description'=>'The Beyond indicates that the solution to the situation lies outside the current situation, this may mean a trip outside the affected area is required, or that the solution lies with some outsider who is new to the area, occasionally it means that no solution will be found without resorting to some kind of time-travel, parallel universes, or magical shenanigans.') //*
);
	private static $revelations= array(
	//Diamonds
 array('About'=>'World-Building Ambition','About_Description'=>'The information is about the background, or setting, not the current plot or situation. It might include pertinent details for the current plot, but is usually just information about a (somewhat) common ambition, aspiration, or hope among the character\'s peers. The Yarn-Teller that played the card should specify what this ambition is (Holo-Star, Splice-Hockey Player, Dragon-rider etc).','Info'=>'Ambition',  'Info_Description'=>'Information that is about the ambitions of the Embodiment.', 'Vector'=>'Source', 'Vector_Description'=>'A Whistle-blower or some credible source for the information is found (like an old article), or a turncoat from the enemy, who tells you it clearly, but privately. They probably want to keep their identity secret, or certainly protected, but maybe not, perhaps they wish to be paid, or need something else from the Character.', 'Alternate'=>'Incarna', 'Alternate_Description'=>'The information is about the Incarna of someone or something. If the Incarna is specified it is usually because it is special. So probably not Flesh and Blood...', 'Detail'=>'Weakness', 'Detail_Description'=>'A weakness detail may be a Hitch, or some Umbral condition, or just knowledge of a low Facet Boon.'),//A -ambition
 array('About'=>'World-Building Ghosts','About_Description'=>'The information is about the background, or setting, not the current plot or situation. It might include pertinent details for the current plot, but is usually just information about a local ghost story or haunting. The Yarn-Teller that played the card should specify how the ghost story.','Info'=>'Hints',  'Info_Description'=>'Not necessarily information, but the wraiths of information that act as pointers in the right direction. There is a lot of crossover with the Clue Wyrd Tarot Card here. Hints are generally a little more direct, (such as "Perhaps a Guild-Mage could be paid to tell you...") while a Clue must be worked out or pieced together.', 'Vector'=>'Phantasm', 'Vector_Description'=>'The information is conveyed by some supernatural means, often a ghost or spirit that appears and brings word of importance (often their own passing). If you are not comfortable with a ghost in your cyberpunk universe, you can always use a Cyberwraith, a digital soul, or transhuman, or phantasms can also be a holographic image, an illusion or hallucination.', 'Alternate'=>'Hitch', 'Alternate_Description'=>'The information reveals a Hitch. Often this revealed Hitch is added to a Lore.', 'Detail'=>'Specific', 'Detail_Description'=>'A specific detail is a tiny, but important details. It might include knowledge that a particular Annex or Descendant has a particular Umbral or Nimbed, or that a Character uses a specific Descendant, Proficiency, etc. Such specificity usually has a reason behind it, that may also be revealed.'),//2 - wraith
 array('About'=>'World-Building Work','About_Description'=>'The information is about the background, or setting, not the current plot or situation. It might include pertinent details for the current plot, but is usually just information about a fairly common task, job, occupation or occasionally a hobby. It could be mucking out stables, scrubbing dragon scales, emptying night-soil, shovelling coal into a furnace, downloading an update, uploading a social status, or flamacksing the flange-straightener.', 'Info'=>'Forte','Info_Description'=>'The information is about what they are good at, this may reveal their profession, occupation, or simply be a warning about a character\'s strengths.', 'Vector'=>'Details', 'Vector_Description'=>'The information is hidden as easily overlooked details. Like an addressed, but empty envelope, or a circled phone number in the phone book. Such Details sometimes require a "Spot Hidden" Key (or a "Knowledge" Orthodox or Heresy, as appropriate) Test to reveal them. Maybe it won\'t be noticed until later.', 'Alternate'=>'Skills', 'Alternate_Description'=>'The information reveals some knowledge of the Skills available to the Narrative Element. This may simply be a Lore Skill.', 'Detail'=>'Functional', 'Detail_Description'=>'A functional detail is information about a function of the Narrative Element being revealed. It might include the fact that a particular car make cannot make certain tyre tracks, or that Rumble mountain isn\'t actually a volcano, but has a huge machine built within it.'),//3 -grindstone
 array('About'=>'World-Building Authority','About_Description'=>'The information is about the background, or setting, not the current plot or situation. It might include pertinent details for the current plot, but is usually just about what is the accepted authority of the world. Is there a codified book of laws? Is there a constitution for government? Is this a crypto-anarchist collective that accepts no authority beyond itself.','Info'=>'Facts',  'Info_Description'=>'The available information is in the form of raw facts, such as "Character X owns a yacht", "Character X comes from a poor family and neighbourhood", "Character X was arrested fifteen years ago, charges were not pressed at that time" and "Character Y was arrested for running a huge drug laboratory fourteen years ago" usually these facts can be used to draw a number of conclusions, some of which may even be true.', 'Vector'=>'Writing', 'Vector_Description'=>'The information is found in writing. This could be a memorandum, a letter, a text, or a book. Sometimes the information will be hidden with a code or cipher within the text, perhaps even a work of fiction might hide some hidden truths.', 'Alternate'=>'Chi', 'Alternate_Description'=>'The information gives some idea of the Chi cost (or Purchase Price), stored Chi (Wealth and Experience), or methods of Gaining Chi (usually the Persona) of the Embodiment.', 'Detail'=>'Linguistic', 'Detail_Description'=>'A detail about the language (and therefore culture) of a people or area. Such as the Western Orcs having no word for "<em>Mercy</em>", but Southern Orcs have words that mean "<em>Has displayed a combination of Lenience and/or laziness</em>" and "<em>not Ruthless</em>" which might mean the same thing.'),//4 - book
 array('About'=>'World-Building Geography','About_Description'=>'The information is about the background, or setting, not the current plot or situation. It might include pertinent details for the current plot, but is usually just about the geography of the world, it could be the literal location of a forest, a city or even a fortress.','Info'=>'Which?',  'Info_Description'=>'Information that reveals which conclusion, opinion, or option is correct. Like which way round the next piece of the puzzle is, which wire should be cut to stop the bomb, or which of your many enemies is actually on your trail.', 'Vector'=>'Minutia', 'Vector_Description'=>'The information is encoded in the smallest, most easily overlooked details, this maybe a "can\'t see the wood for the trees issue" with hundreds of small "off" details, a Freudian slip here, a glossed over point there, a pointed insult thrown at random, these can lead to that "Just one more thing..." question that busts everything open.', 'Alternate'=>'Core', 'Alternate_Description'=>'The information conveys core information, either about the Character\'s Personality Annex Core, or about the work, toil, labour or sacrifices that are key to the events to come.', 'Detail'=>'Ecology', 'Detail_Description'=>'Some Ecological detail about an area or people is shared, such as the Forest Elves bred the first horses, but as a food stock animal, since then the animals have been declared Taboo, only to eaten by the priesthood, and nobility, and their numbers shrank so no horses remain in their forests.'),//5 - forest
 array('About'=>'World-Building Light and Shadow','About_Description'=>'The information is about the background, or setting, not the current plot or situation. It might include pertinent details for the current plot, but is usually about the morality of the world. Is this world a dark place, or is it filled with hope? Is there are balance between the forces of good and evil, or has one side overwhelmed the other, or has some covenant, pact or treaty been signed that guarantees a few sparks of light in the darkness?', 'Info'=>'By What Means?','Info_Description'=>'Information about how far someone may go to achieve their Ends. Will they kill, or die for it? Or will they not even get out of bed in the morning?', 'Vector'=>'Images', 'Vector_Description'=>'The information reaches the characters by images and images alone, this usually means in the form of static photographs (or portraits or sketches), but this might include video files, visions (whether spiritual, psychic or psycho-pharmaceutical in origin, seeing something at great distance or seeing only the shadows cast by the actions behind a curtain.' //This could be an audio recording, minutes of a meeting, a written transcript, or some jotted shorthand notes, but it reveals something important, often historical.'
 , 'Alternate'=>'Success', 'Alternate_Description'=>'The information is about the Successes or accomplishments of a Character, Pact, or Descendant.', 'Detail'=>'Fine', 'Detail_Description'=>'Fine details include minutia about the Character etc. these might include one of the ways they <strong>Gain Yin</strong> / Yang, or which brand of Laser gun they prefer.'),//6 - sun
 array('About'=>'World-Building Vehicles','About_Description'=>'The information is about the background, or setting, not the current plot or situation. It might include pertinent details for the current plot, but is usually just about a reasonably common vehicle or mode of transport in the world. This might be information about a horse, a cart, a car, a mono-cycle, a starship, a time-ship, or a teleport booth', 'Info'=>'With What?', 'Info_Description'=>'Information about a Descendant, that may help or be hindering.', 'Vector'=>'Manual', 'Vector_Description'=>'The information is found in a manual, or similar technical document. It should be an owner\'s manual, accounting ledgers, a treatise, a science paper, or perhaps a map or log-book, rather than an encyclopaedia that contains this information.', 'Alternate'=>'Travels', 'Alternate_Description'=>'The Alternative information reveals where someone or something has been. Where have they been and who they have met can tell you a lot about a person or thing.'//The information is about Finances, Bank accounts, takings, and money. It could simply be a measure of wealth, or perhaps access to another\'s account details.'
 , 'Detail'=>'Common Knowledge', 'Detail_Description'=>'The detail is a piece of common knowledge that should be known to everyone in the world. Careful with the Narration that you give this Revelation, it can easily become "As you know, Bob" exposition, instead consider a child singing a nursery rhyme about it, or a local curse that includes the information, "He\'s gone like King Samand\'s marbles".'),//7 -drive
 array('About'=>'World-Building Fashion','About_Description'=>'The information is about the background, or setting, not the current plot or situation. It might include pertinent details for the current plot, but is usually information about the fashions, fads, conventions, trends and crazes in the world. Is everyone wearing roses to court this season? Are cod-pieces meant to be big? Is brown really the new black? Is fur or leather worn in the city? Has there been a run on goose-down and wool? Is mirror-chrome or are implanted-cyber-weapons the new hotness?','Info'=>'What?', 'Info_Description'=>'What is a broad question, what is it? What does he want? What are their Goals / Plans / Ends?', 'Vector'=>'Head-Canon', 'Vector_Description'=>'The Information does not come from a reputable source, but some amateur, or fan, who may or may not have access to the truth, but has developed their own theory about what really happened. This can be true as "those in the know, know", but it can also be "crack-pot musings on the internet", occasionally though even these crack-pot conspiracy theories can pass true information to a needful party.', 'Alternate'=>'A Belief', 'Alternate_Description'=>'The information is specifically about a belief held by a character, this might be a religion or particular political or life philosophy that someone subscribes to.', 'Detail'=>'Fundamental', 'Detail_Description'=>'Fundamental Details are the big pieces that we often need to make sense of a situation. They might include that two families are at war, or that two members of those families are in love, or that a culture has no magic, only technology. Fundamental Details are often key plot points.'),//8 - cultist
 array('About'=>'World-Building Religion','About_Description'=>'The information is about the background, or setting, not the current plot or situation. It might include pertinent details for the current plot, but is usually information about the priesthood and religions in the world. Often this information is presented about a single religion (although you might get information about a pantheon of gods from one god\'s religion where that is appropriate).', 'Info'=>'Faith', 'Info_Description'=>'Information that is narrative in nature, such stories are always embellished, even when based on real events, and may be completely invented, however they always contain some truth, even if it is an inconsequential detail.', 'Vector'=>'Faith', 'Vector_Description'=>'The information may come from a holy book, or via a cleric, or may just be a matter of personal belief for someone who shares it. It might even be an apparent answer to a prayer.', 'Alternate'=>'Morality', 'Alternate_Description'=>'The alternate information is about the morality of a character or situation. Often this is in the form of some terrible thing the enemy has done, but occasionally it will reveal a philanthropic side to even a super-villain.', 'Detail'=>'Virtue', 'Detail_Description'=>'Virtue details tell us about the good done by a Character, Pact or Descendant. These details are occasionally easily overlooked, but a lot of Characters will draw attention to their positive impact on the world around them.'),//9 - priest
 array('About'=>'World-Building Problems','About_Description'=>'The information is about the background, or setting, not the current plot or situation. It might include pertinent details for the current plot, but is usually just about the problems faced by the majority (or even a minority) of people. These issues can range from obvious such as finding potable water, and edible food, to obscurities like the feather headdresses worn by the nobility must be properly oiled daily.','Info'=>'Issues',  'Info_Description'=>'Information about the issues a character is facing, this can be news that is commonly known ("His wife just died"), or something considered secret ("His doctor told me, in strictest confidence, of course, that it isn\'t actually a physical problem, nothing mechanically wrong, if you get my drift?")', 'Vector'=>'Voices', 'Vector_Description'=>'The information is conveyed by voice, it may be an overheard conversation, a chatty taxi driver, or simply crop up as a topic during a morning exchange, and can, of course, even appear as nothing but rumour, gossip and hearsay. There is often a lot of nonsense that surrounds and may even occlude the revelation with red herrings and misinformation. Sometimes, for example, the voices in your head tell you something, the truth revealed then might be intuition, or something more, or perhaps you just overheard it somewhere.', 'Alternate'=>'Gains', 'Alternate_Description'=>'The information is about a Gain that a Character might make, or how to gain the Descendant or Location. You might need to know how to gain an Ally, or how to retrieve an artefact of ancient power.', 'Detail'=>'Social', 'Detail_Description'=>'Social details tell us about a person by the company they keep, are they a member of a church, a charity, a guild or other professional body, did they attend a certain school, join a secret society, a book, fan, or gentleman\'s club, or are they a member of an owners association?'),//10 - loner
 array( 'About'=>'Mentor','About_Description'=>'The information is about a Teacher or Mentor that can educate the Characters in some Skill or ability that is often unique to the Setting or Story.','Info'=>'Education', 'Info_Description'=>'Information about a Character that tells you what they are skilled in as well as revealing some of their social circle (school friends) and probably any famous mentors or masters they may have previously had. In some societies knowing what school someone attended, or which wizard taught them their skills can be invaluable in assessing their threat.', 'Vector'=>'Broadcast', 'Vector_Description'=>'The information is announced or pronounced by official sources. Announced by a teacher in form-room or assembly, a priest in a sermon, cried out by a town-crier, or perhaps all over the local press and TV stations, the information is broadcast somewhere the PCs can hear or see it.', 'Alternate'=>'Method', 'Alternate_Description'=>'The information is about a method, list, or step-by-step plan. Villains often have a method that they are all too willing to share with their captives as a way of gloating before they finish them off...', 'Detail'=>'Positive', 'Detail_Description'=>'A positive detail is something pleasant about an otherwise terrible Character (such as how patient they are, or how charming), Location (Castle Donotenta has the most amazing tapestries on the continent), or Descendant (Well, it\'s called a Death Ray, but actually it started out as a medical scanner).'),//J - teacher
 array( 'About'=>'McGuffin','About_Description'=>'The information is about a piece of equipment, treasure or device. A physical (Prop) Descendant that may be required or just desired by the Character. This Descendant is also sometimes known as a Plot Device, Plot Coupon, fetch-quest object, the Dooberry, Big Dumb Object, and the Weenie.', 'Info'=>'What?','Info_Description'=>'Information that answers a Why question, like why are they doing it, why is it that way, or why won\'t the enemy leave their fortress?', 'Vector'=>'', 'Vector_Description'=>'', 'Alternate'=>'Construction', 'Alternate_Description'=>'How something was built, or is being built can be very important, just think about giant space stations and the construction plans for them...', 'Detail'=>'Practical', 'Detail_Description'=>'Practical details are details you can act on, who cares that the Arch-Mage\'s Tower is constructed in the Lorican Style, instead the practical details are that it is in a swamp, and can only be approached by boat.'),//Q -forge
 array('About'=>'Treasure','About_Description'=>'The information is about an item of treasure or legendary artefact that may ','Info'=>'How?',  'Info_Description'=>'How exactly is what they plan to do, going to be done? You may get the full plan, or just the important pieces. Sometimes you might even know how to stop them, but not what they plan to do. It all depends on the situation at hand.', 'Vector'=>'Portent', 'Vector_Description'=>'The information is presented via some sign or portent, perhaps some strange planetary conjunction reveals some pertinent astrological facts, or more likely some augury, aura, superstition or warning is seen.', 'Alternate'=>'True Name', 'Alternate_Description'=>'Knowing a True Name is very important for some people. In T13 it lets you know a Character\'s Geometry, but it also let\'s us understand and control Increated a little better, since their True Name is the only reason they exist.', 'Detail'=>'Important', 'Detail_Description'=>'An important detail is revealed. This varies from case to case, but might include knowledge that the device has to charge for an hour before turning it on, or an invading force is on its way, or that unless stopped, the angels will end the world on Thursday. You know, things that people might like to know.'),//K -star
	//Hearts
array('About'=>'Love Interest','About_Description'=>'The information is about a Character\'s Love Interest, it may be a potential new love Interest, or just something you never knew about the one you have.', 'Info'=>'Decisions', 'Info_Description'=>'The Information revealed is about the decisions that the Character must make, or decisions they have made in the past that reveal pertinent things about their character.', 'Vector'=>'Whispers', 'Vector_Description'=>'The information is a secret, perhaps an intimate or delicate one, that is shared in a whisper. Often such whispers can be misheard as they spread, but some inkling of truth should still be discernible.', 'Alternate'=>'Happiness', 'Alternate_Description'=>'Information about the happiness, or not, of the Embodiment(s) or population at large. Perhaps there is a holiday approaching...', 'Detail'=>'Intimate', 'Detail_Description'=>'This is an intimate detail about a character, such as, who are their best friends, who are their past and present lovers, who is their confidante, who do they trust, and sometimes even details about intimate preferences.'),//A -lovers
 array('About'=>'Yours','About_Description'=>'The information is about your own side, or own self. This might reveal your weaknesses or strengths, if you aren\'t already painfully aware of them.', 'Info'=>'Former Glories', 'Info_Description'=>'Some people and things have seem better days, this is information about somethings former glories. Did they once win a gold medal? A science prize? Were they the largest city port in the west long ago?', 'Vector'=>'Red Herring', 'Vector_Description'=>'False information can be as useful as true information, sometimes. Maybe not this time, as the information is actually incorrect or misleading somehow.', 'Alternate'=>'Friends', 'Alternate_Description'=>'Knowledge of a Character\'s friends and allies can tell you a lot about a person.', 'Detail'=>'Remains', 'Detail_Description'=>'Remains details are the often overlooked lingering details, it is the trace of paper ash on a saucer, the clinging strands of DNA that respond to UV light, the fingerprints of a killer on a blade, and of course the dismembered corpse of a serial killer\'s victim.'),//2 -burnout
 array('About'=>'Yours','About_Description'=>'The information is about your own side, or own self. This might reveal your weaknesses or strengths, if you aren\'t already painfully aware of them.','Info'=>'Facets',  'Info_Description'=>'Information about the Facets of a Character or Plot, what are they good at, what are they bad at. The information can be relative to the Character themselves (she is much Stronger in attack than defence), or to another (he is much better-looking than you), or be absolute (the standard unit can lift 3 tonnes, but only moves at a slow walking pace).', 'Vector'=>'Quandary', 'Vector_Description'=>'Sometimes the information given  is a secret itself, perhaps hidden in riddling rhymes and puzzlingly ambiguous statements. It might be a coincidental clue in a crossword puzzle, a question asked by a Sphinx, an ancient symbolic prophecy, or a substitution cipher scrawled in blood by a dying man. The information is available, but a clever mind will be required to reveal all.', 'Alternate'=>'Injuries', 'Alternate_Description'=>'The information is about injuries, perhaps damage that something has taken in the past, or what <em>really</em> happened to the test-pilot...', 'Detail'=>'Questions', 'Detail_Description'=>'Everyone has questions, these details are questions that either the Embodiment itself would ask, or those who know the Embodiment should be asking. These might include "Who out of all my lieutenants is most likely to be behind this coup?", "What is the optimum number of guards for a secret base this size?", "Where will the enemy strike back?", "When is the best time of year to invade Russia? I mean everyone knows the worst time...", "Which says arch-mage better, polymorphing their king into a frog, forcing their entire kingdom to sleep for a thousand years, trapping their capitol city in a painting or turning them all into statues?", or "How many weapons does one man really need to be carrying?"'),//3 -question
 array('About'=>'Yours','About_Description'=>'The information is about your own side, or own self. This might reveal your weaknesses or strengths, if you aren\'t already painfully aware of them.','Info'=>'Lies', 'Info_Description'=>'The Information is about lies that have been told, sometimes the truth is revealed, and sometimes we just know that a lie has been told without knowing the actual truth.','Vector'=>'A Lie', 'Vector_Description'=>'A Lie reveals the information somehow. Perhaps the falsehood protects someone else, or the lie may be part of an alibi that cannot be true, or maybe the lie is an extrapolation of an actual truth that they didn\'t realise they were revealing, and do they know they have been caught out?','Alternate'=>'Myths', 'Alternate_Description'=>'Myths inevitably form around things, no story is ever retold without some form of mythologising the subject. This alternate information is about the myths that surround the Embodiment, these are exaggerations and misinformation that usually make things seem more powerful than they actually are.', 'Detail'=>'Cultural', 'Detail_Description'=>'Cultural details tell us about the culture of a Character, or the people that constructed, or live around a Descendant. You might want to reveal they are a warrior people, how is this expressed? Does every adult carry a sword, a shield, or a gun at all times? Do they wear armour as part of their uniform, or is it something more subtle, like chess being the national game, their cultural heroes are all military leaders from their past, or ammo pockets and bandoleers are really in fashion right now?'),//4 - myth
 array('About'=>'Yours','About_Description'=>'The information is about your own side, or own self. This might reveal your weaknesses or strengths, if you aren\'t already painfully aware of them.','Info'=>'Grotesque', 'Info_Description'=>'The information gained is in the form of a grotesque, this is information about how the Embodiment is viewed by others, but not simply a description. This is more a caricature, with the worst features emphasised usually for comedic effect. At their simplest grotesques can seem little more than a "Your Moma" joke, but a truly great grotesque will not only draw attention to some ugliness of spirit, but will draw some hybrid like comparison to an animal, that matches the Embodiment\'s temperament.', 'Vector'=>'Joke', 'Vector_Description'=>'The information is disguised within a joke that someone tells. It might be the punchline, but is most likely to be a part of the set-up of the joke.', 'Alternate'=>'Humour', 'Alternate_Description'=>'This alternate information is about the humour that surrounds the Embodiment. If they are a character this may be their own preferred style of humour, perhaps even their favourite joke, occasionally (and for Descendants, Locations, etc) this humour will be about or feature the Embodiment, it is a joke told about them, or about the place, or that features them.', 'Detail'=>'Fun', 'Detail_Description'=>'Fun details are those weird pieces of information that are often surprising and somewhat incongruous with other knowledge about them. This can lead to these details being known as "Fun Facts".'),//5 - joke
 array('About'=>'Yours','About_Description'=>'The information is about your own side, or own self. This might reveal your weaknesses or strengths, if you aren\'t already painfully aware of them.','Info'=>'To What Degree?',  'Info_Description'=>'How bad will or can it get? Is everyone a traitor or just a select few? How many will die of the plague? How many swords march against you?', 'Vector'=>'Dream', 'Vector_Description'=>'There is a long history of dreams being an important part of a discovery, they can reveal information that it can be difficult to obtain in other ways; it is true that dreams can present information that the mind has previously observed back to the conscious mind after it has been processed in new ways. This can be used to draw attention to something that was previously overlooked, if you throw in unconscious extra-sensory perception as well, dreams can show events that are occurring far away in real time, or can just be the usual nonsense with a hidden message. Information presented in dreams is usually symbolic in some way, rather than easily understood.', 'Alternate'=>'Magic', 'Alternate_Description'=>'Sometimes things are magical, they may be created by magic, have access to magic, or simply be magical in nature. The Alternative information here is about the magic that surrounds and is available to the Embodiment. Can they cast spells, have a magical sword, or are they immune to magic?', 'Detail'=>'Impressions', 'Detail_Description'=>'Impression details can be quite varied. Some impressions like foot-prints can be obvious, letting a hunter know which way the deer or monster went, but some can be subtle, such as the minute scratches around a picked lock. Then again not all impressions are physical, there is a reason some people try very hard to make a good first impression.'),//6 - unicorn
 array('About'=>'Yours','About_Description'=>'The information is about your own side, or own self. This might reveal your weaknesses or strengths, if you aren\'t already painfully aware of them.','Info'=>'What for?',  'Info_Description'=>'The information is about what something is for, not necessarily what it is, or what is the expected result. For example when a bald super-villain steals a nuclear weapon, and is buying up desert property, the what for in this case would reveal they wish to destabilise fault lines and flood California.', 'Vector'=>'Senses', 'Vector_Description'=>'The information reaches the character via their senses, normally this is a direct sensing, they see flashes of light, hear shots fired, and smell and taste the gun-smoke. Sometimes all the senses will be involved, other times only one or two. This vector often is used when the sensory pathway is unusual, as most characters are primarily visual and auditory information based, scent, taste, sense of balance, thermoception (our ability to feel heat), etc. are more likely to be carrying the information.', 'Alternate'=>'Grace', 'Alternate_Description'=>'The Alternate information is about the grace of the Embodiment. There is an elegance, beauty, style or poise to the Embodiment that is worth commenting upon, and reveals something about their strength, fitness, or fashion sense that will be important.', 'Detail'=>'Biological', 'Detail_Description'=>'Biological details tell us about the biology of a Character or people. They may include genetic markers, or just knowledge about their species or bloodline. The Carracam for example, clone themselves on death, birthing at least 3 larval children that eat their way out of the corpse.' ),//7 - stag A nuance detail can shine a light on some previously overlooked element of an Embodiment. If a vicious warlord spared half a village after he saw their shrine, does that mean he was from that village? Or that he believes in the same Saint? If later he spares another town, bypassing it completely because it is named for the same Saint, then you can decide.
 array('About'=>'Yours','About_Description'=>'The information is about your own side, or own self. This might reveal your weaknesses or strengths, if you aren\'t already painfully aware of them.','Info'=>'Expertise', 'Info_Description'=>'The information reveals something about the expertise of a character or the skill that was required to construct a Descendant or Location. In some cases the information will reveal the actual creator, or the only other expert who could understand something.', 'Vector'=>'Symbols', 'Vector_Description'=>'The information is presented in the form of symbols, this can mean simply a written message, but more often with symbols there is additional nuance that must be used when interpreting them. Perhaps this is a text-message that is written in emojis, txt, H@xor or 1337 speak, or the information may have been encoded into a painting or even into building plans. Then again it can be as obvious as a radiation warning symbol.', 'Alternate'=>'Training', 'Alternate_Description'=>'Information about the training that a character has received or the training that is necessary to correctly use a given Descendant can be very pertinent information indeed.', 'Detail'=>'Professional', 'Detail_Description'=>'Professional details are those tiny touches that let you know that something was done by a very skilled and practised person, as such they are usually only spotted by another skilled professional. A professional detail might reveal that the thief wore gloves, and a hat so they left no fingerprints or hairs in the crime scene, or that the programmer of a nasty virus had previous experience working with the banking machines that have been hardest hit.'),//8 -wizard
 array('About'=>'Yours','About_Description'=>'The information is about your own side, or own self. This might reveal your weaknesses or strengths, if you aren\'t already painfully aware of them.','Info'=>'Chance', 'Info_Description'=>'The Information is about a chance or probability of something, it does not represent a fact, or something that necessarily has or will occur, but rather a probability or chance that something will or has happened. For example the chances of successfully navigating through an asteroid field is approximately three-thousand, seven hundred and twenty to one.', 'Vector'=>'Coincidence', 'Vector_Description'=>'The information is revealed by some strange or unexpected circumstance or event that lacks a causal relationship. If you run into your friend in a field for no reason, that\'s a coincidence, if a third friend owns the field and is hosting a birthday party there, not so much.', 'Alternate'=>'Claims', 'Alternate_Description'=>'Claims are things that people believe the Embodiment has achieved in the past. Often these claims were made by the Embodiment themselves (or their Creator), and may or may not be true.', 'Detail'=>'Superstition', 'Detail_Description'=>'A Superstition detail can be very subtle or very obvious depending upon how familiar with the superstition the observer is, and how blatant the superstition. Subtle examples might include finding a lemon or potato with iron nails driven through it at a crime scene, indicating someone believed they were being targeted by the evil eye. Blatant examples might include a character stepping into traffic rather than walk under a ladder, or a building not having a thirteenth floor.'),//9 -lady
 array('About'=>'Yours','About_Description'=>'The information is about your own side, or own self. This might reveal your weaknesses or strengths, if you aren\'t already painfully aware of them.','Info'=>'Position', 'Info_Description'=>'Positions are important, whether it is knowing where someone or something is, their rank in society, their reputation, or an attitude, situation or viewpoint that they hold. Knowing those things about someone can tell you a lot about them. Of course knowing the position of a castle can help plan an assault, and the position of an army can help plan a defence.', 'Vector'=>'Entertainment', 'Vector_Description'=>'The information is embedded or encoded in a piece of entertainment, this might be a case of the infamous "play-within-a-play", a novelist who commits a murder exactly like one they have written in a book, or a song sung by a court-jester that derides the King\'s cousin and his many short-comings. Bards and Heralds for centuries used folk songs to create and spread news stories and gossip, and this is something similar.', 'Alternate'=>'Home', 'Alternate_Description'=>'Where someone lives currently can be important information about a person, especially if you are looking for them. Where they came from can also be useful.', 'Detail'=>'Political', 'Detail_Description'=>'Political details are details about how a character or location is viewed politically, who are their allies and enemies in court, to which political party do they belong (or vote) and what image do they project to others (are they known as a respectable family man, billionaire philanthropist, or are they remembered for a fiasco?).'),//10 -jester
 array('About'=>'Mystery','About_Description'=>'The information is about some mystery or unknown thing. This might be a secret hidden down the ages, or just who took the last doughnut.','Info'=>'With Whom?', 'Info_Description'=>'You can find out a lot about a person from the company they keep. And it always helps to know how many are in the gang you are hunting.', 'Vector'=>'Obvious Lie', 'Vector_Description'=>'Sometimes information includes something so preposterous that it is an obvious lie. Sometimes the obvious lie can hide a deeper truth, this can happen often when someone reveals they know nothing about a subject they have claimed knowledge of by asking a question they should obviously know the answer too. Worse yet is when the obvious lie is actually the truth, but made to seem so preposterous that it is dismissed out of hand.', 'Alternate'=>'Guises', 'Alternate_Description'=>'The information is about how a character or descendant likes to be perceived. Sometimes this can be an alternate name, an alias, codename, pen name, or secret identity that they use. For example, traditionally Robin Hood is known to have employed a disguise as a peasant farmer at tournament. ', 'Detail'=>'Disguised', 'Detail_Description'=>'Disguised details are those cleverly arranged details that misdirect and misinform the unwary observer, this can be as simple as making handwriting unrecognisable by writing with their off-hand, or as complex as arranging the sniper shot to exactly coincide with the cannon-fire in the 1812 Overture.'),//J - mask
 array('About'=>'Secret','About_Description'=>'The Information is about some secret. This might be a secret group, door, passageway or perhaps information like a password.','Info'=>'Obscure',  'Info_Description'=>'Obscure information is information that is difficult to find, sometimes this is because someone would prefer the information was not available at all, other times it is because the information is genuinely difficult to find out. Examples might include, finding out the real name of the Dark Lord, or the exact frequencies that will negate that battleship\'s Electronic Counter Measures.', 'Vector'=>'Clothing', 'Vector_Description'=>'Clothing can convey a lot of information about a person or culture, from the level of trade and wealth they have to specific details of kinship, or favourite TV show.', 'Alternate'=>'Comfort', 'Alternate_Description'=>'The information is about the comforts that the Embodiment enjoys, these are usually specific, rather than generic comforts, perhaps that character is known to sleep only in an oxygen tent, on duckling eiderdown, or with a teddy bear, a Monster may take comfort in eating only those people who are overweight, or those who are exceptionally healthy, or bathes daily in a specific spring, pool or grotto, or perhaps a Descendant must be cleaned only with neat grain alcohol, must kept in a secure but silk-lined, rose-oak case, or must be polished with only wax from a particular region\'s bees.', 'Detail'=>'Hidden', 'Detail_Description'=>'A hidden detail is placed deliberately and always carries a communication of some sort, whether it is a hidden maker\'s mark, the references to other movies in a scene\'s set dressing, an invisible ink, an easily overlooked microdot, or an engineered quantum signature. These are the details that may be obvious if you are looking for them, but are unnoticeable if you are unaware.'),//Q -cloak
 array('About'=>'Help','About_Description'=>'The information is about a Character can help the Character, it might be someone who can patch your wounds, or fix your car. They may not be an Ally exactly, but they aren\'t an enemy either.','Info'=>'How?', 'Info_Description'=>'The information revealed answers the how question. How are the enemy going to infiltrate the kingdom? How did the monster get in the house? How does one conduct open heart surgery? The answers can be exceptionally detailed or just the broad strokes though, and will usually tell you nothing about the reasons behind anything or even who is doing it. You may know the enemy is among the party guests, but not who they are. The smashed down door tells you how the monster got in, but nothing about what it looks like, or whether it left again.', 'Vector'=>'Blood', 'Vector_Description'=>'Blood is usually a good indicator something bad has happened, but at times it can convey a lot more information to either a mage, a cleric, detective, physician, or a forensic biologist.', 'Alternate'=>'Health', 'Alternate_Description'=>'The information is about the health of the Embodiment. This can be as simple as a splatter of blood revealing that someone (or something) was injured, a terrible cough, sweats or fever indicating some one is ill, or as complex as noticing that the locals all have mud-streaked but perfect, blemish-free skin, apart from the lord who is bathed and acne-ridden.', 'Detail'=>'Cunning', 'Detail_Description'=>'Cunning details are the careful touches of a design, secret compartments, doors, rooms and elevators, and of course the tales of actual cunning that people tell about a Character.'),//K -physician Acts of violence are something that people tend to discuss, whether it is the violence that they did, or that was done to them (often both). It is the reputation of a warlord, the CV of an assassin, and the dark secret of a cleric or medic.
	 //Clubs
 array('About'=>'The Story', 'About_Description'=>'The information is about the current situation and plot. It might include information about one side of the Conflict, all the sides and anything in between. It is normal when providing information to always reveal information about the Dominant Side as well as any others.', 'Info'=>'Costly',  'Info_Description'=>'Information that is valuable and useful, somehow always has a cost. The costs can vary from a simple money transaction to longer, more permanent costs.', 'Vector'=>'Records', 'Vector_Description'=>'Records can be tally marks on clay tablets; written laws and history on vellum; detailed client databases; the tangled, knotted, weavings the Eelafin call writing; musical or speech recordings, even several slightly contradictory witness statements. Regardless of how they tell us, they always have something to share, if we know how to interpret them correctly.', 'Alternate'=>'Legal', 'Alternate_Description'=>'The information is legal in nature, this may mean anything from thousands of pages of legal tomes, to a parking ticket. Often legal information will reveal past transgressions, but can also reveal property and business ownership, banking paper trails, familial connections, even contracts, treaties and alliances.','Detail'=>'Loophole', 'Detail_Description'=>'Loophole details reveal an ambiguity or deficiency in a system. Originally loopholes were places for archers to shoot out of a castle, and their placement was important to allow archers to cover the out walls, stopping ladders or sappers from approaching, sometimes during a siege a single archer not manning his loophole, or a loophole being misplaced, or deficient somehow could mean a section of wall was not being covered, and a push there could breach the wall. Later this attention to these details became used to describe other situations where something could be circumvented because of a technical defect.'),//A - court
 array('About'=>'The Story', 'About_Description'=>'The information is about the current situation and plot. It might include information about one side of the Conflict, all the sides and anything in between. It is normal when providing information to always reveal information about the Dominant Side as well as any others.','Info'=>'Suspicions',  'Info_Description'=>'Suspicions vary in scope and accuracy more than any other Information. If a detective suspects some one of a crime, they are probably right more often than a conspiracy theorist is right about the government, but both can be wrong, or ultimately proved right. Suspicions lack evidence, and are often little more than a reaction to a person or group.', 'Vector'=>'Tapestry', 'Vector_Description'=>'The information is present upon a tapestry, poster, billboard, or perhaps is read from Wyrd\'s Tapestry directly, by Doom-reading from cards in play "The bad guy has a Wyrd Tarot Hand?! He must be at least a Mercari.", "She negated a Yarn card?! Run! Flee with extra flee!"', 'Alternate'=>'Power', 'Alternate_Description'=>'The information is specifically about the powers the Embodiment has, whether Annexes or political power and pacts.', 'Detail'=>'Peculiar', 'Detail_Description'=>'Peculiar details are odd little out-of-place touches that point to something bigger, or more extraordinary than you might first have guessed. They are the footprints that stop in the middle of the field, or that pass through (or over) a solid wall.'),//2 - Eelafin
 array('About'=>'The Story', 'About_Description'=>'The information is about the current situation and plot. It might include information about one side of the Conflict, all the sides and anything in between. It is normal when providing information to always reveal information about the Dominant Side as well as any others.', 'Info'=>'Warning', 'Info_Description'=>'Some information is just a warning, the rattlesnake does not shake its tail when hunting, but only when it is afraid. Warnings tell us things aren\'t safe, that some people are not to be trusted, or that now they are coming for you. Some warn us to back off, or simply that a food might contain nuts...', 'Vector'=>'Insinuations', 'Vector_Description'=>'Insinuations tell you nothing directly, but hint and suggest information, they are meant to be artful, covert and subtle idea inceptions. A master manipulator can make you question or believe anything they want with their insinuations, without any of those beliefs or doubts ever being directly stated.', 'Alternate'=>'Sins', 'Alternate_Description'=>'The information is all negative information about a Character or thing. It may be a police rap sheet, or the tales of infamy about a ruler or villain.', 'Detail'=>'Disinformation', 'Detail_Description'=>'Disinformation details can be subtle evasions and distortions of an actual truth or just blatant lies. At their most basic and simple disinformation details may be a lie, like a cover story that doesn\'t even explain what a single observer reported, at their most complex and covert the disinformation may include logical traps and assumptions that will even misdirect and misinform those who ignore the actual disinformation that is presented.'),//3 - serpent
 array( 'About'=>'The Story', 'About_Description'=>'The information is about the current situation and plot. It might include information about one side of the Conflict, all the sides and anything in between. It is normal when providing information to always reveal information about the Dominant Side as well as any others.', 'Info'=>'Answers','Info_Description'=>'When we have questions, all we want is answers. Of course, an answer is not always the same as <em>the</em> answer. What are the biggest questions someone would have about the Embodiment? Now create two answers to each of those questions.', 'Vector'=>'Fluids', 'Vector_Description'=>'The information is carried by a fluid medium, this may mean the sonar that dolphins or submarines use, the electrical signals tracked by some bottom-feeding species, how a blood splattered crime scene tells the story of the crime, how liquid ink running from a fountain pen can write a message, or how much emotional information can be convened in a single tear welling and rolling forth.', 'Alternate'=>'Abyss', 'Alternate_Description'=>'The information is about the depths that this Embodiment have plumbed. This is often profound information, revealing much of the character and strengths, as well as an occasional exploitable weakness. Sometimes the depths revealed are only glimpses of something truly unfathomable, literally immeasurable or infinite in scope, such as the abyss of space or time.', 'Detail'=>'Emotional', 'Detail_Description'=>'Emotional details are the details the carry emotional information, and are read so easily by empathic characters. A kiss to the forehead says "I love you." but it can also carry connotations such as "Good luck", "Goodbye", "Please stop" or "Do your chores" depending on context. '),//4 - waters
 array('About'=>'The Story', 'About_Description'=>'The information is about the current situation and plot. It might include information about one side of the Conflict, all the sides and anything in between. It is normal when providing information to always reveal information about the Dominant Side as well as any others.', 'Info'=>'Defences.', 'Info_Description'=>'The information is about the defences of the Embodiment. Do they always have an anti-stab vest, or security detail, is the location a veritable fortress, or does the computer have an AI Firewall?', 'Vector'=>'Device', 'Vector_Description'=>'The information is presented by or in a device of sort sort. This might be the shield of a knight baring his coat of arms, or its modern equivalent the unit patch, or the device may be a scanner, radio, or often now a phone that provides the information.', 'Alternate'=>'Privileges', 'Alternate_Description'=>'The information is about the privileges that the Embodiment enjoys. Whether they are from a rich family, inherited land, had a good education, were not rejected by society despite their crimes, or whether they are trusted with a hall pass because of their status as head of some club or another. Privileges were originally private laws that effectively protect an individual or select group, often granting then immunity or exemption from another law.', 'Detail'=>'Ambient', 'Detail_Description'=>'Ambient details are atmospheric touches and subtle clues about the Embodiment. They are the hints of lilly scent on the air near the vampire, the shadows deepening as the demon draws breath, or the ultra-high pitched electronic whine that only children and animals can hear, that the otherwise perfect android makes.'),//5 -shield
 array('About'=>'The Story', 'About_Description'=>'The information is about the current situation and plot. It might include information about one side of the Conflict, all the sides and anything in between. It is normal when providing information to always reveal information about the Dominant Side as well as any others.','Info'=>'Organization',  'Info_Description'=>'Information about how the Embodiment is organized. Are they part of an army, a guild or group, or do they act alone? Are they part of something larger than themselves?', 'Vector'=>'Cries', 'Vector_Description'=>'Cries can carry a lot of information, from screams of terror, anguish, pain or despair, through to sobbed words of grieving, yelled insults, and battle orders. Cries are loud, intended to draw attention, although not always to carry information beyond something bad is happening here.', 'Alternate'=>'Associates', 'Alternate_Description'=>'Who does the Embodiment hang out with? Do they have known allies, friends, a family? The information you get will go some way towards answering these questions.', 'Detail'=>'Public', 'Detail_Description'=>'Public details are information that the general public has access to, if a character is famous for some reason, that reason is public, and the more famous a person is the more public details that will be available about them, from wikipedia entries, magazine articles, recorded interviews and social media posts.'),//6 - horde
 array('About'=>'The Story', 'About_Description'=>'The information is about the current situation and plot. It might include information about one side of the Conflict, all the sides and anything in between. It is normal when providing information to always reveal information about the Dominant Side as well as any others.','Info'=>'Properties',  'Info_Description'=>'Information about Properties can be as simple as a Location\'s address, the buildings and treasures that the Embodiment owns, or it can be a list of known properties of the Embodiment or one of its abilities.', 'Vector'=>'Fractures', 'Vector_Description'=>'Fractures can carry information, with smashed glass telling you how a room was entered, or how fast a car was travelling before it crashed. Fractures can also occur in injuries, which can certainly send a message.', 'Alternate'=>'Fragility', 'Alternate_Description'=>'The information is about how the Embodiment is fragile, they may have some weakness or flaw that might be exploited somehow. A castle wall might have been raised on a section of weaker sandstone, or may have been made with lower quality mortar, and characters always have Hitches that can be revealed.', 'Detail'=>'Clear', 'Detail_Description'=>'Some details are clear, they draw attention to themselves. They are the blinking countdown lights on the side of the bomb, the clearly labelled "Drink Me" label, or the glow deep within the flesh of the mutant as it builds its power.'),//7 - crystal
 array( 'About'=>'The Story', 'About_Description'=>'The information is about the current situation and plot. It might include information about one  side of the Conflict, or all. It is normal when providing information to only reveal information about a single Side of the Conflict, usually the Dominant or Above sides.','Info'=>'How Much?', 'Info_Description'=>'Information that tells us something about amounts, volumes, or weights. It could be as simple as a receipt, or a tax return, or as complex as the number of work-hours something might take, but often reveals something more interesting than you\'d think.', 'Vector'=>'Wounds', 'Vector_Description'=>'Wounds can carry information, even if it is the wounded messenger that carries them. Even the wounds on a corpse can tell us things about the height, handedness, strength and weight of the attacker, as well as information about the weapon used if you know how to read them. Especially if the bad guy used them to leave letters, perhaps spelling "DETH", such a message might be a damning indictment of the education system, or point to a specific group or killer.', 'Alternate'=>'Work', 'Alternate_Description'=>'The information is about the work of the Embodiment, whether that is work that they have done, are currently doing or will do. This is not necessarily the profession of the Embodiment, but more their accomplishments, deeds, or achievements.', 'Detail'=>'Morbid', 'Detail_Description'=>'Morbid details are details of an especially gloomy, grisly, and gruesome nature, they tend to focus on darkness, depression, death and disease, aggrandizing and even glorifying these, although in a chilling and cheerless way. These may be details about the Embodiment themselves, detailing their long fight with cancer, the details of the afternoon and evening when their family were butchered, or about the Embodiments own "achievements" in these realms, such as a serial killer\'s kill count.'),//8 - scythe
 array( 'About'=>'The Story', 'About_Description'=>'The information is about the current situation and plot. It might include information about one side of the Conflict, all the sides and anything in between. It is normal when providing information to always reveal information about the Dominant Side as well as any others.','Info'=>'Official', 'Info_Description'=>'Official Information can be information about someone\'s rank or class within a society, or it can be the information that governments have at their disposal, be it police records, intelligence reports, or military records.', 'Vector'=>'Political', 'Vector_Description'=>'Politics is always about messages, and so political campaigns can carry information about Embodiments (obviously if those Embodiments are politicians, or are voted non-political positions).', 'Alternate'=>'Accomplishment', 'Alternate_Description'=>'The information concerns the Embodiment\'s greatest, or most impressive accomplishment. Do they have the highest tower in the country, or did they kill the most Goblins in the battle of Fellmeer?', 'Detail'=>'Geopolitical', 'Detail_Description'=>'The details concern the geopolitics of the situation or Characters. Where are their allegiances, how far away are their banner-men, where is the armoury inside the fortress walls? Those sorts of questions can be answered.'),//9 - crown
 array('About'=>'The Story', 'About_Description'=>'The information is about the current situation and plot. It might include information about either side of the Conflict, or both. It is normal when providing information to only reveal information about a single Side of the Conflict, usually the Dominant or Above sides.', 'Info'=>'Safety', 'Info_Description'=>'This could tell you information about someone\'s safety, where do they feel safe, who with and why? Or it could as easily be instructions on how to train dragons without being broiled or a simple warning to avoid the forest.', 'Vector'=>'Walls', 'Vector_Description'=>'Walls and barriers can tell us things about buildings and people, but they can also be a source of graffiti and bill posters that spread word of bands, club nights, impending temporal schisms, and so on.', 'Alternate'=>'Family', 'Alternate_Description'=>'The information concerns Family connections that surround the Embodiment.', 'Detail'=>'Flaw', 'Detail_Description'=>'Everyone and and everything have their flaws, in T13 they often have at least one Hitch of the Flaw Tier, but this might be a flaw in their story, or a flaw in the prosecution\'s case.'),//10 - guardian
 array('About'=>'Danger', 'About_Description'=>'The information is about a danger that threatens the Character. This might be some imminent disaster, an ever-present threat or a distant concern.','Info'=>'Violence',  'Info_Description'=>'The information is about the violence that surrounds or is created by the Embodiment.', 'Vector'=>'Atmosphere', 'Vector_Description'=>'The information is carried by the atmosphere, this can be a scent on the wind, the rain or that thunder-like rumble could be a sign of a storm or the sound of distant guns.', 'Alternate'=>'Obstacles', 'Alternate_Description'=>'The information is either about the Obstacles that stand in an Ordeal, or may be encoded as Obstacles in the next (or last) Ordeal. When they realise they were meant to count the number of spears in the pit trap. Oh, the look on their faces...', 'Detail'=>'Confused', 'Detail_Description'=>'Confused details occur when some details never seem to be consistent, some witnesses say the dragon is red, others say it is black, the truth is there are two dragons in the swamp.'),//J - tempest
 array('About'=>'Pleasures', 'About_Description'=>'The information is about a pleasure that is available. This might be a particular food, drug, or experience unique to the Location or Story, or could be information about some common pleasure.', 'Info'=>'Pleasures', 'Info_Description'=>'Information about what an Embodiment likes to do with their time is always useful. Sometimes we can learn more from someone\'s Vices than from their words.', 'Vector'=>'Advertisement', 'Vector_Description'=>'Adverts are everywhere in our society and always conveying some information to us. But this one is different, maybe its a private ad, simply saying "Safety not guaranteed", or perhaps it\'s the yells of a street vendor, telling us of distant lands and the quality of their silks and spices. Then again news vendors yelling out "click-bait" headlines is as old as printing.', 'Alternate'=>'Sympathetic', 'Alternate_Description'=>'The information covers the reasons the bad guy is doing what he is doing and it turns out that, yeah, he might be doing the right thing after all. Maybe he is leading an army invading the country because his twin sister has been kidnapped by the king, or perhaps the reason he butchers the desert snake tribes <em>that way</em> is because he was raised by a nest of serpent people hiding in the capital city, after they slaughtered his family in front of him.', 'Detail'=>'Mistake', 'Detail_Description'=>'A Mistake detail could be a misspelled word, or an auto-corrected text, or it could be a deliberate mistake. So are the outlaws you\'re tracking inside the barn and forgot to post a rear guard, or are they well aware you are out here and have deliberately left a way in?'),//Q - inn
 array('About'=>'Magic', 'About_Description'=>'The information is about some magical power or treasure that exists in the world, it my be part of the Story or just a part of the background.','Info'=>'Doom',  'Info_Description'=>'Sometimes information can include Dooms, Mercari can get reads on other people\'s fate from time to time, and Prophets can do that for a whole people or region, or time-travellers may believe that they know exactly what is going to happen ahead of time. Of course, they aren\'t always right. Sometimes it is enough to know that the bad guy will get it in the very end, other times it isn\'t.', 'Vector'=>'Hunch', 'Vector_Description'=>'Intuition can be more than wild guesses. Sometimes subtle clues are not noticed by the conscious mind, but they tease at the subconscious, sometimes these clues emerge in dreams, but other times they present as gut instincts, or intuitions. For some Character\'s these hunches can be more valuable than another man\'s word, at least until they are proved wrong.', 'Alternate'=>'TMI', 'Alternate_Description'=>'Sometimes the information we get is Too Much Information, this might be that there are months of transcripts to work through, or that you now have detailed records of lavatory activities. There will be important information in there, if you can sift through the stuff you\'d rather not know.', 'Detail'=>'Magical', 'Detail_Description'=>'Magical details share information about the magic the '),//K - fairy noble
//Spades
 array('About'=>'Dominant','About_Description'=>'The information revealed is about the Dominant Conflict Embodiment. Sometimes they are Characters, but almost as often they are Locations, Quests, Ordeals, or similar. Where this is true the Revelation should reveal details about future Quests the Pressed Characters must complete, or places they should visit. The Revelation can be little more than a call-back or foreshadowing if handled correctly.','Info'=>'Connections',  'Info_Description'=>'The information is about the connections that the character or location has.', 'Vector'=>'Aura', 'Vector_Description'=>'Auras are for some people a spiritual or emotional energy field that they see, or they may just be another word for a fragrance.', 'Alternate'=>'Sacrifices', 'Alternate_Description'=>'The information may be about the Sacrifices the Embodiment has made, or Sacrifices that will have to be made. These Sacrifices might be great and grand, or just toll for the tunnel, or it could just be information about a Sacrifice Umbral.', 'Detail'=>'Target', 'Detail_Description'=>'A target detail is simply that, where, what, or whom the target of the Embodiment is.'),//A - threshold
 array('About'=>'Pressed','About_Description'=>'The information is about the Pressed Conflict Embodiment, which is often a PC in a game, and is usually the antagonist in a Story.', 'Info'=>'Corruption', 'Info_Description'=>'Corruption can range from a little bribery to actual demonic influences, and everything in between. Finding out about corruption is easy, although rarely will you get the details.', 'Vector'=>'Scent', 'Vector_Description'=>'Scents can tell us a lot, reminding us of places, people, animals and of course events. The lingering scent of gun-smoke or fire can pass more than enough information for action.', 'Alternate'=>'Influences', 'Alternate_Description'=>'The information is about the influences that are working in the plot, or on the Character. These might be just the politics of their social media friends, the meddlings of some Seelie Noble, or the machinations of an Increated, you just never know.', 'Detail'=>'Critical', 'Detail_Description'=>'Critical details are either spotting flaws in an otherwise perfect planet killer space base, or a critique that one can use to improve one\'s performance.'),//2 - swamp
 array('About'=>'Above','About_Description'=>'The information revealed is about the Above Conflict Embodiment. The Above side usually oversees the Conflict from above, they might be the local government, law enforcement, or a divinity.','Info'=>'Aspects',  'Info_Description'=>'Information about an exploitable weakness or a warning about a strength.', 'Vector'=>'Flashback', 'Vector_Description'=>'The information is revealed via a Flashback Scene. This might be played out, or just narrated, depending on how far back and how well planned the Ref is.', 'Alternate'=>'Sorrows', 'Alternate_Description'=>'The information is about sad things. Perhaps it details how the young orphan was passed from abusive home to abusive home, until finally he was taken in by a clan of thieves. Or perhaps it details how an Assassin\'s first contract was his childhood friend. Or how much they loved that dog they had to shoot when it got rabid.', 'Detail'=>'Woes', 'Detail_Description'=>'Some people don\'t just have problems, they have Woes. Huge Hitches in some cases, when they create Demons, who are like Mercari but with Twisted abilities, but for others, their woes just huge mistakes that the Embodiment wishes it could undo.'),//3 - key
 array( 'About'=>'Internal','About_Description'=>'The information revealed is about the Internal Conflict Embodiment. The Internal side of a Conflict may be within all sides or just one. It might be traitors, moles, spies, spirits or just a Character\'s internal conflict.','Info'=>'Conclusions', 'Info_Description'=>'The available information points to a number of potential conclusions. Usually only one of them is true.', 'Vector'=>'Vision', 'Vector_Description'=>'A Hallucination that reveals information is common enough that it gets a mention. Of course, what we don\'t hear about are all the times hallucinations aren\t useful. ', 'Alternate'=>'Safety', 'Alternate_Description'=>'The information is about a place, or time where either Embodiment will feel, or be safe. If you need a safe space, this tells you where to find one, if you have a safe space, it tells you where your Opposed Embodiment feels safe.', 'Detail'=>'Legal', 'Detail_Description'=>'A Legal detail can be a point of law, a loophole, or miscarriage of justice that can be exploited somehow. You may not have the villain\'s address, but thanks to this restraining order you know who his lawyers are...'),//4 - tower
 array('About'=>'Below','About_Description'=>'The information revealed is about the Below Conflict Embodiment. The Below side is lowly, considered beneath the normal scope of the conflict. This might include the Peasants, Plebs, or normal people, depending on the level of the conflict.','Info'=>'Which?',  'Info_Description'=>'Information that reveals which Conclusion or option is correct. Like which way the next piece of the puzzle is, or which wire should be cut.', 'Vector'=>'Deduction', 'Vector_Description'=>'Facts appear that support the evidence, but it isn\'t directly stated. ', 'Alternate'=>'Failures', 'Alternate_Description'=>'The information is all about past failures. How did the first five test subjects die? Where are the original fixtures? How many people were in that building he designed, you know, the one that fell in the river?', 'Detail'=>'Unreliable', 'Detail_Description'=>'Unreliable details, sometimes the details don\'t point you in the right direction. They just might not be true, no matter how much you want to believe that the Vampires and Unicorns are working together on some Undead F&aelig;ry Cavalry, they are natural enemies.'),//5 - sail
 array('About'=>'External','About_Description'=>'The information revealed is about the External Conflict Embodiment. This is a side that is considered outside of the normal Conflict, this could be aliens, or more likely, the next town over.','Info'=>'When?',  'Info_Description'=>'Information about an event that is happening, will happen, or already did, take place.', 'Vector'=>'Reasoning', 'Vector_Description'=>'The Character will be given evidence that points towards the information, but they will have to put the pieces together themselves (and probably get it wrong at least once).',  'Alternate'=>'Ways', 'Alternate_Description'=>'The information is about ways, ways things can be done, ways things can go, and ways into. and out of, town without being noticed by the guard.', 'Detail'=>'Axiom', 'Detail_Description'=>'The detail is a truism, or at least an aphorism, or saying, that strongly applies to the situation.'),//6 - clock
 array('About'=>'Shadows','About_Description'=>'The information revealed is about the Shadows Conflict Embodiment. All Conflicts have hidden actors and influences. This Revelation should not actually reveal the Shadows (that would make them not Shadows after all), only highlight their actions, and movements, revealing the existence of these hidden actors.','Info'=>'With What?',  'Info_Description'=>'Information about a Descendant, that may help or be hindering.', 'Vector'=>'Residue', 'Vector_Description'=>'Maybe there\'s gunpowder burns on their fingers, or perhaps a smear of a specific engine grease on their glove, maybe some left over "product" has turned up on the streets. Some residue points to the information others need.', 'Alternate'=>'Danger', 'Alternate_Description'=>'The information is about a danger, this may be that a character is dangerous, a dangerous spell, weapon or just some kind of situational hazard that you should be aware of.', 'Detail'=>'Dangerous', 'Detail_Description'=>'The detail is about some danger or hazard to do with the Embodiment. Perhaps the Death-Ray pistol everyone is hunting for is actually not completed and if shaken when fired can short-circuit, or perhaps the fact that the warlord just purchased a number of Kallidian Moat Vipers should make the party rethink the "We can just swim that" plan.'),//7 -sword Fascinating details draw someone\'s attention to themselves. They may even cause you to overlook more boring details. "He\'s known for roasting and eating his enemies and famously he has a glass eye that is made from a single giant emerald."
 array('About'=>'Deeper Shadows','About_Description'=>'The information revealed is about the Deeper Shadows Conflict Embodiment. Even more hidden than the Shadow side are the Deeper Shadows. Even their actions are hidden, this Revelation should reveal only that their is a potential for some deeply hidden group to be influencing the Conflict in some way.','Info'=>'What?',  'Info_Description'=>'Information about the Opposition\'s Ends, what are their goals, or plans.', 'Vector'=>'Traces', 'Vector_Description'=>'Maybe there are trace materials or chemicals found by forensic scientists, or maybe the police traced the call, or maybe you saw through a piece of paper.', 'Alternate'=>'Weaponry', 'Alternate_Description'=>'The information is about the weaponry, offensive capability, or defensibility of the Embodiment.', 'Detail'=>'Mixed', 'Detail_Description'=>'Mixed details are the worst. Important facts mixed in with useless lies, and properly hard to tell the one from the other, until it is proven, one way or another.'),//8 - rival
 array( 'About'=>'Dominant','About_Description'=>'The information revealed is about the Dominant Conflict Embodiment. Sometimes they are Characters, but almost as often they are Locations, Quests, Ordeals, or similar. Where this is true the Revelation should reveal details about future Quests the Pressed Characters must complete, or places they should visit. The Revelation can be little more than a call-back or foreshadowing if handled correct.','Info'=>'By What Means?','Info_Description'=>'Information about how far someone may go to achieve their Ends.', 'Vector'=>'Argument', 'Vector_Description'=>'Perhaps you overhear an argument that just happens to contain info you need, or maybe while you are having an argument something comes to light.',  'Alternate'=>'Wants', 'Alternate_Description'=>'What does the Embodiment want? You may not know how, or why, they are going to steal the Sceptre of Brass, but you do know they are after it.', 'Detail'=>'Doubtful', 'Detail_Description'=>'These details are probably mostly lies. Unlikely to be true, they hint at something that, at the very least, you hope cannot be.' ),//9 - robot
 array('About'=>'Pressed','About_Description'=>'The information is about the Pressed Conflict Embodiment, which is often a PC in a game, and is usually the antagonist in a Story.', 'Info'=>'Where?', 'Info_Description'=>'Information about a Location.', 'Vector'=>'Exchange', 'Vector_Description'=>'Maybe you overhear an exchanging of words, or maybe you are part of the exchange, trading information you know, for information back.',  'Alternate'=>'Ruins', 'Alternate_Description'=>'The information may be about a location, fallen into disrepair, or some hint of the Hitches of the Embodiment.', 'Detail'=>'Coherent', 'Detail_Description'=>'Coherent details all point to the same conclusion. All the details line up pointed at what must appear a forgone conclusion. Of course, just because it all lines up doesn\'t mean it can\'t be wrong or misinterpreted.'),//10 - lion
 array('About'=>'Opposed Embodiment / A Rival', 'About_Description'=>'The Information is specifically about the Opposed Embodiment, or a particular Rival of the Yarn-Teller.','Info'=>'Who?',  'Info_Description'=>'Information about a Character, usually an Embodiment. It might be their name, or genealogy, perhaps their CV.', 'Vector'=>'Communications', 'Vector_Description'=>'The information comes via a communications technology, perhaps the radio, or a cell phone call, or in another age a messenger or pigeon.', 'Alternate'=>'Changes', 'Alternate_Description'=>'The information is about changes that have occurred to or because of the Embodiment. It can also signify that the information itself changes. Appearing as one thing to begin with, but then being later revealed by a detail to be something else (or could magically change).', 'Detail'=>'Delicate', 'Detail_Description'=>'Delicate details are the finer points, little bits of information that might be overlooked easily, and could even be destroyed accidentally before they can be properly examined. A delicate detail might indicate a quirk, vulnerability, or flaw in some cases, but will be hard to spot. "He was a rakish, whip of a man, dressed in black leather, mail and silks. His eyes were dark and tired, close set, above a thin nose, broad cheekbones and confident grin..." '),//J - explorer
 array( 'About'=>'The Bad Guy','About_Description'=>'The information revealed is about the "Bad Guy", generally this is a Monster Character (often of the Dominant side, although Pressed Bad Guys are common to Tragic Storylines).', 'Info'=>'Why?','Info_Description'=>'Information that answers a Why question, like why are they doing it, or why is it/they that way?', 'Vector'=>'Letters', 'Vector_Description'=>'The information is written, usually as a letter or email. It may be a correspondence to the Character, or be something they found or intercepted.', 'Alternate'=>'Perceptions', 'Alternate_Description'=>'Perceptions represent the information that the Embodiment has about the Player/PCs. "I knew, that you knew. I also know what you planned to do about it."', 'Detail'=>'Quick', 'Detail_Description'=>'Quick details are of the blink and you\'ll miss it variety. They can be missed at first, and sometimes that will mean they are missed forever. Perhaps there was a flash of the face behind the mask, just after the smoke bomb went off. If the Player is lucky there may be video footage, a scrying attempt, or Femite recordings that can be viewed later, in slow motion.'),//Q - scope
 array('About'=>'The Big Bad','About_Description'=>'The information revealed is about the most powerful foe the Yarn-Teller might encounter. The Big Bad may not even be a part of the current Conflict, but represent a higher tier of Plot (perhaps even the Dominant side of the Cycle Conflict)','Info'=>'How?',  'Info_Description'=>'How exactly is what they plan to do, going to be done? You may get the full plan or just the important pieces. You might get How to stop it, but not what they do. It all depends on the situation at hand.', 'Vector'=>'Subtlety', 'Vector_Description'=>'Some sweet, subtle details, or a very tricky to decipher clue, conveys the information. It may be the things that were left unsaid in a conversation, a tone of voice or an expression used, but something gives away the information.', 'Alternate'=>'Designs', 'Alternate_Description'=>'Designs are sometimes detailed plans, other times they are broad sketches, depending how early in the process the designs were made. Designs can also be what the Embodiment is trying to achieve, without even a sketch of a plan.', 'Detail'=>'Salient', 'Detail_Description'=>'Salient details are just the most important things that anyone might need to know. "So... We are <em>all</em> going to die."'),//K -butcher
 //Jokers
 array( 'About'=>'Hidden Influences','About_Description'=>'There are Hidden influences in any universe. Sometimes they are the Increated working behind the scenes, other times they are the manipulative Faeries, ensuring the Doom of Wyrd, still other groups include time-travellers and inter-dimensional visitors who have all their own agendas. This Revelation reveals something about one of these groups.','Info'=>'Ref Special', 'Info_Description'=>'The Yarn cards can\'t decide everything that is happening, this one is all down to the Ref to decide.', 'Vector'=>'Mystical', 'Vector_Description'=>'The information arrives in a mystical or via magickal means. This might be the result of scrying or a message spell.', 'Alternate'=>'Quest', 'Alternate_Description'=>'The Revelation is actually a Quest that must be followed to find out the important information.', 'Detail'=>'Wild', 'Detail_Description'=>'Wild details might be details about how wild the situation or a Character is or may just be wild card details, randomly providing truths and lies across the board.'),//RJ - world
 array('About'=>'Magical / Divine Influences','About_Description'=>'Gods and magicians walk amongst us, at least in the Omniverse they do. The gods have great power, but are often limited in how they can apply it, magicians are not so restricted, but don\'t have as much power. Anyway this card allows you to reveal something about how these mages and gods are reacting to events in the Story.' ,'Info'=>'Player Decides',  'Info_Description'=>'So there\'s something the Players would really want to know (like who is out to kill them, and why, and what they need to do about it, but then the Player\'s choose which one to know.', 'Vector'=>'Direct', 'Vector_Description'=>'Direct Revelations are where the Villain monologues his plan to the captured hero, demonstrates his super-weapon to the United Nations, or shape-shifts in front of the Characters for the first time. Confessions, suicide notes, scientific papers, mission logs and journal and press conferences can all be Direct Revelations too. I\'m sure you can think of others.', 'Alternate'=>'Story', 'Alternate_Description'=>'The information contains the entire story, within the story (or play within the play), if anyone can see.', 'Detail'=>'Haphazard', 'Detail_Description'=>'A random collection of lies and truths that weirdly seem to tie into each other.')//BJ  - beyond
);
	private static $obstacles = array(
	array('Type'=>'Required',
	'Description'=>'The way is blocked by some required descendant, or business that must be completed before proceeding. It usually involves a payment of some sort being made.'),  //ace - ambition
	array('Type'=>'Wraith',
	'Description'=>'The way is blocked by a jump-scare, fright, terror or horror of some sort, usually as a 1-3 card Psych attack that affects all present in the Stage simultaneously, and then resets.'),  //2 - wraith
	array('Type'=>'Hard Work',
	'Description'=>'The way is blocked by debris or stacked items that must be moved out of the way by a proper application of elbow grease.'),  //3 - grindstone
	array('Type'=>'Specialist Knowledge',
	'Description'=>'The way ahead isn\'t blocked exactly, but getting past requires some specialist knowledge, maybe you need to know what that sign says, or how to turn off the electricity... Knowledge is usually a specific required Proficiency.'),  //4 - book
	array('Type'=>'Plants',
	'Description'=>'The way is blocked, by plants, such as roses, poison ivy, thorns, hawthorn hedges, stinging nettles, holly bushes, or some other "unpleasant" plant.'),  //5 - forest
	array('Type'=>'Bright',
	'Description'=>'The way is blocked, by bright lights that could ruin night and low-light vision. '),  //6 - sun
	array('Type'=>'Moving Traffic','Description'=>'The way is blocked, by fast paced, flowing traffic.'),  //7 - drive
	array('Type'=>'Pedestrians','Description'=>'The way is blocked, by a crowd of pedestrians, they may be troops, passers-by or pedestrians, depending on the Stakes.') , //8 - cultist
	array('Type'=>'Moral Compass','Description'=>'The Obstacle is an Ethical or Moral Dilemma, such as a good man having to do evil for the greater good.'),  //9 - priest
	array('Type'=>'Lone Guardian','Description'=>'This way is blocked, by a Solitary Guardian, perhaps a Samurai, or maybe a sewer dragon.'),  //10 - loner
	array('Type'=>'Lesson','Description'=>'The way is blocked by a method that in order to pass it a lesson must first be demonstrated to have been learned. This is usually a simple lesson, like sometimes we have to fail to find a better way.'),  //J - teacher
	array('Type'=>'Heat','Description'=>'The way is ahead is blocked by heat, there is probably smoke or flame too, or it may be scorching desert asphalt.'),  //Q - forge
	array('Type'=>'Dark','Description'=>'The way ahead is dark, and full of terrors.'),  //K - star
	//hearts
	array('Type'=>'Love Interest','Description'=>'The Obstacle is an attractive individual who catches at least one Character\'s eye. Positive Emotional affects may cause love at first sight, and the Stakes may raise to Soul, then again they may just be a temptation easily ignored.'),  //ace - lovers
	array('Type'=>'Burn-Out','Description'=>'The Obstacle is an area that has been weakened and damaged (usually by a fire), you will have to tread carefully to not bring something down.'),  //2 -burnout
	array('Type'=>'Question','Description'=>'The way ahead is blocked by a question, this may be a riddle, or conundrum, that halts finding the next Stage (common to mysteries, who is the killer?), or it may be a guardian that demands an answer.'),  //3 - question
	array('Type'=>'Myth','Description'=>'When a Myth blocks the way, you are either talking about some Superstition that must be overcome, some commonly believed factoid that must be discarded, or Guardians that are actually Mythic (Dragons, Knight of Round Table, etc)'),  //4 - myth
	array('Type'=>'Joke','Description'=>'Sometimes the way is blocked by some prank or facade, pranks are a type of psych snare, that can provide both positive and negative emotional effects, usually negative to the target but with positive effects on an audience. A bucket of water over a door, or a lubed banana-skin under a rug are examples. You may draw again and create a humorous version of that Obstacle.'),  //5 - joke
	array('Type'=>'Unicorn','Description'=>'The way is blocked either by a magical illusions, figment of the imagination, an aspect of a dream/nightmare, or a powerful F&aelig;ry-creature or minor Increated.'),  //6 - unicorn
	array('Type'=>'Animals','Description'=>'The way is blocked by a large group of animals (or drunken adults) who may pass naturally but may be aggressive if threatened.'),  //7 - stag
	array('Type'=>'Ward','Description'=>'The Obstacle is a magical ward, or curse, that either magically or psychologically blocks the way. Magical Wards can be very specific what they block and what they allow through, which can allow Yarn-Tellers to split parties and teach lessons.'),  //8 - wizard
	array('Type'=>'Wheel of Fortune','Description'=>'The way is blocked by some random effect or portal, passing through the Obstacle will result in a random effect. Yarn-Tellers should prepare their own table for each one, similar to this "example". e.g. <div class="t13ne-tablewrap"><table class="t13ne-table"><thead><tr><td>Dice (d6)</td><td>Suggested Results</td><td>Secondary Effect</td></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>1</td><td>Wounded</td><td>Add 1d6 to Pips/Boon</td></tr><tr><td>2</td><td>Changed Appearance (hair colour, style, skin tone, eye colour)</td><td>Subtract 1d6 from Pips/Boon</td></tr><tr><td>3</td><td>Changed Body (gender, species, Incarna, Hitch)</td><td>Swap for another Facet/Proficiency</td></tr><tr><td>4</td><td>Changed Character (Annex, Persona, Core, I-Ching, Facets, Alternates)</td><td>Alter name / Hitch name / Annex Title / Descendant Name</td></tr><tr><td>5</td><td>Changed Time-line (past, present, future, side-step, retcon) </td><td>Swap Umbrals for Nimbeds and Vice Versa</td></tr><tr><td>6</td><td>Prize (Chi Gain or Skill Annex Descendant)</td><td>Roll Twice apply both</td></tr></tbody></table></div>'),  //9 lady
	array('Type'=>'Ridicule','Description'=>'The way is blocked unless the Character subjects themselves to some ridicule or mockery. This is usually a psych attack and may have a Character who performs the ridicule. Or you may draw again and create a humorous, but more dangerous (dark-humour) version of that Obstacle.'),  //10 - jester
	array('Type'=>'Lie','Description'=>'The Obstacle requires you to Lie for all you&#39;re worth and pretend to be something you are not. It might be that the way ahead is only allowed for someone of a particular rank, gender, religion or race, and you have to bluff your way past Guardians.'),  //J - mask
	array('Type'=>'Hidden','Description'=>'The way ahead is hidden or secret. Secret doors, hidden trapdoors, wall safes and the like, must be searched or spotted to find.'),  //Q - cloak
	array('Type'=>'Medical','Description'=>'The way is blocked by something medical, it may be a scan or fitness test, or a contagious disease, or anaesthetic gas may block the way.'),  //K - physician
	//clubs
	array('Type'=>'Legal','Description'=>'The way ahead is blocked by some legal obstacle (such as a one way street, crime scene tape, lack of warrant, etc). This must be "lawyered" and negotiated around, or there will be legal repercussions.'),  //ace - court
	array('Type'=>'Unstable','Description'=>'The ground ahead is unstable, it might be loose rocks, scree, rubble, or fallen logs, who knows. You\'ll have to be careful and have great balance, though. It looks like the kind of place that people say, "...and that\'s how I lost my leg" about.'),  //2 -Eelafin
	array('Type'=>'Hitch','Description'=>'The way ahead is blocked by some device that will trigger a Hitch for one Character (often the PCs Love Interest). If a Character is afraid of Spiders then the way is blocked with webs.'),  //3 - serpent
	array('Type'=>'Water','Description'=>'The way is blocked by water. It might be a flash flood, a swollen river, a flooded passage, or just a huge puddle, but you will have to get wet, or clever to move on. If the Ordeal is on water then the way is blocked by earth, ice, fog, or fire as the Yarn-Teller prefers.'),  //4 -waters
	array('Type'=>'Defences','Description'=>'The way ahead is blocked by some shield, walls, fences, gates, doors, guards, or perhaps automated laser turrets. Twice the normal Difficulty to pass or disable.'),  //5 - shield
	array('Type'=>'Horde','Description'=>'The way ahead may be blocked by a horde, army, rioting crowd, swarm of vermin, or similar danger. The Horde is a powerful Pact of Chorus or Vex Extras, the Pact should be large enough to mimic at least a Minor Guardian.'),  //6 - horde
	array('Type'=>'Window','Description'=>'The way ahead is blocked by a window, it may be broken, which will turn it from an Obstacle to a Trap, the trap must then be disarmed. It is possible to break the window and pass the trap simultaneously with a Stunt or Trick.'),  //7 - crystal
	array('Type'=>'Work','Description'=>'The Obstacle requires work to be done to pass it. This might be pulling a rope, turning a wheel, drawing water, shovelling coal, splitting wood, that primes a mechanism, lowers a bridge, or opens a way.'),  //9 - scythe
	array('Type'=>'Orders','Description'=>'The way ahead is blocked by official orders, such as "No High Speed Pursuits In The Financial District". Failure to comply (and not avoid the Obstacle) will result in repercussions.'),  //9 - crown
	array('Type'=>'Guardian','Description'=>'The way ahead is defended by a powerful Major Guardian, it might be your date\'s Father, a Dragon, or Asterion, the Minotaur who guards the centre of C&aelig;ster. They are often more powerful than the whole party of PCs and must be persuaded, beguiled, impressed, misled, bribed, fought, knocked out, killed, or vaporised, before they will let any of you past.'),  //10 - guardian
	array('Type'=>'Weather','Description'=>'It seems the Weather is not on your side and is hampering your progress, winds are against you, rain, hail, snow, even the sun, whatever really. The Weather is a (Vex / Chorus / Cast) Extra, depending on the Ref\'s mood and the Narrative (if you have been told about the storm rolling in for hours don\'t expect the a Vex).'),  //J - tempest
	array('Type'=>'Temptation','Description'=>'The Obstacle is a temptation, traditionally this is represented by a Pleasure Dome filled with loads of semi-naked, sexually-alluring people, but temptations vary, drink (a bar), gambling (casino), drugs (opium den / crack-house), money or valuables lying around, or even a video game may also qualify.'),  //Q - inn
	array('Type'=>'Doom','Description'=>'The way is blocked by the forces of history somehow. Perhaps some F&aelig;ry Noble has been tasked to keep that route free as part of Wyrd\'s Tapestry for an hour, enter it, and the full forces of a powerful Yarn-Teller will be raised against you. It may not always be instant death... Although I\'m not sure if that\'s meant to be reassuring, or terrifying.'),  //K - fae noble
	//spades
	array('Type'=>'Portal','Description'=>'The way is blocked by what may be just a closed, locked, barred, or trapped door, airlock, gateway or it could be a portal to another realm. Portals have a tendency to be a bit final, especially when you open them when you don\'t know where they go.'),  //ace - threshold
	array('Type'=>'Repulsive','Description'=>'The way ahead is repulsive, icky or disgusting. A Swamp, sewer, river of blood, pile of manure, shower of vomit. Strong nerves, stronger stomachs and the strongest immune systems will be required.'),  //2 -swamp
	array('Type'=>'Lock','Description'=>'The way ahead is blocked by a Lock, you will require a key, pass-code, or lock-picking skills to unlock the way.'),  //3 - key
	array('Type'=>'Tower','Description'=>'The way is blocked by a building, wall or tower. There may be guards, locked doors, or similar, but you have to go through, around, or over this obstacle.'),  //4 - tower
	array('Type'=>'Clouds','Description'=>'The way ahead is blocked by fog, clouds, smoke or gas. A favourite of villains, who may choose deadly, knock-out, or hallucinogenic chemicals for Traps.'),  //5 - sail
	array('Type'=>'Mechanism','Description'=>'The way is blocked by some mechanism (such as a raising or rotating bridge, crane or vehicle), often used to create complex mechanical traps, that usually have some timer and reset mechanism, such as crushing walls, swinging blades, spinning chains. Such mechanisms usually have some hidden reset or control panel.'),  //6 - clock
	array('Type'=>'Death-Trap','Description'=>'A Death-Trap is a deadly obstacle that is not intended to be survived. Land-Mines, poison coated spikes, decapitating blades, quantum annihilation fields, black mist filled mirrors, and unshielded black-holes within arms length, are all example Death-Traps.'),  //7 - sword
	array('Type'=>'Rival','Description'=>'The way is blocked by one of the Character\'s Rivals, this will usually block the path of only the Characters with Rivalries with that Rival, depending upon the Rival.'),  //8 - rival
	array('Type'=>'Robotic','Description'=>'Robotic traps come in all shapes and sizes, from automatic spike traps, to actual robots. The robotic trap usually targets a moving individual and wounds them. Then it selects a new moving target (or the same target randomly if they\'re still moving) and wounds them. The trap may be limited in duration, or range, as well as Limit.'),//9 - robot
	array('Type'=>'Lion','Description'=>'The Obstacle may be a Beast Guardian (such as a dog or actual lion), but is more normally a test of either the physical body (strength) or humility and true sense of worth (pride). Something may have to be lifted, or something given up to proceed.'),  //10 - lion
	array('Type'=>'Maze','Description'=>'The way is blocked, but by a maze or labyrinth that represents a complex, difficult to memorise or work out route. A Maze can be handled as an Ordeal within an Ordeal (with finer detail on the Stages, corridors instead of roads, or cubicles instead of rooms), or simply as a Navigation test, fail and you are lost in the maze... Fail again and you may be lost more than that.'),  //J - explorer
	array('Type'=>'Watched','Description'=>'The way ahead is watched, usually by motion sensitive alarms, security cameras, guards or perhaps scrying. Any unhidden motion into the area (and some hidden probably) will cause alarms to be raised and security to completely block this route.'), //Q -scope
	array('Type'=>'Bloody','Description'=>'The way is blocked by a deadly trap and the remains of its last victim. The Trap must be Extreme Stakes and be primed with at least one Mortal or Carnage Wound. The remains will make a one, two or three card psych attack automatically depending upon how long ago the trap last fired.'), //K- butcher
	array('Type'=>'Destructive','Description'=>'A Destructive Trap is a one shot trap, it might demolish the building, drop all the floors, flood the valley the building is in, destabilize the volcano, or unleash giant rolling balls to chase intruders out and block the exits. Once triggered there is no stopping or undoing the devastation and carnage that will follow. Luckily such traps usually have a number of Phases that they take to complete, and you usually get at least one Phase of hearing the thing fire up as a warning.'), // world
	array('Type'=>'Incursion','Description'=>'The way is blocked by some direct expression of the Beyond, it could be a Hellmouth, a portal into U-space, a gate to Shades, or a tear in space-time, or simply a dark spot full of Neechies (the least of the Increated), looking for inspiration and nightmare fuel to become perhaps even a new Patron.') // beyond
);
	public static $ordeals = array(
	//Diams
	array('Ordeal_Type'=>'Solitary Ordeal', 'Stages'=>'6','Ordeal_Spread'=>'Map-Geography', 'Stakes'=>'Blended Low-Medium-High-Extreme', 'Test'=>'Collect (Burden)', 'Obstacles'=>'3 Obstacles in every Stage', 'Suggested_Action'=>'Acquire / Negotiate', 'Stage'=>'Speed Stunt', 'Stage_Description'=>'Something needs to be done at speed, maybe its a skid, shooting rapids, speed typing, rapid mental arithmetic, dashing through a closing gate, or speed reading.', 'Motional'=>'Dangerous Vehicular Dash', 'Motional_Description'=>'The Ordeal is meant to be done with haste and speed. Get somewhere or do something as quickly as possible, through a dangerous area or dangerous situations.', 'Tide_of_Battle'=>'Flanking','Tide_of_Battle_Text'=>'The Flowing side moves to the Flanks of the Ebbing enemy, able to attack ignoring active defences.', 'Fight'=>'Ambush', 'Fight_Description'=>'Ambushed by a group of weaker foes (often Chorus or Vex Extras), with numbers greater then those they attack, usually equivalent weapons and armour to the PCs, they may attempt to retreat after the third Phase.'), //A -ambition
	array('Ordeal_Type'=>'Solitary Ordeal', 'Stages'=>'1','Ordeal_Spread'=>'Railroad', 'Stakes'=>'Low', 'Test'=>'Scare (Awe)', 'Obstacles'=>'Usually none', 'Suggested_Action'=>'Intimidate / Cower', 'Stage'=>'Short Straight', 'Stage_Description'=>'A short, straight path, street or road, simple preparation or research', 'Motional'=>'Ground Vehicle Dash', 'Motional_Description'=>'The Ordeal is meant to be done quickly, along the ground in, or on, a vehicle.', 'Tide_of_Battle'=>'Push','Tide_of_Battle_Text'=>'The Ebbing foe falls back (+1 Pips to movement or Disengament actions), and the Flowing forces push forward into the breach (+1 Pips for movement and defence).', 'Fight'=>'Vex Fright', 'Fight_Description'=>'An aggressive, solitary Vex attacks, usually with a Duck Psych Attack, or a Toxic sting, then it will retreat after the first Phase, if it survives.'), //2 -wraith
	array('Ordeal_Type'=>'Solitary Ordeal', 'Stages'=>'1','Ordeal_Spread'=>'Railroad', 'Stakes'=>'Medium', 'Test'=>'Endurance (Inertia)', 'Obstacles'=>'Usually none', 'Suggested_Action'=>'Prepare / Repair', 'Stage'=>'Sharp corner', 'Stage_Description'=>'A sharp corner, change of direction, preparation or research', 'Motional'=>'Aerial Vehicle Dash', 'Motional_Description'=>'The Ordeal is meant to involve travel quickly in an aerial vehicle, such as a plane, or somewhere high, perhaps swinging from cranes.', 'Tide_of_Battle'=>'Cornered','Tide_of_Battle_Text'=>'The Ebbing enemy is backed into a corner, they cannot escape, but may prepare siege defences and counter-attacks. The Flowing force should demand surrender.', 'Fight'=>'Stand-off', 'Fight_Description'=>'Two or more forces that are evenly matched in size and power can form a Stand-off.'), //3 -grindstone
	array('Ordeal_Type'=>'Solitary Ordeal', 'Stages'=>'1','Ordeal_Spread'=>'Railroad', 'Stakes'=>'High', 'Test'=>'Authority (Dominion)', 'Obstacles'=>'Usually none', 'Suggested_Action'=>'Read / Research', 'Stage'=>'Small rise', 'Stage_Description'=>'A short, but slight rise, a slope, step or few steps.', 'Motional'=>'Ground Riding Dash', 'Motional_Description'=>'Working alone, but riding a beast or a vehicle, quickly. Try to get as far as possible.', 'Tide_of_Battle'=>'Higher Ground','Tide_of_Battle_Text'=>'The Flowing forces have the higher ground and a slight situational advantage. They  add +1 Pip to each card they play to Defend during the Stage. The Ebbing forces have the lower ground, which confers them no advantage, or real disadvantage of note.', 'Fight'=>'Assault', 'Fight_Description'=>'Entrenched or armoured opponents that are greater in number, but lower in quality (start with Extras) or have lesser equipment than the attacking force.'), //4 -book
	array('Ordeal_Type'=>'Solitary Ordeal', 'Stages'=>'2','Ordeal_Spread'=>'Railroad', 'Stakes'=>'Low', 'Test'=>'Survival (Nature)', 'Obstacles'=>'1 Obstacle in 1 Court Stage', 'Suggested_Action'=>'Walk / Observe', 'Stage'=>'Medium Straight', 'Stage_Description'=>'A medium length, straight path, street or road. Complex preparations or research. Working normally.', 'Motional'=>'Water Vehicle Dash', 'Motional_Description'=>'Pass through as many watery Ordeal stages as possible in your boat, before the time (Rounds or Phases) limit expires.', 'Tide_of_Battle'=>'The Slog','Tide_of_Battle_Text'=>'The battle has become a chaotic crush of blows in close melee. The Tide of Battle has become a churning swirl. Both sides have lost all momentum and fine control. No side has any advantages.', 'Fight'=>'Minor Guardian', 'Fight_Description'=>'A single opponent, at least as powerful as a PC (Extras match Highest Annex Boon), that has some interesting abilities (I-Ching, Core) and Annexes, or powerful Descendants.'), //5 - forest
	array('Ordeal_Type'=>'Solitary Ordeal', 'Stages'=>'2','Ordeal_Spread'=>'Forking', 'Stakes'=>'Medium', 'Test'=>'Burning (Phoenix)', 'Obstacles'=>'1 Obstacle in 1 Court Stage', 'Suggested_Action'=>'Wait / Smile', 'Stage'=>'Curve', 'Stage_Description'=>'A medium length, curved path, street or road, a slightly odd situation or place.', 'Motional'=>'Aerial Riding Dash', 'Motional_Description'=>'Reach and complete the goal Stage as quickly as possible, usually riding a jet-bike, eagle or something similar.', 'Tide_of_Battle'=>'The Gap','Tide_of_Battle_Text'=>'The Flowing and Ebbing foes are drawn apart by the battle. Causing a lull or pause between assaults for both sides. Either side can use this moment to heal, or stabilize a Wound, or to take stock of the battle, and decide where to lend your strength (Prepare an Action in your Preferred Style).', 'Fight'=>'Major Guardian', 'Fight_Description'=>'A group of PC level opponents, or a single Monster with at least one Monster Facet and a Boon equal to the Value equal to at least three quarters of the total Value of all PCs Personality Annexes [t13ne type="facetsuitaspect" suit=1 aspect="Monster"/]' ), //6 - sun
	array('Ordeal_Type'=>'Solitary Ordeal', 'Stages'=>'2','Ordeal_Spread'=>'Pyramid', 'Stakes'=>'High', 'Test'=>'Control (Dominion) or Repair (Craft)', 'Obstacles'=>'1 Obstacle in 1 Court Stage', 'Suggested_Action'=>'Drive / Encourage', 'Stage'=>'Descent', 'Stage_Description'=>'A sloping route, or stairs down. A low spot or day.', 'Motional'=>'Water Riding Dash', 'Motional_Description'=>'Act quickly, and get through the watery Stages to the goal as fast as you, on your surfboard / giant-seahorse can.', 'Tide_of_Battle'=>'Pressed','Tide_of_Battle_Text'=>'The Flowing Characters side press on the Ebbing Characters, trying to force them back by strength and weight of numbers. Ebbing Side Attack with -1 Pips on each card.', 'Fight'=>'Greater Guardian', 'Fight_Description'=>'A single Monster as powerful as the whole Party, or a Group with each member at least as powerful as the most powerful PC.[t13ne type="facetsuitaspect" suit=1 aspect="Monster"/]'), //7 -drive
	array('Ordeal_Type'=>'Solitary Ordeal', 'Stages'=>'3','Ordeal_Spread'=>'Railroad', 'Stakes'=>'Low', 'Test'=>'Esoteric Knowledge (Heresy)', 'Obstacles'=>'1 non-Court Stage Obstacle + Obstacles in all Court Stages', 'Suggested_Action'=>'Persuade / Sing', 'Stage'=>'Uphill Slog', 'Stage_Description'=>'A long, straight, but steeply climbing way, or long hours of work, preparation or research.', 'Motional'=>'Ground Riding Dash', 'Motional_Description'=>'Whatever you are doing on that bike, or horse, you have to do it quickly.','Tide_of_Battle'=>'Battle Styling','Tide_of_Battle_Text'=>'One Flowing Style Reserve has dominance over all Ebbing Styles. That Flowing Style Reserve may randomly draw and add an additional card whenever an Action is Prepared to it.', 'Fight'=>'Gang Battle', 'Fight_Description'=>'Lesser opponents (Chorus Extras) that outnumber the PCs by at least 3 to 1.'), //8 - cultist
	array('Ordeal_Type'=>'Solitary Ordeal', 'Stages'=>'3','Ordeal_Spread'=>'Forking', 'Stakes'=>'Medium', 'Test'=>'Inspire (Awe)', 'Obstacles'=>'2 non-Court Stage Obstacles + 2 Obstacles in all Court Stages', 'Suggested_Action'=>'Dodge / Curse', 'Stage'=>'Long Straight', 'Stage_Description'=>'A long, straight path, street, road, or boulevard. Working hard, or long hours of preparation or research.', 'Motional'=>'Dangerous Riding Dash', 'Motional_Description'=>'Get to the end of the Ordeal in as few Phases as possible. Across dangerous territory on a horse or bike that can help.', 'Tide_of_Battle'=>'Trading Shots','Tide_of_Battle_Text'=>'The Flowing and Ebbing sides exchange shots at range, either while closing in, or while keeping cover. Neither side has clear advantage.', 'Fight'=>'Rival Battle', 'Fight_Description'=>'A fight between perfectly matched opponents, may use Rivals, Dark, Mirrors, Corrupted Clones, Animus etc. You can create Dark Parties for example or mix and match.'), //9 - priest
	array('Ordeal_Type'=>'Solitary Ordeal', 'Stages'=>'3','Ordeal_Spread'=>'Pyramid', 'Stakes'=>'High', 'Test'=>'Hide (Enigma)', 'Obstacles'=>'1 Obstacle in each Stage with 2 in all Court Stages.', 'Suggested_Action'=>'Run / Agree', 'Stage'=>'Fields', 'Stage_Description'=>'A very long, wide-open fields, spaces, straight paths, roads, or highways. Very long, hard, days of labour, research or travel.', 'Motional'=>'Ground Foot Dash', 'Motional_Description'=>'Get through the Stages before the time limit (limited in Rounds), on foot, or face serious consequences.', 'Tide_of_Battle'=>'Lesson learned','Tide_of_Battle_Text'=>'The Flowing forces have learned the tactics of the Ebbing enemy. This advantage can allow the Flowing forces to discard half of all prepared Style Reserve cards from one Ebbing Style Reserve.', 'Fight'=>'Pitched Battle', 'Fight_Description'=>'Attacked by a Group at least as powerful as the PCs, but greater in number (usually by one or two).'), //10 -loner
	array('Ordeal_Type'=>'Solitary Ordeal', 'Stages'=>'4','Ordeal_Spread'=>'Forking', 'Stakes'=>'Blended Low-Medium', 'Test'=>'Preparation (Craft)', 'Obstacles'=>'1 Obstacle in each Stage with 2 in all Court Stages', 'Suggested_Action'=>'Educate / Lecture', 'Stage'=>'Jump Stunt', 'Stage_Description'=>'Leap forwards, across, or skip ahead a Stage or Obstacle if successful.', 'Motional'=>'Water Swimming Dash', 'Motional_Description'=>'Get to through the water as fast as you can, skipping anything you can skip. Swim or wade as required.', 'Tide_of_Battle'=>'Final Push','Tide_of_Battle_Text'=>'The Flowing side seem close to winning, so they raise the Stakes with a bold assault (Stakes raised to Extreme or Soul-Stakes).', 'Fight'=>'Knave', 'Fight_Description'=>'A single Monster (usually with at least Two &diams; Monster Facets), that is equivalent Boon Value to any 2 PCs Personality Annex Values added`.[t13ne type="facetsuitaspect" suit=1 aspect="Monster"/]'), //J -teacher
	array('Ordeal_Type'=>'Solitary Ordeal', 'Stages'=>'4','Ordeal_Spread'=>'Pyramid', 'Stakes'=>'Blended Medium-High', 'Test'=>'Destroy (Miasma)', 'Obstacles'=>'2 Obstacles in every Stage and 3 in all Court Stages', 'Suggested_Action'=>'Construct / Lie', 'Stage'=>'Quick Stunt', 'Stage_Description'=>'A game of chicken, remember the facts, listen, pray, or race / sprint / speed', 'Motional'=>'Aerial Winged Dash', 'Motional_Description'=>'Get through the Stages as fast as possible, if the Character has natural flight this is just a flight, otherwise they may swing from a rope / spider-web / lianna, or have to balance, climb and jump from roof-top to rooftop.', 'Tide_of_Battle'=>'Charge!','Tide_of_Battle_Text'=>'The Flowing forces rush the Ebbing enemy, closing to melee distance as quickly as possible.', 'Fight'=>'Femme Fatale', 'Fight_Description'=>'A Femme (or Homme) Fatale is a seductive enemy, that will manipulate and single out weaker members, to eliminate them. Usually equivalent of PC in power, although often a Monster of some type.[t13ne type="facetsuitaspect" suit=1 aspect="Monster" /]'), //Q -forge
	array('Ordeal_Type'=>'Solitary Ordeal', 'Stages'=>'5','Ordeal_Spread'=>'Map-Grid', 'Stakes'=>'Blended Low-Medium-High', 'Test'=>'Impress (Awe)', 'Obstacles'=>'2 Obstacles in every Stage and 3 in Court Stages', 'Suggested_Action'=>'Distract / Flatter', 'Stage'=>'Crossing', 'Stage_Description'=>'A Creative Dilemma, intersection or busy, dangerous crossing.', 'Motional'=>'Dangerous Gauntlet Dash', 'Motional_Description'=>'Get to the end of the Ordeal as quickly as possible in one piece, on foot, while opponents defend each dangerous Stage.', 'Tide_of_Battle'=>'Turning Point','Tide_of_Battle_Text'=>'The Turning Point is a moment where the Ebbing enemy and Flowing forces are inverted somehow. Some change of situation, such as the arrival of reinforcements, or a terrible accident, causes the Flow and Ebb to reverse.', 'Fight'=>'Lieutenant', 'Fight_Description'=>'One of the Villain\'s Henchmen (equivalent to any 2 PCs) accompanied by a number of lesser opponents at least equal in number to the Party.'), //K -star
	//Hearts
	array('Ordeal_Type'=>'Opposed Ordeal', 'Stages'=>'7','Ordeal_Spread'=>'Map-Geography', 'Stakes'=>'Blended Low-Medium-High-Extreme', 'Test'=>'Instincts (Nature)', 'Obstacles'=>'1 per Stage and 3 per Court Stage', 'Suggested_Action'=>'Take a risk / Flirt', 'Stage'=>'Fire Stunt', 'Stage_Description'=>'A dangerous Stunt with flames and explosions, or a medical emergency.', 'Motional'=>'Dangerous Vehicular Race', 'Motional_Description'=>'This Opposed Ordeal involves trying to get through the Stages of dangerous terrain in a vehicle, before the Opposition.', 'Tide_of_Battle'=>'Fire-fight','Tide_of_Battle_Text'=>'Bullets are flying and things are exploding, its mayhem wherever you look. No one has any advantages, everyone is threatening or suppressing everyone else, but even attempting to close to melee is likely to involve getting shot.', 'Fight'=>'Bout', 'Fight_Description'=>'The fight is a training session, or bout, this is a Low Stakes Fight, intended to teach Proficiencies or similar.'), //A -lovers
	array('Ordeal_Type'=>'Opposed Ordeal', 'Stages'=>'1','Ordeal_Spread'=>'Railroad', 'Stakes'=>'Low', 'Test'=>'Abuse (Sin)', 'Obstacles'=>'None', 'Suggested_Action'=>'Recover / Wait', 'Stage'=>'Bustling', 'Stage_Description'=>'A busy road, or path, a social occasion or situation.', 'Motional'=>'Ground Vehicle Race', 'Motional_Description'=>'Get you and your car through the Stages of the Ordeal faster than your Opponents.', 'Tide_of_Battle'=>'Break','Tide_of_Battle_Text'=>'The Ebbing enemy breaks, some of their number flee (or attempt to regroup), the Flowing forces can pursue with a +1 Pip to each card played, or can take this time to regroup themselves.', 'Fight'=>'Competition', 'Fight_Description'=>'The Fight is a competitive bout of a contact sport, such as a boxing match, or fencing. Such Fights are usually Medium or Low Stakes against at least Cast Extras.'), //2 -burnout
	array('Ordeal_Type'=>'Opposed Ordeal', 'Stages'=>'2','Ordeal_Spread'=>'Railroad', 'Stakes'=>'Medium', 'Test'=>'Questioning (Enigma)', 'Obstacles'=>'None', 'Suggested_Action'=>'Accuse / Inquire', 'Stage'=>'Question', 'Stage_Description'=>'Either you need to formulate a question or an answer, usually while lots of other people ask theirs. This might be the first stage of the Scientific method, or you may be at a press conference. Otherwise you are looking at a cul-de-sac style turn, that might have a way out, if you are willing to think outside the box (or at least off the road).',  'Motional'=>'Flying Machine Race', 'Motional_Description'=>'Those magnificent men in their flying machines are trying to get through the Stages faster than you.', 'Tide_of_Battle'=>'Rock and Roll','Tide_of_Battle_Text'=>'The battle is loud and distracting, but there is a rhythm to it. Roll 1d3, during each Phase of the Stage, any Character of either Flowing or Ebbing side that makes an Action that does not play that many cards will automatically take an Unsoakable Distract Wound if Flowing and an Unsoakable Flesh Wound if Ebbing.', 'Fight'=>'Scrap', 'Fight_Description'=>'The Scrap is a usually Medium Stakes punch-up or street fight, between more than two people (at least Chorus Extras), who each are fighting individually in a chaotic, last-man-standing way. The Scrap can shift to High Stakes if someone pulls a weapon, or starts stamping on necks.'), //3 -question
	array('Ordeal_Type'=>'Opposed Ordeal', 'Stages'=>'2','Ordeal_Spread'=>'Forking', 'Stakes'=>'High', 'Test'=>'Knowledge (Orthodox)', 'Obstacles'=>'None', 'Suggested_Action'=>'Tell a story / Lie', 'Stage'=>'Crowds', 'Stage_Description'=>'A large crowd of people, an audience, a stadium or theatre. A convention or conference.', 'Motional'=>'Road Race', 'Motional_Description'=>'First to finish wins. Sometimes they race for pink slips.', 'Tide_of_Battle'=>'Out of Control','Tide_of_Battle_Text'=>'The battle is now out of anyone\'s control. Civilians may be caught in the crossfire, or some other unforeseen problem has occurred. No side has clear advantage.', 'Fight'=>'Hold-fast', 'Fight_Description'=>'The fight takes place in a single, usually, defensive location. The location is assaulted by a stream, or waves, of lesser or equal (Vex - Cast)opponents. Generally, the defending side is waiting for back-up, or relief to arrive.'), //4 - myth
	array('Ordeal_Type'=>'Opposed Ordeal', 'Stages'=>'3','Ordeal_Spread'=>'Forking', 'Stakes'=>'Medium', 'Test'=>'Timing (Inertia)', 'Obstacles'=>'None', 'Suggested_Action'=>'Enrage / Quip', 'Stage'=>'Bridge', 'Stage_Description'=>'A small gathering of influential, or professional people, or a route over something.', 'Motional'=>'Boat Race', 'Motional_Description'=>'First to get their boat through the final Stage, wins.', 'Tide_of_Battle'=>'Humiliation','Tide_of_Battle_Text'=>'The Flowing forces will be jeering and mocking the Ebbing enemy for what is happening, maybe they lost their sword, perhaps they just charged into a pit trap, or maybe perhaps their trousers just fell off while they were running. The Flowing side has a +1 Success Level to any social or Psyche attacks.', 'Fight'=>'Minor Monster', 'Fight_Description'=>'A solitary Monster, at least comparable to a PC, that has at least two &hearts; Monster Facets.[t13ne type="facetsuitaspect" suit=2 aspect="Monster" /]'), //5 - joke
	array('Ordeal_Type'=>'Opposed Ordeal', 'Stages'=>'3','Ordeal_Spread'=>'Pyramid', 'Stakes'=>'Low', 'Test'=>'Magic (Wyrd)', 'Obstacles'=>'None', 'Suggested_Action'=>'Cast / Perform', 'Stage'=>'Tunnel', 'Stage_Description'=>'An often narrow or confined route, usually straight, that passes under something, or extremely hard work.', 'Motional'=>'Aerial Riding Race', 'Motional_Description'=>'Whichever dragon and rider crosses the line first, wins.', 'Tide_of_Battle'=>'Safe Space','Tide_of_Battle_Text'=>'Surrounded by danger, the Flow and Ebbing sides have found a safe space in the battlefield, perhaps under a partially collapsed building, or behind a burned-out car. Flowing Characters can Stabilise one Wound for Free, take any Action, and take stock of the battle. Ebbing Characters may only take a Healing Action or Prepare a Healing or Defence Action.', 'Fight'=>'Monsters', 'Fight_Description'=>'A Group of Monsters (usually the same type) comparable to a PC that has at least 2 &hearts; Monster Facets.[t13ne type="facetsuitaspect" suit=2 aspect="Monster" /]'), //6 -unicorn
	array('Ordeal_Type'=>'Opposed Ordeal', 'Stages'=>'3','Ordeal_Spread'=>'Block', 'Stakes'=>'Medium', 'Test'=>'Combat (Trial)', 'Obstacles'=>'None', 'Suggested_Action'=>'Charge / Run', 'Stage'=>'Hubbub', 'Stage_Description'=>'A busy market, square or park, a social or professional engagement.', 'Motional'=>'Aquatic Riding Race', 'Motional_Description'=>'Get to the end of the Ordeal, on your jet-ski, battle-ray, or riding-shark  through all the Checkpoints, before everyone else.', 'Tide_of_Battle'=>'Unexpected','Tide_of_Battle_Text'=>'Something unexpected by both sides occurs, perhaps a third side joins, the train brakes, an earthquake happens, or a warp vortex opens between the combatants. This has the effect of cancelling any accumulated Flowing Success or Ebbing Failure Levels or emotional effects.', 'Fight'=>'Monstrous Horde', 'Fight_Description'=>'A Group of Monsters (Cast Extra), with at least 1 &hearts; Monster Facet and that outnumber the party at least 3 to 1.[t13ne type="facetsuitaspect" suit=2 aspect="Monster" /]'), //7 -stag
	array('Ordeal_Type'=>'Opposed Ordeal', 'Stages'=>'4','Ordeal_Spread'=>'Forking', 'Stakes'=>'High', 'Test'=>'Charms (Awe) / Create (Craft) / Magic (Wyrd)', 'Obstacles'=>'1 per Court Stage', 'Suggested_Action'=>'Tinker / Discuss', 'Stage'=>'Harmony', 'Stage_Description'=>'Music fills the space, perhaps there is Muzak playing in the mall, or an outdoor concert in the park, maybe its just the music blaring from some kids loud car stereo. There might be crowds of people, maybe dancing. Or this could just be about everyone moving along the same way.', 'Motional'=>'Horse Race', 'Motional_Description'=>'Everyone else should be behind you, or unhorsed, when you reach that last Stage.', 'Tide_of_Battle'=>'Battle Dancer','Tide_of_Battle_Text'=>'The Flowing side is synced with the rhythm of the battle. Roll 1d3 each Phase during the Stage, during any Action that plays this many cards a Flowing Character may automatically choose to Stabilise a Wound, make an Attack Immune to Active Defences, or Prepare one card from their Pool to their preferred Style Reserve. Ebbing Characters receive no bonus or penalty.', 'Fight'=>'Skirmish', 'Fight_Description'=>'A Skirmish is an unplanned encounter between two enemy forces. Skirmishes are often Medium or High Stakes (even during Warfare), and will become a fighting retreat after the first Round.'), //8 -wizard
	array('Ordeal_Type'=>'Opposed Ordeal', 'Stages'=>'4','Ordeal_Spread'=>'Pyramid', 'Stakes'=>'High', 'Test'=>'Harm (Fury) / Bluff (Heresy) / Bless (Virtue)', 'Obstacles'=>'1 per Court Stage', 'Suggested_Action'=>'Play / Bet', 'Stage'=>'Dust', 'Stage_Description'=>'The Stage is dusty and windswept, there are few features to break up the monotony, perhaps footprints in the dust. The dust could be lying on the ground, a lack of cleaning, or it might hang in the air, a result of bad air filters, or a light, fine sandy desert.', 'Motional'=>'Dangerous Steeplechase', 'Motional_Description'=>'Survive all the way to the end of the slog through dangerous territory, and even try to make it there first, if you can keep the horse alive.', 'Tide_of_Battle'=>'Gun-Smoke','Tide_of_Battle_Text'=>'Gun-Smoke (or smoke from fires, gas grenades, or the like) engulfs the battlefield, cutting visibility drastically for all combatants. This doubles Range and Movement costs (unless Crawling) for both sides and can make hiding easier for both sides (+1 Pips per card).', 'Fight'=>'Encounter', 'Fight_Description'=>'An Encounter with a not necessarily hostile force, often a Group of (Chorus Extra) Monsters.[t13ne type="facetsuitaspect" suit=2 aspect="Monster" /]'), //9 -lady
	array('Ordeal_Type'=>'Opposed Ordeal', 'Stages'=>'4','Ordeal_Spread'=>'Block', 'Stakes'=>'Extreme', 'Test'=>'Tale-Telling (Heresy)', 'Obstacles'=>'1 per Stage', 'Suggested_Action'=>'Trick / Amuse', 'Stage'=>'Countryside', 'Stage_Description'=>'Rolling hills, grasslands, trees and countryside, or maybe just a really good park, or an incredible garden', 'Motional'=>'Foot Race', 'Motional_Description'=>'Reach the goal on foot, before anyone else to secure the victory.', 'Tide_of_Battle'=>'Caught out','Tide_of_Battle_Text'=>'The smoke of battle clears, and one member of the Ebbing side is caught out away from their line, engaged with the enemy in their territory. They can either charge to melee reach, or retreat back to their line with a Disengament Action.', 'Fight'=>'Fire fight', 'Fight_Description'=>'A battle against opponents with prepared defences and ranged (and / or heavy) weapons. The opponent should be at least equal in number and power to the party.'), //10 -jester
	array('Ordeal_Type'=>'Opposed Ordeal', 'Stages'=>'5','Ordeal_Spread'=>'Pyramid', 'Stakes'=>'Blended Low-Medium', 'Test'=>'Pretend (Jeer)', 'Obstacles'=>'1 per Stage', 'Suggested_Action'=>'Disguise / Pretend', 'Stage'=>'Jump Stunt', 'Stage_Description'=>'Jump down, Jump into shadows, a Joke, a Quantum Leap.','Motional'=>'Swimming Race', 'Motional_Description'=>'Swim for the goal, before anyone else, to secure the victory.', 'Tide_of_Battle'=>'Playing Dead','Tide_of_Battle_Text'=>'At least one of the Flowing Side that was previously defeated returns to the Battle with their Wounds Stabilised.', 'Fight'=>'Knave', 'Fight_Description'=>'A single Monster (usually with at least Two &diams; Monster Facets), that is at least equivalent to any 2 PCs.[t13ne type="facetsuitaspect" suit=2 aspect="Monster" /]'), //J -mask
	array('Ordeal_Type'=>'Opposed Ordeal', 'Stages'=>'5','Ordeal_Spread'=>'Block', 'Stakes'=>'Blended Medium-High', 'Test'=>'Protect (Rook)', 'Obstacles'=>'1 per Stage and 2 per Court Stage', 'Suggested_Action'=>'Cover / Hide', 'Stage'=>'Evade', 'Stage_Description'=>'Evade or dodge something, come up with a story, a Blending in opportunity, or Medical emergency.', 'Motional'=>'Winged Race', 'Motional_Description'=>'If you can fly then you might stand a chance, if you aren\'t gifted with wings you are going to have to climb, swing, balance and jump.', 'Tide_of_Battle'=>'The Brink','Tide_of_Battle_Text'=>'The Flowing forces believe they are on the brink of success, and this causes them to potentially make a mistake, revealing themselves from cover, dropping their defences, or pushing into attack too hard (+1 Flowing Failure Level). ', 'Fight'=>'Argument', 'Fight_Description'=>'The fight is normally a Low or Soul Stakes argument between two Characters (at least Chorus Extra). The opponent may be a Monster of some sort.[t13ne type="facetsuitaspect" suit=2 aspect="Monster" /]'), //Q -cloak
	array('Ordeal_Type'=>'Opposed Ordeal', 'Stages'=>'6','Ordeal_Spread'=>'Map-Hex', 'Stakes'=>'Blended Medium-High-Extreme', 'Test'=>'Medicine (Miasma)', 'Obstacles'=>'1 per Stage and 2 per Court Stage', 'Suggested_Action'=>'Investigate / Heal', 'Stage'=>'Skip ahead', 'Stage_Description'=>'A short-cut, chance to skip ahead, or Lucky Break', 'Motional'=>'Dangerous Foot Race', 'Motional_Description'=>'First survive the Stages, then worry about if anyone made it to the end before you.', 'Tide_of_Battle'=>'Offered Succour','Tide_of_Battle_Text'=>'The Flowing forces may offer the Ebbing Side succour, in the form of medicines, Stabilised Wounds, and respite from the combat, if they simply surrender. This can have a profound psychological effect, adding an additional Ebbing Failure Level.', 'Fight'=>'Honour Duel', 'Fight_Description'=>'The Fight is a Duel, usually between two unbalanced individuals (one will be of higher power level than the other). Rules are formal, and normally observed at least by the more powerful or higher ranked opponent. Opponent may be a Monster. [t13ne type="facetsuitaspect" suit=2 aspect="Monster" /]'), //K -physician
	//Clubs
	array('Ordeal_Type'=>'Opposed Ordeal', 'Stages'=>'8','Ordeal_Spread'=>'Map-Geography', 'Stakes'=>'Blended Low-Medium-High', 'Test'=>'Judge (Wyrd)', 'Obstacles'=>'3 Obstacles per Stage', 'Suggested_Action'=>'Finesse / Decide', 'Stage'=>'Control Stunt', 'Stage_Description'=>'Do something that requires immense amounts of control over your vehicle, or self-control. There is always at least one Obstacle in a Control Stunt Stage.', 'Motional'=>'Dangerous Vehicular Chase', 'Motional_Description'=>'Someone is trying to get away, across the lava fields / glacier / tidal bridge / mountain-goat road you have to chase them, in a Jeep, for some reason.', 'Tide_of_Battle'=>'Set a Trap','Tide_of_Battle_Text'=>'The Flowing forces are able to direct the battle enough that they can create a trap on the battle-field. This allows the Flowing forces to Prepare 1 additional card from their Pool to their Style Reserves, in addition to any cards they may Prepare as an Action.', 'Fight'=>'Prepared Ambush', 'Fight_Description'=>'The Fight is an ambush by a well prepared opponent with defences and escape strategies in place. The opponents are usually weaker than the party, but have good defences and specialised weapons and tactics that give them at least one Preparation Phase, before combat is begun.'), //A - court
	array('Ordeal_Type'=>'Opposed Ordeal', 'Stages'=>'3','Ordeal_Spread'=>'Railroad', 'Stakes'=>'Low', 'Test'=>'Perceive (Key)', 'Obstacles'=>'1 Obstacle in a Court Stage', 'Suggested_Action'=>'Evade / Rhyme', 'Stage'=>'Cluttered', 'Stage_Description'=>'The route ahead is cluttered, perhaps with parked cards, litter bins. Book stacks, filing cabinets, shelves, scaffolding poles, pipes, trees or bamboo poles can also create clutter.', 'Motional'=>'Ground Vehicle Chase', 'Motional_Description'=>'Who is that ahead of you? You need to catch them to find out. Drop a gear and put your foot to the floor.', 'Tide_of_Battle'=>'Holding','Tide_of_Battle_Text'=>'The Ebbing enemy position is good, they are in the best place to control the battle, the only issue is the Flowing forces are massing to test these defences. Defend hard enough and the Tide will turn. Defend any Attack and you can retaliate with a Personality Annex Psych Attack as a free action.', 'Fight'=>'Vigil', 'Fight_Description'=>'The fight mostly consists of watching, and waiting. Occasionally a solitary usually Vex or Chorus Extra Opponent will test your defences, very occasionally something bigger will come.[t13ne type="facetsuitaspect" suit=3 aspect="Monster" /]'), //2 -Eelafin
	array('Ordeal_Type'=>'Opposed Ordeal', 'Stages'=>'3','Ordeal_Spread'=>'Forking', 'Stakes'=>'Medium', 'Test'=>'Lie (Heresy)', 'Obstacles'=>'1 Obstacle in a Court Stage', 'Suggested_Action'=>'Sneak / Tempt', 'Stage'=>'Negotiate', 'Stage_Description'=>'Sometimes there are things in the we that you have to negotiate your way past, other times there are just difficult negotiations that you have to conduct.', 'Motional'=>'Flying Machine Chase', 'Motional_Description'=>'They\'re getting away in that aeroplane / helicopter / grav-platform, get after them, or better yet, get ahead of them.', 'Tide_of_Battle'=>'Ceasefire','Tide_of_Battle_Text'=>'The Ebbing forces call a ceasefire offering the Flowing forces a chance to accept and push for surrender, or attack with an advantage (+1 Pip per card).', 'Fight'=>'Third Force', 'Fight_Description'=>'The fight is initially between two sides, often equally matched, during the third Phase a third force arrives that is at least as powerful as the least powerful force already fighting.'), //3 -serpent
	array('Ordeal_Type'=>'Opposed Ordeal', 'Stages'=>'3','Ordeal_Spread'=>'Pyramid', 'Stakes'=>'Medium', 'Test'=>'Swimming / Sailing (Zeal)', 'Obstacles'=>'1 Obstacle in a Court Stage', 'Suggested_Action'=>'Swim / Calm', 'Stage'=>'Wrangling', 'Stage_Description'=>'The way ahead is winding and difficult to get through. There may be passing traffic or too many pedestrians, only the Ref can say for sure.', 'Motional'=>'Street Chase', 'Motional_Description'=>'This can be as powerful and simple as "Follow-That-Car!", or you can be the one at the wheel.', 'Tide_of_Battle'=>'Swirling','Tide_of_Battle_Text'=>'The Ebb and Flow of the Tide of Battle has become chaotic, there are no advantages to be had by either side.', 'Fight'=>'Siege', 'Fight_Description'=>'One side is entrenched and well-prepared. The other side must lay siege. The attacking side will usually have a numerical advantage and may have a power advantage too. Defenders have a tactical advantage in their defences which will apply Location Bonus Cards to suitable Style Reserves .'), //4 - waters
	array('Ordeal_Type'=>'Opposed Ordeal', 'Stages'=>'3','Ordeal_Spread'=>'Forking', 'Stakes'=>'High', 'Test'=>'Endure (Inertia)', 'Obstacles'=>'1 Obstacle in every Court Stage', 'Suggested_Action'=>'Defend / Warn', 'Stage'=>'Water', 'Stage_Description'=>'The way ahead is flooded. It might be an ocean, sea, lake, a river, a pond, or a storm drain, but there is water ahead.', 'Motional'=>'Water Vehicle Chase', 'Motional_Description'=>'Roaring engines, skipping hulls and Rooster-tail wakes, or whistling wind, humming lines and the slap of waves on wood, either way, they\'ll get away, unless you catch or kill them!', 'Tide_of_Battle'=>'Surrounded','Tide_of_Battle_Text'=>'The Flowing forces engulf and surround the Ebbing side. The Ebbing enemy must break out of this box, surrender or be destroyed.', 'Fight'=>'Minor Guardian', 'Fight_Description'=>'Either a solitary Monster or small team (2-3) of Chorus Extras guard the way ahead. [t13ne type="facetsuitaspect" suit=3 aspect="Monster" /]' ), //5 - shield
	array('Ordeal_Type'=>'Opposed Ordeal', 'Stages'=>'4','Ordeal_Spread'=>'Pyramid', 'Stakes'=>'Low', 'Test'=>'Overwhelm (Fury)', 'Obstacles'=>'1 Obstacle in every Court Stage', 'Suggested_Action'=>'Overwhelm / Shout', 'Stage'=>'Mental', 'Stage_Description'=>'It may be that the way ahead is simply something you have to think about, you may have to strategize. Then again the route may be through a Laboratory, a Library, or similar. Then again maybe the way ahead is bedlam, filled with loud noises, sudden flashes of light, or some other distractions.', 'Motional'=>'Aerial Riding Chase', 'Motional_Description'=>'The prisoners! They are escaping on para-wings / hover-boards / giant eagles! Quick, after them!', 'Tide_of_Battle'=>'Confusion','Tide_of_Battle_Text'=>'Both sides of the battle are now engulfed by confusion. Orders and plans become meaningless, and all Prepared Cards are Discarded. Both sides will take a Failure Level this Stage.', 'Fight'=>'Major Guardian', 'Fight_Description'=>'A powerful guardian stands in the way. Usually a large force (dozens) of Chorus Extras, small group of Monster Cast Extras or a Force of Nature Monster with at least 2 &clubs; Monster Facets.[t13ne type="facetsuitaspect" suit=3 aspect="Monster" /]'), //6 -horde
	array('Ordeal_Type'=>'Opposed Ordeal', 'Stages'=>'4','Ordeal_Spread'=>'Block', 'Stakes'=>'Medium', 'Test'=>'Impress (Awe)', 'Obstacles'=>'1 Obstacle in every Court Stage', 'Suggested_Action'=>'Smash / Purchase', 'Stage'=>'Defences', 'Stage_Description'=>'The way ahead is through, or around, or on defences of some sort. These might be as simple as a hedge or chain-link fence, or be a gatehouse, or even a fortified citadels walls.', 'Motional'=>'Aquatic Riding Chase', 'Motional_Description'=>'The lizard men are getting away on a giant Alligator, you\'ll have to chase them, perhaps on those jet-skis?', 'Tide_of_Battle'=>'The Wall','Tide_of_Battle_Text'=>'The Flowing forces have formed (or reformed) a defensive line, this might be a wall of shields, a powered defence, a line of armoured vehicles, or a low garden wall. The point is they have something to defend, that offers them a slight advantage (+1 Pips on all Defence cards they play).', 'Fight'=>'Greater Guardian', 'Fight_Description'=>'The way ahead is defended by a Kaiju or Force-of-Nature Monsters, or dozens or hundreds of well armed Cast Extras.[t13ne type="facetsuitaspect" suit=3 aspect="Monster" /]'), //7 - crystal
	array('Ordeal_Type'=>'Opposed Ordeal', 'Stages'=>'5','Ordeal_Spread'=>'Forking', 'Stakes'=>'High', 'Test'=>'Tool-Use (Craft)', 'Obstacles'=>'1 Obstacle in every Stage', 'Suggested_Action'=>'Strike / Gather', 'Stage'=>'Web', 'Stage_Description'=>'The way ahead is some sort of webbing, net, or weave, maybe the internet, or perhaps a suspension bridge, or maybe a confluence of roads, threads or wires. Or perhaps the way ahead is just heavy with old cobwebs.', 'Motional'=>'Ground Riding Chase', 'Motional_Description'=>'They\'re just ahead, you can hear the pounding hoof-beats on the dark forest road. You pursue pushing your horse harder, until you can see their cloaks flapping in the wind. One turns in the saddle, there is a flash of fire that reveals his face, masked beneath his Tricorn hat, and then the crack-whistle of a musket shot.', 'Tide_of_Battle'=>'Prisoners','Tide_of_Battle_Text'=>'Several members of the Ebbing side are taken prisoner or surrender. The Flowing side must decide to capture and guard the prisoners, or whether to take no prisoners, either way may have positive or negative effects on both sides, depending how things unfold.', 'Fight'=>'Capture', 'Fight_Description'=>'The enemy needs to be captured alive (and conscious ideally). Usually this enemy is a solitary Monster (Cast Extra) with 2 Monster Facets .[t13ne type="facetsuitaspect" suit=3 aspect="Monster" /]'), //8 -scythe
	array('Ordeal_Type'=>'Opposed Ordeal', 'Stages'=>'5','Ordeal_Spread'=>'Pyramid', 'Stakes'=>'Low', 'Test'=>'Continuing (Inertia)', 'Obstacles'=>'1 Obstacle in every Stage', 'Suggested_Action'=>'Order / Reassure', 'Stage'=>'Squeeze', 'Stage_Description'=>'A squeeze can be a tight space, or something a little more romantic, it can even be an illegal operation. Here the chances are it is a very narrow gap, too small for a normal vehicle or person to pass, without some clever thinking.', 'Motional'=>'Dangerous Riding Chase', 'Motional_Description'=>'The enemy cavalry and the Baron\'s standard, break. Retreating past their own lines. Ignoring the fusillade of cannon, and the still unbroken archers on the right flank, you wheel your horses to follow.', 'Tide_of_Battle'=>'Closing the Breach','Tide_of_Battle_Text'=>'The Flowing forces have breached the Ebbing defences, this could be the end, unless the Ebbing enemy can close the breach and hold the ground, or fall-back to a new position.', 'Fight'=>'Protect', 'Fight_Description'=>'A Force is attacking that will attempt to kill one of the Party\'s Allies. Usually this force is around the PCs in power level and numbers, but may have lower or higher powered reserves arriving in following Rounds. The Party must protect the Ally, usually for ethical or narrative reasons.'), //9 -crown
	array('Ordeal_Type'=>'Opposed Ordeal', 'Stages'=>'5','Ordeal_Spread'=>'Block', 'Stakes'=>'Medium', 'Test'=>'Watch (Key)', 'Obstacles'=>'1 Obstacle in every Non-Court Stage, 2 in every Court Stage', 'Suggested_Action'=>'Protect / Supervise', 'Stage'=>'Skid-row', 'Stage_Description'=>'Red-light districts are the home of sin, down and outs litter the streets (to say nothing of the litter). There\'s plenty going on at all times of the day or night, and you can\'t generally drive through at speed because of the crawling cars and occasional police presence.', 'Motional'=>'Foot Chase', 'Motional_Description'=>'Each breath burns your lungs, but you can still see them ahead, as they cross the bridge, and head down to the platform and waiting train below. Ignoring the pain, you push on, you have to make it to that train.', 'Tide_of_Battle'=>'Temptation','Tide_of_Battle_Text'=>'The Flowing side is offered some tactical temptation that could win the battle, but risks turning the Tide against them. This may be a case of abandoning a current position for one that may offer an advantage, but they could be caught in a cross-fire. The Flowing forces must play a Trick during this Stage. Failure to play a Trick will cause them to become Ebbing instead.', 'Fight'=>'Targeted Assault', 'Fight_Description'=>'A force around the Party\'s size and power-level attacks. The attackers focus their attack on one Party member (usually the most Pressed or Hooked), trying to inflict maximum damage for one Round, after which they retreat, fighting a retreating battle. Also called a Drive-By.'), //10 -guardian
	array('Ordeal_Type'=>'Opposed Ordeal', 'Stages'=>'6','Ordeal_Spread'=>'Map-Grid', 'Stakes'=>'Blended Low-Medium', 'Test'=>'Destruction (Miasma)', 'Obstacles'=>'1 Obstacle in every Non-Court Stage, 2 in every Court Stage', 'Suggested_Action'=>'Assault / Endure', 'Stage'=>'Jump Stunt', 'Stage_Description'=>'Jump over, past, or through an Obstacle. There\'s always at least one Obstacle that must be jumped over or through in this Stage.', 'Motional'=>'Swimming Chase', 'Motional_Description'=>'They swim, you swim after them.', 'Tide_of_Battle'=>'Last Desperate Push','Tide_of_Battle_Text'=>'The Ebbing enemy are on their last legs, but they have decided to make a desperate fool-hardy assault with no advantages. If the Flowing forces survive the assault they will have won.', 'Fight'=>'Knight', 'Fight_Description'=>'The opponent is a solitary Monster, usually well armoured (passive defences) and with strong attacks. Should be at least as powerful as any Two PCs. At least 2 &clubs; Monster Facets[t13ne type="facetsuitaspect" suit=3 aspect="Monster" /]'), //J -tempest
	array('Ordeal_Type'=>'Opposed Ordeal', 'Stages'=>'6','Ordeal_Spread'=>'Map-Hex', 'Stakes'=>'Blended Medium-High', 'Test'=>'Sleep (Inertia)', 'Obstacles'=>'2 Obstacles in every Non-Court Stage, 3 in every Court Stage', 'Suggested_Action'=>'Celebrate / Whisper', 'Stage'=>'Quick Stunt', 'Stage_Description'=>'A number of Obstacles, A trap/or other Obstacles, an unforeseen expense', 'Motional'=>'Winged Chase', 'Motional_Description'=>'He blows you a kiss, and steps back from the edge of the building, dropping from sight, before he unfurls his wings and slips into a long glide across the rooftops. You hurl your grappling hook, and swing to chase.', 'Tide_of_Battle'=>'The Ploy','Tide_of_Battle_Text'=>'Most of the Ebbing side are in poor positions, and either need a ploy to create a distraction to allow them to redeploy, or need to be used as a distraction while a ploy is attempted. If the Ebbing side can manage to play a Trick this Stage then they will turn the Tide and the battle will start Flowing for them, failure to play a Trick will result in defeat.', 'Fight'=>'Bad Boy / Girl', 'Fight_Description'=>'The fight is against a solitary opponent who is around the level of the strongest PC. Usually the opponent will use subterfuge and asymmetrical warfare to isolate and neutralise the PCs. Usually a Monster with at least one &clubs; Monster Facet. [t13ne type="facetsuitaspect" suit=3 aspect="Monster" /]'), //Q -Inn
	array('Ordeal_Type'=>'Opposed Ordeal', 'Stages'=>'6','Ordeal_Spread'=>'Map-Geography', 'Stakes'=>'Blended Low-Medium-High', 'Test'=>'Politics (Dominion)', 'Obstacles'=>'2 Obstacles in every Non-Court Stage, 3 in every Court Stage', 'Suggested_Action'=>'Choose / Obey', 'Stage'=>'Intersection Stunt', 'Stage_Description'=>'A choice of three directions. A negotiation or a demonstration of power', 'Motional'=>'Dangerous Foot Chase', 'Motional_Description'=>'We\'re halting pursuit, Captain. Sir, yes I understand, but... Sir... Yessir... Okay, you heard the Captain, follow them into the minefield.', 'Tide_of_Battle'=>'Do or Die','Tide_of_Battle_Text'=>'This is it, the final choice that it all comes down to. Charge the Ebbing enemy, taking losses, and perhaps win, or wait for them regroup and mop you up. The Flowing forces must take at least a Maiming Wound to succeed during this Stage or they will become the Ebbing side.', 'Fight'=>'Boss Fight', 'Fight_Description'=>'The Fight is a major battle against a very powerful Monster. Sometimes a Force of Nature Monster with at least 2 &clubs; Monster Facets, or even a Kaiju.[t13ne type="facetsuitaspect" suit=3 aspect="Monster" /]'), //K - fae noble
	//Spades
	array('Ordeal_Type'=>'Opposed Ordeal', 'Stages'=>'9','Ordeal_Spread'=>'Map-Geography', 'Stakes'=>'Blended Medium-High-Extreme', 'Test'=>'Strength (Gossamer) / Secure (Rook) / Escape (Liberty)', 'Obstacles'=>'3 Obstacles per Stage', 'Suggested_Action'=>'Push / Influence', 'Stage'=>'Danger Stunt', 'Stage_Description'=>'Maybe the buildings are collapsing, or an earthquake is happening. You know the sort of thing, jets of flame leap from the ground, the floor bucks and shakes, power cables spark and fall. Danger is all around.', 'Motional'=>'Dangerous Vehicular Flee', 'Motional_Description'=>'The smoke and flames are thick, but you can still see the headlights behind you. They aren\'t giving up...', 'Tide_of_Battle'=>'Out Manoeuvred','Tide_of_Battle_Text'=>'The Ebbing enemy have gone for a pincer tactic and have the Flowing forces pinned between groups that are closing in. The Flowing side has a choice, Good mobility and speed will let you escape the trap, or you can hunker down and hope you can smash them as they come. Either way offers the Flowing side +1 Pips per card', 'Fight'=>'Shock Attack', 'Fight_Description'=>'This is a special Extreme Stakes Ambush, where the Ambushers actually rapidly assault (rather than being hidden). Shock Attackers have +1 Success Level to all rolls and cards during the opening Phase. Although they are rarely more than a Cast Extra, they may be Vex Monsters. With 1 Monster Facet [t13ne type="facetsuitaspect" suit=4 aspect="Monster" /]'), //A -threshold
	array('Ordeal_Type'=>'Opposed Ordeal', 'Stages'=>'4','Ordeal_Spread'=>'Railroad', 'Stakes'=>'Low', 'Test'=>'Medicine (Phoenix)', 'Obstacles'=>'1 Obstacle in a Court Stage', 'Suggested_Action'=>'Struggle / Give Up', 'Stage'=>'Broken glass', 'Stage_Description'=>'The route ahead is dangerous, littered with sharp stones, broken glass, or even landmines.', 'Motional'=>'Ground Vehicle Flee', 'Motional_Description'=>'Hit the gas! They\'re right behind us!', 'Tide_of_Battle'=>'Breaking Point','Tide_of_Battle_Text'=>'The Ebbing enemy are at breaking point, one good assault should see them done. The Flowing force need only cause more Wounds than they take this Stage to win the round.', 'Fight'=>'Scare', 'Fight_Description'=>'A Scare is a sudden Psych attack (such as a Duck attack), from a Vex or Chorus Monster that quickly retreats. [t13ne type="facetsuitaspect" suit=4 aspect="Monster" /]'), //2 - swamp
	array('Ordeal_Type'=>'Opposed Ordeal', 'Stages'=>'4','Ordeal_Spread'=>'Forking', 'Stakes'=>'Medium', 'Test'=>'Discover (Yonder)', 'Obstacles'=>'1 Obstacle in a Court Stage', 'Suggested_Action'=>'Turn / Tease', 'Stage'=>'Balance', 'Stage_Description'=>'The way ahead is narrow, perhaps a thin, mountain-goat path, or a plank across a gap. Maybe the route is across ceiling beams or the girders of the top of a box-bridge.', 'Motional'=>'Air Vehicle Flee', 'Motional_Description'=>'Foxtrot-Bravo-Two you have Echo-Charlie on your Six, accelerate to point Seven and try to shake them.', 'Tide_of_Battle'=>'Penetration','Tide_of_Battle_Text'=>'The Flowing forces are able to pierce through the Ebbing Defences, pushing through their lines and armour. All Ebbing sides cards are are at -1 Pips for Defence', 'Fight'=>'3 Way Battle', 'Fight_Description'=>'The Fight is between 3 equal and unaligned forces that meet in a Square, Field, or other mostly open area.'), //3 -key
	array('Ordeal_Type'=>'Opposed Ordeal', 'Stages'=>'4','Ordeal_Spread'=>'Pyramid', 'Stakes'=>'High', 'Test'=>'Construction (Craft)', 'Obstacles'=>'1 Obstacle in a Court Stage', 'Suggested_Action'=>'Drop / Observe', 'Stage'=>'Slick', 'Stage_Description'=>'The way ahead is slick, perhaps a recently polished floor, or something has been spilt, like oil. Or maybe the ground is icy.', 'Motional'=>'Ground Vehicle Flee', 'Motional_Description'=>'They\'re right on top of us, take the wheel and keep down, I need to shoot back. Oh, try not to crash, yeah?', 'Tide_of_Battle'=>'Hold','Tide_of_Battle_Text'=>'The Flowing side has captured a defensible position or acquired some tactical advantage. If they can hold this position for this Stage they will secure their momentum into the next Round. Failure to hold this position however will result in the Tide reversing.', 'Fight'=>'Infiltration', 'Fight_Description'=>'The Fight is a Stealth mission, to penetrate a secure facility, achieve some goal (often an assassination or theft) and then escape. Opponents are usually Cast Extras (security guards) although they may be Chorus Monsters.[t13ne type="facetsuitaspect" suit=4 aspect="Monster" /]'), //4 -tower
	array('Ordeal_Type'=>'Opposed Ordeal', 'Stages'=>'5','Ordeal_Spread'=>'Forking', 'Stakes'=>'High', 'Test'=>'Travelling (Zeal)', 'Obstacles'=>'1 Obstacle in every Court Stage', 'Suggested_Action'=>'Change Direction / Bluster', 'Stage'=>'Unstable', 'Stage_Description'=>'The way ahead is fraught with problems, you may be dealing with an unstable floor, or an unstable building, or perhaps the person you are dealing with is themselves unstable.', 'Motional'=>'Water Vehicle Flee', 'Motional_Description'=>'Keep rowing, I think we\'re losing them.', 'Tide_of_Battle'=>'External Forces','Tide_of_Battle_Text'=>'There is some force, beyond the immediate battle field that holds some command upon it. This External force will decide the next Tide of Battle, not the actions of those already fighting. This may include a third force who ride into battle, an attack by a dragon or intervention by law enforcement.', 'Fight'=>'Pair of Monsters', 'Fight_Description'=>'This is a Fight against a pair of Monsters (for example two Vampires or a Vampire and a Werewolf). Each Monster is at least equal to a PC in power and has 2 &spades; Monster Facets.[t13ne type="facetsuitaspect" suit=4 aspect="Monster" /]'), //5 - sail
	array('Ordeal_Type'=>'Opposed Ordeal', 'Stages'=>'5','Ordeal_Spread'=>'Pyramid', 'Stakes'=>'High', 'Test'=>'Mechanics (Craft)', 'Obstacles'=>'1 Obstacle in every Court Stage', 'Suggested_Action'=>'Measure / Be Patient', 'Stage'=>'Dark', 'Stage_Description'=>'There\'s a lot of potential dangers in the darkness, ranging from the occasional Lego brick, or upturned plug, or nail, to holes and of course, monsters.', 'Motional'=>'Flying Riding Flee', 'Motional_Description'=>'The hover-board gangs boards roared as they engaged their plasma burners, and they raced for us, as I took the ornithopter over a grav-transport and onto the north-bound express level.', 'Tide_of_Battle'=>'Fog of War','Tide_of_Battle_Text'=>'The Tide of Battle is difficult to read for both sides, and neither side will have any advantage. Visibilty is restricted by fog, smoke, darkness or similar such that when two combatants threaten each other they are already at engaged distances. Disengagement Actions have two automatic Success Levels that may cancel a Failure Level.', 'Fight'=>'Major Trouble', 'Fight_Description'=>'The Fight is a seriously dangerous one. High or Extreme Stakes against a stream of Cast Monsters (with at least 3 Monster Facets). [t13ne type="facetsuitaspect" suit=4 aspect="Monster" /]'), //6 -clock
	array('Ordeal_Type'=>'Opposed Ordeal', 'Stages'=>'5','Ordeal_Spread'=>'Block', 'Stakes'=>'High', 'Test'=>'Slash / Swing (Inertia)', 'Obstacles'=>'1 Obstacle in every Court Stage', 'Suggested_Action'=>'Attack / Berate', 'Stage'=>'Suspect', 'Stage_Description'=>'The way ahead is suspect somehow, maybe the clouds of vapour are just steam, or maybe they are poisonous. Perhaps the Stage involves tracking or finding a suspect or dealing with a suspicious package or place.', 'Motional'=>'Water Riding Flee', 'Motional_Description'=>'Don\'t stop now, their squid-riders are gaining!', 'Tide_of_Battle'=>'Fall-back','Tide_of_Battle_Text'=>'The Ebbing Enemy falls-back, disengaging where possible, trying to reach a more secure position. The Flowing forces will add +1 Pips to all cards they play during Disengagements to attack.', 'Fight'=>'Great Threat', 'Fight_Description'=>'The Fight is against a powerful enemy such as a Greater Demon or Horde of Monsters. [t13ne type="facetsuitaspect" suit=4 aspect="Monster" /]'), //7 - sword
	array('Ordeal_Type'=>'Opposed Ordeal', 'Stages'=>'6','Ordeal_Spread'=>'Forking', 'Stakes'=>'High', 'Test'=>'Charm (Awe)', 'Obstacles'=>'1 Obstacle in every Stage', 'Suggested_Action'=>'Challenge / Compete', 'Stage'=>'Foetid', 'Stage_Description'=>'The way ahead stinks. It may not necessarily be a foul smell, but it usually is. A perfume store is less likely than an open sewer, or pile of trash, but not impossible.', 'Motional'=>'Ground Riding Flee', 'Motional_Description'=>'The horses are sweating, foaming as the bit, and you should stop, and rest them, but the Warg-Riders are somewhere behind you and already trying to flank.', 'Tide_of_Battle'=>'Collapse','Tide_of_Battle_Text'=>'The Tide of Battle is in transition, unsure who is winning, defences are abandonned by both sides to close to melee. All Prepared Defences are abandoned, and all Style Reserves Discard a card. All physical movement and attack cards by either side add +1 Pips.', 'Fight'=>'Gang Warfare', 'Fight_Description'=>'The enemy is a large group of rag-tag, undisciplined, but often surprisingly strong, well-trained or heavily-armed Cast Extras.'), //8 -rival
	array('Ordeal_Type'=>'Opposed Ordeal', 'Stages'=>'6','Ordeal_Spread'=>'Block', 'Stakes'=>'Extreme', 'Test'=>'Work (Craft) / Program (Orthodox) / Control (Dominion)', 'Obstacles'=>'1 Obstacle in every Stage', 'Suggested_Action'=>'Hack / Survive', 'Stage'=>'Competition', 'Stage_Description'=>'The route ahead involves some extra competition. Maybe the race you are in suddenly has a stampede cross it, or you have to reach the level crossing before the train, the road runs along side. Then again it could just mean that what you thought was a dash is now something else.', 'Motional'=>'Dangerous Riding Flee', 'Motional_Description'=>'Ride! Pedal faster! We need to get to high ground, ahead of the flood-waters.', 'Tide_of_Battle'=>'Extreme Violence','Tide_of_Battle_Text'=>'Both sides are extrememly dangerous right now, and the Stakes are lifted to a minimum of Extreme. The Flowing side may add +2 Pips to any Attack card, the Ebbing side may add +1 Pips to an Attack card.', 'Fight'=>'Bullies and Thugs', 'Fight_Description'=>'The enemy is a larger group of Cast Extras (or Force-of-Nature for powerful Characters) who attempt to inflict harm on the Party, usually trying to humiliate or steal from the PCs. They rarely intend to kill, and will usually retreat if any PC or member is seriously injured.'), //9 - robot
	array('Ordeal_Type'=>'Opposed Ordeal', 'Stages'=>'6','Ordeal_Spread'=>'Pyramid', 'Stakes'=>'Extreme', 'Test'=>'Confrontation (Trial)', 'Obstacles'=>'1 Obstacle in every Non-Court Stage, 2 in every Court Stage', 'Suggested_Action'=>'Fight / Brag', 'Stage'=>'Encounter', 'Stage_Description'=>'The way ahead involves an encounter, and often a fight, perhaps with the Dominant Embodiment, or perhaps with a different foe. Wiles, or weapons, may be needed to get by, and it is bound to slow you down. This might be a place where the route arcs back, allowing shots to be fired between Chaser and Chased, but more often is a third party encounter that both sides must contend with (unaffiliated street gang / raiders, bear etc)', 'Motional'=>'Foot Flee', 'Motional_Description'=>'The Robots are hunting, they\'ve got guns, they\'re coming.', 'Tide_of_Battle'=>'Every Shot Counts','Tide_of_Battle_Text'=>'Everyone is low on ammo, and needs to reload, and resupply. Both sides may only make Prepared Attacks at Range, spontaneous attacks must be made with Reach weapons.', 'Fight'=>'Army,', 'Fight_Description'=>'Large scale military battles involve Armies. Usually two of them, but PCs may not always have the resources to create their own army. The opposition however has hundreds of Grunts (or Cast Extras) who have military grade equipment suitable for their time period (Chain-mail and sword, tac-vest and assault rifle, power-armour and a pew-pew-pulsed-plasma-pistol).'), //10 -lion
	array('Ordeal_Type'=>'Opposed Ordeal', 'Stages'=>'7','Ordeal_Spread'=>'Map-Grid', 'Stakes'=>'Blended Low-Extreme', 'Test'=>'Investigating (Key)', 'Obstacles'=>'1 Obstacle in every Non-Court Stage, 2 in every Court Stage', 'Suggested_Action'=>'Shoot / Survey', 'Stage'=>'Jump Stunt', 'Stage_Description'=>'Jump (or balance) over danger. Leaping between catwalks over molten metal, missing slats on rope bridges over unlikely crocodile-filled rapids, or a rooftop run over a burning building, are all good examples.', 'Motional'=>'Swim Flee', 'Motional_Description'=>'Swim faster! They\'re right behind us!', 'Tide_of_Battle'=>'Escape','Tide_of_Battle_Text'=>'The Ebbing side of the battle is offered a chance to escape, this may be a deliberate tactic by the Flowing side, or just represent an opportunity that appears to them. The Ebbing side will have +1 Pips on any card played in a Disengagement Action, but a -1 Pips on any Attack or Defence Actions.', 'Fight'=>'Knight', 'Fight_Description'=>'The Fight is against a powerful soldier or military type, well equipped, with Attack and Defence dedicated Annexes. The Knight is at least equal in power to the most powerful PC, and has Armour and at least two Weapon Descendants. The Knight may also be a Monster.[t13ne type="facetsuitaspect" suit=4 aspect="Monster" /]'), //J -explorer
	array('Ordeal_Type'=>'Opposed Ordeal', 'Stages'=>'7','Ordeal_Spread'=>'Map-Hex', 'Stakes'=>'Blended Extreme-Soul', 'Test'=>'Spot (Key)', 'Obstacles'=>'2 Obstacles in every Non-Court Stage, 3 in every Court Stage', 'Suggested_Action'=>'Inspect / Interrogate', 'Stage'=>'Cliff Stunt', 'Stage_Description'=>'The route ahead is very dangerous, mists hide details, the moisture coated rocks are treacherous underfoot, you are high, over broken spires of mist-shrouded rock, clinging to rough foot and handholds that were carved long ago.', 'Motional'=>'Air Winged Flee', 'Motional_Description'=>'You may not know who is chasing you, or what they may do, if they catch up to your Hippogriff...', 'Tide_of_Battle'=>'No Retreat','Tide_of_Battle_Text'=>'The Ebbing side is trapped by their location, or circumstances. They may have a clif behind them, or have backed into a dead-end canyon, but they can no longer retreat. Instead they will have to fight their way out. The Ebbing side add +2 Pips to any card played to Attack. The Flowing forces will have a +2 Pips to any Disengagement Actions they make.', 'Fight'=>'Queen', 'Fight_Description'=>'Queens come in two main types, politically powerful women (who may have a flair for violence, dark magic, manipulation or poisoning) and matriarchs noted for their huge (and surprisingly often violent, monstrous, or cannibalistic) families. Queens are often Monsters [t13ne type="facetsuitaspect" suit=4 aspect="Monster" /]'), //Q -scope
	array('Ordeal_Type'=>'Opposed Ordeal', 'Stages'=>'8','Ordeal_Spread'=>'Map-Geography', 'Stakes'=>'Blended Extreme-Paradoxical', 'Test'=>'Feed (Nature)', 'Obstacles'=>'2 Obstacles in every Non-Court Stage, 3 in every Court Stage', 'Suggested_Action'=>'Chop / Prepare', 'Stage'=>'Fork', 'Stage_Description'=>'A fork in the road (two directions to choose from), perhaps a navigation way-point, a place to search, or a chance to spot dangers ahead. A decision point, where you may be choosing between two equally perilous ways to proceed.', 'Motional'=>'Dangerous Footing Flee', 'Motional_Description'=>'Run! No, across the cracking ice. It is right behind you!', 'Tide_of_Battle'=>'Peak Assault','Tide_of_Battle_Text'=>'The Flowing side add an additional Success Level to all Attacks that they make while the Tide is at Peak, all Defence and Healing actions add a Failure Level during this Stage, but immediately after this peak the Ebb and Flow will reverse automatically.', 'Fight'=>'King of the Monsters', 'Fight_Description'=>'The Fight is against a huge Monster, such as a Kaiju (a Location with Monster Facets). This may be Demonic in nature too, or just extremely radioactive or something. [t13ne type="facetsuitaspect" suit=4 aspect="Monster" /]'), //K -butcher
	//wilds
	array('Ordeal_Type'=>'Opposed Ordeal', 'Stages'=>'12','Ordeal_Spread'=>'Map-Geography', 'Stakes'=>'Blended Low-Soul', 'Test'=>'Luck (Liberty)', 'Obstacles'=>'3 Obstacles per Non-Court Stage, 4 per Court Stage', 'Suggested_Action'=>'Impossibilties', 'Stage'=>'Maelstrom', 'Stage_Description'=>'The way ahead is chaos-ridden. Perhaps bullets strafe the landscape, or shells explode across No-man\'s land, or maybe the waters swirl in huge whirlpool. Then again perhaps it is just a swirl of litter and flashing lights that blocks the way.', 'Motional'=>'Circuit Race', 'Motional_Description'=>'Race around the Stages of the Ordeal repeatedly. Often a vehicle race, but it can be any form as required.', 'Tide_of_Battle'=>'Bullet Hell','Tide_of_Battle_Text'=>'Shots riddle the air, zinging from the stones of the ground and ricocheting through the melee. Anyone on the Battlefield will be Wounded by a random Unsoakable Extreme Stakes Wound card, every Phase, until one side are all dead or everyone is out of ammo.', 'Fight'=>'Insult Tennis', 'Fight_Description'=>'For whatever reason during the combat actual damage is unlikely, perhaps the combatants are Mech-pilots, or these are two immortals crossing swords. The real contest is in the barbs, insults and quips that they make. The right insult, in this context, can be deadly.'), //RJ -world
	array('Ordeal_Type'=>'Opposed Ordeal', 'Stages'=>'12','Ordeal_Spread'=>'Map-Geography', 'Stakes'=>'Blended Low-Paradoxical', 'Test'=>'Beyond (Yonder)', 'Obstacles'=>'None', 'Suggested_Action'=>'Inaction', 'Stage'=>'Dead Space', 'Stage_Description'=>'The way ahead is a void, or huge open space. Maybe there\'s no cover, maybe not even air. Then again it could just be the space behind the walls, secret passages, or simply a way most people would never go.', 'Motional'=>'Circuit Chase', 'Motional_Description'=>'A Chase (or Flee) that goes around through the same Stages again. ', 'Tide_of_Battle'=>'Open Ground','Tide_of_Battle_Text'=>'The Fight is taking place on open terrain, devoid of cover or natural advantages. Only a desperate fool would fight here by choice. Both sides would be best served by retreating now. +1 Pips to any Disengagement Action by either side.', 'Fight'=>'Wave after Wave', 'Fight_Description'=>'The fight consists of waves of combatants. Each Round a new Wave begins, a Round ends automatically if all Combatants on one side are incapacitated. Typically each wave is of a different type, often beginning with Vex Monsters, rising in type and adding another Monster Facet, or doubling in number each Wave. [t13ne type="facetsuitaspect" suit="all" aspect="Monster" /]'), //BJ -beyond
);
public static $lea=array(
	//Diamonds
	array('PathColour'=>'Brown/Blue Omnivore','Bulmas'=>'Broccen, Vermis, Labyrinthine, All-Walkers','AnimalCategory'=>'All-path','Example'=>'Any','Bodypart'=>'Soul', 'Notes'=>'The Paths of the All-Walkers can allow Bulmäs to do extraordinary things, like walking an individual’s life-path, so that all of their personal history is known to them. Bulmäs can assume even the forms and souls of other people by using these paths, without directly eating of the Soul if they are skilled enough. Bulmäs can even Doom-Weave or Yarn-Tell and play other cards from their Hand as Wyrd Tarot cards or Yarn cards, once they have played an Ace on themselves.'), //A =ambition
	array('PathColour'=>'Brown/Blue Omnivore','Bulmas'=>'Broccen, Vermis, Labyrinthine, All-Walkers','AnimalCategory'=>'Microfauna','Example'=>'Plankton / Zooplankton / Tardigrade','Bodypart'=>'Tendrils/Tentacles', 'Notes'=>'Microscopic animal and bacterial paths, often overlooked. It is often in these paths that the Broccen store their food caches in the Lea.'), //2 - wraith
	array('PathColour'=>'Brown/Blue Omnivore','Bulmas'=>'Broccen, Vermis, Labyrinthine, All-Walkers','AnimalCategory'=>'Meiofauna','Example'=>'Small Nematode worms / shrimps','Bodypart'=>'Carapace', 'Notes'=>'A lot of parasite paths at this level. Parasitic Broccen are rare, but very dangerous.'), //3 - grindstone
	array('PathColour'=>'Brown/Blue Omnivore','Bulmas'=>'Broccen, Vermis, Labyrinthine, All-Walkers','AnimalCategory'=>'Mesofauna','Example'=>'Greenfly / Midge / Mosquito','Bodypart'=>'Wings', 'Notes'=>'Tiny Arthropods, often includes larval forms of larger arthropods'), //4 - book
	array('PathColour'=>'Brown/Blue Omnivore','Bulmas'=>'Broccen, Vermis, Labyrinthine, All-Walkers','AnimalCategory'=>'Macrofauna','Example'=>'Earthworm / Beetles / Ants / Minnows / Wasp','Bodypart'=>'Legs', 'Notes'=>'Small (often burrowing) creatures. May include the Smallest omnivorous vertebrates, such as the smallest fish, amphibians and shrews (as the smallest rodentia). Broccen often dig tunnels in the Lea at this level as they are common enough to be overlooked, and can stretch incredible distances, even between worlds.'), //5 - forest
	array('PathColour'=>'Brown/Blue Omnivore','Bulmas'=>'Broccen, Vermis, Labyrinthine, All-Walkers','AnimalCategory'=>'Megafauna – Tiny','Example'=>'Mice / Hedgehog / Squirrel / "Small" Fish and most Birds including Pigeons','Bodypart'=>'Feathers', 'Notes'=>'Omnivorous Animals weighing less than 500 grams. These often have the widest distributions crossing whole worlds, but seldom create migratory paths that can be followed a long way, without risking the deep Lea or Labyrinth.'), //6 - sun
	array('PathColour'=>'Brown/Blue Omnivore','Bulmas'=>'Broccen, Vermis, Labyrinthine, All-Walkers','AnimalCategory'=>'Megafauna – Small','Example'=>'Rat / Chicken / Crow / Piranha / Small Turtles','Bodypart'=>'Teeth', 'Notes'=>'These paths often migrate long distances between two small territories, crossing oceans or continents, with many cross connections to other paths.'), //7 - drive
	array('PathColour'=>'Brown/Blue Omnivore','Bulmas'=>'Broccen, Vermis, Labyrinthine, All-Walkers','AnimalCategory'=>'Megafauna – Medium','Example'=>'Badger (Brwc) / Raccoon / Small Primates/ Geese / Catfish / Sea Turtles','Bodypart'=>'Claws', 'Notes'=>'The Badger (or Brwc) is where the Broccen get their name. These Animals tend to keep territories, although they may have a nomadic stage or migration between two or more territories. These animals can get quite heavy, or large, depending upon their diet.'), //8 - cultist
	array('PathColour'=>'Brown/Blue Omnivore','Bulmas'=>'Broccen, Vermis, Labyrinthine, All-Walkers','AnimalCategory'=>'Megafauna – Large','Example'=>'Pig / Boar/ Bear / Cassowary / Large Primate','Bodypart'=>'Fangs', 'Notes'=>'These animals keep and patrol large territories. Technically humans do qualify as a specific example of Large Primate and this path can be used to become Hominids.'), //9 - priest
	array('PathColour'=>'Brown/Blue Omnivore','Bulmas'=>'Broccen, Vermis, Labyrinthine, All-Walkers','AnimalCategory'=>'Megafauna – Largest','Example'=>'Cave Bear / Dinosaurs / Mystery Animals / Cryptids', 'Bodypart'=>'Bone armour', 'Notes'=>'These Paths are often lost, causing the Bulmäs that use them to appear cryptozoological. Broccen often enjoy using these paths to scare humans from their territory, it is often easier to pick up a lost path if the animal became extinct more recently. Dinosaur paths are vary rare except where significant numbers of their specific fossils are found.'), //10 - loner
	array('PathColour'=>'Brown/Blue Omnivore','Bulmas'=>'Broccen, Vermis, Labyrinthine, All-Walkers','AnimalCategory'=>'Human-paths/Broccen Territory','Example'=>'Human / Groonians / Eelafin / Eusaivean / Mer-person / Bigfoot / Giant / Goblin, etc', 'Bodypart'=>'Tongue', 'Notes'=>'Broccen may use Jack’s to walk human paths (social and technological beings), or to dig new tunnels in the Lea, creating species to fill niches. Jacks may also be used to create Chimerical changes, blending parts of different animals together, each Jack played adds another place the Bulmäs can play Lea cards.'), //J - teacher
	array('PathColour'=>'Brown/Blue Omnivore','Bulmas'=>'Broccen, Vermis, Labyrinthine, All-Walkers','AnimalCategory'=>'Black paths and Migratory','Example'=>'Native Form / Dragon', 'Bodypart'=>'Head', 'Notes'=>'These paths open and close naturally through the Lea from time to time, they are easily walked by all Bulmäs in their native form, but Vermis and All-Walkers may walk them in Swarm or Dragon configurations. Queens may also be used by Broccen to create Chimeras, with each Queen played offering another place (or swarm) where cards may be played.'), //Q - forge
	array('PathColour'=>'Brown/Blue Omnivore','Bulmas'=>'Broccen, Vermis, Labyrinthine, All-Walkers','AnimalCategory'=>'Labyrinth','Example'=>'Labrys patterned human-animal hybrids','Bodypart'=>'Ear', 'Notes'=>'Kings represent the deep paths in the Lea that touch the Labyrinth, and C&aelig;ster in the centre. A normal Bulmäs that tries to walk the Labyrinth will often be lost, and would then be recruited into the Labyrinth. The Labyrinth can connect any point in space and time to any other, allowing Bulmäs to consciously time-travel through the Lea. A King can allow a Bulmäs to create or reload a Chronolith or side-step to another universe, or travel backward or forward in time, depending on the power-level of the Bulmäs. However, walking so close to the Labyrinth is not something that most will attempt, as it is too easy to become lost.'), //K - star
	//hearts
	array('PathColour'=>'Blue Aquatic or Black Migratory','Bulmas'=>'All','AnimalCategory'=>'All-path','Example'=>'All-Walkers and Vermis', 'Bodypart'=>'Heart / Soul', 'Notes'=>'The Paths of the All-Walkers can allow Bulmäs to do extraordinary things, like walking an individual’s life-path, so that all of their personal history is known to them. Bulmäs can assume even the forms and souls of other people by using these paths, without directly eating of the Soul. Bulmäs can even Doom Weave and play other cards from their hands as Wyrd Tarot cards, once they have played an Ace on themselves. Vermis particularly use this path to track and hunt Bulmäs souls before they are lost.'), //A - lovers
	array('PathColour'=>'Blue Aquatic or Black Migratory','Bulmas'=>'All','AnimalCategory'=>'Microfauna','Example'=>'Plankton / Zooplankton / Fungal spores / Bacteria ', 'Bodypart'=>'Tendrils', 'Notes'=>'Microscopic animal and bacterial paths, often overlooked, they can be amongst the most peaceful of the Black paths, as the Vermis sleep in this form often.'), //2 - burnout
	array('PathColour'=>'Blue Aquatic or Black Migratory','Bulmas'=>'All','AnimalCategory'=>'Meiofauna','Example'=>'Small Nematode worms / shrimps','Bodypart'=>'Gut', 'Notes'=>'A lot of parasite paths at this level and the Vermis do use theses paths often as they approach human habitation without risking the deep Lea.'), //3 - question
	array('PathColour'=>'Blue Aquatic or Black Migratory','Bulmas'=>'All','AnimalCategory'=>'Mesofauna','Example'=>'Greenfly / Midge / Maggots / Woodlice','Bodypart'=>'Antenna', 'Notes'=>'Tiny Arthropods that are often detritivores, also they can also be mistaken for vegetarian in many circumstances.'), //4 - myth
	array('PathColour'=>'Blue Aquatic or Black Migratory','Bulmas'=>'All','AnimalCategory'=>'Macrofauna','Example'=>'Fly / Earthworm / Moth / Wasp','Bodypart'=>'Mandibles', 'Notes'=>'Small (often burrowing) creatures, although a number fly as well, many of these paths run deep through the Lea.'), //5 - joke
	array('PathColour'=>'Blue Aquatic or Black Migratory','Bulmas'=>'All','AnimalCategory'=>'Megafauna – Tiny','Example'=>'Mole / Starfish / Corvids / Migratory birds','Bodypart'=>'Scales', 'Notes'=>'Animals smaller than 500 grams. The Vermis that show traces of personality favour these paths, but Broccen and a few Field will walk these paths to fight Vermis.'), //6 - unicorn
	array('PathColour'=>'Blue Aquatic or Black Migratory','Bulmas'=>'All','AnimalCategory'=>'Megafauna – Small','Example'=>'Rays / Skates / Vulture','Bodypart'=>'Tail', 'Notes'=>'These migratory paths lead huge distances across and between continents and sometimes between worlds, but without diving too deep in the Lea. These are considered safe roads by the Fields.'), //7 - stag
	array('PathColour'=>'Blue Aquatic or Black Migratory','Bulmas'=>'All','AnimalCategory'=>'Megafauna – Medium','Example'=>'Hyena / Condor / Albatross','Bodypart'=>'Beak', 'Notes'=>'The largest of the living Black Paths, that still open naturally on modern Earths. These paths are considered unsafe by the Fields, but are considered ideal by the Hunters, probably for that reason.'), //8 - wizard
	array('PathColour'=>'Blue Aquatic or Black Migratory','Bulmas'=>'All','AnimalCategory'=>'Megafauna – Large','Example'=>'Human / Horse / Pachycrocuta (Prehistoric Striped Hyena)','Bodypart'=>'Hooves', 'Notes'=>'The Black Horse Paths are actually ancient trade and invasion routes that were created by horsemen. They are called Warhorse paths by the Hunters, and they may end the path in a Centauroid form if appropriate.'), //9 - lady
	array('PathColour'=>'Blue Aquatic or Black Migratory','Bulmas'=>'All','AnimalCategory'=>'Megafauna – Largest','Example'=>'Pseudo-Dragon','Bodypart'=>'Frills / Spines', 'Notes'=>'The Pseudo-Dragons are large reptiles, monitor lizards and the like, usually ancient paths like these can become blended with later animal paths leading to complex monstrous chimeras. Such as the Wyvern, a Lizard / Pterosaur / Bat Hybrid, Thunderbird (a Pterosaur / Condor Hybrid), Wyrms ( Snake / Dinosaur / Eel Hybrids) or Lake Monster (a blend of Dinosaur / Sturgeon / Seal / Eel Hybrids). Pseudo-dragon paths can be walked by any Bulmäs but many find these paths confusing and difficult.'), //10 - jester
	array('PathColour'=>'Blue Aquatic or Black Migratory','Bulmas'=>'All','AnimalCategory'=>'Troglodyte','Example'=>'Cave-dwelling Hominids, Kobolds, etc','Bodypart'=>'Prehensile Hand/Thumb', 'Notes'=>'Troglodyte paths always end in caves and pits, usually with signs of ancient habitation. Some lead deep into the past, twisting deep into the Labyrinth. Broccen may use Jack’s to dig new tunnels in the Lea, creating species to fill niches. Jacks may also be used to create Chimerical changes, blending parts of different animals together, each Jack adds another place the Bulmäs can play Lea cards.'), //J - mask
	array('PathColour'=>'Blue Aquatic or Black Migratory','Bulmas'=>'All','AnimalCategory'=>'Black paths and Migratory','Example'=>'Native Form / Dragon / Swarm / School','Bodypart'=>'Gills', 'Notes'=>'These paths open and close naturally through the Lea from time to time, and world to world, they are easily walked by all Bulmäs, but Vermis and All-Walkers may walk them in Swarm or True Dragon configurations.'), //Q - cloak
	array('PathColour'=>'Blue Aquatic or Black Migratory','Bulmas'=>'All','AnimalCategory'=>'Labyrinth','Example'=>'Labrys patterned Minotaur','Bodypart'=>'Brain', 'Notes'=>'Kings represent the deep paths in the Lea that touch the Labyrinth, and C&aelig;ster in the centre. A normal Bulmäs that tries to walk the Labyrinth will often be lost, and would then be recruited into the Labyrinth. The Labyrinth can connect any point in space and time to any other, allowing Bulmäs to consciously time-travel through the Lea. A King can allow a Bulmäs to create or reload a Chronolith or side-step to another universe, or travel backward or forward in time, depending on the power-level of the Bulmäs. However, walking so close to the Labyrinth is not something that most will attempt, as it is too easy to become lost.'), //K - physician
	//clubs
	array('PathColour'=>'Green/Turquoise Herbivore','Bulmas'=>'Herd, Broccen, Vermis, Labyrinthine, All-Walkers','AnimalCategory'=>'All-path','Example'=>'All-Walkers / Brahman','Bodypart'=>'Nerves (Instinct)', 'Notes'=>'The Paths of the All-Walkers and Brahman can allow Bulmäs to do extraordinary things, like walking an individual’s life-path, so that all of their personal history is known to them. All-Walkers can assume even the forms and souls of other people by using these paths, without directly eating of the Soul. All-Walkers can even Doom Weave and play other cards from their hands as Wyrd Tarot cards, once they have played an Ace on themselves.'), //A - court
	array('PathColour'=>'Green/Turquoise Herbivore','Bulmas'=>'Herd, Broccen, Vermis, Labyrinthine, All-Walkers','AnimalCategory'=>'Microfauna','Example'=>'Plankton/Phytoplankton/Algae','Bodypart'=>'Skin', 'Notes'=>'Microscopic animal and algal plant and bacterial paths, often overlooked. For the Fields these paths form the gateway into the Plant paths that their souls often rest in.'), //2 -Eelafin
	array('PathColour'=>'Green/Turquoise Herbivore','Bulmas'=>'Herd, Broccen, Vermis, Labyrinthine, All-Walkers','AnimalCategory'=>'Meiofauna','Example'=>'Small Nematode worms / shrimps / Lavae / Grubs ','Bodypart'=>'Eggs', 'Notes'=>'A lot of boring insects paths at this level, often parasitic to plants.'), //3 - serpent
	array('PathColour'=>'Green/Turquoise Herbivore','Bulmas'=>'Herd, Broccen, Vermis, Labyrinthine, All-Walkers','AnimalCategory'=>'Mesofauna','Example'=>'Greenfly / Grubs / Larvae','Bodypart'=>'Silk Glands', 'Notes'=>'Tiny Arthropods, including a lot of boring insects paths at this level, and vegetarian larvae of some other paths adults.'), //4 - waters
	array('PathColour'=>'Green/Turquoise Herbivore','Bulmas'=>'Herd, Broccen, Vermis, Labyrinthine, All-Walkers','AnimalCategory'=>'Macrofauna','Example'=>' Termites / Bees / Caterpillars / Hummingbirds ','Bodypart'=>'Lungs', 'Notes'=>'Small (often burrowing) mammals and large insects as well as hummingbirds are found on this path. There is a lot of nectar drinking '), //5 - shield
	array('PathColour'=>'Green/Turquoise Herbivore','Bulmas'=>'Herd, Broccen, Vermis, Labyrinthine, All-Walkers','AnimalCategory'=>'Megafauna – Tiny','Example'=>'Most herbivorous birds (Parrot) / Voles / Hamsters / Pika / Rabbit / Hare /  Iguana / Fruit-bats','Bodypart'=>'Nose', 'Notes'=>'Animals smaller than 40 Kilograms note that vegetarian animals may be larger than the equivalents on other paths, but not always.'), //6 - horde
	array('PathColour'=>'Green/Turquoise Herbivore','Bulmas'=>'Herd, Broccen, Vermis, Labyrinthine, All-Walkers','AnimalCategory'=>'Megafauna – Small','Example'=>'Capybara  / Sheep / Goats / Small Antelope ','Bodypart'=>'Cloven Hooves', 'Notes'=>'Small domesticated animals are the most common green paths in human occupied lands. These paths are also commonly short migration paths that lead between common pastures.'), //7- crystal
	array('PathColour'=>'Green/Turquoise Herbivore','Bulmas'=>'Herd, Broccen, Vermis, Labyrinthine, All-Walkers','AnimalCategory'=>'Megafauna – Medium','Example'=>'Cattle / Deer / Large Antelope / Horse','Bodypart'=>'Horns', 'Notes'=>'These are the most commonly walked paths amongst the Herd. The Paths often blend numerous animals together into super-herds that are common in modern Africa. These migratory paths can travel across or along entire continents, usually with an oval path.'), //8 - scythe
	array('PathColour'=>'Green/Turquoise Herbivore','Bulmas'=>'Herd, Broccen, Vermis, Labyrinthine, All-Walkers','AnimalCategory'=>'Megafauna – Large','Example'=>'Wildebeest / Bison / Moose / Auroch / Giraffe / Rhino','Bodypart'=>'Antler', 'Notes'=>'The largest of the common paths that can still be walked today. In some areas these paths have become dead, and will result in larger versions of domesticated cattle or wildly out of place animals, if the Bulmäs aren&apos;t lost to the Labyrinth.'), //9 - crown
	array('PathColour'=>'Green/Turquoise Herbivore','Bulmas'=>'Herd, Broccen, Vermis, Labyrinthine, All-Walkers','AnimalCategory'=>'Megafauna – Largest','Example'=>'Hippopotamus / Elephant / Sauropod / Mammoth ','Bodypart'=>'Trunk / Tentacle / Tusk', 'Notes'=>'These uncommon paths are only really walkable in Africa and India. Elsewhere on Earth they are more likely to connect back to the Palaeolithic (or earlier), becoming buried beneath more modern paths. Walking such dead paths can easily result in lost Bulmäs if they try to force a local path, although at least occasionally the "lost" Bulmäs will find themselves luckily in a zoo somewhere.'), //10 -guardian
	array('PathColour'=>'Green/Turquoise Herbivore','Bulmas'=>'Herd, Broccen, Vermis, Labyrinthine, All-Walkers','AnimalCategory'=>'Man-paths/Broccen Territory','Example'=>'Human / Groonians / Eelafin / Eusaivean / Mer-person / Bigfoot / Giant / Goblin, etc','Bodypart'=>'Arms', 'Notes'=>'Many humanoids follow a vegetarian diet and create green human paths as they travel. A few Field Bulmäs have been known to incarnate among such communities. Broccen may use Jack’s to dig new tunnels in the Lea, creating species to fill niches, in this case specific Herbivores may be created. Jacks may also be used to create Chimerical changes, blending parts of different animals together, each Jack adds another place the Bulmäs can play Lea cards.'), //J -tempest
	array('PathColour'=>'Green/Turquoise Herbivore','Bulmas'=>'Herd, Broccen, Vermis, Labyrinthine, All-Walkers','AnimalCategory'=>'Black paths and Migratory','Example'=>'Native Form / Dragon / Swarm','Bodypart'=>'Unusual Anatomy', 'Notes'=>'These paths open and close naturally through the Lea from time to time, they are easily walked by all Bulmäs, but Vermis and All-Walkers may walk them in Swarm or Dragon configurations. Field, Broccen and Vermis Bulmäs can use Queens to sleep in the Lea. This involves sleeping within a plant in the real world, often as a tree. This is one way that Soul-Fruit can be cultivated, if a Bulmäs sleeps for long enough in one tree.'), //Q - inn
	array('PathColour'=>'Green/Turquoise Herbivore','Bulmas'=>'Herd, Broccen, Vermis, Labyrinthine, All-Walkers','AnimalCategory'=>'Labyrinth','Example'=>'Labrys patterned Beastmen','Bodypart'=>'Foot', 'Notes'=>'Kings represent the deep paths in the Lea that touch the Labyrinth, and C&aelig;ster in the centre. A normal Bulmäs that tries to walk the Labyrinth will often be lost, and would then be recruited into the Labyrinth. The Labyrinth can connect any point in space and time to any other, allowing Bulmäs to consciously time-travel through the Lea. A King can allow a Bulmäs to create or reload a Chronolith or side-step to another universe, or travel backward or forward in time, depending on the power-level of the Bulmäs. However, walking so close to the Labyrinth is not something that most will attempt, as it is too easy to become lost.'), //K - fae noble
	//spades
	array('PathColour'=>'Red/Purple Carnivore','Bulmas'=>'Hunters, Broccen, Vermis, Labyrinthine, All-Walkers','AnimalCategory'=>'All-path','Example'=>'All-Walkers','Bodypart'=>'Heart (Emotions)', 'Notes'=>'The Paths of the All-Walkers can allow Bulmäs to do extraordinary things, like walking an individual’s life-path, so that all of their personal history is known to them. All-Walkers can assume even the forms and souls of other people by using these paths, without directly eating of the Soul. All-Walkers can even Doom Weave and play other cards from their hands as Wyrd Tarot cards, once they have played an Ace on themselves.'), //A - threshold
	array('PathColour'=>'Red/Purple Carnivore','Bulmas'=>'Hunters, Broccen, Vermis, Labyrinthine, All-Walkers','AnimalCategory'=>'Microfauna','Example'=>'Bacteria / Viral paths','Bodypart'=>'Lower Intestine / Cloaca', 'Notes'=>'Microscopic viral and bacterial paths, often overlooked, this can mimic any larger animal paths. Broccen and Hunters can learn to cut into the Lea and coat their claws with deadly viruses, even flinging them at enemies.'), //2 - swamp
	array('PathColour'=>'Red/Purple Carnivore','Bulmas'=>'Hunters, Broccen, Vermis, Labyrinthine, All-Walkers','AnimalCategory'=>'Meiofauna','Example'=>'Small Nematode worms / Lice ','Bodypart'=>'Mucus Membranes', 'Notes'=>'A lot of parasitic carnivore paths at this level, these can follow much larger animal paths within that animal. These paths often thread invisibly through long migratory paths and offer Hunters secretive ways to approach Fields.'), //3 - key
	array('PathColour'=>'Red/Purple Carnivore','Bulmas'=>'Hunters, Broccen, Vermis, Labyrinthine, All-Walkers','AnimalCategory'=>'Mesofauna','Example'=>'Midge / Flea / Bugs / Ticks','Bodypart'=>'Mandibles / Proboscis / Teeth', 'Notes'=>'Tiny Arthropods usually with biting mouth parts. Hunters that a use these forms typically use them to suck blood to hunt, they soon learn to Soul-taste, essentially taking a copy of a soul as though they had consumed it from an often unnoticed nip.'), //4 - tower
	array('PathColour'=>'Red/Purple Carnivore','Bulmas'=>'Hunters, Broccen, Vermis, Labyrinthine, All-Walkers','AnimalCategory'=>'Macrofauna','Example'=>'Spider / Centipede / Wasp / Scorpion / Songbird / Bat','Bodypart'=>'Venom-sacs', 'Notes'=>'Small, often venomous predators, usually insectivores, often leaping, flying, or parachuting. These Hunters focus their efforts on hunting Vermis souls. Often these are fragments of sleeping Vermis, that hold disjointed memories from a thousand different lives, but if you eat enough sometimes the pieces begin to make some sense.'), //5 - sail
	array('PathColour'=>'Red/Purple Carnivore','Bulmas'=>'Hunters, Broccen, Vermis, Labyrinthine, All-Walkers','AnimalCategory'=>'Megafauna – Tiny','Example'=>' Snake / Domestic Cat / Owl / Hawk','Bodypart'=>'Talons /  Retractable Claws', 'Notes'=>'Animals smaller than 1 Kilograms, usually eat smaller mammals and birds. Very common path in human occupied territories. These paths are favoured by Hunters who are human incarnated.'), //6 - clock
	array('PathColour'=>'Red/Purple Carnivore','Bulmas'=>'Hunters, Broccen, Vermis, Labyrinthine, All-Walkers','AnimalCategory'=>'Megafauna – Small','Example'=>'Dog / Wolf / Eagle / Cobra','Bodypart'=>'Hunting Senses (Binocular Vision Eyes / Scent Tracking nose)', 'Notes'=>'Traditionally the most common animal path in human occupied territory. Dog paths run alongside human paths for thousands of years, although the breeds get more and more wolf-like the deeper the path goes. These paths are often the first ones run by Hunters when they are first blooded. Especially when they Hunt their own previous favoured form.'), //7 - sword
	array('PathColour'=>'Red/Purple Carnivore','Bulmas'=>'Hunters, Broccen, Vermis, Labyrinthine, All-Walkers','AnimalCategory'=>'Megafauna – Medium','Example'=>'Dire Wolf / Lion / Large Snake / Shark','Bodypart'=>'Spine', 'Notes'=>'These paths are uncommon in human occupied areas, except where they tend to be end in Zoos. Many are long dead and may result in lost Bulmäs as they run so deep into the past.'), //8 - rival
	array('PathColour'=>'Red/Purple Carnivore','Bulmas'=>'Hunters, Broccen, Vermis, Labyrinthine, All-Walkers','AnimalCategory'=>'Megafauna – Large','Example'=>'Tiger / Python / Alligator / Polar Bear / Large Shark','Bodypart'=>'Muscle', 'Notes'=>'These Paths are usually lost in any area where the Labyrinth is strong. Human-occupied lands are too closely tied to the Labyrinth. Out in the wilds however these paths are often very much alive, and still stretch beyond the current ranges of the animals.'), //9 - robot
	array('PathColour'=>'Red/Purple Carnivore','Bulmas'=>'Hunters, Broccen, Vermis, Labyrinthine, All-Walkers','AnimalCategory'=>'Megafauna – Largest','Example'=>'Salt Water Crocodile / Whale / Therapod / Pteradon','Bodypart'=>'Spikes / Bone Scales / Tooth Scales', 'Notes'=>'These Paths tend to be lost on Earth, although a few cling on. Hunters that walk these paths usually stay far from any worlds that touch the Labyrinth.'), //10 - lion
	array('PathColour'=>'Red/Purple Carnivore','Bulmas'=>'Hunters, Broccen, Vermis, Labyrinthine, All-Walkers','AnimalCategory'=>'Man-paths/Broccen Territory','Example'=>'Human / Groonians / Eelafin / Eusaivean / Mer-person / Bigfoot / Giant / Goblin / Apex Predator','Bodypart'=>'Brain (Imagination)', 'Notes'=>'Hunters have been known to use the Human path (that they call the Hunter path) to create traps, snares and weapons. They (and many Broccen) can Play other Lea cards as Traps and Obstacles as long as they have the Jack in play. Broccen may use Jack’s to dig new tunnels in the Lea, creating species to fill niches. Jacks may also be used to create Chimerical changes, blending parts of different animals together, each Jack adds another place the Bulmäs can play Lea cards.'), //J - explorer
	array('PathColour'=>'Red/Purple Carnivore','Bulmas'=>'Hunters, Broccen, Vermis, Labyrinthine, All-Walkers','AnimalCategory'=>'Black paths and Migratory','Example'=>'Native Form — Dragon','Bodypart'=>'Senses', 'Notes'=>'These paths open and close naturally through the Lea from time to time, they are easily walked by all Bulmäs, but Vermis and All-Walkers may walk them in Swarm or Dragon configurations. Hunters and Broccen have occasionally transformed into a Dragon on these paths, however all have immediately been lost to Vermis. It is said that those who hunt Vermis should not walk these roads.'), //Q - scope
	array('PathColour'=>'Red/Purple Carnivore','Bulmas'=>'Hunters, Broccen, Vermis, Labyrinthine, All-Walkers','AnimalCategory'=>'Labyrinth','Example'=>'Labrys patterned Theriocephalic (Animal-Headed) Humanoids','Bodypart'=>'Head', 'Notes'=>'Kings represent the deep paths in the Lea that touch the Labyrinth, and C&aelig;ster in the centre. A normal Bulmäs that tries to walk the Labyrinth will often be lost, and would then be recruited into the Labyrinth. The Labyrinth can connect any point in space and time to any other, allowing Bulmäs to consciously time-travel through the Lea. A King can allow a Bulmäs to create or reload a Chronolith or side-step to another universe, or travel backward or forward in time, depending on the power-level of the Bulmäs. However, walking so close to the Labyrinth is not something that most will attempt, as it is too easy to become lost.'), //K - butcher
	array('PathColour'=>'Rainbow','Bulmas'=>'All','AnimalCategory'=>'Any','Example'=>'Can create new paths that exploit new niches, rather like Broccen digging paths into the Lea.','Bodypart'=>'Skin Patterns / Coloured Feathers / Camouflage / Chromatophores', 'Notes'=>'These paths reshape the local Lea creating new species that exploit a specific niche (as required by the Bulmäs walking it) from one of the local species. Several of the local animals will be evolved to exploit the new niche instantly. Such transformations are usually as slight as possible to meet the requirement of exploiting the niche and are typically at a genetic level appearing identical to normal mutation and evolution.'), //jkr  - world
	array('PathColour'=>'Grey','Bulmas'=>'Sleeping','AnimalCategory'=>'None','Example'=>'A Plant / Fossil', 'Bodypart'=>'Bone', 'Notes'=>'The Grey path allows a Bulmäs Soul to sleep in the landscape. Their Soul may live in a skull, horn, tree or fossil for years, millennia or millions of years, until it is passed on, by ingestion of a fruit or nut, or by a Soul-Release ceremony. Fossil Bulmäs include Moon-Staves, Flint Weapons (Axes or Knives) and Elf-shot Armour that can only be worn / controlled by a Bulmäs who have a Soul related to the Fossil Soul.'), //jkr - beyond
);
